\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458182632,1),('8704','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8704\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:46:\"Ng Shek Wai v The Medical Council of Hong Kong\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8704\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1430956800\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450249301\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8704\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450249301\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:4009:\"Request for identity of members sitting at disciplinary inquiry, legal adviser and defence counsel – decision not to disclose information quashed – failed to take into account principle of open justice<p>\n	Ng Shek Wai v The Medical Council of Hong Kong</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad629030000014cdad39e079f8c7b72&amp;docguid=I2E8ED3D4373E43108A06FA715B5AF4A0&amp;hitguid=I2E8ED3D4373E43108A06FA715B5AF4A0&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=14\">[2015] HKEC 301</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Constitutional and Administrative Law List No. 167 of 2013<br />\n	Godfrey Lam J<br />\n	18 February 2015</p>\n<p>\n	The Medical Council (the &ldquo;Council&rdquo;) held a disciplinary inquiry in relation to M, a medical practitioner. The inquiry was conducted in public and the names of the members of the Council were disclosed on name plates placed in front of them. After M was sentenced, the Council was alerted by the media that M did not have a clear record and reviewed its original decision. The written decision of the Council only stated the name of the Chairman. The matter was reported in the news. X, a member of the public unconnected with the case, enquired with the Council of the identity of members sitting at the inquiry, the Legal Adviser of the Council and the defence counsel. X refused to answer repeated enquiries by the Council as to his purpose of the inquiry and intended use of the information. X applied for judicial review to quash the Council&rsquo;s decision in refusing to disclose the requested information (the &ldquo;Decision&rdquo;). The Council contended that Data Protection Principle (&ldquo;DPP&rdquo;) 3 in Sch. 1 of the Personal Data (Privacy) Ordinance (Cap. 486) (the &ldquo;Ordinance&rdquo;) applied to restrict disclosure to X and that none of the statutory exemptions from DPP applied.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, allowing the application, quashing the Decision and remitting the matter to the Council, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		The Council had taken into account an irrelevant consideration, namely the restriction in DPP 3, and failed to take into account a relevant consideration, namely the requirements of the principle of open justice. If disclosure was required or authorised by the common law principle of open justice, DPP 3 posed no obstacle to disclosure because the exemption in s. 60B(a) applied. However, the fact that the exemption applied did not imply that the Council was required to make disclosure.</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>(Obiter)</em> Disclosing the names to X would not constitute a &ldquo;new purpose&rdquo; as defined in s. 3(4) of Sch. 1. There was no evidence of any statement of the purpose for collecting personal data. In ascertaining the original purpose or any directly related purpose, it was legitimate to have regard to &ldquo;the reasonable expectations of the data subject&rdquo;. The names of the Council&rsquo;s members were disclosed on name plates placed in front of them at the inquiry. Members of the Council, the Legal Adviser and defence counsel would reasonably expect that the Council could disclose, either in its written decision or otherwise, their names and the capacity in which they attended.</li>\n	<li>\n		The principle of open justice applied to all tribunals exercising judicial power and was not limited to physical access to the court room where a judicial hearing was taking place. As far as its disciplinary functions were concerned, the Council was a tribunal to which the principle applied. Public interest in the administration of justice and accountability of the judicial process required that basic information about the identities of the key persons who had taken part in a public judicial hearing should normally be published. If the information was not disclosed in the written decision of the tribunal, it should be disclosed upon inquiry made at a time reasonably close to the hearing.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:205:\"Request for identity of members sitting at disciplinary inquiry, legal adviser and defence counsel – decision not to disclose information quashed – failed to take into account principle of open justice\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3956:\"<p>Request for identity of members sitting at disciplinary inquiry, legal adviser and defence counsel – decision not to disclose information quashed – failed to take into account principle of open justice\n</p><p>\n	Ng Shek Wai v The Medical Council of Hong Kong</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad629030000014cdad39e079f8c7b72&amp;docguid=I2E8ED3D4373E43108A06FA715B5AF4A0&amp;hitguid=I2E8ED3D4373E43108A06FA715B5AF4A0&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=14\">[2015] HKEC 301</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Constitutional and Administrative Law List No. 167 of 2013<br />\n	Godfrey Lam J<br />\n	18 February 2015</p>\n<p>\n	The Medical Council (the “Council”) held a disciplinary inquiry in relation to M, a medical practitioner. The inquiry was conducted in public and the names of the members of the Council were disclosed on name plates placed in front of them. After M was sentenced, the Council was alerted by the media that M did not have a clear record and reviewed its original decision. The written decision of the Council only stated the name of the Chairman. The matter was reported in the news. X, a member of the public unconnected with the case, enquired with the Council of the identity of members sitting at the inquiry, the Legal Adviser of the Council and the defence counsel. X refused to answer repeated enquiries by the Council as to his purpose of the inquiry and intended use of the information. X applied for judicial review to quash the Council’s decision in refusing to disclose the requested information (the “Decision”). The Council contended that Data Protection Principle (“DPP”) 3 in Sch. 1 of the Personal Data (Privacy) Ordinance (Cap. 486) (the “Ordinance”) applied to restrict disclosure to X and that none of the statutory exemptions from DPP applied.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, allowing the application, quashing the Decision and remitting the matter to the Council, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		The Council had taken into account an irrelevant consideration, namely the restriction in DPP 3, and failed to take into account a relevant consideration, namely the requirements of the principle of open justice. If disclosure was required or authorised by the common law principle of open justice, DPP 3 posed no obstacle to disclosure because the exemption in s. 60B(a) applied. However, the fact that the exemption applied did not imply that the Council was required to make disclosure.</li>\n<li>\n		<em>(Obiter)</em> Disclosing the names to X would not constitute a “new purpose” as defined in s. 3(4) of Sch. 1. There was no evidence of any statement of the purpose for collecting personal data. In ascertaining the original purpose or any directly related purpose, it was legitimate to have regard to “the reasonable expectations of the data subject”. The names of the Council’s members were disclosed on name plates placed in front of them at the inquiry. Members of the Council, the Legal Adviser and defence counsel would reasonably expect that the Council could disclose, either in its written decision or otherwise, their names and the capacity in which they attended.</li>\n<li>\n		The principle of open justice applied to all tribunals exercising judicial power and was not limited to physical access to the court room where a judicial hearing was taking place. As far as its disciplinary functions were concerned, the Council was a tribunal to which the principle applied. Public interest in the administration of justice and accountability of the judicial process required that basic information about the identities of the key persons who had taken part in a public judicial hearing should normally be published. If the information was not disclosed in the written decision of the tribunal, it should be disclosed upon inquiry made at a time reasonably close to the hearing.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:213:\"<p>Request for identity of members sitting at disciplinary inquiry, legal adviser and defence counsel – decision not to disclose information quashed – failed to take into account principle of open justice</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:46:\"Ng Shek Wai v The Medical Council of Hong Kong\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:46:\"Ng Shek Wai v The Medical Council of Hong Kong\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"102\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-05-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad629030000014cdad39e079f8c7b72&docguid=I2E8ED3D4373E43108A06FA715B5AF4A0&hitguid=I2E8ED3D4373E43108A06FA715B5AF4A0&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=14\";s:5:\"title\";s:15:\"[2015] HKEC 301\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"18 February 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"18 February 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"Data Privacy\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"Data Privacy\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:46:\"Ng Shek Wai v The Medical Council of Hong Kong\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1430956800\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458127752,1),('8732','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8732\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:51:\"Secretary for Justice v Global Merchant Funding Ltd\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8732\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1435881600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450249301\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8732\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450249301\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3421:\"Carrying on business as money lender without licence – purchase of future credit card receivables from merchants for consideration of one-off merchant cash advance at discount – not “loan” within meaning of s. 2 of Money Lenders Ordinance (Cap. 163)<p>\n	Secretary for Justice v Global Merchant Funding Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d05f0000014e4da30d37ea393afb&amp;docguid=I5004ED82922D4C4F974DC4D67EA9DC4B&amp;hitguid=I5004ED82922D4C4F974DC4D67EA9DC4B&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=14&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=15\">[2015] 2 HKLRD 843</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Magistracy Appeal No. 716 of 2013<br />\n	Lunn V-P, Kwan JA and Derek Pang J<br />\n	2 April 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D was acquitted of carrying on business as a money lender without a licence. D, under an agreement entitled &ldquo;Merchant Cash Advance Sale and Purchase Contract&rdquo; (the &ldquo;MCA Contract&rdquo;), purchased a fixed amount of a merchant&rsquo;s future credit card receivables (the &ldquo;Purchased Amount&rdquo;) and in return for a one-off upfront merchant cash advance at a discount (the &ldquo;MCA&rdquo;). The merchant gave an irrevocable authorisation to its credit card processing bank, B, to split the cash sum from its credit card sales between the merchant and D; and to pay a fixed percentage to D until the Purchased Amount was collected in full with no deadline for repayment. The Magistrate held that the MCA was not a loan within the meaning of s. 2 of the Money Lenders Ordinance (Cap. 163) (the &ldquo;MLO&rdquo;). The Secretary for Justice (the &ldquo;SJ&rdquo;) appealed by way of case stated against D&rsquo;s acquittal.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		The MCA was not a loan within s. 2 of the MLO. What mattered was the substance and legal effect of the transaction as a whole. As regards a document which was not a sham and expressed as an agreement for sale and purchase, as here, it was necessary to consider the overall provisions to decide whether it amounted to an agreement for the sale and purchase of future receivables or a loan.</li>\n	<li>\n		The terms of the MCA Contract expressly provided for an agreement of sale and purchase of future receivables, not a loan. The agreement of a discount at the outset, with no interest to be charged regardless of how long it took for the Purchased Amount to be collected in full by D, was consistent with a sale and purchase transaction, but inconsistent with a loan with interest accruing daily on the outstanding amount.</li>\n	<li>\n		The SJ&rsquo;s argument that D could recover the Purchased Amount from only the merchant, whose liability was that of a borrower under a loan agreement was rejected. Under the MCA Contract, D purchased a clearly identified and recognisable chose in action (ie, B&rsquo;s obligation to pay the merchant the amount of the credit card sales, and collected the Purchased Amount from B). Thus, the primary source of recovery of the Purchased Amount was not the merchant but B.</li>\n	<li>\n		The fact that D had a right of recourse against no third-party debtor other than the merchant if the Purchased Amount of future credit receivables failed to materialise and the recourse provisions in the MCA Contract, did not alter the nature of the contract of sale and purchase or turn it into a loan.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:257:\"Carrying on business as money lender without licence – purchase of future credit card receivables from merchants for consideration of one-off merchant cash advance at discount – not “loan” within meaning of s. 2 of Money Lenders Ordinance (Cap. 163)\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3359:\"<p>Carrying on business as money lender without licence – purchase of future credit card receivables from merchants for consideration of one-off merchant cash advance at discount – not “loan” within meaning of s. 2 of Money Lenders Ordinance (Cap. 163)\n</p><p>\n	Secretary for Justice v Global Merchant Funding Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d05f0000014e4da30d37ea393afb&amp;docguid=I5004ED82922D4C4F974DC4D67EA9DC4B&amp;hitguid=I5004ED82922D4C4F974DC4D67EA9DC4B&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=14&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=15\">[2015] 2 HKLRD 843</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Magistracy Appeal No. 716 of 2013<br />\n	Lunn V-P, Kwan JA and Derek Pang J<br />\n	2 April 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D was acquitted of carrying on business as a money lender without a licence. D, under an agreement entitled “Merchant Cash Advance Sale and Purchase Contract” (the “MCA Contract”), purchased a fixed amount of a merchant’s future credit card receivables (the “Purchased Amount”) and in return for a one-off upfront merchant cash advance at a discount (the “MCA”). The merchant gave an irrevocable authorisation to its credit card processing bank, B, to split the cash sum from its credit card sales between the merchant and D; and to pay a fixed percentage to D until the Purchased Amount was collected in full with no deadline for repayment. The Magistrate held that the MCA was not a loan within the meaning of s. 2 of the Money Lenders Ordinance (Cap. 163) (the “MLO”). The Secretary for Justice (the “SJ”) appealed by way of case stated against D’s acquittal.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		The MCA was not a loan within s. 2 of the MLO. What mattered was the substance and legal effect of the transaction as a whole. As regards a document which was not a sham and expressed as an agreement for sale and purchase, as here, it was necessary to consider the overall provisions to decide whether it amounted to an agreement for the sale and purchase of future receivables or a loan.</li>\n<li>\n		The terms of the MCA Contract expressly provided for an agreement of sale and purchase of future receivables, not a loan. The agreement of a discount at the outset, with no interest to be charged regardless of how long it took for the Purchased Amount to be collected in full by D, was consistent with a sale and purchase transaction, but inconsistent with a loan with interest accruing daily on the outstanding amount.</li>\n<li>\n		The SJ’s argument that D could recover the Purchased Amount from only the merchant, whose liability was that of a borrower under a loan agreement was rejected. Under the MCA Contract, D purchased a clearly identified and recognisable chose in action (ie, B’s obligation to pay the merchant the amount of the credit card sales, and collected the Purchased Amount from B). Thus, the primary source of recovery of the Purchased Amount was not the merchant but B.</li>\n<li>\n		The fact that D had a right of recourse against no third-party debtor other than the merchant if the Purchased Amount of future credit receivables failed to materialise and the recourse provisions in the MCA Contract, did not alter the nature of the contract of sale and purchase or turn it into a loan.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:265:\"<p>Carrying on business as money lender without licence – purchase of future credit card receivables from merchants for consideration of one-off merchant cash advance at discount – not “loan” within meaning of s. 2 of Money Lenders Ordinance (Cap. 163)</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:51:\"Secretary for Justice v Global Merchant Funding Ltd\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:51:\"Secretary for Justice v Global Merchant Funding Ltd\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"101\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-07-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:233:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744d05f0000014e4da30d37ea393afb&docguid=I5004ED82922D4C4F974DC4D67EA9DC4B&hitguid=I5004ED82922D4C4F974DC4D67EA9DC4B&spos=2&epos=2&td=14&crumb-action=append&context=15\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 2 HKLRD 843\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"2 April 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"2 April 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:26:\"Criminal Law and Procedure\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:26:\"Criminal Law and Procedure\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:51:\"Secretary for Justice v Global Merchant Funding Ltd\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1435881600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8734','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8734\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:64:\"Ever Judger Holding Co Ltd v Kroman Celik Sanayii Anonim Sirketi\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8734\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1435881600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450249301\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8734\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450249301\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2640:\"Anti-suit injunction should ordinarily be granted unless defendant could demonstrate strong reason to contrary<p>\n	Ever Judger Holding Co Ltd v Kroman Celik Sanayii Anonim Sirketi</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad8289e0000014e4da1c7e7244cac62&amp;docguid=I5FDEE003ADD541A7A7475C7210723B9E&amp;hitguid=I5FDEE003ADD541A7A7475C7210723B9E&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=2&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=12\">[2015] 2 HKLRD 866</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Construction and Arbitration Proceedings No. 6 of 2015<br />\n	Godfrey Lam J in Chambers<br />\n	17 April 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D, a Turkish company, acquired steel wire rods to be carried on a vessel from the PRC to Turkey. The vessel was chartered by P, its registered owner, on a voyage charterparty which contained a clause, incorporated in the bill of lading, referring all disputes to arbitration in Hong Kong. When the vessel arrived in Turkey, D alleged that the cargo was damaged and arrested it. D filed a claim against P with the Turkish Court for damages. P then served notice of arbitration on D and obtained an ex parte anti-suit injunction against D to restrain further conduct of the proceedings in Turkey, which P now sought to continue on an inter partes basis. D opposed the application on the grounds that: (a) P came to the Court with unclean hands as the master issued clean bills of lading fraudulently; (b) D had commenced related proceedings in Turkey against its cargo insurer; (c) P had already filed a jurisdictional challenge in the Turkish Court; and (d) there was delay by P in seeking the injunction.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, allowing P&rsquo;s application, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		A party to an arbitration agreement had a contractual right to have the contract enforced. The court should ordinarily grant an injunction to restrain the pursuit of foreign proceedings brought in breach of an agreement for Hong Kong arbitration, at any rate where the injunction had been sought without delay and the foreign proceedings were not too far advanced, unless the defendant could demonstrate strong reason to the contrary.</li>\n	<li>\n		Whether such a strong reason existed would depend on all the circumstances. It did not have to be shown that the contractual forum was more appropriate than any other. Nor could mere complaints of inconvenience suffice. The power was ultimately a discretionary one to be exercised in the interests of justice and the factors raised against the injunction must be sufficiently strong to warrant not holding the opposing party to his contract.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:110:\"Anti-suit injunction should ordinarily be granted unless defendant could demonstrate strong reason to contrary\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2640:\"<p>Anti-suit injunction should ordinarily be granted unless defendant could demonstrate strong reason to contrary\n</p><p>\n	Ever Judger Holding Co Ltd v Kroman Celik Sanayii Anonim Sirketi</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad8289e0000014e4da1c7e7244cac62&amp;docguid=I5FDEE003ADD541A7A7475C7210723B9E&amp;hitguid=I5FDEE003ADD541A7A7475C7210723B9E&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=2&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=12\">[2015] 2 HKLRD 866</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Construction and Arbitration Proceedings No. 6 of 2015<br />\n	Godfrey Lam J in Chambers<br />\n	17 April 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D, a Turkish company, acquired steel wire rods to be carried on a vessel from the PRC to Turkey. The vessel was chartered by P, its registered owner, on a voyage charterparty which contained a clause, incorporated in the bill of lading, referring all disputes to arbitration in Hong Kong. When the vessel arrived in Turkey, D alleged that the cargo was damaged and arrested it. D filed a claim against P with the Turkish Court for damages. P then served notice of arbitration on D and obtained an ex parte anti-suit injunction against D to restrain further conduct of the proceedings in Turkey, which P now sought to continue on an inter partes basis. D opposed the application on the grounds that: (a) P came to the Court with unclean hands as the master issued clean bills of lading fraudulently; (b) D had commenced related proceedings in Turkey against its cargo insurer; (c) P had already filed a jurisdictional challenge in the Turkish Court; and (d) there was delay by P in seeking the injunction.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, allowing P’s application, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		A party to an arbitration agreement had a contractual right to have the contract enforced. The court should ordinarily grant an injunction to restrain the pursuit of foreign proceedings brought in breach of an agreement for Hong Kong arbitration, at any rate where the injunction had been sought without delay and the foreign proceedings were not too far advanced, unless the defendant could demonstrate strong reason to the contrary.</li>\n<li>\n		Whether such a strong reason existed would depend on all the circumstances. It did not have to be shown that the contractual forum was more appropriate than any other. Nor could mere complaints of inconvenience suffice. The power was ultimately a discretionary one to be exercised in the interests of justice and the factors raised against the injunction must be sufficiently strong to warrant not holding the opposing party to his contract.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:118:\"<p>Anti-suit injunction should ordinarily be granted unless defendant could demonstrate strong reason to contrary</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:64:\"Ever Judger Holding Co Ltd v Kroman Celik Sanayii Anonim Sirketi\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:64:\"Ever Judger Holding Co Ltd v Kroman Celik Sanayii Anonim Sirketi\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:0:{}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-07-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad8289e0000014e4da1c7e7244cac62&docguid=I5FDEE003ADD541A7A7475C7210723B9E&hitguid=I5FDEE003ADD541A7A7475C7210723B9E&spos=2&epos=2&td=2&crumb-action=append&context=12\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 2 HKLRD 866\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:13:\"17 April 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:13:\"17 April 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"Conflict of Laws\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"Conflict of Laws\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:64:\"Ever Judger Holding Co Ltd v Kroman Celik Sanayii Anonim Sirketi\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1435881600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8736','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8736\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:36:\"HKSAR v Hip Hing Construction Co Ltd\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8736\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1435881600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450249301\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8736\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450249301\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2536:\"Summons defective in disclosing no offence known to law — whether power to amend summons should be exercised<p>\n	HKSAR v Hip Hing Construction Co Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad8289e0000014e4da4f1f7c8f4c90a&amp;docguid=I899D4845C39147E1B49640078F42E171&amp;hitguid=I899D4845C39147E1B49640078F42E171&amp;spos=4&amp;epos=4&amp;td=145&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=18\">[2015] 2 HKLRD 831</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Magistracy Appeal No. 914 of 2009<br />\n	Louis Tong J<br />\n	2 April 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D, the main contractor of a construction site, was summonsed for and convicted of, being a proprietor of an industrial undertaking, failing to provide and maintain a system of work that was safe and without risk to the health of two persons, X1&ndash;2, employed by SC, contrary to <em>inter alia</em> ss. 6A(1) and 13(1) of the Factories and Industrial Undertakings Ordinance (Cap. 59). SC was a subcontractor for the site, where X1 had died as a result of an industrial accident. At trial, the prosecution successfully applied to amend the summons by adding the particular that Xs were workers of SC. It was an admitted fact that SC had pleaded guilty to failing to ensure the safety of its employees contrary to <em>inter alia</em> ss.6A(1) of the Ordinance. The Magistrate found that SC was guilty of s.6A and so, by reason of s. 13(1), D was also guilty of failing to maintain a safe system of work. D appealed against conviction, arguing that the information laid in the summons was defective in disclosing no offence known in law.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, allowing the appeal and quashing the conviction, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Sections 6A and 13 of the Ordinance, in combination, did not impose a duty on a proprietor to ensure safety extending beyond its employees. The summons here conflated the two sections and failed to distinguish between the predicate offence under s. 6A from the derivative offence under s. 13. The fundamental averment that an offence under s. 6A had been committed, and by whom, was lacking. The averment as to the identity of Xs&rsquo; employer did not cure this defect. Unless the s. 6A offence was proved to have been committed, the proprietor charged under s. 13 could not be guilty of a like offence.</li>\n	<li>\n		The defect was fundamental to the nature of the charge and it was not appropriate to amend it at this stage and to remit the case to the Magistrate for a trial <em>de novo</em>.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:110:\"Summons defective in disclosing no offence known to law — whether power to amend summons should be exercised\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2532:\"<p>Summons defective in disclosing no offence known to law — whether power to amend summons should be exercised\n</p><p>\n	HKSAR v Hip Hing Construction Co Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad8289e0000014e4da4f1f7c8f4c90a&amp;docguid=I899D4845C39147E1B49640078F42E171&amp;hitguid=I899D4845C39147E1B49640078F42E171&amp;spos=4&amp;epos=4&amp;td=145&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=18\">[2015] 2 HKLRD 831</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Magistracy Appeal No. 914 of 2009<br />\n	Louis Tong J<br />\n	2 April 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D, the main contractor of a construction site, was summonsed for and convicted of, being a proprietor of an industrial undertaking, failing to provide and maintain a system of work that was safe and without risk to the health of two persons, X1–2, employed by SC, contrary to <em>inter alia</em> ss. 6A(1) and 13(1) of the Factories and Industrial Undertakings Ordinance (Cap. 59). SC was a subcontractor for the site, where X1 had died as a result of an industrial accident. At trial, the prosecution successfully applied to amend the summons by adding the particular that Xs were workers of SC. It was an admitted fact that SC had pleaded guilty to failing to ensure the safety of its employees contrary to <em>inter alia</em> ss.6A(1) of the Ordinance. The Magistrate found that SC was guilty of s.6A and so, by reason of s. 13(1), D was also guilty of failing to maintain a safe system of work. D appealed against conviction, arguing that the information laid in the summons was defective in disclosing no offence known in law.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, allowing the appeal and quashing the conviction, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		Sections 6A and 13 of the Ordinance, in combination, did not impose a duty on a proprietor to ensure safety extending beyond its employees. The summons here conflated the two sections and failed to distinguish between the predicate offence under s. 6A from the derivative offence under s. 13. The fundamental averment that an offence under s. 6A had been committed, and by whom, was lacking. The averment as to the identity of Xs’ employer did not cure this defect. Unless the s. 6A offence was proved to have been committed, the proprietor charged under s. 13 could not be guilty of a like offence.</li>\n<li>\n		The defect was fundamental to the nature of the charge and it was not appropriate to amend it at this stage and to remit the case to the Magistrate for a trial <em>de novo</em>.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:118:\"<p>Summons defective in disclosing no offence known to law — whether power to amend summons should be exercised</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:36:\"HKSAR v Hip Hing Construction Co Ltd\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:36:\"HKSAR v Hip Hing Construction Co Ltd\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"101\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-07-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:234:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad8289e0000014e4da4f1f7c8f4c90a&docguid=I899D4845C39147E1B49640078F42E171&hitguid=I899D4845C39147E1B49640078F42E171&spos=4&epos=4&td=145&crumb-action=append&context=18\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 2 HKLRD 831\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"2 April 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"2 April 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"Criminal Procedure\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"Criminal Procedure\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:36:\"HKSAR v Hip Hing Construction Co Ltd\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1435881600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8738','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8738\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:40:\"Chan Kam Chuen v Secretary for Transport\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8738\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1435881600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450249301\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8738\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450249301\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2561:\"Resumption – Lands Tribunal had no jurisdiction to deal with application for ex gratia payment – Lands Resumption Ordinance (Cap. 124) s. 10(2)(c)<p>\n	Chan Kam Chuen v Secretary for Transport</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad8289e0000014e4da6949a0a1e325f&amp;docguid=I8DFF94DF77E245DDA9A74FD6A548AF1D&amp;hitguid=I8DFF94DF77E245DDA9A74FD6A548AF1D&amp;spos=8&amp;epos=8&amp;td=447&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=23\">[2015] 2 HKLRD 770</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Civil Appeal No. 321 of 2001<br />\n	Cheung, Chu JJA and Jeremy Poon J<br />\n	30 March 2015</p>\n<p>\n	X operated a pig farm on land in Yuen Long. The Government resumed the land pursuant to the Railways Ordinance (Cap. 519) (the &ldquo;RO&rdquo;) and offered X an ex gratia payment for certain structures on it. X refused and applied to the Lands Tribunal (the &ldquo;Tribunal&ldquo;) for an ex gratia payment purportedly under s. 34 of the RO, relying on s. 10(2)(c) of the Lands Resumption Ordinance (Cap. 124) (the &ldquo;LRO&rdquo;) which provides that &ldquo;The Tribunal shall determine the compensation (if any) payable &hellip; on the basis of &ndash; &hellip; (c) the amount of loss or damage suffered by any claimant due to the severance of the land resumed or any building erected thereon from any other land of the claimant, or building erected thereon, contiguous or adjacent thereto.&rdquo; The Tribunal dismissed X&rsquo;s application on the ground it had no jurisdiction to deal with ex gratia payments. X appealed.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		The Tribunal was right to decline jurisdiction. As was apparent from both the RO and the LRO, an <em>ex gratia</em> payment was not part of the statutory compensation scheme. The words &ldquo;the amount of loss and damages&rdquo; in s. 10(2)(c) of the LRO referred to statutory compensation. Section 10(2)(c) was not a free-standing claim which could encompass an <em>ex gratia</em> payment.</li>\n	<li>\n		Compensation and <em>ex gratia</em> payments were two different concepts. An <em>ex gratia </em>payment was based on a policy of administrative convenience, to replace the statutory compensation so as to avoid disputes over the amount of such compensation, and the delay and inconvenience involved in the judicial process. If an applicant was dissatisfied with an <em>ex gratia</em> payment offer or compensation, he could lodge a claim in the Tribunal for it to assess the statutory compensation.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:150:\"Resumption – Lands Tribunal had no jurisdiction to deal with application for ex gratia payment – Lands Resumption Ordinance (Cap. 124) s. 10(2)(c)\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2507:\"<p>Resumption – Lands Tribunal had no jurisdiction to deal with application for ex gratia payment – Lands Resumption Ordinance (Cap. 124) s. 10(2)(c)\n</p><p>\n	Chan Kam Chuen v Secretary for Transport</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad8289e0000014e4da6949a0a1e325f&amp;docguid=I8DFF94DF77E245DDA9A74FD6A548AF1D&amp;hitguid=I8DFF94DF77E245DDA9A74FD6A548AF1D&amp;spos=8&amp;epos=8&amp;td=447&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=23\">[2015] 2 HKLRD 770</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Civil Appeal No. 321 of 2001<br />\n	Cheung, Chu JJA and Jeremy Poon J<br />\n	30 March 2015</p>\n<p>\n	X operated a pig farm on land in Yuen Long. The Government resumed the land pursuant to the Railways Ordinance (Cap. 519) (the “RO”) and offered X an ex gratia payment for certain structures on it. X refused and applied to the Lands Tribunal (the “Tribunal“) for an ex gratia payment purportedly under s. 34 of the RO, relying on s. 10(2)(c) of the Lands Resumption Ordinance (Cap. 124) (the “LRO”) which provides that “The Tribunal shall determine the compensation (if any) payable … on the basis of – … (c) the amount of loss or damage suffered by any claimant due to the severance of the land resumed or any building erected thereon from any other land of the claimant, or building erected thereon, contiguous or adjacent thereto.” The Tribunal dismissed X’s application on the ground it had no jurisdiction to deal with ex gratia payments. X appealed.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		The Tribunal was right to decline jurisdiction. As was apparent from both the RO and the LRO, an <em>ex gratia</em> payment was not part of the statutory compensation scheme. The words “the amount of loss and damages” in s. 10(2)(c) of the LRO referred to statutory compensation. Section 10(2)(c) was not a free-standing claim which could encompass an <em>ex gratia</em> payment.</li>\n<li>\n		Compensation and <em>ex gratia</em> payments were two different concepts. An <em>ex gratia </em>payment was based on a policy of administrative convenience, to replace the statutory compensation so as to avoid disputes over the amount of such compensation, and the delay and inconvenience involved in the judicial process. If an applicant was dissatisfied with an <em>ex gratia</em> payment offer or compensation, he could lodge a claim in the Tribunal for it to assess the statutory compensation.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:158:\"<p>Resumption – Lands Tribunal had no jurisdiction to deal with application for ex gratia payment – Lands Resumption Ordinance (Cap. 124) s. 10(2)(c)</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:40:\"Chan Kam Chuen v Secretary for Transport\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:40:\"Chan Kam Chuen v Secretary for Transport\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"112\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-07-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:234:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad8289e0000014e4da6949a0a1e325f&docguid=I8DFF94DF77E245DDA9A74FD6A548AF1D&hitguid=I8DFF94DF77E245DDA9A74FD6A548AF1D&spos=8&epos=8&td=447&crumb-action=append&context=23\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 2 HKLRD 770\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:13:\"30 March 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:13:\"30 March 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:8:\"Land Law\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:8:\"Land Law\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:40:\"Chan Kam Chuen v Secretary for Transport\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1435881600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8740','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8740\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:36:\"Solicitor v Law Society of Hong Kong\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8740\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1435881600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450249301\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8740\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450249301\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:4528:\"Disciplinary proceedings – striking off not limited to cases involving dishonesty – could be imposed in appropriate cases of falling below required standards of integrity, probity and trustworthiness<p>\n	Solicitor v Law Society of Hong Kong</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad8289e0000014e4da9a73215a6959f&amp;docguid=IC85CA22819F043E9B03DE4B95A542A04&amp;hitguid=IC85CA22819F043E9B03DE4B95A542A04&amp;spos=40&amp;epos=40&amp;td=3695&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=29\">[2015] 2 HKLRD 802</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal [2015] 2 HKLRD 802<br />\n	Civil Appeal Nos. 20 &amp; 78 of 2014<br />\n	Lam V-P, Barma and McWalters JJA<br />\n	2 April 2015</p>\n<p>\n	H and W, who were formerly married and joint tenants of a Home Ownership Scheme property, instructed S, a principal partner of a solicitor&rsquo;s firm, to transfer the property to H&rsquo;s sole name. The Housing Authority (the &ldquo;HA&rdquo;) granted approval in principle conditional on inter alia it approving the draft assignment. H and W signed the draft assignment, which S had explained would probably be amended by the HA. H subsequently died, but S did not inform the HA of this. When the HA returned the draft assignment with extensive amendments and required the assignee to endorse his agreement to the conditions imposed, S replaced pages in the copy of the draft assignment signed by the parties except the signature page and the backsheet. S left the date unchanged and registered that version, together with the HA&rsquo;s letter imposing conditions endorsed by H&rsquo;s father and sole executor of his estate (&ldquo;F&rdquo;), at the Land Registry. F, believing that under the assignment he had inherited the property from H, paid off the mortgage but could not sell the property due to the defect in the assignment. The Solicitors Disciplinary Tribunal (the &ldquo;Tribunal&rdquo;) found S in breach of Principle 6.01 of the Hong Kong Solicitors&rsquo; Guide to Professional Conduct (the duty to act competently) and r. 2(a), (c) and (e) of the Solicitors&rsquo; Practice Rules (Cap. 159H, Sub. Leg.) and fined him $40,000 (the &ldquo;1st Complaint&rdquo;). The Tribunal also found that S had concealed or failed to disclose to the Hong Kong Solicitors Indemnity Fund Ltd that as part of a proposed settlement, he would obtain a personal interest in the property; and imposed a fine of $80,000 (the &ldquo;2nd Complaint&rdquo;). S abandoned his appeal against the finding of guilt under the 1st Complaint, but in CACV 20/2014, appealed against the finding of guilt under the 2nd Complaint. The Law Society, in CACV 78/2014, appealed against the penalty under the 1st Complaint (the &ldquo;Penalty&rdquo;), submitting that the proper sentence was the striking off or suspension of S.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, allowing the appeal by the Law Society on the 1st Complaint by setting aside the Penalty and making an order of suspension from practice for 2 years against S, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		There was room for flexibility in the circumstances under which a striking off penalty was appropriate and they should not be straitjacketed to cases involving dishonesty. Hence, in an appropriate case of a solicitor being found to have fallen below the required standards of integrity, probity and trustworthiness, the Tribunal could impose a penalty of striking off.</li>\n	<li>\n		However, while the Penalty was clearly wrong, it was not appropriate to order a striking off. The appropriate penalty was a suspension for 2 years with the condition that when S resumed practice, he was prohibited from practising as a sole proprietor or partner or manager of a solicitor&rsquo;s firm until the Law Society was satisfied he was fit to do so.</li>\n	<li>\n		S&rsquo;s conduct constituted a gross dereliction of his duty to the HA and gross incompetence. Even though there was no dishonesty on S&rsquo;s part and he did not derive any personal benefit from the transaction, it was still a very serious matter for a solicitor to swap pages in a conveyancing document and then have it registered in the Land Registry creating a false impression in a public registry as to F&rsquo;s title to the property. It was a serious breach of the public&rsquo;s trust in S. This was not a victimless infraction. F had suffered financial losses and he and W had to litigate to resolve the problem as to title. Substantial public resources also had been incurred as a result of S&rsquo;s wrongdoing.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:203:\"Disciplinary proceedings – striking off not limited to cases involving dishonesty – could be imposed in appropriate cases of falling below required standards of integrity, probity and trustworthiness\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:4435:\"<p>Disciplinary proceedings – striking off not limited to cases involving dishonesty – could be imposed in appropriate cases of falling below required standards of integrity, probity and trustworthiness\n</p><p>\n	Solicitor v Law Society of Hong Kong</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad8289e0000014e4da9a73215a6959f&amp;docguid=IC85CA22819F043E9B03DE4B95A542A04&amp;hitguid=IC85CA22819F043E9B03DE4B95A542A04&amp;spos=40&amp;epos=40&amp;td=3695&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=29\">[2015] 2 HKLRD 802</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal [2015] 2 HKLRD 802<br />\n	Civil Appeal Nos. 20 &amp; 78 of 2014<br />\n	Lam V-P, Barma and McWalters JJA<br />\n	2 April 2015</p>\n<p>\n	H and W, who were formerly married and joint tenants of a Home Ownership Scheme property, instructed S, a principal partner of a solicitor’s firm, to transfer the property to H’s sole name. The Housing Authority (the “HA”) granted approval in principle conditional on inter alia it approving the draft assignment. H and W signed the draft assignment, which S had explained would probably be amended by the HA. H subsequently died, but S did not inform the HA of this. When the HA returned the draft assignment with extensive amendments and required the assignee to endorse his agreement to the conditions imposed, S replaced pages in the copy of the draft assignment signed by the parties except the signature page and the backsheet. S left the date unchanged and registered that version, together with the HA’s letter imposing conditions endorsed by H’s father and sole executor of his estate (“F”), at the Land Registry. F, believing that under the assignment he had inherited the property from H, paid off the mortgage but could not sell the property due to the defect in the assignment. The Solicitors Disciplinary Tribunal (the “Tribunal”) found S in breach of Principle 6.01 of the Hong Kong Solicitors’ Guide to Professional Conduct (the duty to act competently) and r. 2(a), (c) and (e) of the Solicitors’ Practice Rules (Cap. 159H, Sub. Leg.) and fined him $40,000 (the “1st Complaint”). The Tribunal also found that S had concealed or failed to disclose to the Hong Kong Solicitors Indemnity Fund Ltd that as part of a proposed settlement, he would obtain a personal interest in the property; and imposed a fine of $80,000 (the “2nd Complaint”). S abandoned his appeal against the finding of guilt under the 1st Complaint, but in CACV 20/2014, appealed against the finding of guilt under the 2nd Complaint. The Law Society, in CACV 78/2014, appealed against the penalty under the 1st Complaint (the “Penalty”), submitting that the proper sentence was the striking off or suspension of S.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, allowing the appeal by the Law Society on the 1st Complaint by setting aside the Penalty and making an order of suspension from practice for 2 years against S, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		There was room for flexibility in the circumstances under which a striking off penalty was appropriate and they should not be straitjacketed to cases involving dishonesty. Hence, in an appropriate case of a solicitor being found to have fallen below the required standards of integrity, probity and trustworthiness, the Tribunal could impose a penalty of striking off.</li>\n<li>\n		However, while the Penalty was clearly wrong, it was not appropriate to order a striking off. The appropriate penalty was a suspension for 2 years with the condition that when S resumed practice, he was prohibited from practising as a sole proprietor or partner or manager of a solicitor’s firm until the Law Society was satisfied he was fit to do so.</li>\n<li>\n		S’s conduct constituted a gross dereliction of his duty to the HA and gross incompetence. Even though there was no dishonesty on S’s part and he did not derive any personal benefit from the transaction, it was still a very serious matter for a solicitor to swap pages in a conveyancing document and then have it registered in the Land Registry creating a false impression in a public registry as to F’s title to the property. It was a serious breach of the public’s trust in S. This was not a victimless infraction. F had suffered financial losses and he and W had to litigate to resolve the problem as to title. Substantial public resources also had been incurred as a result of S’s wrongdoing.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:211:\"<p>Disciplinary proceedings – striking off not limited to cases involving dishonesty – could be imposed in appropriate cases of falling below required standards of integrity, probity and trustworthiness</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:36:\"Solicitor v Law Society of Hong Kong\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:36:\"Solicitor v Law Society of Hong Kong\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"113\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-07-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:237:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad8289e0000014e4da9a73215a6959f&docguid=IC85CA22819F043E9B03DE4B95A542A04&hitguid=IC85CA22819F043E9B03DE4B95A542A04&spos=40&epos=40&td=3695&crumb-action=append&context=29\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 2 HKLRD 802\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"2 April 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"2 April 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"Legal Profession\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"Legal Profession\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:36:\"Solicitor v Law Society of Hong Kong\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1435881600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8742','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8742\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:74:\"Re China Metal Recycling (Holdings) Ltd (Private examination under s. 221)\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8742\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1436140800\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8742\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3316:\"Liquidation – private examination of officer of company pursuant to s.221 – whether jurisdiction to order examination in relation to subsidiaries of company – whether reasonable to order examination in relation to subsidiaries of company<p>\n	Re China Metal Recycling (Holdings) Ltd (Private examination under s. 221)</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad629030000014e616558dcb6ee7c51&amp;docguid=I93E1D99238424032B4592759E55BFD1F&amp;hitguid=I93E1D99238424032B4592759E55BFD1F&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] 2 HKLRD 747</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Companies Winding-Up Proceedings No. 210 of 2013<br />\n	Godfrey Lam J in Chambers<br />\n	25 June 2014</p>\n<p>\n	Ls were appointed the provisional liquidators of C, a listed company; and were empowered to take control of all of its subsidiaries (the &ldquo;Group&rdquo;), including those in mainland China which carried out C&rsquo;s scrap metal recycling business (the &ldquo;Mainland Subsidiaries&rdquo;). X was the founder, Chairman, CEO and majority shareholder of C. Following an investigation, the Securities and Futures Commission (the &ldquo;SFC&rdquo;) reported that C had deceived the market by substantially overstating its profits and trading in C&rsquo;s shares were suspended. The SFC presented a winding-up petition against C alleging fraud and dishonesty by its senior management, based on records of fictitious transactions, forged documents and a round robin of funds. Ls also caused an action to be brought in the name of C and a Macau subsidiary against X and other defendants based largely on the petition, for, <em>inter alia</em>, fraudulent breach of duties (the &ldquo;Action&rdquo;). Despite numerous requests, Ls could not obtain sufficient information from X about, or gain any meaningful access to and control over, the Mainland Subsidiaries. Ls therefore sought an order under s.221 of the Companies (Winding Up and Miscellaneous Provisions) Ordinance (Cap. 32) that X be examined on oath concerning &ldquo;the promotion, formation, trade, dealings, affairs or property of the Group &hellip; and its associated companies for the purpose of identifying and preserving the assets of the Group&rdquo; and also for understanding and stabilising their businesses and operations.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, granting the application, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		There was jurisdiction to order private examination relating to C&rsquo;s subsidiaries. Under s.221 of Ordinance, information concerning the company&rsquo;s &ldquo;dealings&rdquo; or &ldquo;affairs&rdquo; was wide enough, in an appropriate case, to include information concerning the activities of a subsidiary. Ls had a duty to preserve the assets of C and, given the business reality of the Group, also to be informed about the assets of the Mainland Subsidiaries and, where necessary, to take steps to protect them.</li>\n	<li>\n		Ls had been unable to become the directors or legal representatives of the Mainland Subsidiaries. They remained strangers to the Group and needed the assistance of X, who played a key role in the Group&rsquo;s management. An oral examination was therefore reasonably required to enable Ls to carry out their functions.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:243:\"Liquidation – private examination of officer of company pursuant to s.221 – whether jurisdiction to order examination in relation to subsidiaries of company – whether reasonable to order examination in relation to subsidiaries of company\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3239:\"<p>Liquidation – private examination of officer of company pursuant to s.221 – whether jurisdiction to order examination in relation to subsidiaries of company – whether reasonable to order examination in relation to subsidiaries of company\n</p><p>\n	Re China Metal Recycling (Holdings) Ltd (Private examination under s. 221)</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad629030000014e616558dcb6ee7c51&amp;docguid=I93E1D99238424032B4592759E55BFD1F&amp;hitguid=I93E1D99238424032B4592759E55BFD1F&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] 2 HKLRD 747</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Companies Winding-Up Proceedings No. 210 of 2013<br />\n	Godfrey Lam J in Chambers<br />\n	25 June 2014</p>\n<p>\n	Ls were appointed the provisional liquidators of C, a listed company; and were empowered to take control of all of its subsidiaries (the “Group”), including those in mainland China which carried out C’s scrap metal recycling business (the “Mainland Subsidiaries”). X was the founder, Chairman, CEO and majority shareholder of C. Following an investigation, the Securities and Futures Commission (the “SFC”) reported that C had deceived the market by substantially overstating its profits and trading in C’s shares were suspended. The SFC presented a winding-up petition against C alleging fraud and dishonesty by its senior management, based on records of fictitious transactions, forged documents and a round robin of funds. Ls also caused an action to be brought in the name of C and a Macau subsidiary against X and other defendants based largely on the petition, for, <em>inter alia</em>, fraudulent breach of duties (the “Action”). Despite numerous requests, Ls could not obtain sufficient information from X about, or gain any meaningful access to and control over, the Mainland Subsidiaries. Ls therefore sought an order under s.221 of the Companies (Winding Up and Miscellaneous Provisions) Ordinance (Cap. 32) that X be examined on oath concerning “the promotion, formation, trade, dealings, affairs or property of the Group … and its associated companies for the purpose of identifying and preserving the assets of the Group” and also for understanding and stabilising their businesses and operations.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, granting the application, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		There was jurisdiction to order private examination relating to C’s subsidiaries. Under s.221 of Ordinance, information concerning the company’s “dealings” or “affairs” was wide enough, in an appropriate case, to include information concerning the activities of a subsidiary. Ls had a duty to preserve the assets of C and, given the business reality of the Group, also to be informed about the assets of the Mainland Subsidiaries and, where necessary, to take steps to protect them.</li>\n<li>\n		Ls had been unable to become the directors or legal representatives of the Mainland Subsidiaries. They remained strangers to the Group and needed the assistance of X, who played a key role in the Group’s management. An oral examination was therefore reasonably required to enable Ls to carry out their functions.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:251:\"<p>Liquidation – private examination of officer of company pursuant to s.221 – whether jurisdiction to order examination in relation to subsidiaries of company – whether reasonable to order examination in relation to subsidiaries of company</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:74:\"Re China Metal Recycling (Holdings) Ltd (Private examination under s. 221)\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:74:\"Re China Metal Recycling (Holdings) Ltd (Private examination under s. 221)\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:2:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"100\";}i:1;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-07-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:231:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad629030000014e616558dcb6ee7c51&docguid=I93E1D99238424032B4592759E55BFD1F&hitguid=I93E1D99238424032B4592759E55BFD1F&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=4\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 2 HKLRD 747\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"25 June 2014\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"25 June 2014\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:11:\"Company Law\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:11:\"Company Law\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:74:\"Re China Metal Recycling (Holdings) Ltd (Private examination under s. 221)\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1436140800\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8744','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8744\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:43:\"Lenovo (Beijing) Ltd v Lenovo (Beijing) Ltd\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8744\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1436832000\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8744\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:5252:\"Intellectual Property – ICANN Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (“UDRP”) – A party’s readiness to abandon a domain name would lead to Panel’s inference that it has no rights or legitimate interests – Passive holding of domain name comprising a trademark may constitute bad faith usage<p>\n	Lenovo (Beijing) Ltd v Lenovo (Beijing) Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500731_Decision.pdf\">HK-1500731</a> &quot;lenovo.biz&quot;<br />\n	Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)<br />\n	Assen Alexiev (Panelist)<br />\n	18 May 2015</p>\n<p>\n	Complainant (hereinafter &ldquo;C&rdquo;) was the holder of a number of trademarks incorporating the mark of &ldquo;Lenovo&rdquo; (the &ldquo;Mark&rdquo;). Respondent (hereinafter &ldquo;R&rdquo;) was an individual domiciled in the Russian Federation who registered the domain name <lenovo.biz>(the &ldquo;Disputed Domain Name&rdquo;).</lenovo.biz></p>\n<p>\n	<lenovo.biz>\n	<p>\n		On 26 March 2014, C filed an UDRP complaint against R with the Hong Kong Office of the Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (the &ldquo;ADNDRC&rdquo;), seeking transfer of the Disputed Domain Name based on the elements specified below:-</p>\n	<ul>\n		<li>\n			C had spent substantial time and effort for advertising and promotion of the Mark throughout the world and was the largest personal computer vendor by unit sales in 2014. C further claimed that the Disputed Domain Name was highly similar to its domain name <lenovo.com>and registered trademark (the &ldquo;Trademark&rdquo;) which had been registered in multiple jurisdictions including the Russian Federation, being the domicile of R.</lenovo.com></li>\n		<li>\n			the Mark was a word created by C and had no literature meaning to it. R was not affiliated or authorised in any way with C to use the Trademark and R had no fair reason to use the Mark as the distinguishing part of the Disputed Domain Name.</li>\n		<li>\n			the Disputed Domain Name was not in use. R&rsquo;s passive holding of the Disputed Domain Name with the knowledge of C and C&rsquo;s Trademarks and without having rights or legitimate interests in it constituted bad faith. C asserted that R&rsquo;s purpose of cybersquatting the Disputed Domain Name was to obtain improper profits.</li>\n	</ul>\n	<lenovo.com>\n	<p>\n		R did not file a formal Response using the designated response form, but sent an email to the ADNDRC within the required period of time for the Response, primarily asserting that:</p>\n	<ul>\n		<li>\n			The Disputed Domain Name was available for registration and could be registered by anyone.</li>\n		<li>\n			The Disputed Domain Name was a common word in several languages. R registered the Disputed Domain Name for non-commercial purpose and the registration was not a violation.</li>\n		<li>\n			R did not know that the Mark was a registered trademark and had spent resources for the development of a non-commercial website.</li>\n	</ul>\n	<p>\n		Nonetheless, R also indicated his readiness to transfer the Disputed Domain Name to C.</p>\n	<p>\n		<strong>Held</strong>, granting the remedy sought, that:</p>\n	<p>\n		The Panel was not persuaded by R that the Mark was a dictionary word. Conversely, the Panel found that the Mark was a fancy word with a high level of inherent distinctiveness which consumers associated exclusively with C, and it was identical to the Disputed Domain Name.</p>\n	<p>\n		The Panel did not accept R&rsquo;s argument that the Disputed Domain Name was available for registration and could be registered by anyone. As evident from the provision of the UDRP, the mere availability of a domain name for registration does not per se mean that it could be registered by anyone disregard of or in violation of the rights of third parties. In this case, the Trademark had been officially published in the Russian Federation, the domicile of R, and any person could check its status by accessing the official public database of the Russian Federal Institute of Industrial Property. Furthermore, R&lsquo;s readiness to transfer the Disputed Domain Name to C lead the Panel to infer that R implicitly accepted that it had no rights or legitimate interests in respect of the Disputed Domain Name.</p>\n	<p>\n		The Panel again did not accept R&rsquo;s contention that even though it was not using the Disputed Domain Name, it had already started preparations to set up a non-commercial website under the Disputed Domain Name, for which R did not provide any details or evidence. Referring to <em>Telstra Corp. Ltd v Nuclear Marshmallows</em>, WIPO Case No. D2000-0003, the Panel was of the same view as other UDRP panels that the apparent lack of so-called active use of a domain name without any active attempt to sell or to contact the trademark holder does not as such prevent a finding of bad faith.</p>\n	<p>\n		In accordance with para. 4(i) of the UDRP, the Panel granted the relief sought by ordering the transfer of the Disputed Domain Name to C.</p>\n	<hr />\n	<p>\n		The full decision can be downloaded in the website of ADNDRC at <a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500731_Decision.pdf\">http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500731_Decision.pdf</a>.</p>\n	</lenovo.com></lenovo.biz></p>\";s:7:\"summary\";s:310:\"Intellectual Property – ICANN Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (“UDRP”) – A party’s readiness to abandon a domain name would lead to Panel’s inference that it has no rights or legitimate interests – Passive holding of domain name comprising a trademark may constitute bad faith usage\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:5154:\"<p>Intellectual Property – ICANN Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (“UDRP”) – A party’s readiness to abandon a domain name would lead to Panel’s inference that it has no rights or legitimate interests – Passive holding of domain name comprising a trademark may constitute bad faith usage\n</p><p>\n	Lenovo (Beijing) Ltd v Lenovo (Beijing) Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500731_Decision.pdf\">HK-1500731</a> \"lenovo.biz\"<br />\n	Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)<br />\n	Assen Alexiev (Panelist)<br />\n	18 May 2015</p>\n<p>\n	Complainant (hereinafter “C”) was the holder of a number of trademarks incorporating the mark of “Lenovo” (the “Mark”). Respondent (hereinafter “R”) was an individual domiciled in the Russian Federation who registered the domain name <lenovo.biz>(the “Disputed Domain Name”).</lenovo.biz></p>\n<p>\n	<lenovo.biz></lenovo.biz></p>\n<p>\n		On 26 March 2014, C filed an UDRP complaint against R with the Hong Kong Office of the Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (the “ADNDRC”), seeking transfer of the Disputed Domain Name based on the elements specified below:-</p>\n<ul><li>\n			C had spent substantial time and effort for advertising and promotion of the Mark throughout the world and was the largest personal computer vendor by unit sales in 2014. C further claimed that the Disputed Domain Name was highly similar to its domain name <lenovo.com>and registered trademark (the “Trademark”) which had been registered in multiple jurisdictions including the Russian Federation, being the domicile of R.</lenovo.com></li>\n<li>\n			the Mark was a word created by C and had no literature meaning to it. R was not affiliated or authorised in any way with C to use the Trademark and R had no fair reason to use the Mark as the distinguishing part of the Disputed Domain Name.</li>\n<li>\n			the Disputed Domain Name was not in use. R’s passive holding of the Disputed Domain Name with the knowledge of C and C’s Trademarks and without having rights or legitimate interests in it constituted bad faith. C asserted that R’s purpose of cybersquatting the Disputed Domain Name was to obtain improper profits.</li>\n</ul><p>	<lenovo.com></lenovo.com></p>\n<p>\n		R did not file a formal Response using the designated response form, but sent an email to the ADNDRC within the required period of time for the Response, primarily asserting that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n			The Disputed Domain Name was available for registration and could be registered by anyone.</li>\n<li>\n			The Disputed Domain Name was a common word in several languages. R registered the Disputed Domain Name for non-commercial purpose and the registration was not a violation.</li>\n<li>\n			R did not know that the Mark was a registered trademark and had spent resources for the development of a non-commercial website.</li>\n</ul><p>\n		Nonetheless, R also indicated his readiness to transfer the Disputed Domain Name to C.</p>\n<p>\n		<strong>Held</strong>, granting the remedy sought, that:</p>\n<p>\n		The Panel was not persuaded by R that the Mark was a dictionary word. Conversely, the Panel found that the Mark was a fancy word with a high level of inherent distinctiveness which consumers associated exclusively with C, and it was identical to the Disputed Domain Name.</p>\n<p>\n		The Panel did not accept R’s argument that the Disputed Domain Name was available for registration and could be registered by anyone. As evident from the provision of the UDRP, the mere availability of a domain name for registration does not per se mean that it could be registered by anyone disregard of or in violation of the rights of third parties. In this case, the Trademark had been officially published in the Russian Federation, the domicile of R, and any person could check its status by accessing the official public database of the Russian Federal Institute of Industrial Property. Furthermore, R‘s readiness to transfer the Disputed Domain Name to C lead the Panel to infer that R implicitly accepted that it had no rights or legitimate interests in respect of the Disputed Domain Name.</p>\n<p>\n		The Panel again did not accept R’s contention that even though it was not using the Disputed Domain Name, it had already started preparations to set up a non-commercial website under the Disputed Domain Name, for which R did not provide any details or evidence. Referring to <em>Telstra Corp. Ltd v Nuclear Marshmallows</em>, WIPO Case No. D2000-0003, the Panel was of the same view as other UDRP panels that the apparent lack of so-called active use of a domain name without any active attempt to sell or to contact the trademark holder does not as such prevent a finding of bad faith.</p>\n<p>\n		In accordance with para. 4(i) of the UDRP, the Panel granted the relief sought by ordering the transfer of the Disputed Domain Name to C.</p>\n<hr /><p>\n		The full decision can be downloaded in the website of ADNDRC at <a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500731_Decision.pdf\">http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500731_Decision.pdf</a>.</p>\n<p>	</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:318:\"<p>Intellectual Property – ICANN Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (“UDRP”) – A party’s readiness to abandon a domain name would lead to Panel’s inference that it has no rights or legitimate interests – Passive holding of domain name comprising a trademark may constitute bad faith usage</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:62:\"Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:62:\"Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:43:\"Lenovo (Beijing) Ltd v Lenovo (Beijing) Ltd\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:43:\"Lenovo (Beijing) Ltd v Lenovo (Beijing) Ltd\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-07-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:63:\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500731_Decision.pdf\";s:5:\"title\";s:10:\"HK-1500731\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:11:\"18 May 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:11:\"18 May 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"Dispute Resolution\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"Dispute Resolution\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:43:\"Lenovo (Beijing) Ltd v Lenovo (Beijing) Ltd\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1436832000\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8746','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8746\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:44:\"Envato Pty Ltd (‘Envato’) v James Smith.\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8746\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1438732800\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8746\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:4916:\"Intellectual Property – ICANN Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (“UDRP”) – Treatment of administratively late and deficient response – Inaction is within the concept of bad faith – A party readiness to sell the disputed domain name for large amount demonstrates that the Respondent considers the Disputed Domain Name to have significant monetary value which, in turn, is not only testament to the Complainant’s reputation in the trade mark, but also serves to demonstrate that the Respondent was aware of the Complainant’s reputation in the trade mark<p>\n	Envato Pty Ltd (&lsquo;Envato&rsquo;) v James Smith</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500752_Decision.pdf\">HK &ndash; 1500752 </a>&quot;envatostudio.com&quot;<br />\n	Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)<br />\n	Julien Chaisse (Panelist)<br />\n	17 June 2015</p>\n<p>\n	<envatostudio.com>\n	<p>\n		On 20 April 2015, Complainant (hereinafter &ldquo;C&rdquo;) submitted a complaint concerning the domain name (hereinafter &ldquo;Disputed Domain Name&rdquo;) to Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (the &ldquo;Centre&rdquo;) in accordance with the Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (the &ldquo;Policy&rdquo;) adopted by the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (&ldquo;ICANN&rdquo;) on 26 August 1999. The Respondent (hereinafter &ldquo;R&rdquo;) was the registrant of the Disputed Domain Name.</p>\n	<p>\n		In its email of 21 May 2015 to the Centre and in the Complainant, R asserted ownership of the disputed domain name. However, R failed to respond within the required period of time and its Response was deficient. Therefore, an important issue was whether the Panel had to consider the administratively late and deficient Response before dealing with the substantive issues.</p>\n	<p>\n		For late response, referring to the previous UDRP decisions in Young Genius Software AB v MWD, James Vargas (Case No. D2000-0591), the Panel agreed with that the lateness of R&rsquo;s response was de minimis and had not prejudiced the C nor had it delayed the Decision in this Administrative Proceeding. The Panel therefore admitted and considered the submission set out in the Response.</p>\n	<p>\n		For deficient response, referring to the Rule 5(b)(viii) and WIPO&rsquo;s UDRP decision in Talk City, Inc. v Robertson (Case No. D2000-0009), the Panel declined to treat it as a response because, among other things, the email did not contain the requisite certification that the information contained therein is, &ldquo;to the best of R&rsquo;s knowledge, complete and accurate&rdquo;. Accordingly, the Panel decided to draw such inferences from the R&rsquo;s failure to comply with the Rules as it considered appropriate.</p>\n	<p>\n		C submitted that it had proved that the Disputed Domain Name is identical and/or confusingly similar to its registered trade marks in which C had rights or interests for the purposes of para. 4(a)(i) of the Policy.</p>\n	<p>\n		Furthermore, C contended that R had no rights or legitimate interests in the disputed domain name pursuant to paras. 4(a) (ii) and 4(c) of the Policy.</p>\n	<p>\n		At last, C contended that R registered and was using the disputed domain name in bad faith under para. 4(a) (iii) of the Policy.</p>\n	<p>\n		As the Centre did not receive a response from R for the disputed domain name but an email dated 21 May 2015, R was in default.</p>\n	<p>\n		<strong>Held</strong>, granting the remedy sought, that:</p>\n	<ul>\n		<li>\n			First, the Panel found that the disputed domain name is confusingly similar to a trade mark in which C has rights, because referring to Rohde &amp; Schwarz GmbH &amp; Co. HG v Pertshire Marketing, Ltd (Case No. D2006-0762), the domain extension should be disregarded in making an enquiry as to whether a trade mark is identical or confusingly similar to a domain name.</li>\n		<li>\n			Second, the Panel found that R was not using the name on either a non-commercial or fair use basis without intent to misleadingly divert consumers or tarnish any of the C&rsquo;s marks, or, prior to receiving notice of this dispute, in connecting with any bona fide offering of goods or services or demonstrate preparations for making such an offering, thus failing to qualify under either of paras. 4(c) (i) and 4(c) (iii) of the Policy.</li>\n		<li>\n			Finally, after examining the examples in para. 4(b), the Panel found that the registration and use of domain name constituted bad faith.</li>\n	</ul>\n	<p>\n		On this basis, the Panel ordered the disputed domain name be transferred to C.</p>\n	<hr />\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;The full decision can be downloaded in the website of ADNDRC at <a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500752_Decision.pdf\">http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500752_Decision.pdf</a>.&nbsp;</p>\n	</envatostudio.com></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\";s:7:\"summary\";s:579:\"Intellectual Property – ICANN Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (“UDRP”) – Treatment of administratively late and deficient response – Inaction is within the concept of bad faith – A party readiness to sell the disputed domain name for large amount demonstrates that the Respondent considers the Disputed Domain Name to have significant monetary value which, in turn, is not only testament to the Complainant’s reputation in the trade mark, but also serves to demonstrate that the Respondent was aware of the Complainant’s reputation in the trade mark\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:4791:\"<p>Intellectual Property – ICANN Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (“UDRP”) – Treatment of administratively late and deficient response – Inaction is within the concept of bad faith – A party readiness to sell the disputed domain name for large amount demonstrates that the Respondent considers the Disputed Domain Name to have significant monetary value which, in turn, is not only testament to the Complainant’s reputation in the trade mark, but also serves to demonstrate that the Respondent was aware of the Complainant’s reputation in the trade mark\n</p><p>\n	Envato Pty Ltd (‘Envato’) v James Smith</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500752_Decision.pdf\">HK – 1500752 </a>\"envatostudio.com\"<br />\n	Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)<br />\n	Julien Chaisse (Panelist)<br />\n	17 June 2015</p>\n<p>\n	<envatostudio.com></envatostudio.com></p>\n<p>\n		On 20 April 2015, Complainant (hereinafter “C”) submitted a complaint concerning the domain name (hereinafter “Disputed Domain Name”) to Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (the “Centre”) in accordance with the Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (the “Policy”) adopted by the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (“ICANN”) on 26 August 1999. The Respondent (hereinafter “R”) was the registrant of the Disputed Domain Name.</p>\n<p>\n		In its email of 21 May 2015 to the Centre and in the Complainant, R asserted ownership of the disputed domain name. However, R failed to respond within the required period of time and its Response was deficient. Therefore, an important issue was whether the Panel had to consider the administratively late and deficient Response before dealing with the substantive issues.</p>\n<p>\n		For late response, referring to the previous UDRP decisions in Young Genius Software AB v MWD, James Vargas (Case No. D2000-0591), the Panel agreed with that the lateness of R’s response was de minimis and had not prejudiced the C nor had it delayed the Decision in this Administrative Proceeding. The Panel therefore admitted and considered the submission set out in the Response.</p>\n<p>\n		For deficient response, referring to the Rule 5(b)(viii) and WIPO’s UDRP decision in Talk City, Inc. v Robertson (Case No. D2000-0009), the Panel declined to treat it as a response because, among other things, the email did not contain the requisite certification that the information contained therein is, “to the best of R’s knowledge, complete and accurate”. Accordingly, the Panel decided to draw such inferences from the R’s failure to comply with the Rules as it considered appropriate.</p>\n<p>\n		C submitted that it had proved that the Disputed Domain Name is identical and/or confusingly similar to its registered trade marks in which C had rights or interests for the purposes of para. 4(a)(i) of the Policy.</p>\n<p>\n		Furthermore, C contended that R had no rights or legitimate interests in the disputed domain name pursuant to paras. 4(a) (ii) and 4(c) of the Policy.</p>\n<p>\n		At last, C contended that R registered and was using the disputed domain name in bad faith under para. 4(a) (iii) of the Policy.</p>\n<p>\n		As the Centre did not receive a response from R for the disputed domain name but an email dated 21 May 2015, R was in default.</p>\n<p>\n		<strong>Held</strong>, granting the remedy sought, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n			First, the Panel found that the disputed domain name is confusingly similar to a trade mark in which C has rights, because referring to Rohde &amp; Schwarz GmbH &amp; Co. HG v Pertshire Marketing, Ltd (Case No. D2006-0762), the domain extension should be disregarded in making an enquiry as to whether a trade mark is identical or confusingly similar to a domain name.</li>\n<li>\n			Second, the Panel found that R was not using the name on either a non-commercial or fair use basis without intent to misleadingly divert consumers or tarnish any of the C’s marks, or, prior to receiving notice of this dispute, in connecting with any bona fide offering of goods or services or demonstrate preparations for making such an offering, thus failing to qualify under either of paras. 4(c) (i) and 4(c) (iii) of the Policy.</li>\n<li>\n			Finally, after examining the examples in para. 4(b), the Panel found that the registration and use of domain name constituted bad faith.</li>\n</ul><p>\n		On this basis, the Panel ordered the disputed domain name be transferred to C.</p>\n<hr /><p>\n		 The full decision can be downloaded in the website of ADNDRC at <a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500752_Decision.pdf\">http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500752_Decision.pdf</a>. </p>\n<p>	</p>\n<p>\n	 </p>\n<p>\n	 </p>\n<p>\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:587:\"<p>Intellectual Property – ICANN Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (“UDRP”) – Treatment of administratively late and deficient response – Inaction is within the concept of bad faith – A party readiness to sell the disputed domain name for large amount demonstrates that the Respondent considers the Disputed Domain Name to have significant monetary value which, in turn, is not only testament to the Complainant’s reputation in the trade mark, but also serves to demonstrate that the Respondent was aware of the Complainant’s reputation in the trade mark</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:62:\"Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:62:\"Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:44:\"Envato Pty Ltd (‘Envato’) v James Smith.\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:44:\"Envato Pty Ltd (‘Envato’) v James Smith.\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-08-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:63:\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500752_Decision.pdf\";s:5:\"title\";s:14:\"HK – 1500752\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"17 June 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"17 June 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"Dispute Resolution\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"Dispute Resolution\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:44:\"Envato Pty Ltd (‘Envato’) v James Smith.\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1438732800\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8748','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8748\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:13:\"The Ruby Star\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8748\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1438819200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8748\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:1857:\"Action in rem – order of priorities – plaintiff held only judgment obtained against vessel – no reason justifying departure from prima facie order of priorities<p>\n	The Ruby Star</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad629030000014ee2faf580b0b3cdf5&amp;docguid=I9683B7E41C1C430D94917E3ED8E6C99F&amp;hitguid=I9683B7E41C1C430D94917E3ED8E6C99F&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=9&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=7\">[2015] 3 HKLRD 81 </a><br />\n	Court of First Instance <br />\n	Admiralty Action No. 129 of 2013<br />\n	Queeny Au-Yeung J<br />\n	30 April 2015</p>\n<p>\n	P held the only judgment against a vessel and her proceeds of sale (the &quot;Proceeds&quot;). The bailiff&rsquo;s fees and expenses had already been paid out from the Proceeds. P&rsquo;s costs for arrest, preservation and sale <em>pendente lite</em> and its party-and-party costs in respect of arrest and sale <em>pendente lite</em> had been agreed. P sought orders that it have first priority against the remaining Proceeds held by the Court with interest.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, granting the application, there was no reason why the Court should depart from the <em>prima facie</em> order of priorities, ie, (a) the court&rsquo;s bailiff fees for the arrest, preservation and sale of the vessel; (b) the expenses of arrest, preservation and sale <em>pendente lite</em>; (c) the costs of the arresting party; (d) maritime liens attached to the ship, not the sister ship, to which the claim arose; (e) secured maritime claims; and (f) unsecured maritime claims. The judgment sum exceeded the Proceeds. P should be paid their entire remainder together with interest thereon in satisfaction of P&rsquo;s party-and-party costs of the arrest and sale <em>pendente lite</em> and in partial satisfaction of P&rsquo;s judgment.</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:166:\"Action in rem – order of priorities – plaintiff held only judgment obtained against vessel – no reason justifying departure from prima facie order of priorities\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:1835:\"<p>Action in rem – order of priorities – plaintiff held only judgment obtained against vessel – no reason justifying departure from prima facie order of priorities\n</p><p>\n	The Ruby Star</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad629030000014ee2faf580b0b3cdf5&amp;docguid=I9683B7E41C1C430D94917E3ED8E6C99F&amp;hitguid=I9683B7E41C1C430D94917E3ED8E6C99F&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=9&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=7\">[2015] 3 HKLRD 81 </a><br />\n	Court of First Instance <br />\n	Admiralty Action No. 129 of 2013<br />\n	Queeny Au-Yeung J<br />\n	30 April 2015</p>\n<p>\n	P held the only judgment against a vessel and her proceeds of sale (the \"Proceeds\"). The bailiff’s fees and expenses had already been paid out from the Proceeds. P’s costs for arrest, preservation and sale <em>pendente lite</em> and its party-and-party costs in respect of arrest and sale <em>pendente lite</em> had been agreed. P sought orders that it have first priority against the remaining Proceeds held by the Court with interest.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, granting the application, there was no reason why the Court should depart from the <em>prima facie</em> order of priorities, ie, (a) the court’s bailiff fees for the arrest, preservation and sale of the vessel; (b) the expenses of arrest, preservation and sale <em>pendente lite</em>; (c) the costs of the arresting party; (d) maritime liens attached to the ship, not the sister ship, to which the claim arose; (e) secured maritime claims; and (f) unsecured maritime claims. The judgment sum exceeded the Proceeds. P should be paid their entire remainder together with interest thereon in satisfaction of P’s party-and-party costs of the arrest and sale <em>pendente lite</em> and in partial satisfaction of P’s judgment.</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:174:\"<p>Action in rem – order of priorities – plaintiff held only judgment obtained against vessel – no reason justifying departure from prima facie order of priorities</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:13:\"The Ruby Star\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:13:\"The Ruby Star\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:2:\"94\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-08-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:231:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad629030000014ee2faf580b0b3cdf5&docguid=I9683B7E41C1C430D94917E3ED8E6C99F&hitguid=I9683B7E41C1C430D94917E3ED8E6C99F&spos=1&epos=1&td=9&crumb-action=append&context=7\";s:5:\"title\";s:17:\"[2015] 3 HKLRD 81\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:13:\"30 April 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:13:\"30 April 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:9:\"Admiralty\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:9:\"Admiralty\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:13:\"The Ruby Star\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1438819200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8750','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8750\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:67:\"Man Hing Medical Suppliers (International) Ltd v Director of Health\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8750\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1438819200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8750\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3620:\"Decision ultra vires – Director of Health had no implied power under Chinese Medicine Ordinance (Cap. 549) to order recall of such products<p>\n	Man Hing Medical Suppliers (International) Ltd v Director of Health</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744c09a0000014ed8b47466413019cc&amp;docguid=I9B9EF004F54E47E2A1F64A5E7E6F7049&amp;hitguid=I9B9EF004F54E47E2A1F64A5E7E6F7049&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=3&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=7\">[2015] 3 HKLRD 890</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Constitutional and Administrative Law List No 62 of 2014<br />\n	Thomas Au J<br />\n	21 May 2015</p>\n<p>\n	X was a licensed wholesaler of proprietary Chinese medicine (&ldquo;pCm&rdquo;) which sold two moisturising throat products as &ldquo;candies&rdquo; (the &ldquo;Products&rdquo;). Following a complaint, the Department of Health (the &ldquo;DH&rdquo;) obtained samples from various shops and made a preliminary assessment that there was reasonable cause to suspect that the Products were unregistered pCm. DH&rsquo;s inspectors then visited X&rsquo;s premises. Although X&rsquo;s director claimed the Products were not pCm, the inspectors told him they were suspected to be unregistered pCm, seized them under s. 146(2)(f) of the Chinese Medicine Ordinance (Cap. 549) (the &ldquo;CMO&rdquo;) for investigation and instructed X to recall them from customers. Later the same day, the DH issued a public announcement about the Products entitled &ldquo;Recall of two unregistered [pCms]&rdquo;. X obtained leave to judicially review the Director&rsquo;s decisions to: (a) instruct X to recall the Products; (b) issue the public announcement insofar as it stated that X was ordered by the Director to recall the Products; and (c) refuse requests by X to revoke or suspend the instruction to recall (the &ldquo;Decisions&rdquo;). X argued that there was no express statutory power to recall the Products so that the Decisions were unlawful. The Director contended that an incidental power to recall a product which was reasonably suspected to be a pCm and was unregistered (the &ldquo;Suggested Power&rdquo;) should be implied under, <em>inter alia</em>, s. 146(2)(c) and/or (f) of the CMO which respectively empowered an inspector &ldquo;to seize, remove and detain any article &hellip; which appears &hellip; to be or contain evidence of an offence against this Ordinance.&rdquo;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, allowing the application, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		The power to recall could not be implied into s. 146(2)(c) and (f) of the CMO.</li>\n	<li>\n		The Suggested Power was not reasonably necessary for the effective exercise of the express power to seize, remove and detain under s. 146(2)(c) and (f), since the two powers related to acts of a distinctly different nature. It would be contrary to principle to imply such power merely because a recall would be more convenient and desirable than having inspectors go to every premises and outlet which sold the Products to confiscate them, particularly when there was no evidence that the power to seize and remove would not be effective without a power to recall. Further, in respect of s. 146(2)(f), there could not be any implied power to order the recall of products which were only suspected, not determined, to be pCm.</li>\n	<li>\n		Moreover, if the Suggested Power were to be implied under s. 146, any persons delaying or obstructing a recall would commit an offence under s. 146(3). It was not clear and obvious in the present context to imply such a power which entailed a penal element.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:141:\"Decision ultra vires – Director of Health had no implied power under Chinese Medicine Ordinance (Cap. 549) to order recall of such products\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3525:\"<p>Decision ultra vires – Director of Health had no implied power under Chinese Medicine Ordinance (Cap. 549) to order recall of such products\n</p><p>\n	Man Hing Medical Suppliers (International) Ltd v Director of Health</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744c09a0000014ed8b47466413019cc&amp;docguid=I9B9EF004F54E47E2A1F64A5E7E6F7049&amp;hitguid=I9B9EF004F54E47E2A1F64A5E7E6F7049&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=3&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=7\">[2015] 3 HKLRD 890</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Constitutional and Administrative Law List No 62 of 2014<br />\n	Thomas Au J<br />\n	21 May 2015</p>\n<p>\n	X was a licensed wholesaler of proprietary Chinese medicine (“pCm”) which sold two moisturising throat products as “candies” (the “Products”). Following a complaint, the Department of Health (the “DH”) obtained samples from various shops and made a preliminary assessment that there was reasonable cause to suspect that the Products were unregistered pCm. DH’s inspectors then visited X’s premises. Although X’s director claimed the Products were not pCm, the inspectors told him they were suspected to be unregistered pCm, seized them under s. 146(2)(f) of the Chinese Medicine Ordinance (Cap. 549) (the “CMO”) for investigation and instructed X to recall them from customers. Later the same day, the DH issued a public announcement about the Products entitled “Recall of two unregistered [pCms]”. X obtained leave to judicially review the Director’s decisions to: (a) instruct X to recall the Products; (b) issue the public announcement insofar as it stated that X was ordered by the Director to recall the Products; and (c) refuse requests by X to revoke or suspend the instruction to recall (the “Decisions”). X argued that there was no express statutory power to recall the Products so that the Decisions were unlawful. The Director contended that an incidental power to recall a product which was reasonably suspected to be a pCm and was unregistered (the “Suggested Power”) should be implied under, <em>inter alia</em>, s. 146(2)(c) and/or (f) of the CMO which respectively empowered an inspector “to seize, remove and detain any article … which appears … to be or contain evidence of an offence against this Ordinance.”</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, allowing the application, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		The power to recall could not be implied into s. 146(2)(c) and (f) of the CMO.</li>\n<li>\n		The Suggested Power was not reasonably necessary for the effective exercise of the express power to seize, remove and detain under s. 146(2)(c) and (f), since the two powers related to acts of a distinctly different nature. It would be contrary to principle to imply such power merely because a recall would be more convenient and desirable than having inspectors go to every premises and outlet which sold the Products to confiscate them, particularly when there was no evidence that the power to seize and remove would not be effective without a power to recall. Further, in respect of s. 146(2)(f), there could not be any implied power to order the recall of products which were only suspected, not determined, to be pCm.</li>\n<li>\n		Moreover, if the Suggested Power were to be implied under s. 146, any persons delaying or obstructing a recall would commit an offence under s. 146(3). It was not clear and obvious in the present context to imply such a power which entailed a penal element.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:149:\"<p>Decision ultra vires – Director of Health had no implied power under Chinese Medicine Ordinance (Cap. 549) to order recall of such products</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:67:\"Man Hing Medical Suppliers (International) Ltd v Director of Health\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:67:\"Man Hing Medical Suppliers (International) Ltd v Director of Health\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:2:\"93\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-08-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:231:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744c09a0000014ed8b47466413019cc&docguid=I9B9EF004F54E47E2A1F64A5E7E6F7049&hitguid=I9B9EF004F54E47E2A1F64A5E7E6F7049&spos=1&epos=1&td=3&crumb-action=append&context=7\";s:5:\"title\";s:15:\"[2015] HKEC 890\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:11:\"21 May 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:11:\"21 May 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"Administrative Law\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"Administrative Law\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:67:\"Man Hing Medical Suppliers (International) Ltd v Director of Health\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1438819200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8752','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8752\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:55:\"Hugo Boss Trademark v Britain Boss International Co Ltd\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8752\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1438819200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8752\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3456:\"Default judgment – setting aside – distinction between setting aside regular and irregular judgment<p>\n	Hugo Boss Trademark v Britain Boss International Co Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744c0970000014ed8b5a2c6863d781b&amp;docguid=I96A28C66681145D4A1BBCFEE1B6F2199&amp;hitguid=I96A28C66681145D4A1BBCFEE1B6F2199&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=2&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=10\">[2015] 3 HKLRD 4</a> <br />\n	High Court Action No. 2231 of 2013<br />\n	Zervos J in Chambers<br />\n	22 April 2015</p>\n<p>\n	P1&ndash;3 were members of a group of companies (the &ldquo;Group&rdquo;), which traded as a well-known global manufacturer and retailer of luxury clothing and accessories, operating primarily through its brand names and marks &ldquo;HUGO BOSS&rdquo; and &ldquo;BOSS&rdquo; (&ldquo;Ps&rsquo; marks&rdquo;), including in Hong Kong and mainland China. Ps&rsquo; marks were registered trademarks in Hong Kong. D1, &ldquo;BRITAIN BOSS INTERNATIONAL CO LTD&rdquo;, was a Hong Kong company controlled by D2. Ps brought this action against Ds for trademark infringement and passing off. Ps served the writ on both Ds at D1&rsquo;s registered office, which D2 had listed as her residential address in D1&rsquo;s annual returns, although she ordinarily resided in mainland China. The writ was sent to D2 by registered post and inserted into the letter box as her &ldquo;usual or last known address&rdquo; pursuant to O. 10 r. 1(2) of the Rules of the High Court (Cap. 4A, Sub.Leg.) (the &ldquo;RHC&rdquo;). D1&rsquo;s office was shared with an unrelated company owned by its secretary, L, who would forward documents addressed to Ds to D2. Some three months later, Ps obtained final judgment against Ds in default of defence, including a permanent injunction restraining Ds from infringing Ps&rsquo; marks and an order that D1 change its company name. Ds claimed that they only received notice of the action after the default judgment. Ds now applied to set aside the default judgment against D2 on the grounds that service of the writ was irregular.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, setting aside the judgment against D2, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		As a general proposition, irregular judgments should be set aside as of right, but the court retained a residual discretion to have regard to the conduct of the parties in determining whether to exercise such a right or not, or to impose terms upon the setting aside of the judgment. &ldquo;As of right&rdquo; meant without going into the actual merits of the defence and did not mean shutting one&rsquo;s eyes to the circumstances surrounding the issues of the case and why things went wrong.</li>\n	<li>\n		It was a fundamental principle that a writ of summons or its originating equivalent must be served on a defendant. While a key requirement was that a writ must be served personally on a defendant, O. 10 r. 1(2) of the RHC provides an alternative method of service to be effected on a defendant within the jurisdiction. Here, D2 was not within the jurisdiction at the time of service. On this basis, the service was irregular and so was the default judgment. Even though there was delay in making the setting aside application and D2&rsquo;s evidence was doubtful as to when she became aware of these proceedings, it was not enough for the Court to exercise its residual discretion to refuse to set aside the irregular judgment.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:103:\"Default judgment – setting aside – distinction between setting aside regular and irregular judgment\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3360:\"<p>Default judgment – setting aside – distinction between setting aside regular and irregular judgment\n</p><p>\n	Hugo Boss Trademark v Britain Boss International Co Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744c0970000014ed8b5a2c6863d781b&amp;docguid=I96A28C66681145D4A1BBCFEE1B6F2199&amp;hitguid=I96A28C66681145D4A1BBCFEE1B6F2199&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=2&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=10\">[2015] 3 HKLRD 4</a> <br />\n	High Court Action No. 2231 of 2013<br />\n	Zervos J in Chambers<br />\n	22 April 2015</p>\n<p>\n	P1–3 were members of a group of companies (the “Group”), which traded as a well-known global manufacturer and retailer of luxury clothing and accessories, operating primarily through its brand names and marks “HUGO BOSS” and “BOSS” (“Ps’ marks”), including in Hong Kong and mainland China. Ps’ marks were registered trademarks in Hong Kong. D1, “BRITAIN BOSS INTERNATIONAL CO LTD”, was a Hong Kong company controlled by D2. Ps brought this action against Ds for trademark infringement and passing off. Ps served the writ on both Ds at D1’s registered office, which D2 had listed as her residential address in D1’s annual returns, although she ordinarily resided in mainland China. The writ was sent to D2 by registered post and inserted into the letter box as her “usual or last known address” pursuant to O. 10 r. 1(2) of the Rules of the High Court (Cap. 4A, Sub.Leg.) (the “RHC”). D1’s office was shared with an unrelated company owned by its secretary, L, who would forward documents addressed to Ds to D2. Some three months later, Ps obtained final judgment against Ds in default of defence, including a permanent injunction restraining Ds from infringing Ps’ marks and an order that D1 change its company name. Ds claimed that they only received notice of the action after the default judgment. Ds now applied to set aside the default judgment against D2 on the grounds that service of the writ was irregular.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, setting aside the judgment against D2, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		As a general proposition, irregular judgments should be set aside as of right, but the court retained a residual discretion to have regard to the conduct of the parties in determining whether to exercise such a right or not, or to impose terms upon the setting aside of the judgment. “As of right” meant without going into the actual merits of the defence and did not mean shutting one’s eyes to the circumstances surrounding the issues of the case and why things went wrong.</li>\n<li>\n		It was a fundamental principle that a writ of summons or its originating equivalent must be served on a defendant. While a key requirement was that a writ must be served personally on a defendant, O. 10 r. 1(2) of the RHC provides an alternative method of service to be effected on a defendant within the jurisdiction. Here, D2 was not within the jurisdiction at the time of service. On this basis, the service was irregular and so was the default judgment. Even though there was delay in making the setting aside application and D2’s evidence was doubtful as to when she became aware of these proceedings, it was not enough for the Court to exercise its residual discretion to refuse to set aside the irregular judgment.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:111:\"<p>Default judgment – setting aside – distinction between setting aside regular and irregular judgment</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:10:\"High Court\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:10:\"High Court\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:55:\"Hugo Boss Trademark v Britain Boss International Co Ltd\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:55:\"Hugo Boss Trademark v Britain Boss International Co Ltd\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-08-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744c0970000014ed8b5a2c6863d781b&docguid=I96A28C66681145D4A1BBCFEE1B6F2199&hitguid=I96A28C66681145D4A1BBCFEE1B6F2199&spos=2&epos=2&td=2&crumb-action=append&context=10\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] 3 HKLRD 4\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:13:\"22 April 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:13:\"22 April 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:55:\"Hugo Boss Trademark v Britain Boss International Co Ltd\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1438819200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8754','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8754\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:28:\"Poon Ching Man v Lam Hoi Pun\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8754\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1438819200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8754\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3657:\"Judgment – perfection rule – court’s jurisdiction to revisit previously perfected order – power to be exercised for specific limited purposes only which did not violate principle of functus officio<p>\n	Poon Ching Man v Lam Hoi Pun</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad629030000014ed8b70b2a7460d12a&amp;docguid=I9C37C474CABB4183B5DA81BB32FE6601&amp;hitguid=I9C37C474CABB4183B5DA81BB32FE6601&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=5&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=13\">[2015] 3 HKLRD 57<br />\n	</a>District Court<br />\n	Personal Injuries Action No. 1585 of 2011<br />\n	Deputy Judge Winnie Tsui in Chambers<br />\n	22 April 2015</p>\n<p>\n	P&rsquo;s personal injuries action against D was dismissed with a costs order <em>nisi</em> made against P (the &ldquo;Order&rdquo;). After the Order became absolute pursuant to O. 42 r. 5B(3) of the Rules of the District Court (Cap. 336H, Sub. Leg.) (the &ldquo;RDC&rdquo;) and the judgment was then drawn up and sealed, P sought to vary the Order out of time. P argued that a new modern approach granted the Court a wide discretionary power under O. 3 r. 5 of the RDC to grant a retrospective extension of the 14-day time limit even after the judgment had been perfected so as to bring P&rsquo;s application to vary within time.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		There was no &ldquo;new modern approach&rdquo; under which the court enjoyed an unlimited power to revisit any previous order which had been perfected. Even where the court had jurisdiction to revisit a previously perfected order, such power was to be exercised for specific and limited purposes only within well-defined parameters.</li>\n	<li>\n		The discrete categories of situations in which the court had the power to revisit its previous order which had been sealed were where the court:\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				amended a previous order so as to reflect its original intention which was manifest as appearing from the body of the order or judgment;</li>\n			<li>\n				amended a previous order in order to correct a clerical error or accidental slip;</li>\n			<li>\n				clarified, amended or supplemented a previous order under the &ldquo;liberty to apply&rdquo; provisions; and</li>\n			<li>\n				pursuant to applicable rules of court, amended a previous order, including but not limited to enlarging time specified in it.</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Such power was exercised within well-settled confines (as opposed to the broad or blanket power as argued by P) and therefore did not violate the principle of <em>functus officio</em>.</li>\n	<li>\n		Specifically, under category (d), the court could revisit and amend a previous order by enlarging time, even after sealing, if it was granted an express power to do so by the applicable statutory rules of the court such as O.3 r. 5 of the RDC. Such power to revisit stemmed not from its original jurisdiction over the case, which had come to an end upon sealing (applying the principle of <em>functus officio</em>), but from a &ldquo;fresh&rdquo; power to act conferred on it by the statute.</li>\n	<li>\n		Applying this principle, the Court was inclined to hold that it did have jurisdiction pursuant to the express power under O.3 r. 5 to extend time to bring P&rsquo;s application to vary within time. However, under the rule of stare decisis, the Court was bound by the decision of the Court of First Instance in <em>RTX Products Hong Kong Ltd v Li Yiu Fai</em> and accordingly, it had no jurisdiction to revisit the Order once it was sealed. It became absolute when the judgment was perfected.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:205:\"Judgment – perfection rule – court’s jurisdiction to revisit previously perfected order – power to be exercised for specific limited purposes only which did not violate principle of functus officio\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3585:\"<p>Judgment – perfection rule – court’s jurisdiction to revisit previously perfected order – power to be exercised for specific limited purposes only which did not violate principle of functus officio\n</p><p>\n	Poon Ching Man v Lam Hoi Pun</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad629030000014ed8b70b2a7460d12a&amp;docguid=I9C37C474CABB4183B5DA81BB32FE6601&amp;hitguid=I9C37C474CABB4183B5DA81BB32FE6601&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=5&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=13\">[2015] 3 HKLRD 57<br /></a>District Court<br />\n	Personal Injuries Action No. 1585 of 2011<br />\n	Deputy Judge Winnie Tsui in Chambers<br />\n	22 April 2015</p>\n<p>\n	P’s personal injuries action against D was dismissed with a costs order <em>nisi</em> made against P (the “Order”). After the Order became absolute pursuant to O. 42 r. 5B(3) of the Rules of the District Court (Cap. 336H, Sub. Leg.) (the “RDC”) and the judgment was then drawn up and sealed, P sought to vary the Order out of time. P argued that a new modern approach granted the Court a wide discretionary power under O. 3 r. 5 of the RDC to grant a retrospective extension of the 14-day time limit even after the judgment had been perfected so as to bring P’s application to vary within time.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		There was no “new modern approach” under which the court enjoyed an unlimited power to revisit any previous order which had been perfected. Even where the court had jurisdiction to revisit a previously perfected order, such power was to be exercised for specific and limited purposes only within well-defined parameters.</li>\n<li>\n		The discrete categories of situations in which the court had the power to revisit its previous order which had been sealed were where the court:\n<ul><li>\n				amended a previous order so as to reflect its original intention which was manifest as appearing from the body of the order or judgment;</li>\n<li>\n				amended a previous order in order to correct a clerical error or accidental slip;</li>\n<li>\n				clarified, amended or supplemented a previous order under the “liberty to apply” provisions; and</li>\n<li>\n				pursuant to applicable rules of court, amended a previous order, including but not limited to enlarging time specified in it.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>\n		Such power was exercised within well-settled confines (as opposed to the broad or blanket power as argued by P) and therefore did not violate the principle of <em>functus officio</em>.</li>\n<li>\n		Specifically, under category (d), the court could revisit and amend a previous order by enlarging time, even after sealing, if it was granted an express power to do so by the applicable statutory rules of the court such as O.3 r. 5 of the RDC. Such power to revisit stemmed not from its original jurisdiction over the case, which had come to an end upon sealing (applying the principle of <em>functus officio</em>), but from a “fresh” power to act conferred on it by the statute.</li>\n<li>\n		Applying this principle, the Court was inclined to hold that it did have jurisdiction pursuant to the express power under O.3 r. 5 to extend time to bring P’s application to vary within time. However, under the rule of stare decisis, the Court was bound by the decision of the Court of First Instance in <em>RTX Products Hong Kong Ltd v Li Yiu Fai</em> and accordingly, it had no jurisdiction to revisit the Order once it was sealed. It became absolute when the judgment was perfected.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:213:\"<p>Judgment – perfection rule – court’s jurisdiction to revisit previously perfected order – power to be exercised for specific limited purposes only which did not violate principle of functus officio</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:14:\"District Court\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:14:\"District Court\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:28:\"Poon Ching Man v Lam Hoi Pun\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:28:\"Poon Ching Man v Lam Hoi Pun\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-08-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad629030000014ed8b70b2a7460d12a&docguid=I9C37C474CABB4183B5DA81BB32FE6601&hitguid=I9C37C474CABB4183B5DA81BB32FE6601&spos=1&epos=1&td=5&crumb-action=append&context=13\";s:5:\"title\";s:17:\"[2015] 3 HKLRD 57\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:13:\"22 April 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:13:\"22 April 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:28:\"Poon Ching Man v Lam Hoi Pun\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1438819200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8756','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8756\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:55:\"Beijing Tong Gang Da Sheng Trade Co Ltd v Allen & Overy\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8756\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1438819200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252664\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8756\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252664\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:4218:\"Maintenance and champerty – litigation funding agreement and assignment of cause of action – whether champertous<p>\n	Beijing Tong Gang Da Sheng Trade Co. Ltd v Allen &amp; Overy</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744c0970000014ed8b81b79863d782f&amp;docguid=I8A27A95DD9124329ADBD51151EC605A1&amp;hitguid=I8A27A95DD9124329ADBD51151EC605A1&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=5&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=16\">[2015] HKEC 893</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Civil Appeal Nos. 34 and 124 of 2014<br />\n	Cheung CJHC, Lam V-P, Kwan JA<br />\n	22 May 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D1&ndash;2, a solicitors&rsquo; firm and a barrister respectively, were alleged to have rendered negligent advice to a company, C, in about 2005 or 2006. P and C entered into an agreement (the &ldquo;Funding Agreement&rdquo;) whereby P agreed, <em>inter alia</em>, to lend $3.4 million to C at an interest rate of 25 percent for a term of two years for an intended litigation against Ds, guaranteed by the recourse to proceeds that C would recover from Ds, and entitling P to 20 percent of any such proceeds. About 14 months after the Funding Agreement, C issued a writ against Ds in the present action. About four months later, C assigned to P the cause of action against Ds and <em>inter alia</em> the right to the proceeds arising from such action (the &ldquo;Assignment&rdquo;) for $100,000 and 10 percent of the net proceeds of the action. P also gave notice of the Assignment to Ds and C removed itself substituting P in its place as plaintiff. Ds alleged that the Assignment was champertous. P denied this on the grounds that it was a major creditor of C and its controlling shareholder and so had a genuine commercial interest in the enforcement of the action; but failed to provide supporting documentary evidence. P eventually offered to cancel the Assignment and C would continue with the action. Ds then sought to strike out the action. Before the hearing of the striking-out application, P and C sought leave to add C as a plaintiff in the action. In a first decision (see <a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad629030000014f0620421bf06cf7e0&amp;docguid=I61782129F30B411AB9811BDCDD3B9C46&amp;hitguid=I61782129F30B411AB9811BDCDD3B9C46&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2014] 2 HKLRD 86</a>) the Judge found that both the Funding Agreement and the Assignment were champertous and struck out P&rsquo;s action, but deferred drawing up the order until after the joinder application was heard. In a second decision (see <a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad629030000014f06250b1e85d5cc0e&amp;docguid=I0456D70F9E254F57BBBE2F3D9A4BCCC5&amp;hitguid=I0456D70F9E254F57BBBE2F3D9A4BCCC5&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=7\">[2014] 3 HKLRD 292</a>) the Judge refused to join C as a party to the action, finding that the proceedings had been abandoned by C which was the only party with locus to sue, and that the application to reinstate it was time-barred. P appealed against both decisions.</p>\n<p>\n	<em><strong>Held</strong></em>, upholding the ruling on champerty, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		The finding of champerty would be upheld. All the aspects of the transaction should be taken together for the purpose of considering the single question whether there was wanton and officious intermeddling with the disputes of others in which the maintainer had no interest whatever, and where the assistance he rendered to the one or the other party was without justification or excuse. The Judge had examined the totality of the facts in concluding that the transactions would pose a genuine risk to the integrity of the Court&rsquo;s processes. There were vastly disproportionate potential returns for the outlay in the Funding Agreement and the Assignment, which was relevant and significant to the genuineness of the impugned transaction. The transaction relied on made no or little commercial sense. The merits of the underlying claim need not always be taken into account in concluding that a transaction was champertous.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:116:\"Maintenance and champerty – litigation funding agreement and assignment of cause of action – whether champertous\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:4191:\"<p>Maintenance and champerty – litigation funding agreement and assignment of cause of action – whether champertous\n</p><p>\n	Beijing Tong Gang Da Sheng Trade Co. Ltd v Allen &amp; Overy</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744c0970000014ed8b81b79863d782f&amp;docguid=I8A27A95DD9124329ADBD51151EC605A1&amp;hitguid=I8A27A95DD9124329ADBD51151EC605A1&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=5&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=16\">[2015] HKEC 893</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Civil Appeal Nos. 34 and 124 of 2014<br />\n	Cheung CJHC, Lam V-P, Kwan JA<br />\n	22 May 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D1–2, a solicitors’ firm and a barrister respectively, were alleged to have rendered negligent advice to a company, C, in about 2005 or 2006. P and C entered into an agreement (the “Funding Agreement”) whereby P agreed, <em>inter alia</em>, to lend $3.4 million to C at an interest rate of 25 percent for a term of two years for an intended litigation against Ds, guaranteed by the recourse to proceeds that C would recover from Ds, and entitling P to 20 percent of any such proceeds. About 14 months after the Funding Agreement, C issued a writ against Ds in the present action. About four months later, C assigned to P the cause of action against Ds and <em>inter alia</em> the right to the proceeds arising from such action (the “Assignment”) for $100,000 and 10 percent of the net proceeds of the action. P also gave notice of the Assignment to Ds and C removed itself substituting P in its place as plaintiff. Ds alleged that the Assignment was champertous. P denied this on the grounds that it was a major creditor of C and its controlling shareholder and so had a genuine commercial interest in the enforcement of the action; but failed to provide supporting documentary evidence. P eventually offered to cancel the Assignment and C would continue with the action. Ds then sought to strike out the action. Before the hearing of the striking-out application, P and C sought leave to add C as a plaintiff in the action. In a first decision (see <a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad629030000014f0620421bf06cf7e0&amp;docguid=I61782129F30B411AB9811BDCDD3B9C46&amp;hitguid=I61782129F30B411AB9811BDCDD3B9C46&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2014] 2 HKLRD 86</a>) the Judge found that both the Funding Agreement and the Assignment were champertous and struck out P’s action, but deferred drawing up the order until after the joinder application was heard. In a second decision (see <a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad629030000014f06250b1e85d5cc0e&amp;docguid=I0456D70F9E254F57BBBE2F3D9A4BCCC5&amp;hitguid=I0456D70F9E254F57BBBE2F3D9A4BCCC5&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=7\">[2014] 3 HKLRD 292</a>) the Judge refused to join C as a party to the action, finding that the proceedings had been abandoned by C which was the only party with locus to sue, and that the application to reinstate it was time-barred. P appealed against both decisions.</p>\n<p>\n	<em><strong>Held</strong></em>, upholding the ruling on champerty, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		The finding of champerty would be upheld. All the aspects of the transaction should be taken together for the purpose of considering the single question whether there was wanton and officious intermeddling with the disputes of others in which the maintainer had no interest whatever, and where the assistance he rendered to the one or the other party was without justification or excuse. The Judge had examined the totality of the facts in concluding that the transactions would pose a genuine risk to the integrity of the Court’s processes. There were vastly disproportionate potential returns for the outlay in the Funding Agreement and the Assignment, which was relevant and significant to the genuineness of the impugned transaction. The transaction relied on made no or little commercial sense. The merits of the underlying claim need not always be taken into account in concluding that a transaction was champertous.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:124:\"<p>Maintenance and champerty – litigation funding agreement and assignment of cause of action – whether champertous</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:55:\"Beijing Tong Gang Da Sheng Trade Co Ltd v Allen & Overy\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:59:\"Beijing Tong Gang Da Sheng Trade Co Ltd v Allen &amp; Overy\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"100\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-08-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744c0970000014ed8b81b79863d782f&docguid=I8A27A95DD9124329ADBD51151EC605A1&hitguid=I8A27A95DD9124329ADBD51151EC605A1&spos=1&epos=1&td=5&crumb-action=append&context=16\";s:5:\"title\";s:15:\"[2015] HKEC 893\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:11:\"22 May 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:11:\"22 May 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"Contract Law\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"Contract Law\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:55:\"Beijing Tong Gang Da Sheng Trade Co Ltd v Allen & Overy\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1438819200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8758','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8758\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:33:\"Chi Yuk Pui v Grace Mind Corp Ltd\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8758\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1438819200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252664\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8758\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252664\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3820:\"Assessment of damages in which defendant-employer uninsured and Employees Compensation Assistance Fund Board did not wish to intervene – new protocol for case management of undefended cases to ensure costs controlled and kept at reasonable level<p>\n	Chi Yuk Pui v Grace Mind Corp Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad629030000014ed8c37f407460d166&amp;docguid=IB9C8C6894F8A498BB87AB7709DF613CD&amp;hitguid=IB9C8C6894F8A498BB87AB7709DF613CD&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=2&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=20\">[2015] HKEC 919</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Personal Injuries Action No. 917 of 2014<br />\n	Bharwaney J in Chambers<br />\n	22 May 2015</p>\n<p>\n	P injured his wrist at work. He was awarded employees&rsquo; compensation (&ldquo;EC&rdquo;) of $72,328 (the &ldquo;EC Award&rdquo;), which his employer, D, had not paid. D was uninsured and P applied for a relief payment from the Employees Compensation Assistance Fund Board (the &ldquo;ECAS Fund Board&rdquo;). P also brought proceedings against D in the District Court for damages at common law; and obtained default judgment with damages to be assessed. The ECAS Fund Board did not participate in the action, which was transferred to the High Court for case management. At the present hearing for the assessment of damages, the Judge made a net total award (after deducting $72,328 for the EC Award) of $154,015.45; and then proceeded to deal with the issue of costs.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, that:</p>\n<p>\n	<em>Summary Assessment of Costs</em></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		An important part of the case management of cases, such as here, was to make a summary assessment of the costs incurred, so as to protect, as much as reasonably possible, against the depletion of the relief payment by excessive or unreasonably incurred costs. P&rsquo;s solicitors&rsquo; claim for just under $137,000 in party-and-party costs of the proceedings at the District Court scale and disbursements of just under $2,800 was excessive, given that most of the work was already done in the EC proceedings. The matters raised in these proceedings were fairly straightforward. Taking a broad-brush approach, profit costs were allowed in the sum of $75,000 plus disbursements of $1,764. Despite the less than generous approach for a case of this nature, the costs allowed constituted about 50% of the expected relief payment which could be expected from the ECAS Fund Board as a result of the award of damages. It was unjust that a great, or greater, part of the amount from the ECAS Fund Board to compensate for loss and damage and pain and suffering should be utilised to pay the legal costs incurred to obtain the judgment for damages.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<em>Pro bono legal representation</em></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Going forward, it was hoped that solicitors assigned by the Director of Legal Aid in claims where the defendant employer was uninsured and the ECAS Fund Board did not wish to intervene, might consider conducting the proceedings on a <em>pro bono</em> basis to avoid the injustice that a substantial part of a relief payment would be absorbed by their costs; and that the junior Bar also provided pro bono assistance by conducting undefended assessments of damages, whether in the High Court or the District Court.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<em>New protocol for case management to control costs</em></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Further, the Court set out a new protocol in such undefended cases as guidance to the District Court Personal Injuries Judge and his Masters so they could actively manage the costs incurred by plaintiffs in obtaining the undefended judgment and ensuring that steps were taken to proceed to an assessment of damages which were proportionate and that excessive costs were not incurred.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:247:\"Assessment of damages in which defendant-employer uninsured and Employees Compensation Assistance Fund Board did not wish to intervene – new protocol for case management of undefended cases to ensure costs controlled and kept at reasonable level\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3783:\"<p>Assessment of damages in which defendant-employer uninsured and Employees Compensation Assistance Fund Board did not wish to intervene – new protocol for case management of undefended cases to ensure costs controlled and kept at reasonable level\n</p><p>\n	Chi Yuk Pui v Grace Mind Corp Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad629030000014ed8c37f407460d166&amp;docguid=IB9C8C6894F8A498BB87AB7709DF613CD&amp;hitguid=IB9C8C6894F8A498BB87AB7709DF613CD&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=2&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=20\">[2015] HKEC 919</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Personal Injuries Action No. 917 of 2014<br />\n	Bharwaney J in Chambers<br />\n	22 May 2015</p>\n<p>\n	P injured his wrist at work. He was awarded employees’ compensation (“EC”) of $72,328 (the “EC Award”), which his employer, D, had not paid. D was uninsured and P applied for a relief payment from the Employees Compensation Assistance Fund Board (the “ECAS Fund Board”). P also brought proceedings against D in the District Court for damages at common law; and obtained default judgment with damages to be assessed. The ECAS Fund Board did not participate in the action, which was transferred to the High Court for case management. At the present hearing for the assessment of damages, the Judge made a net total award (after deducting $72,328 for the EC Award) of $154,015.45; and then proceeded to deal with the issue of costs.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, that:</p>\n<p>\n	<em>Summary Assessment of Costs</em></p>\n<ul><li>\n		An important part of the case management of cases, such as here, was to make a summary assessment of the costs incurred, so as to protect, as much as reasonably possible, against the depletion of the relief payment by excessive or unreasonably incurred costs. P’s solicitors’ claim for just under $137,000 in party-and-party costs of the proceedings at the District Court scale and disbursements of just under $2,800 was excessive, given that most of the work was already done in the EC proceedings. The matters raised in these proceedings were fairly straightforward. Taking a broad-brush approach, profit costs were allowed in the sum of $75,000 plus disbursements of $1,764. Despite the less than generous approach for a case of this nature, the costs allowed constituted about 50% of the expected relief payment which could be expected from the ECAS Fund Board as a result of the award of damages. It was unjust that a great, or greater, part of the amount from the ECAS Fund Board to compensate for loss and damage and pain and suffering should be utilised to pay the legal costs incurred to obtain the judgment for damages.</li>\n</ul><p>\n	<em>Pro bono legal representation</em></p>\n<ul><li>\n		Going forward, it was hoped that solicitors assigned by the Director of Legal Aid in claims where the defendant employer was uninsured and the ECAS Fund Board did not wish to intervene, might consider conducting the proceedings on a <em>pro bono</em> basis to avoid the injustice that a substantial part of a relief payment would be absorbed by their costs; and that the junior Bar also provided pro bono assistance by conducting undefended assessments of damages, whether in the High Court or the District Court.</li>\n</ul><p>\n	<em>New protocol for case management to control costs</em></p>\n<ul><li>\n		Further, the Court set out a new protocol in such undefended cases as guidance to the District Court Personal Injuries Judge and his Masters so they could actively manage the costs incurred by plaintiffs in obtaining the undefended judgment and ensuring that steps were taken to proceed to an assessment of damages which were proportionate and that excessive costs were not incurred.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:255:\"<p>Assessment of damages in which defendant-employer uninsured and Employees Compensation Assistance Fund Board did not wish to intervene – new protocol for case management of undefended cases to ensure costs controlled and kept at reasonable level</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:33:\"Chi Yuk Pui v Grace Mind Corp Ltd\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:33:\"Chi Yuk Pui v Grace Mind Corp Ltd\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-08-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad629030000014ed8c37f407460d166&docguid=IB9C8C6894F8A498BB87AB7709DF613CD&hitguid=IB9C8C6894F8A498BB87AB7709DF613CD&spos=1&epos=1&td=2&crumb-action=append&context=20\";s:5:\"title\";s:15:\"[2015] HKEC 919\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:11:\"22 May 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:11:\"22 May 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:7:\"Damages\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:7:\"Damages\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:33:\"Chi Yuk Pui v Grace Mind Corp Ltd\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1438819200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8760','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8760\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:21:\"Chan Sang v Chan Kwok\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8760\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1438819200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252664\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8760\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252664\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2534:\"Constructive trust – common intention constructive trust – could be invoked outside “domestic consumer context” (ie, in commercial context)<p>\n	Chan Sang v Chan Kwok</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e0000014ed8c5327565257afc&amp;docguid=IFFCFC5B151054FB4A98B57F92D1C3E79&amp;hitguid=IFFCFC5B151054FB4A98B57F92D1C3E79&amp;spos=10&amp;epos=10&amp;td=442&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=23\">[2015] 3 HKLRD 131</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	High Court Action No. 1539 of 2012<br />\n	Anderson Chow J<br />\n	15 May 2015</p>\n<p>\n	P and D were brothers and, since 1983, tenants in common in equal shares of a shop wherein P ran an electrical business. P claimed that he, D and their father, F, agreed that D would be registered as a co-owner only to secure repayment of a loan used to finance the purchase of the shop by P to F (the &ldquo;Loan&rdquo;); and once the Loan was fully repaid, D would remove his name; but despite the Loan being repaid and repeated demands, D had refused and/or failed to do so. P brought proceedings against D seeking a declaration that he was the sole beneficial owner of the shop and D held his half share in the shop on trust for P; and an order to compel D to transfer his half share to him.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, granting the declaration and order sought, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		As a matter of principle, there was no reason why the doctrine of &ldquo;common intention constructive trust&rdquo; could only be invoked in the &ldquo;domestic consumer context&rdquo;, although the context could be relevant in considering the parties&rsquo; common intention as to the beneficial ownership of a property purchased either in their joint names or in the sole name of one party. Rather, the presumption of equality applicable where members of the same family purchased in joint names a property which they intended to be and in fact was occupied by them as a home, would not apply outside the &ldquo;domestic consumer context&rdquo;. In a &ldquo;commercial context&rdquo;, the presumption of resulting trust would apply.</li>\n	<li>\n		On the facts here, the shop was purchased and paid for solely by P; D was made a tenant in common of the shop to secure P&rsquo;s repayment of the Loan advanced by F; and the Loan was repaid by P in or about June 1998. P was therefore at all material times the sole beneficial owner of the shop (whether on a resulting trust or a common intention constructive trust).</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:147:\"Constructive trust – common intention constructive trust – could be invoked outside “domestic consumer context” (ie, in commercial context)\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2490:\"<p>Constructive trust – common intention constructive trust – could be invoked outside “domestic consumer context” (ie, in commercial context)\n</p><p>\n	Chan Sang v Chan Kwok</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e0000014ed8c5327565257afc&amp;docguid=IFFCFC5B151054FB4A98B57F92D1C3E79&amp;hitguid=IFFCFC5B151054FB4A98B57F92D1C3E79&amp;spos=10&amp;epos=10&amp;td=442&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=23\">[2015] 3 HKLRD 131</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	High Court Action No. 1539 of 2012<br />\n	Anderson Chow J<br />\n	15 May 2015</p>\n<p>\n	P and D were brothers and, since 1983, tenants in common in equal shares of a shop wherein P ran an electrical business. P claimed that he, D and their father, F, agreed that D would be registered as a co-owner only to secure repayment of a loan used to finance the purchase of the shop by P to F (the “Loan”); and once the Loan was fully repaid, D would remove his name; but despite the Loan being repaid and repeated demands, D had refused and/or failed to do so. P brought proceedings against D seeking a declaration that he was the sole beneficial owner of the shop and D held his half share in the shop on trust for P; and an order to compel D to transfer his half share to him.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, granting the declaration and order sought, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		As a matter of principle, there was no reason why the doctrine of “common intention constructive trust” could only be invoked in the “domestic consumer context”, although the context could be relevant in considering the parties’ common intention as to the beneficial ownership of a property purchased either in their joint names or in the sole name of one party. Rather, the presumption of equality applicable where members of the same family purchased in joint names a property which they intended to be and in fact was occupied by them as a home, would not apply outside the “domestic consumer context”. In a “commercial context”, the presumption of resulting trust would apply.</li>\n<li>\n		On the facts here, the shop was purchased and paid for solely by P; D was made a tenant in common of the shop to secure P’s repayment of the Loan advanced by F; and the Loan was repaid by P in or about June 1998. P was therefore at all material times the sole beneficial owner of the shop (whether on a resulting trust or a common intention constructive trust).</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:155:\"<p>Constructive trust – common intention constructive trust – could be invoked outside “domestic consumer context” (ie, in commercial context)</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:21:\"Chan Sang v Chan Kwok\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:21:\"Chan Sang v Chan Kwok\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"117\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-08-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:236:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad69f8e0000014ed8c5327565257afc&docguid=IFFCFC5B151054FB4A98B57F92D1C3E79&hitguid=IFFCFC5B151054FB4A98B57F92D1C3E79&spos=10&epos=10&td=442&crumb-action=append&context=23\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 3 HKLRD 131\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:11:\"15 May 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:11:\"15 May 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:6:\"Trusts\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:6:\"Trusts\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:21:\"Chan Sang v Chan Kwok\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1438819200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8762','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8762\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:17:\"The Bo Shi Ji 393\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8762\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1441324800\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252664\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8762\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252664\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:4663:\"Action in rem – jurisdiction – claim by cargo owners for loss of cargo – in rem action against sister ship – whether requirements of s. 12B(4) satisfied<p>\n	The Bo Shi Ji 393</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d05f0000014f6822b8e564188f61&amp;docguid=ID4FFC36D95B549A09647F590013443C4&amp;hitguid=ID4FFC36D95B549A09647F590013443C4&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=11\">[2015] HKEC 1013</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Admiralty Action No. 44 of 2014<br />\n	Peter Ng J<br />\n	3 June 2015</p>\n<p>\n	In March 2013, the vessel &ldquo;Bo Shi Ji 393&rdquo; (the &ldquo;Claim Vessel&rdquo;) sank in Chinese waters. In March 2014, Ps issued an in rem writ (the &ldquo;Writ&rdquo;) for the loss of two cargoes on board the Claim Vessel. The bills of lading contained a demise clause which provided that if the ship was not owned by or chartered by demise to the corporation by whom the bills were issued, the bills would take effect as contracts with the shipowner or demise charterer as the case might be as principal. Ps&rsquo; original case was that the person who would be liable in respect of an action <em>in personam</em> was C, whom they believed to be the sole registered owner of the Claim Vessel. On 6 March 2015, Ps obtained a warrant of arrest against the vessel &ldquo;Bo Shi Ji 838&rdquo; (the &ldquo;Arrest Vessel&rdquo;) on the basis of s. 12B(4) of the High Court Ordinance (Cap. 4) that C, being the &ldquo;relevant person&rdquo;, was its sole beneficial owner. After the Arrest Vessel was arrested on 18 March 2015, Ds provided to Ps, <em>inter alia</em>, the Vessel Ownership Registration Certificates (the &ldquo;VORCs&rdquo;) of: (a) the Claim Vessel, which showed that it had been co-owned by C (51 percent) and an individual X1 (49percent) since December 2010; and (b) the Arrest Vessel, which showed that it was solely owned by C between June2008 and September 2014. The VORCs were not formal documents from the shipping registry of Hui Zhou, which was not open for public inspection. In light of the VORCs, Ps now claimed that both C and X1 were the &ldquo;relevant person&rdquo;. Ds contended that X1 and another individual, X2, was the sole beneficial owner and operator of the Claim Vessel and the Arrest Vessel respectively; and that C was only their agent for the purpose of handling all documentation matters for the vessels under two management agreements. Ds submitted therefore that (a) only X1, and not C, was the &ldquo;relevant person&rdquo; under s.12B(4)(b); and (b) the Arrest Vessel was not at the time of the Writ a sister ship of Claim Vessel for the purposes of s. 12B(4)(ii) because C was not the beneficial owner of all its shares. Ps applied for the appraisal and sale of the Vessel pendente lite. Ds cross-applied to set aside the service of the Writ on the Vessel on the ground that the requirements of s.12B(4) were not satisfied, to strike out P&rsquo;s claims, and to set aside the warrant of arrest.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing Ds&rsquo; applications, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		&ldquo;Relevant person&rdquo; in s.12B(4)(b) meant the person who would be liable in an action <em>in personam</em> on the assumption that the action succeeded. It was not necessary for Ps to establish, in order to found jurisdiction, that that person was in fact liable on the claim.</li>\n	<li>\n		Here, the requirements under s.12B(4) were satisfied.\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				As for s. 12B(4)(b), in the absence of any contrary suggestion, the Court would proceed on the basis that C and X1 were the registered owners of the Claim Vessel as shown in the VORC. Since the Claim Vessel was not under demise charter when the cargoes were lost, <em>prima facie</em>, they as owners would be liable to the shippers and/or cargo owners for the loss of cargo shipped under the bills of lading. It was untenable to suggest that only X1 was the &ldquo;relevant person&rdquo; as this was in substance asking the Court to accept the evidence adduced by Ds, including in particular the effect of the management agreement, while ignoring the VORC.</li>\n			<li>\n				In respect of s. 12B(4)(ii), Ds adduced no expert evidence as to whether the requirements of a trust of ships, if any, under PRC law had been met and how trusts of ships interacted with the shipping registration laws in the PRC. The Court was not prepared to overlook the VORC and was not satisfied that C was not the beneficial owner of all shares in the Vessel at the time of the Writ.</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		The Court would not strike out the claims.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:160:\"Action in rem – jurisdiction – claim by cargo owners for loss of cargo – in rem action against sister ship – whether requirements of s. 12B(4) satisfied\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:4553:\"<p>Action in rem – jurisdiction – claim by cargo owners for loss of cargo – in rem action against sister ship – whether requirements of s. 12B(4) satisfied\n</p><p>\n	The Bo Shi Ji 393</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d05f0000014f6822b8e564188f61&amp;docguid=ID4FFC36D95B549A09647F590013443C4&amp;hitguid=ID4FFC36D95B549A09647F590013443C4&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=11\">[2015] HKEC 1013</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Admiralty Action No. 44 of 2014<br />\n	Peter Ng J<br />\n	3 June 2015</p>\n<p>\n	In March 2013, the vessel “Bo Shi Ji 393” (the “Claim Vessel”) sank in Chinese waters. In March 2014, Ps issued an in rem writ (the “Writ”) for the loss of two cargoes on board the Claim Vessel. The bills of lading contained a demise clause which provided that if the ship was not owned by or chartered by demise to the corporation by whom the bills were issued, the bills would take effect as contracts with the shipowner or demise charterer as the case might be as principal. Ps’ original case was that the person who would be liable in respect of an action <em>in personam</em> was C, whom they believed to be the sole registered owner of the Claim Vessel. On 6 March 2015, Ps obtained a warrant of arrest against the vessel “Bo Shi Ji 838” (the “Arrest Vessel”) on the basis of s. 12B(4) of the High Court Ordinance (Cap. 4) that C, being the “relevant person”, was its sole beneficial owner. After the Arrest Vessel was arrested on 18 March 2015, Ds provided to Ps, <em>inter alia</em>, the Vessel Ownership Registration Certificates (the “VORCs”) of: (a) the Claim Vessel, which showed that it had been co-owned by C (51 percent) and an individual X1 (49percent) since December 2010; and (b) the Arrest Vessel, which showed that it was solely owned by C between June2008 and September 2014. The VORCs were not formal documents from the shipping registry of Hui Zhou, which was not open for public inspection. In light of the VORCs, Ps now claimed that both C and X1 were the “relevant person”. Ds contended that X1 and another individual, X2, was the sole beneficial owner and operator of the Claim Vessel and the Arrest Vessel respectively; and that C was only their agent for the purpose of handling all documentation matters for the vessels under two management agreements. Ds submitted therefore that (a) only X1, and not C, was the “relevant person” under s.12B(4)(b); and (b) the Arrest Vessel was not at the time of the Writ a sister ship of Claim Vessel for the purposes of s. 12B(4)(ii) because C was not the beneficial owner of all its shares. Ps applied for the appraisal and sale of the Vessel pendente lite. Ds cross-applied to set aside the service of the Writ on the Vessel on the ground that the requirements of s.12B(4) were not satisfied, to strike out P’s claims, and to set aside the warrant of arrest.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing Ds’ applications, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		“Relevant person” in s.12B(4)(b) meant the person who would be liable in an action <em>in personam</em> on the assumption that the action succeeded. It was not necessary for Ps to establish, in order to found jurisdiction, that that person was in fact liable on the claim.</li>\n<li>\n		Here, the requirements under s.12B(4) were satisfied.\n<ul><li>\n				As for s. 12B(4)(b), in the absence of any contrary suggestion, the Court would proceed on the basis that C and X1 were the registered owners of the Claim Vessel as shown in the VORC. Since the Claim Vessel was not under demise charter when the cargoes were lost, <em>prima facie</em>, they as owners would be liable to the shippers and/or cargo owners for the loss of cargo shipped under the bills of lading. It was untenable to suggest that only X1 was the “relevant person” as this was in substance asking the Court to accept the evidence adduced by Ds, including in particular the effect of the management agreement, while ignoring the VORC.</li>\n<li>\n				In respect of s. 12B(4)(ii), Ds adduced no expert evidence as to whether the requirements of a trust of ships, if any, under PRC law had been met and how trusts of ships interacted with the shipping registration laws in the PRC. The Court was not prepared to overlook the VORC and was not satisfied that C was not the beneficial owner of all shares in the Vessel at the time of the Writ.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>\n		The Court would not strike out the claims.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:168:\"<p>Action in rem – jurisdiction – claim by cargo owners for loss of cargo – in rem action against sister ship – whether requirements of s. 12B(4) satisfied</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:17:\"The Bo Shi Ji 393\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:17:\"The Bo Shi Ji 393\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:2:\"94\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-09-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744d05f0000014f6822b8e564188f61&docguid=ID4FFC36D95B549A09647F590013443C4&hitguid=ID4FFC36D95B549A09647F590013443C4&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=11\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1013\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:11:\"3 June 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:11:\"3 June 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:9:\"Admiralty\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:9:\"Admiralty\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:17:\"The Bo Shi Ji 393\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1441324800\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8764','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8764\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:38:\"A v B (Arbitral awards: setting aside)\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8764\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1441324800\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252664\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8764\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252664\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3818:\"Arbitral award — setting aside — public policy — arbitrator failed to deal with material issue of limitation — resulted in such injustice that contrary to public policy to enforce award — matter remitted to arbitrator<p>\n	A v B (Arbitral awards: setting aside)</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad8289e0000014f68218560a367a719&amp;docguid=I1AF738914EC3437BB0D1E5F1DCB8D035&amp;hitguid=I1AF738914EC3437BB0D1E5F1DCB8D035&amp;spos=4&amp;epos=4&amp;td=270&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=8\">[2015] HKEC 1211</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Construction and Arbitration Proceedings No. 40 of 2014<br />\n	Mimmie Chan J in Chambers<br />\n	15 June 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D commenced arbitration proceedings against P alleging breach of an agreement (the &ldquo;Agreement&rdquo;) for the joint development, manufacture, distribution and marketing of security and integrated circuit solutions for designated goods (the &ldquo;Products&rdquo;). P raised a defence that, even based on its last delivery of the Products to D in September 2009, by the time D commenced the arbitration in February 2011, its claims were time-barred under para. 7.5 of the Agreement which provided that &ldquo;Any action by [D] hereunder must be commenced within one (1) year of the date of delivery of the Product giving rise to the claim or the date the cause of action arose, whichever is earlier.&rdquo; The Arbitrator allowed D&rsquo;s claims and dismissed P&rsquo;s counterclaim, finding that P had failed to deliver the Products in compliance with the technical standards and contractual requirements under the Agreement (the &ldquo;Award&rdquo;). P sought to set aside the Award for being contrary to public policy. D conceded that the Arbitrator had not expressly dealt with the limitation defence in the Award.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, remitting the Award to the Arbitrator under Art. 34(4) of Model Law, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Reading the 126-page Reasons for Final Award in its entirety, and in the context of how the issues were argued before the Tribunal, the reasons expressed were not sufficient to enable P to understand how, and why, the limitation defence was rejected. This was particularly so bearing in mind the need for proportionality. The Arbitrator dealt in meticulous detail with other issues argued, but did not deal with para.7.5 and the issues involved at all.</li>\n	<li>\n		It was fundamental to concepts of fairness, due process and justice that key and material issues raised for determination by a court or the arbitral tribunal, should be considered and dealt with fairly. Under Art. 33(2) of the Model Law, the award should state the reasons on which it was based. It was a serious irregularity and a denial of due process which caused substantial injustice and unfairness to the parties if an important issue was not addressed.</li>\n	<li>\n		There was injustice arising out of the Award which could not be overlooked and its enforcement would offend the notions of justice. Even if the Arbitrator had found in favour of D on all its claims, the limitation defence was a material issue which could have rendered the Award materially different, and the failure to consider it, or to explain its dismissal, resulted in unfairness to P, as well as a real risk of injustice and prejudice to its case.</li>\n	<li>\n		Accordingly, the Award was in conflict with public policy. It would be remitted to the Arbitrator to take such action as he thought appropriate in respect of the limitation defence based on the factual findings already made in the Reasons for Award, so as to eliminate the grounds for setting aside. There was no suggestion of misconduct by the Arbitrator or any real risk of an appearance of prejudgement or bias.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:227:\"Arbitral award — setting aside — public policy — arbitrator failed to deal with material issue of limitation — resulted in such injustice that contrary to public policy to enforce award — matter remitted to arbitrator\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3780:\"<p>Arbitral award — setting aside — public policy — arbitrator failed to deal with material issue of limitation — resulted in such injustice that contrary to public policy to enforce award — matter remitted to arbitrator\n</p><p>\n	A v B (Arbitral awards: setting aside)</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad8289e0000014f68218560a367a719&amp;docguid=I1AF738914EC3437BB0D1E5F1DCB8D035&amp;hitguid=I1AF738914EC3437BB0D1E5F1DCB8D035&amp;spos=4&amp;epos=4&amp;td=270&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=8\">[2015] HKEC 1211</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Construction and Arbitration Proceedings No. 40 of 2014<br />\n	Mimmie Chan J in Chambers<br />\n	15 June 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D commenced arbitration proceedings against P alleging breach of an agreement (the “Agreement”) for the joint development, manufacture, distribution and marketing of security and integrated circuit solutions for designated goods (the “Products”). P raised a defence that, even based on its last delivery of the Products to D in September 2009, by the time D commenced the arbitration in February 2011, its claims were time-barred under para. 7.5 of the Agreement which provided that “Any action by [D] hereunder must be commenced within one (1) year of the date of delivery of the Product giving rise to the claim or the date the cause of action arose, whichever is earlier.” The Arbitrator allowed D’s claims and dismissed P’s counterclaim, finding that P had failed to deliver the Products in compliance with the technical standards and contractual requirements under the Agreement (the “Award”). P sought to set aside the Award for being contrary to public policy. D conceded that the Arbitrator had not expressly dealt with the limitation defence in the Award.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, remitting the Award to the Arbitrator under Art. 34(4) of Model Law, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		Reading the 126-page Reasons for Final Award in its entirety, and in the context of how the issues were argued before the Tribunal, the reasons expressed were not sufficient to enable P to understand how, and why, the limitation defence was rejected. This was particularly so bearing in mind the need for proportionality. The Arbitrator dealt in meticulous detail with other issues argued, but did not deal with para.7.5 and the issues involved at all.</li>\n<li>\n		It was fundamental to concepts of fairness, due process and justice that key and material issues raised for determination by a court or the arbitral tribunal, should be considered and dealt with fairly. Under Art. 33(2) of the Model Law, the award should state the reasons on which it was based. It was a serious irregularity and a denial of due process which caused substantial injustice and unfairness to the parties if an important issue was not addressed.</li>\n<li>\n		There was injustice arising out of the Award which could not be overlooked and its enforcement would offend the notions of justice. Even if the Arbitrator had found in favour of D on all its claims, the limitation defence was a material issue which could have rendered the Award materially different, and the failure to consider it, or to explain its dismissal, resulted in unfairness to P, as well as a real risk of injustice and prejudice to its case.</li>\n<li>\n		Accordingly, the Award was in conflict with public policy. It would be remitted to the Arbitrator to take such action as he thought appropriate in respect of the limitation defence based on the factual findings already made in the Reasons for Award, so as to eliminate the grounds for setting aside. There was no suggestion of misconduct by the Arbitrator or any real risk of an appearance of prejudgement or bias.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:235:\"<p>Arbitral award — setting aside — public policy — arbitrator failed to deal with material issue of limitation — resulted in such injustice that contrary to public policy to enforce award — matter remitted to arbitrator</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:38:\"A v B (Arbitral awards: setting aside)\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:38:\"A v B (Arbitral awards: setting aside)\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-09-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:233:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad8289e0000014f68218560a367a719&docguid=I1AF738914EC3437BB0D1E5F1DCB8D035&hitguid=I1AF738914EC3437BB0D1E5F1DCB8D035&spos=4&epos=4&td=270&crumb-action=append&context=8\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1211\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"15 June 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"15 June 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:11:\"Arbitration\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:11:\"Arbitration\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:38:\"A v B (Arbitral awards: setting aside)\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1441324800\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8766','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8766\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:32:\"Chan Shu Chun v Right Margin Ltd\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8766\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1441324800\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252664\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8766\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252664\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:5005:\"Interlocutory anti-suit injunction restraining defendant from taking part in arbitration proceedings – defendant not party to arbitration – whether arbitration and underlying agreement “shams”<p>\n	Chan Shu Chun v Right Margin Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad8289e0000014f682455601543f6b5&amp;docguid=I4200B66F3FAD4015A649EEC57907603C&amp;hitguid=I4200B66F3FAD4015A649EEC57907603C&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=13&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=14\">[2015] HKEC 1058</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	High Court Action No. 792 of 2015<br />\n	Recorder Linda Chan SC<br />\n	13 May 2015</p>\n<p>\n	P1 was the sole shareholder of D2, which owned all the equity in P2. P2 was a PRC company which held a property development project (&ldquo;Project&rdquo;). D4 was the director of D1. P2, D1&ndash;2 entered into an agency agreement (the &ldquo;Agency Agreement&rdquo;) whereby among other things D1 advanced a sum of RMB120,330,603 to P2 and D2, to be repaid after the period stipulated. As security for the Agency Agreement, the following documents were executed, among others: (a) P1 mortgaged all his shares in D2 to D1; and (b) D2 pledged all its equity in P2 to D1. P2 and D2 failed to pay the amounts due to D1 under the Agency Agreement, and D1 obtained two default judgments against P2 &amp; D2, and P1 respectively. On the basis of the first default judgment, D1 obtained from a PRC court an order: (a) freezing the assets of P2 and D2 up to the amount owed; and (b) recognising and enforcing the first default judgment against them. D1 then exercised its rights under the mortgage and transferred P1&rsquo;s shareholding in D2 to itself. D1 then procured D2 to remove P1 as its director and appointed D3&ndash;4 in his place. As the new directors of D2, D3&ndash;4 passed written resolutions (&ldquo;Resolutions&rdquo;) appointing D4 as D2&rsquo;s authorised signatory. Thereafter, D4 signed several documents replacing the old management of P2 with D3 and D5&ndash;6. By an agreement (the &ldquo;Agreement&rdquo;), D2 (acting by D4) and P2 (acting by D3) agreed that P2 would perform certain obligations, including registering those changes and handing over its company chops and official documents, and the parties agreed to submit any dispute relating to the Agreement to arbitration in the PRC. D2 then commenced arbitration (the &ldquo;Arbitration&rdquo;) against P2 for failing to perform the Agreement. P1 sought an injunction against D1 to stop the Arbitration, alleging that D1 had breached its duty as mortgagee by (a) obtaining the default judgments and freezing the Project while negotiations were ongoing; (b) trying to take control of P2; and (c) using the Agreement and the Arbitration, which were both shams, to obtain an award to effect the change in management of P2.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		There was nothing to show that an injunction against D1 would have the effect of putting a halt to the Arbitration, as it was not a party to the same. Equity did not act in vain and would not grant an injunction which was futile, thus the application should be dismissed <em>in limine</em>.</li>\n	<li>\n		Further, a late proposal to reformulate the application in an attempt to bind D2 was based on a misapprehension that as the sole shareholder of D2, D1 had the right the usurp the powers of D2&rsquo;s directors.</li>\n	<li>\n		As for the other points, first, there was no basis to suggest that the Arbitration was a sham. It was neither conducted in breach of an agreement, nor was D1&rsquo;s conduct unconscionable, vexatious or oppressive. The ends of justice did not require the Court to grant the anti-suit injunction, as the validity of the Agreement was an issue which would be determined by the tribunal in the Arbitration.</li>\n	<li>\n		Second, there was no dispute that P2 and D2 failed to pay the amounts due under the Agency Agreement. Therefore, D1 could exercise the powers under the mortgage on default. There was no breach of duty as the steps taken to seize control over P2 and D2 were within the powers given to D1 under the mortgage.</li>\n	<li>\n		Third, by the Resolutions, P2&rsquo;s old management was replaced by D3 and D5&ndash;6. The Agreement could not be a &ldquo;sham&rdquo; as the legal rights and obligations which the parties intended to create were exactly the same as those which it intended to portray to third parties.</li>\n	<li>\n		Fourth, there was nothing wrong in D1 taking enforcement steps while negotiating with P1 for a possible settlement. There was no implied duty for a party in negotiation to inform the other side of what legal steps he had taken or was going to take to enforce its rights.</li>\n	<li>\n		Finally, a creditor could choose to enforce whichever remedy was open to him. There was no basis for P1 to allege that D1&rsquo;s act in freezing the Project constituted a breach of duty.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:200:\"Interlocutory anti-suit injunction restraining defendant from taking part in arbitration proceedings – defendant not party to arbitration – whether arbitration and underlying agreement “shams”\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:4912:\"<p>Interlocutory anti-suit injunction restraining defendant from taking part in arbitration proceedings – defendant not party to arbitration – whether arbitration and underlying agreement “shams”\n</p><p>\n	Chan Shu Chun v Right Margin Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad8289e0000014f682455601543f6b5&amp;docguid=I4200B66F3FAD4015A649EEC57907603C&amp;hitguid=I4200B66F3FAD4015A649EEC57907603C&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=13&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=14\">[2015] HKEC 1058</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	High Court Action No. 792 of 2015<br />\n	Recorder Linda Chan SC<br />\n	13 May 2015</p>\n<p>\n	P1 was the sole shareholder of D2, which owned all the equity in P2. P2 was a PRC company which held a property development project (“Project”). D4 was the director of D1. P2, D1–2 entered into an agency agreement (the “Agency Agreement”) whereby among other things D1 advanced a sum of RMB120,330,603 to P2 and D2, to be repaid after the period stipulated. As security for the Agency Agreement, the following documents were executed, among others: (a) P1 mortgaged all his shares in D2 to D1; and (b) D2 pledged all its equity in P2 to D1. P2 and D2 failed to pay the amounts due to D1 under the Agency Agreement, and D1 obtained two default judgments against P2 &amp; D2, and P1 respectively. On the basis of the first default judgment, D1 obtained from a PRC court an order: (a) freezing the assets of P2 and D2 up to the amount owed; and (b) recognising and enforcing the first default judgment against them. D1 then exercised its rights under the mortgage and transferred P1’s shareholding in D2 to itself. D1 then procured D2 to remove P1 as its director and appointed D3–4 in his place. As the new directors of D2, D3–4 passed written resolutions (“Resolutions”) appointing D4 as D2’s authorised signatory. Thereafter, D4 signed several documents replacing the old management of P2 with D3 and D5–6. By an agreement (the “Agreement”), D2 (acting by D4) and P2 (acting by D3) agreed that P2 would perform certain obligations, including registering those changes and handing over its company chops and official documents, and the parties agreed to submit any dispute relating to the Agreement to arbitration in the PRC. D2 then commenced arbitration (the “Arbitration”) against P2 for failing to perform the Agreement. P1 sought an injunction against D1 to stop the Arbitration, alleging that D1 had breached its duty as mortgagee by (a) obtaining the default judgments and freezing the Project while negotiations were ongoing; (b) trying to take control of P2; and (c) using the Agreement and the Arbitration, which were both shams, to obtain an award to effect the change in management of P2.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		There was nothing to show that an injunction against D1 would have the effect of putting a halt to the Arbitration, as it was not a party to the same. Equity did not act in vain and would not grant an injunction which was futile, thus the application should be dismissed <em>in limine</em>.</li>\n<li>\n		Further, a late proposal to reformulate the application in an attempt to bind D2 was based on a misapprehension that as the sole shareholder of D2, D1 had the right the usurp the powers of D2’s directors.</li>\n<li>\n		As for the other points, first, there was no basis to suggest that the Arbitration was a sham. It was neither conducted in breach of an agreement, nor was D1’s conduct unconscionable, vexatious or oppressive. The ends of justice did not require the Court to grant the anti-suit injunction, as the validity of the Agreement was an issue which would be determined by the tribunal in the Arbitration.</li>\n<li>\n		Second, there was no dispute that P2 and D2 failed to pay the amounts due under the Agency Agreement. Therefore, D1 could exercise the powers under the mortgage on default. There was no breach of duty as the steps taken to seize control over P2 and D2 were within the powers given to D1 under the mortgage.</li>\n<li>\n		Third, by the Resolutions, P2’s old management was replaced by D3 and D5–6. The Agreement could not be a “sham” as the legal rights and obligations which the parties intended to create were exactly the same as those which it intended to portray to third parties.</li>\n<li>\n		Fourth, there was nothing wrong in D1 taking enforcement steps while negotiating with P1 for a possible settlement. There was no implied duty for a party in negotiation to inform the other side of what legal steps he had taken or was going to take to enforce its rights.</li>\n<li>\n		Finally, a creditor could choose to enforce whichever remedy was open to him. There was no basis for P1 to allege that D1’s act in freezing the Project constituted a breach of duty.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:208:\"<p>Interlocutory anti-suit injunction restraining defendant from taking part in arbitration proceedings – defendant not party to arbitration – whether arbitration and underlying agreement “shams”</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:32:\"Chan Shu Chun v Right Margin Ltd\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:32:\"Chan Shu Chun v Right Margin Ltd\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-09-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:233:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad8289e0000014f682455601543f6b5&docguid=I4200B66F3FAD4015A649EEC57907603C&hitguid=I4200B66F3FAD4015A649EEC57907603C&spos=1&epos=1&td=13&crumb-action=append&context=14\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1058\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:11:\"13 May 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:11:\"13 May 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:32:\"Chan Shu Chun v Right Margin Ltd\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1441324800\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8768','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8768\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:39:\"Wong Chun Tak v Registrar of High Court\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8768\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1441324800\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450249307\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8768\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450249307\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2272:\"Legal aid – merits test – test was whether reasonable, not fanciful, chance of success<p>\n	Wong Chun Tak v Registrar of High Court</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad8289e0000014f68254bfda367a7cd&amp;docguid=I4A7769B1A7A24EF09787AD07877B56D7&amp;hitguid=I4A7769B1A7A24EF09787AD07877B56D7&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=46&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=17\">[2015] HKEC 1049</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Constitutional and Administrative Law List No. 67 of 2014<br />\n	Queeny Au-Yeung J<br />\n	5 June 2015</p>\n<p>\n	The Master dismissed an appeal by X against the refusal of legal aid by the Director of Legal Aid, &ldquo;for the reasons set out in counsel&rsquo;s opinion&rdquo; (the &quot;Decision&quot;). Counsel&rsquo;s opinion was that one head of X&rsquo;s claim had a better prospect of success than the other but, even so, X had only a 50:50 or even prospect of success on that head of claim. X sought an order of <em>certiorari</em> to quash the Decision. At issue was whether the Master erred by applying the wrong merits test.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, allowing the application and remitting the matter to the Master to reconsider and decide it forthwith, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		On a true construction of s. 10(3) of the Legal Aid Ordinance (Cap. 91) and proper interpretation of <em>Nguyen Trong Son v Director of Legal Aid</em> &ldquo;reasonable grounds for taking a legal action&rdquo; might be established even where the &ldquo;chance&rdquo; or &ldquo;prospect&rdquo; of success was considered less than 51 percent. The only pertinent question was whether there was a reasonable, as opposed to a fanciful, chance of the court at trial deciding that issue of fact in the applicant&rsquo;s favour.</li>\n	<li>\n		In giving her reasons, the Master must have adopted counsel&rsquo;s opinion that X had a no better than even chance of success on one head of claim. The Decision was therefore erroneous in law in that the Master failed to apply the proper test. Neither counsel nor the Director of Legal Aid answered the pertinent question. It was advisable that Masters state the test they applied when giving reasons for the dismissal of a legal aid appeal in future.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:90:\"Legal aid – merits test – test was whether reasonable, not fanciful, chance of success\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2214:\"<p>Legal aid – merits test – test was whether reasonable, not fanciful, chance of success\n</p><p>\n	Wong Chun Tak v Registrar of High Court</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad8289e0000014f68254bfda367a7cd&amp;docguid=I4A7769B1A7A24EF09787AD07877B56D7&amp;hitguid=I4A7769B1A7A24EF09787AD07877B56D7&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=46&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=17\">[2015] HKEC 1049</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Constitutional and Administrative Law List No. 67 of 2014<br />\n	Queeny Au-Yeung J<br />\n	5 June 2015</p>\n<p>\n	The Master dismissed an appeal by X against the refusal of legal aid by the Director of Legal Aid, “for the reasons set out in counsel’s opinion” (the \"Decision\"). Counsel’s opinion was that one head of X’s claim had a better prospect of success than the other but, even so, X had only a 50:50 or even prospect of success on that head of claim. X sought an order of <em>certiorari</em> to quash the Decision. At issue was whether the Master erred by applying the wrong merits test.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, allowing the application and remitting the matter to the Master to reconsider and decide it forthwith, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		On a true construction of s. 10(3) of the Legal Aid Ordinance (Cap. 91) and proper interpretation of <em>Nguyen Trong Son v Director of Legal Aid</em> “reasonable grounds for taking a legal action” might be established even where the “chance” or “prospect” of success was considered less than 51 percent. The only pertinent question was whether there was a reasonable, as opposed to a fanciful, chance of the court at trial deciding that issue of fact in the applicant’s favour.</li>\n<li>\n		In giving her reasons, the Master must have adopted counsel’s opinion that X had a no better than even chance of success on one head of claim. The Decision was therefore erroneous in law in that the Master failed to apply the proper test. Neither counsel nor the Director of Legal Aid answered the pertinent question. It was advisable that Masters state the test they applied when giving reasons for the dismissal of a legal aid appeal in future.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:98:\"<p>Legal aid – merits test – test was whether reasonable, not fanciful, chance of success</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:39:\"Wong Chun Tak v Registrar of High Court\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:39:\"Wong Chun Tak v Registrar of High Court\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-09-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:233:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad8289e0000014f68254bfda367a7cd&docguid=I4A7769B1A7A24EF09787AD07877B56D7&hitguid=I4A7769B1A7A24EF09787AD07877B56D7&spos=1&epos=1&td=46&crumb-action=append&context=17\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1049\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:11:\"5 June 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:11:\"5 June 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:39:\"Wong Chun Tak v Registrar of High Court\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1441324800\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8772','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8772\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:28:\"Yip Yuk Kwong v Yip Chun Yin\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8772\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1441324800\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450249307\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8772\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450249307\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2363:\"Constructive trust – common intention constructive trust – whether established<p>\n	Yip Yuk Kwong v Yip Chun Yin</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad82d080000014f9762fd2f78396342&amp;docguid=I9F7393E7B5E1429296C78E62DCBF0C54&amp;hitguid=I9F7393E7B5E1429296C78E62DCBF0C54&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] HKEC 1312</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Miscellaneous Proceedings No. 2552 of 2014<br />\n	Deputy Judge Saunders<br />\n	3 July 2015</p>\n<p>\n	M and F were the parents of S. In May 1997, M and S acquired a Home Ownership Scheme flat, which required M and F to forfeit a public housing unit in which they and their family had been living for 12 years. The purchase was made in S&rsquo;s name only to benefit from concessionary legal fees and F had paid all the mortgage instalments. In May1998, S presented a bankruptcy petition stating that he held his interest in the property as trustee for F. S became bankrupt and his legal title in the property became vested in the Official Receiver. F sought various declarations with the effect of removing S&rsquo;s bankruptcy from the title to the property and recording title in the names of M and F as joint tenants.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, granting the declarations sought, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Applying the standard of proof of a balance of probabilities, in all the circumstances, the parties&rsquo; common intention was that F and M would own the property as joint tenants and S would hold his interest on trust for F.</li>\n	<li>\n		The advantage of the saving in legal fees was more than sufficient to rebut the presumption of advancement here. The fact that S accepted a personal liability under the mortgage was not inconsistent with a trust. To achieve the parties&rsquo; common intention of a purchase by F and M with reduced legal fees, it was vital that S be a registered proprietor and purchaser and thus accept such personal liability. Further, that S contributed to the purchase by effectively guaranteeing with his personal liability his parents&rsquo; liability under the mortgage, was entirely consistent with adult children in Hong Kong assisting their parents out of filial obligation. This did not detract in any way from the parties&rsquo; common intention.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:82:\"Constructive trust – common intention constructive trust – whether established\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2343:\"<p>Constructive trust – common intention constructive trust – whether established\n</p><p>\n	Yip Yuk Kwong v Yip Chun Yin</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad82d080000014f9762fd2f78396342&amp;docguid=I9F7393E7B5E1429296C78E62DCBF0C54&amp;hitguid=I9F7393E7B5E1429296C78E62DCBF0C54&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] HKEC 1312</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Miscellaneous Proceedings No. 2552 of 2014<br />\n	Deputy Judge Saunders<br />\n	3 July 2015</p>\n<p>\n	M and F were the parents of S. In May 1997, M and S acquired a Home Ownership Scheme flat, which required M and F to forfeit a public housing unit in which they and their family had been living for 12 years. The purchase was made in S’s name only to benefit from concessionary legal fees and F had paid all the mortgage instalments. In May1998, S presented a bankruptcy petition stating that he held his interest in the property as trustee for F. S became bankrupt and his legal title in the property became vested in the Official Receiver. F sought various declarations with the effect of removing S’s bankruptcy from the title to the property and recording title in the names of M and F as joint tenants.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, granting the declarations sought, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		Applying the standard of proof of a balance of probabilities, in all the circumstances, the parties’ common intention was that F and M would own the property as joint tenants and S would hold his interest on trust for F.</li>\n<li>\n		The advantage of the saving in legal fees was more than sufficient to rebut the presumption of advancement here. The fact that S accepted a personal liability under the mortgage was not inconsistent with a trust. To achieve the parties’ common intention of a purchase by F and M with reduced legal fees, it was vital that S be a registered proprietor and purchaser and thus accept such personal liability. Further, that S contributed to the purchase by effectively guaranteeing with his personal liability his parents’ liability under the mortgage, was entirely consistent with adult children in Hong Kong assisting their parents out of filial obligation. This did not detract in any way from the parties’ common intention.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:90:\"<p>Constructive trust – common intention constructive trust – whether established</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:28:\"Yip Yuk Kwong v Yip Chun Yin\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:28:\"Yip Yuk Kwong v Yip Chun Yin\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"112\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-09-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:231:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad82d080000014f9762fd2f78396342&docguid=I9F7393E7B5E1429296C78E62DCBF0C54&hitguid=I9F7393E7B5E1429296C78E62DCBF0C54&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=4\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1312\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:11:\"3 July 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:11:\"3 July 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:8:\"Land Law\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:8:\"Land Law\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:28:\"Yip Yuk Kwong v Yip Chun Yin\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1441324800\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8774','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8774\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:48:\"Town Planning Board v Town Planning Appeal Board\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8774\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1441324800\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450249307\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8774\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450249307\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3197:\"Decision on compliance of conditions under planning permission not “decision” of Board under s. 16 – not reviewable under s. 17<p>\n	Town Planning Board v Town Planning Appeal Board</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d0640000014f682773f60af72ef3&amp;docguid=I83C6BDB9D7B745239BEECC58F7926C78&amp;hitguid=I83C6BDB9D7B745239BEECC58F7926C78&amp;spos=8&amp;epos=8&amp;td=378&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=25\">[2015] HKEC 1151</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Civil Appeal No. 25 of 2014<br />\n	Lam V-P, Kwan JA and Jeremy Poon J<br />\n	18 June 2015</p>\n<p>\n	Xs applied to the Town Planning Board (the &ldquo;Board&rdquo;) for planning permission for a proposed development scheme, which was eventually granted by the Town Planning Appeal Board (the &ldquo;Appeal Board&rdquo;) subject to conditions. Xs submitted plans and reports pursuant to the said conditions, but the Board opined that they deviated substantially from the approved scheme and that a fresh planning application would be required (the &ldquo;Decision&rdquo;). On Xs&rsquo; application for a review of the Decision under s. 17 of the Town Planning Ordinance (Cap. 131) (the &ldquo;TPO&rdquo;), the Board declined as it concluded that it had no power to do so. Xs appealed to the Appeal Board, which held that the Decision was reviewable by the Board itself under s. 17. On the Board&rsquo;s successful application for judicial review of the Appeal Board&rsquo;s decision, the Judge held that on a true construction, the Decision was not &ldquo;a decision of the Board under s. 16&rdquo; within the meaning of s. 17 such that the Board had no power to review it under s. 17. Xs appealed. The relevant provisions were the pre-2004 version of ss. 16 and 17 of the TPO introduced in 1991.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Until the amendments to the TPO in 1991, the decision of the Board liable to be reviewed was limited to a refusal to grant planning permission under s. 16 and no more. Section 17(6) provided for an appeal of the Board&rsquo;s decision made on that limited scope of review. It was impermissible to read into the pre-1991 s. 17(1) a power to review a decision taken in relation to an approval or satisfaction with details under a planning condition.</li>\n	<li>\n		By 1991 and before 2004, within the statutory scheme of ss. 16 and 17, the Board might make three primary decisions under s. 16: (a) grant the application for planning permission without conditions; (b) refuse the application; and (c) grant the application with conditions. Where the primary decision was either a refusal or grant of permission with conditions, and if the applicant was aggrieved, he could apply for a review of that primary decision under s. 17(1). For the purpose of s. 17(1), &ldquo;a decision made by the Board under s. 16&rdquo; embraced such a primary decision only. It did not include any incidental decision that the Board might make in the discharge of its functions under s. 16, irrespective of whether the underlying power to do so was derived from any statutory provision or from the common law.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:133:\"Decision on compliance of conditions under planning permission not “decision” of Board under s. 16 – not reviewable under s. 17\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3137:\"<p>Decision on compliance of conditions under planning permission not “decision” of Board under s. 16 – not reviewable under s. 17\n</p><p>\n	Town Planning Board v Town Planning Appeal Board</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d0640000014f682773f60af72ef3&amp;docguid=I83C6BDB9D7B745239BEECC58F7926C78&amp;hitguid=I83C6BDB9D7B745239BEECC58F7926C78&amp;spos=8&amp;epos=8&amp;td=378&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=25\">[2015] HKEC 1151</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Civil Appeal No. 25 of 2014<br />\n	Lam V-P, Kwan JA and Jeremy Poon J<br />\n	18 June 2015</p>\n<p>\n	Xs applied to the Town Planning Board (the “Board”) for planning permission for a proposed development scheme, which was eventually granted by the Town Planning Appeal Board (the “Appeal Board”) subject to conditions. Xs submitted plans and reports pursuant to the said conditions, but the Board opined that they deviated substantially from the approved scheme and that a fresh planning application would be required (the “Decision”). On Xs’ application for a review of the Decision under s. 17 of the Town Planning Ordinance (Cap. 131) (the “TPO”), the Board declined as it concluded that it had no power to do so. Xs appealed to the Appeal Board, which held that the Decision was reviewable by the Board itself under s. 17. On the Board’s successful application for judicial review of the Appeal Board’s decision, the Judge held that on a true construction, the Decision was not “a decision of the Board under s. 16” within the meaning of s. 17 such that the Board had no power to review it under s. 17. Xs appealed. The relevant provisions were the pre-2004 version of ss. 16 and 17 of the TPO introduced in 1991.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		Until the amendments to the TPO in 1991, the decision of the Board liable to be reviewed was limited to a refusal to grant planning permission under s. 16 and no more. Section 17(6) provided for an appeal of the Board’s decision made on that limited scope of review. It was impermissible to read into the pre-1991 s. 17(1) a power to review a decision taken in relation to an approval or satisfaction with details under a planning condition.</li>\n<li>\n		By 1991 and before 2004, within the statutory scheme of ss. 16 and 17, the Board might make three primary decisions under s. 16: (a) grant the application for planning permission without conditions; (b) refuse the application; and (c) grant the application with conditions. Where the primary decision was either a refusal or grant of permission with conditions, and if the applicant was aggrieved, he could apply for a review of that primary decision under s. 17(1). For the purpose of s. 17(1), “a decision made by the Board under s. 16” embraced such a primary decision only. It did not include any incidental decision that the Board might make in the discharge of its functions under s. 16, irrespective of whether the underlying power to do so was derived from any statutory provision or from the common law.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:141:\"<p>Decision on compliance of conditions under planning permission not “decision” of Board under s. 16 – not reviewable under s. 17</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:48:\"Town Planning Board v Town Planning Appeal Board\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:48:\"Town Planning Board v Town Planning Appeal Board\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"112\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-09-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:234:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744d0640000014f682773f60af72ef3&docguid=I83C6BDB9D7B745239BEECC58F7926C78&hitguid=I83C6BDB9D7B745239BEECC58F7926C78&spos=8&epos=8&td=378&crumb-action=append&context=25\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1151\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"18 June 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"18 June 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:13:\"Town Planning\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:13:\"Town Planning\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:48:\"Town Planning Board v Town Planning Appeal Board\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1441324800\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184717,1),('8776','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8776\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:54:\"東莞興業國際物流城有限公司 v Liu Zong Pei\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8776\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1442188800\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1453720441\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8776\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1453720441\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:4740:\"<p>Intellectual Property – whether the complainant has rights to its unregistered trademark – unauthorised transfer of domain name registration</p>\r\n\r\n<p>東莞興業國際物流城有限公司 v Liu Zong Pei</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500751_Decision.pdf\">HK – 1500751</a> \"Chinatimber.org\"<br />\r\nAsian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)<br />\r\nLoke-Khoon Tan (Panelist)<br />\r\n23 June 2015</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On 15 April 2015, Complainant (hereinafter “C”) initiated a domain name dispute resolution proceeding concerning <chinatimber.org>(the “Disputed Domain Name”) under the Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (the “Policy”) by filing a complaint with the Hong Kong Office of Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (the “Centre”). Respondent (hereinafter “R”) was recorded as the Registrant of the Disputed Domain Name in accordance with the Whois information.</chinatimber.org></p>\r\n\r\n<p><chinatimber.org> </chinatimber.org></p>\r\n\r\n<p>C alleged that C was the original registrant of the Disputed Domain Name and operated an online timber trading platform via a website resolved by the Disputed Domain Name, and there were more than 150,000 registered users of the platform. C provided with documentary proofs, evidencing that it held the registration of the Disputed Domain Name from 5 May 2009 till November 2014 when C found the Disputed Domain Name having been transferred to R without its authorisation and permission. The Registrar (domain name registration service provider) had also been changed from the Xinnet to eNom. Although the Disputed Domain Name was still resolved to C’s website, C suffered from losing the control of the Disputed Domain Name and its website.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the Complaint, C contended that the Disputed Domain Name was identical to its mark (<strong>“中国木材网 / www.chinatimber.org”</strong>) (the “Mark”), and that R, who had no rights and legitimate interests in respect of the Disputed Domain Name, had registered and was using the Disputed Domain Name in bad faith.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shortly after the Centre’s notification of commencement of proceedings to R, C reported that its website had been shut down by R, and then filed a supplemental submission that R’s suspension of C’s website also constituted using the domain name in bad faith under the UDRP.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>R failed to file any response within the required period of time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, granting the remedy sought, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A threshold issue before the Panel was whether C had rights to the Mark which was not a registered mark. The Panel accepted the view set out by para. 1.7 of the WIPO Overview of WIPO Panel Views on Selected UDRP Questions, Second Edition and recent ADNDRC decisions under HK-1500709 and HK-1400614, that to successfully assert common law or unregistered trademark rights, a complainant must show that the name had become a distinctive identifier associated with the complainant or its goods or services. In view of the fact that C had used and promoted the Mark in its online platform since 2009, and that many search results of the Mark in a major engine pointed to C, the Panel accepted that C had rights to the Mark which had been a distinctive identifier of C. Further, the Panel found that the Disputed Domain Name was identical and confusingly similar to C’s Mark.</li>\r\n	<li>The Panel also found that R had no rights or legitimate interests in respect of the Disputed Domain Name. Based on the fact that the Disputed Domain Name was resolving to C’s website before and after R’s attainment of the Disputed Domain Name, the Panel inferred that R must have known about C’s Mark. R’s suspension of the Disputed Domain Name’s resolution after receipt of the Centre’s notice of complaint, which resulted in the shutting down of C’s website, had disrupted C’s business and caused losses to C. In the absence of response from R, the Panel accepted C’s submission that C was the original holder of the Disputed Domain Name which had been transferred to and registered by R without C’s permission.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Having found that R had registered and was using the Disputed Domain Name in bad faith, the Panel ordered that the Disputed Domain Name be transferred to C.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><chinatimber.org> </chinatimber.org></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The full decision can be downloaded in the website of ADNDRC at <a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500751_Decision.pdf\">http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500751_Decision.pdf</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:153:\"<p>Intellectual Property – whether the complainant has rights to its unregistered trademark – unauthorised transfer of domain name registration</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:4685:\"<p>Intellectual Property – whether the complainant has rights to its unregistered trademark – unauthorised transfer of domain name registration</p>\n<p>東莞興業國際物流城有限公司 v Liu Zong Pei</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500751_Decision.pdf\">HK – 1500751</a> \"Chinatimber.org\"<br />\nAsian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)<br />\nLoke-Khoon Tan (Panelist)<br />\n23 June 2015</p>\n<p>On 15 April 2015, Complainant (hereinafter “C”) initiated a domain name dispute resolution proceeding concerning <chinatimber.org>(the “Disputed Domain Name”) under the Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (the “Policy”) by filing a complaint with the Hong Kong Office of Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (the “Centre”). Respondent (hereinafter “R”) was recorded as the Registrant of the Disputed Domain Name in accordance with the Whois information.</chinatimber.org></p>\n<p><chinatimber.org></chinatimber.org></p>\n<p>C alleged that C was the original registrant of the Disputed Domain Name and operated an online timber trading platform via a website resolved by the Disputed Domain Name, and there were more than 150,000 registered users of the platform. C provided with documentary proofs, evidencing that it held the registration of the Disputed Domain Name from 5 May 2009 till November 2014 when C found the Disputed Domain Name having been transferred to R without its authorisation and permission. The Registrar (domain name registration service provider) had also been changed from the Xinnet to eNom. Although the Disputed Domain Name was still resolved to C’s website, C suffered from losing the control of the Disputed Domain Name and its website.</p>\n<p>In the Complaint, C contended that the Disputed Domain Name was identical to its mark (<strong>“中国木材网 / <a href=\"http://www.chinatimber.org\">www.chinatimber.org</a>”</strong>) (the “Mark”), and that R, who had no rights and legitimate interests in respect of the Disputed Domain Name, had registered and was using the Disputed Domain Name in bad faith.</p>\n<p>Shortly after the Centre’s notification of commencement of proceedings to R, C reported that its website had been shut down by R, and then filed a supplemental submission that R’s suspension of C’s website also constituted using the domain name in bad faith under the UDRP.</p>\n<p>R failed to file any response within the required period of time.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, granting the remedy sought, that:</p>\n<ul><li>A threshold issue before the Panel was whether C had rights to the Mark which was not a registered mark. The Panel accepted the view set out by para. 1.7 of the WIPO Overview of WIPO Panel Views on Selected UDRP Questions, Second Edition and recent ADNDRC decisions under HK-1500709 and HK-1400614, that to successfully assert common law or unregistered trademark rights, a complainant must show that the name had become a distinctive identifier associated with the complainant or its goods or services. In view of the fact that C had used and promoted the Mark in its online platform since 2009, and that many search results of the Mark in a major engine pointed to C, the Panel accepted that C had rights to the Mark which had been a distinctive identifier of C. Further, the Panel found that the Disputed Domain Name was identical and confusingly similar to C’s Mark.</li>\n<li>The Panel also found that R had no rights or legitimate interests in respect of the Disputed Domain Name. Based on the fact that the Disputed Domain Name was resolving to C’s website before and after R’s attainment of the Disputed Domain Name, the Panel inferred that R must have known about C’s Mark. R’s suspension of the Disputed Domain Name’s resolution after receipt of the Centre’s notice of complaint, which resulted in the shutting down of C’s website, had disrupted C’s business and caused losses to C. In the absence of response from R, the Panel accepted C’s submission that C was the original holder of the Disputed Domain Name which had been transferred to and registered by R without C’s permission.</li>\n</ul><p>Having found that R had registered and was using the Disputed Domain Name in bad faith, the Panel ordered that the Disputed Domain Name be transferred to C.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><chinatimber.org></chinatimber.org></p>\n<hr /><p> </p>\n<p>The full decision can be downloaded in the website of ADNDRC at <a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500751_Decision.pdf\">http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500751_Decision.pdf</a>.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:152:\"<p>Intellectual Property – whether the complainant has rights to its unregistered trademark – unauthorised transfer of domain name registration</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:62:\"Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:62:\"Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:54:\"東莞興業國際物流城有限公司 v Liu Zong Pei\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:54:\"東莞興業國際物流城有限公司 v Liu Zong Pei\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-09-01 00:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:63:\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500751_Decision.pdf\";s:5:\"title\";s:14:\"HK – 1500751\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"23 June 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"23 June 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"Dispute Resolution\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"Dispute Resolution\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:54:\"東莞興業國際物流城有限公司 v Liu Zong Pei\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";s:1:\"0\";s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450249307\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";N;s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8778','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8778\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:39:\"Tsang Kin Chiu v Commissioner of Police\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8778\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450249307\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8778\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450249307\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2681:\"Commissioner of Police – refusal to disclose identities of police officers who allegedly assaulted applicant – whether jurisdiction to compel such disclosure to applicant<p>\n	Tsang Kin Chiu v Commissioner of Police</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d05f0000015027915bf65cd3a5f7&amp;docguid=I04C441270EA54BC78EBBF012CCE781B7&amp;hitguid=I04C441270EA54BC78EBBF012CCE781B7&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=14&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=6\">[2015] HKEC 1368</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Constitutional and Administrative Law List No. 141 of 2014<br />\n	Thomas Au J<br />\n	13 July 2015</p>\n<p>\n	X alleged that he was assaulted by police officers, who were subsequently suspended and arrested, but not charged (the &ldquo;Officers&rdquo;). The Commissioner of Police declined X&rsquo;s request for the Officers&rsquo; identities so he could commence a private prosecution against them. X applied for leave to apply for judicial review seeking inter alia a declaration that the assaults violated the constitutional prohibition on torture and also damages, including aggravated and exemplary damages (&ldquo;Grounds 1&ndash;2&rdquo;); and an order of mandamus to compel the Commissioner to reveal the Officers&rsquo; identities. X argued that he had a right to seek such disclosure and the police were obliged to supply victims of crime with their assailants&rsquo; identities so that the failure to do so amounted to an obstruction of the administration of justice (&ldquo;Ground 4&rdquo;).</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, refusing leave on Grounds 1&ndash;2, but granting leave on Ground 4, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		X&rsquo;s primary claim under Grounds 1&ndash;2 was for damages. A private law writ action could achieve the same and was also more appropriate, since X&rsquo;s claim for exemplary damages was likely to involve the determination of factual disputes, for which judicial review was unsuitable.</li>\n	<li>\n		X therefore had an effective alternative remedy which had not been exhausted. The fact that the claim for damages was based on an alleged breach of public duty by public officials did not constitute exceptional circumstances so as to justify the grant of leave.</li>\n	<li>\n		It was reasonably arguable as to whether there was a legal basis for the Court to order the Commissioner to reveal the Officers&rsquo; identities. Given the parties&rsquo; contentions, including on the Court&rsquo;s jurisdiction and exercise of discretion, the determination of X&rsquo;s mandamus application should only be properly made at a substantive hearing with fuller arguments and evidence.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:174:\"Commissioner of Police – refusal to disclose identities of police officers who allegedly assaulted applicant – whether jurisdiction to compel such disclosure to applicant\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2608:\"<p>Commissioner of Police – refusal to disclose identities of police officers who allegedly assaulted applicant – whether jurisdiction to compel such disclosure to applicant\n</p><p>\n	Tsang Kin Chiu v Commissioner of Police</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d05f0000015027915bf65cd3a5f7&amp;docguid=I04C441270EA54BC78EBBF012CCE781B7&amp;hitguid=I04C441270EA54BC78EBBF012CCE781B7&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=14&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=6\">[2015] HKEC 1368</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Constitutional and Administrative Law List No. 141 of 2014<br />\n	Thomas Au J<br />\n	13 July 2015</p>\n<p>\n	X alleged that he was assaulted by police officers, who were subsequently suspended and arrested, but not charged (the “Officers”). The Commissioner of Police declined X’s request for the Officers’ identities so he could commence a private prosecution against them. X applied for leave to apply for judicial review seeking inter alia a declaration that the assaults violated the constitutional prohibition on torture and also damages, including aggravated and exemplary damages (“Grounds 1–2”); and an order of mandamus to compel the Commissioner to reveal the Officers’ identities. X argued that he had a right to seek such disclosure and the police were obliged to supply victims of crime with their assailants’ identities so that the failure to do so amounted to an obstruction of the administration of justice (“Ground 4”).</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, refusing leave on Grounds 1–2, but granting leave on Ground 4, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		X’s primary claim under Grounds 1–2 was for damages. A private law writ action could achieve the same and was also more appropriate, since X’s claim for exemplary damages was likely to involve the determination of factual disputes, for which judicial review was unsuitable.</li>\n<li>\n		X therefore had an effective alternative remedy which had not been exhausted. The fact that the claim for damages was based on an alleged breach of public duty by public officials did not constitute exceptional circumstances so as to justify the grant of leave.</li>\n<li>\n		It was reasonably arguable as to whether there was a legal basis for the Court to order the Commissioner to reveal the Officers’ identities. Given the parties’ contentions, including on the Court’s jurisdiction and exercise of discretion, the determination of X’s mandamus application should only be properly made at a substantive hearing with fuller arguments and evidence.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:182:\"<p>Commissioner of Police – refusal to disclose identities of police officers who allegedly assaulted applicant – whether jurisdiction to compel such disclosure to applicant</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:39:\"Tsang Kin Chiu v Commissioner of Police\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:39:\"Tsang Kin Chiu v Commissioner of Police\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:2:\"93\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-10-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744d05f0000015027915bf65cd3a5f7&docguid=I04C441270EA54BC78EBBF012CCE781B7&hitguid=I04C441270EA54BC78EBBF012CCE781B7&spos=2&epos=2&td=14&crumb-action=append&context=6\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1368\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"13 July 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"13 July 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"Administrative Law\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"Administrative Law\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:39:\"Tsang Kin Chiu v Commissioner of Police\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8780','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8780\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:35:\"D v Director of Public Prosecutions\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8780\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450249307\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8780\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450249307\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2040:\"Director of Public Prosecutions – decision not to prosecute alleged criminal offences – amenable to judicial review, but only in exceptional circumstances or where exceeded constitutional limits<p>\n	D v Director of Public Prosecutions</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d05e00000150279289dab35d2f41&amp;docguid=IE91AEC745FCF40FD85D5FB8BF69F65CE&amp;hitguid=IE91AEC745FCF40FD85D5FB8BF69F65CE&amp;spos=3&amp;epos=3&amp;td=1272&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=10\">[2015] HKEC 1328</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Constitutional and Administrative Law List No. 88 of 2015<br />\n	Zervos J<br />\n	7 July 2015</p>\n<p>\n	X was a foreign domestic helper whose former male employer committed indecent acts on himself while standing behind her. X saw what M was doing from the reflection in a television and a glass cabinet. After X secretly filmed M in the act on her smartphone, M apologised. The Director of Public Prosecutions (the &ldquo;DPP&rdquo;) decided, by two letters, not to prosecute M for indecent assault as &ldquo;The totality of evidence is equivocal as to whether [M] knew or appreciated the risk that [X] could and did see from the reflection&rdquo; (the &ldquo;Decisions&rdquo;). X applied for leave to judicially review the Decisions, arguing that they applied the wrong test of recklessness and so were perverse. The DPP submitted that the Decisions were not amenable to judicial review.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, granting the application, that it was reasonably arguable that the Director had erred in his understanding and application of the law. The question of amenability to judicially review a decision not to prosecute in a new constitutional order and modern context was reasonably arguable both as a matter of principle and in the circumstances of the case. It was reasonably arguable at least whether the Decisions came within exceptional circumstances, such as dishonesty and bad faith, or had exceeded the constitutional limits.</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:198:\"Director of Public Prosecutions – decision not to prosecute alleged criminal offences – amenable to judicial review, but only in exceptional circumstances or where exceeded constitutional limits\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2024:\"<p>Director of Public Prosecutions – decision not to prosecute alleged criminal offences – amenable to judicial review, but only in exceptional circumstances or where exceeded constitutional limits\n</p><p>\n	D v Director of Public Prosecutions</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d05e00000150279289dab35d2f41&amp;docguid=IE91AEC745FCF40FD85D5FB8BF69F65CE&amp;hitguid=IE91AEC745FCF40FD85D5FB8BF69F65CE&amp;spos=3&amp;epos=3&amp;td=1272&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=10\">[2015] HKEC 1328</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Constitutional and Administrative Law List No. 88 of 2015<br />\n	Zervos J<br />\n	7 July 2015</p>\n<p>\n	X was a foreign domestic helper whose former male employer committed indecent acts on himself while standing behind her. X saw what M was doing from the reflection in a television and a glass cabinet. After X secretly filmed M in the act on her smartphone, M apologised. The Director of Public Prosecutions (the “DPP”) decided, by two letters, not to prosecute M for indecent assault as “The totality of evidence is equivocal as to whether [M] knew or appreciated the risk that [X] could and did see from the reflection” (the “Decisions”). X applied for leave to judicially review the Decisions, arguing that they applied the wrong test of recklessness and so were perverse. The DPP submitted that the Decisions were not amenable to judicial review.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, granting the application, that it was reasonably arguable that the Director had erred in his understanding and application of the law. The question of amenability to judicially review a decision not to prosecute in a new constitutional order and modern context was reasonably arguable both as a matter of principle and in the circumstances of the case. It was reasonably arguable at least whether the Decisions came within exceptional circumstances, such as dishonesty and bad faith, or had exceeded the constitutional limits.</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:206:\"<p>Director of Public Prosecutions – decision not to prosecute alleged criminal offences – amenable to judicial review, but only in exceptional circumstances or where exceeded constitutional limits</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:35:\"D v Director of Public Prosecutions\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:35:\"D v Director of Public Prosecutions\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:2:\"93\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-10-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:235:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744d05e00000150279289dab35d2f41&docguid=IE91AEC745FCF40FD85D5FB8BF69F65CE&hitguid=IE91AEC745FCF40FD85D5FB8BF69F65CE&spos=3&epos=3&td=1272&crumb-action=append&context=10\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1328\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:11:\"7 July 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:11:\"7 July 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"Administrative Law\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"Administrative Law\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:35:\"D v Director of Public Prosecutions\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8782','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8782\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:28:\"Au Yeung Wan v Tsui Sau Ying\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8782\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8782\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252665\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2455:\"Third party proceedings – third party notice – defendant who served defence in writ action required to obtain leave to serve third party notice under Rules of the High Court (Cap.4A, Sub. Leg.) O. 16 r. 1(2)<p>\n	Au Yeung Wan v Tsui Sau Ying</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d064000001502793154556194df4&amp;docguid=I88B286660B1E421793B8FE698D807849&amp;hitguid=I88B286660B1E421793B8FE698D807849&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=4&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=13\">[2015] HKEC 1074</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	High Court Action No. 484 of 2010<br />\n	Registrar Lung Kim Wan in Chambers<br />\n	28 May 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D served his amended defence and counterclaim on P, then issued a notice of third party proceedings against TPs (the Notice) without leave. At the case management hearing, the Master raised the issue of whether D required leave under O. 16 of the Rules of the High Court (Cap. 4A, Sub. Leg.). Order 16 r.1(2) provides that &ldquo;A defendant to an action may not issue a third party notice without the leave of the Court unless the action was begun by writ and he issues the notice before serving his defence on the plaintiff.&rdquo; D argued that leave was not necessary as he should be given the opportunity to issue the Notice &ldquo;at the first available opportunity&rdquo;.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, setting aside the Notice, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		To construe the statutory provisions as proposed by D was tantamount to depriving the Court of its pro-active case management power under CJR. The legislative intent for leave to be obtained was to vest the case management power in the court so that it could exercise its unfettered discretion as to whether or not the application should be allowed. This power entailed a duty on the court. It was the duty of those appearing before the Master to bring to his attention this procedural irregularity under O. 1A r. 3 of the RHC and the court had the power to disallow the application for various reasons, such as proportionality.</li>\n	<li>\n		As D had not obtained leave to issue the Notice under O. 16 r. 1, the Court would not entertain his proposal for the grant of leave. There was no application or affidavit in support and it would be unfair to TPs, who objected to the application and did not have enough time to prepare for argument, much less the supporting affidavit materials.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:211:\"Third party proceedings – third party notice – defendant who served defence in writ action required to obtain leave to serve third party notice under Rules of the High Court (Cap.4A, Sub. Leg.) O. 16 r. 1(2)\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2443:\"<p>Third party proceedings – third party notice – defendant who served defence in writ action required to obtain leave to serve third party notice under Rules of the High Court (Cap.4A, Sub. Leg.) O. 16 r. 1(2)\n</p><p>\n	Au Yeung Wan v Tsui Sau Ying</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d064000001502793154556194df4&amp;docguid=I88B286660B1E421793B8FE698D807849&amp;hitguid=I88B286660B1E421793B8FE698D807849&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=4&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=13\">[2015] HKEC 1074</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	High Court Action No. 484 of 2010<br />\n	Registrar Lung Kim Wan in Chambers<br />\n	28 May 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D served his amended defence and counterclaim on P, then issued a notice of third party proceedings against TPs (the Notice) without leave. At the case management hearing, the Master raised the issue of whether D required leave under O. 16 of the Rules of the High Court (Cap. 4A, Sub. Leg.). Order 16 r.1(2) provides that “A defendant to an action may not issue a third party notice without the leave of the Court unless the action was begun by writ and he issues the notice before serving his defence on the plaintiff.” D argued that leave was not necessary as he should be given the opportunity to issue the Notice “at the first available opportunity”.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, setting aside the Notice, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		To construe the statutory provisions as proposed by D was tantamount to depriving the Court of its pro-active case management power under CJR. The legislative intent for leave to be obtained was to vest the case management power in the court so that it could exercise its unfettered discretion as to whether or not the application should be allowed. This power entailed a duty on the court. It was the duty of those appearing before the Master to bring to his attention this procedural irregularity under O. 1A r. 3 of the RHC and the court had the power to disallow the application for various reasons, such as proportionality.</li>\n<li>\n		As D had not obtained leave to issue the Notice under O. 16 r. 1, the Court would not entertain his proposal for the grant of leave. There was no application or affidavit in support and it would be unfair to TPs, who objected to the application and did not have enough time to prepare for argument, much less the supporting affidavit materials.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:219:\"<p>Third party proceedings – third party notice – defendant who served defence in writ action required to obtain leave to serve third party notice under Rules of the High Court (Cap.4A, Sub. Leg.) O. 16 r. 1(2)</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:28:\"Au Yeung Wan v Tsui Sau Ying\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:28:\"Au Yeung Wan v Tsui Sau Ying\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-10-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744d064000001502793154556194df4&docguid=I88B286660B1E421793B8FE698D807849&hitguid=I88B286660B1E421793B8FE698D807849&spos=2&epos=2&td=4&crumb-action=append&context=13\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1074\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:11:\"28 May 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:11:\"28 May 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:28:\"Au Yeung Wan v Tsui Sau Ying\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8784','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8784\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:42:\"World Fair Court (IO) v Choi Kam Lan Karen\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8784\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252667\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8784\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252667\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2330:\"Small Claims Tribunal – appeal – appeal on point of law under Small Claims Tribunal Ordinance (Cap.338) s. 28 – whether case to be remitted to Tribunal for retrial<p>\n	World Fair Court (IO) v Choi Kam Lan Karen</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad82d080000015027949cc37ba84e8f&amp;docguid=I5E171F1A7A084361BD8072D27279953C&amp;hitguid=I5E171F1A7A084361BD8072D27279953C&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=3&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=18\">[2015] HKEC 1021</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Small Claims Tribunal Appeal No. 15 of 2014<br />\n	Deputy Judge Poon Siu Tung<br />\n	6 October 2014</p>\n<p>\n	In Small Claims Tribunal proceedings, the incorporated owners (the &ldquo;IO&rdquo;) of a building appealed against the Adjudicator&rsquo;s dismissal of their claim against D for management fees and repair and maintenance fees. The Adjudicator found that the only issue was whether a quorum was present at two general meetings of the owners; that this was governed by the terms of the deed of mutual covenant which provided that a quorum was 75 percent of the owners; and so the requisite quorum was lacking and the resolution passed at the meetings was not valid. The IO appealed under s. 28 of the Small Claims Tribunal Ordinance (Cap. 338).</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, allowing the appeal and remitting the case to the Tribunal for retrial before another adjudicator, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Under s. 34C of the Building Management Ordinance (Cap. 344) (the &ldquo;BMO&rdquo;), that part of the BMO relating to deeds of mutual covenant shall prevail over any inconsistent terms of a deed of mutual covenant. Here, since there was an owners&rsquo; corporation, under s. 34D(3)(a) of the BMO, a resolution of the owners should be proposed and passed according to the procedures in Sch. 3, and not a deed of mutual covenant. Under s. 5(1)(b) of Sch. 3, the quorum at a meeting of a corporation shall be 10 percent of the owners. The Adjudicator did not correctly consider Sch.3 or the definition of &ldquo;a resolution of the owners&rdquo; provided in s. 34D(3) and thereby erred in law.</li>\n	<li>\n		As the matters at issue in the trial were not limited to whether there was a quorum present at the general meetings, a retrial was necessary.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:169:\"Small Claims Tribunal – appeal – appeal on point of law under Small Claims Tribunal Ordinance (Cap.338) s. 28 – whether case to be remitted to Tribunal for retrial\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2302:\"<p>Small Claims Tribunal – appeal – appeal on point of law under Small Claims Tribunal Ordinance (Cap.338) s. 28 – whether case to be remitted to Tribunal for retrial\n</p><p>\n	World Fair Court (IO) v Choi Kam Lan Karen</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad82d080000015027949cc37ba84e8f&amp;docguid=I5E171F1A7A084361BD8072D27279953C&amp;hitguid=I5E171F1A7A084361BD8072D27279953C&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=3&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=18\">[2015] HKEC 1021</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Small Claims Tribunal Appeal No. 15 of 2014<br />\n	Deputy Judge Poon Siu Tung<br />\n	6 October 2014</p>\n<p>\n	In Small Claims Tribunal proceedings, the incorporated owners (the “IO”) of a building appealed against the Adjudicator’s dismissal of their claim against D for management fees and repair and maintenance fees. The Adjudicator found that the only issue was whether a quorum was present at two general meetings of the owners; that this was governed by the terms of the deed of mutual covenant which provided that a quorum was 75 percent of the owners; and so the requisite quorum was lacking and the resolution passed at the meetings was not valid. The IO appealed under s. 28 of the Small Claims Tribunal Ordinance (Cap. 338).</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, allowing the appeal and remitting the case to the Tribunal for retrial before another adjudicator, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		Under s. 34C of the Building Management Ordinance (Cap. 344) (the “BMO”), that part of the BMO relating to deeds of mutual covenant shall prevail over any inconsistent terms of a deed of mutual covenant. Here, since there was an owners’ corporation, under s. 34D(3)(a) of the BMO, a resolution of the owners should be proposed and passed according to the procedures in Sch. 3, and not a deed of mutual covenant. Under s. 5(1)(b) of Sch. 3, the quorum at a meeting of a corporation shall be 10 percent of the owners. The Adjudicator did not correctly consider Sch.3 or the definition of “a resolution of the owners” provided in s. 34D(3) and thereby erred in law.</li>\n<li>\n		As the matters at issue in the trial were not limited to whether there was a quorum present at the general meetings, a retrial was necessary.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:177:\"<p>Small Claims Tribunal – appeal – appeal on point of law under Small Claims Tribunal Ordinance (Cap.338) s. 28 – whether case to be remitted to Tribunal for retrial</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:42:\"World Fair Court (IO) v Choi Kam Lan Karen\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:42:\"World Fair Court (IO) v Choi Kam Lan Karen\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-10-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad82d080000015027949cc37ba84e8f&docguid=I5E171F1A7A084361BD8072D27279953C&hitguid=I5E171F1A7A084361BD8072D27279953C&spos=2&epos=2&td=3&crumb-action=append&context=18\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1021\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:14:\"6 October 2014\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:14:\"6 October 2014\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:26:\"Courts and Judicial System\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:26:\"Courts and Judicial System\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:42:\"World Fair Court (IO) v Choi Kam Lan Karen\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8786','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8786\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:21:\"HKSAR v So Suet Chung\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8786\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252667\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8786\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252667\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3280:\"Defence evidence – whether error in approach in summing-up<p>\n	HKSAR v So Suet Chung</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d064000001502795baa21336c237&amp;docguid=I028196235FD24A94AD41322641CEAA8E&amp;hitguid=I028196235FD24A94AD41322641CEAA8E&amp;spos=3&amp;epos=3&amp;td=30&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=21\">[2015] HKEC 1358</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Criminal Appeal No. 113 of 2014<br />\n	Macrae and McWalters JJA and Derek Pang J<br />\n	26 June 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D was convicted of trafficking in dangerous drugs. Police stopped D and found on him 1.47 g of methamphetamine hydrochloride (ice) (&ldquo;Charge 1&rdquo;). D was arrested and cautioned for possession of dangerous drugs, which he said were for his own consumption. Police officers entered D&rsquo;s flat and found 18 tablets containing 0.08 g of nimetazepam, 12.52 g of ice, 0.09 g of a powder and one tablet fragment containing methamphetamine (&ldquo;Charge 2&rdquo;) inside over 40 plastic bags in two metal boxes and one coin purse on a table (the &ldquo;Table&rdquo;); and elsewhere, drug-related paraphernalia. D was not cautioned again. In a video-recorded interview, D admitted that he rented the flat, and said that he had never noticed the drugs there. At trial, D admitted possession of the drugs in Charge 1. He denied all knowledge of the drugs in Charge 2 and testified that the Table was not where the exhibited photographs showed it to be and the drugs might have been left by his friends. In summing up, the Judge directed the jury on the meaning and use of circumstantial evidence and that no inference must be drawn against D unless it was the only reasonable inference; then explained the burden and standard of proof and, the next day, the alternative verdicts available of simple possession. D applied for leave to appeal against conviction, arguing that in his summing-up, the Judge (a) erred by placing the burden of proof on D; and (b) failed to point out with full force the shortcomings of the police evidence of their search of D&rsquo;s flat.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		There was no merit in D&rsquo;s argument that the Judge erred in failing to direct the jury further that they should acquit D of trafficking if the defence version was or might be true. The Judge effectively conveyed the message that, even if the jury did not positively believe the evidence for the defence, they could not find an issue against him contrary to the evidence, if it gave rise to a reasonable doubt as to that issue, despite a day&rsquo;s break between the directions given on the burden and standard of proof and those given on alternative verdicts. The jury in this simple and straightforward case could not have been misled on the issue.</li>\n	<li>\n		As for D&rsquo;s argument that the summing-up was unfair and unbalanced, the Judge was not obliged to repeat everything that was said in oral evidence. Further, counsel conceded that every criticism he now made of the police witnesses was made in his final address to the jury. The jury members were fully apprised of the evidence concerning the house search and its effect on the credibility of the police.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:60:\"Defence evidence – whether error in approach in summing-up\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3240:\"<p>Defence evidence – whether error in approach in summing-up\n</p><p>\n	HKSAR v So Suet Chung</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d064000001502795baa21336c237&amp;docguid=I028196235FD24A94AD41322641CEAA8E&amp;hitguid=I028196235FD24A94AD41322641CEAA8E&amp;spos=3&amp;epos=3&amp;td=30&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=21\">[2015] HKEC 1358</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Criminal Appeal No. 113 of 2014<br />\n	Macrae and McWalters JJA and Derek Pang J<br />\n	26 June 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D was convicted of trafficking in dangerous drugs. Police stopped D and found on him 1.47 g of methamphetamine hydrochloride (ice) (“Charge 1”). D was arrested and cautioned for possession of dangerous drugs, which he said were for his own consumption. Police officers entered D’s flat and found 18 tablets containing 0.08 g of nimetazepam, 12.52 g of ice, 0.09 g of a powder and one tablet fragment containing methamphetamine (“Charge 2”) inside over 40 plastic bags in two metal boxes and one coin purse on a table (the “Table”); and elsewhere, drug-related paraphernalia. D was not cautioned again. In a video-recorded interview, D admitted that he rented the flat, and said that he had never noticed the drugs there. At trial, D admitted possession of the drugs in Charge 1. He denied all knowledge of the drugs in Charge 2 and testified that the Table was not where the exhibited photographs showed it to be and the drugs might have been left by his friends. In summing up, the Judge directed the jury on the meaning and use of circumstantial evidence and that no inference must be drawn against D unless it was the only reasonable inference; then explained the burden and standard of proof and, the next day, the alternative verdicts available of simple possession. D applied for leave to appeal against conviction, arguing that in his summing-up, the Judge (a) erred by placing the burden of proof on D; and (b) failed to point out with full force the shortcomings of the police evidence of their search of D’s flat.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		There was no merit in D’s argument that the Judge erred in failing to direct the jury further that they should acquit D of trafficking if the defence version was or might be true. The Judge effectively conveyed the message that, even if the jury did not positively believe the evidence for the defence, they could not find an issue against him contrary to the evidence, if it gave rise to a reasonable doubt as to that issue, despite a day’s break between the directions given on the burden and standard of proof and those given on alternative verdicts. The jury in this simple and straightforward case could not have been misled on the issue.</li>\n<li>\n		As for D’s argument that the summing-up was unfair and unbalanced, the Judge was not obliged to repeat everything that was said in oral evidence. Further, counsel conceded that every criticism he now made of the police witnesses was made in his final address to the jury. The jury members were fully apprised of the evidence concerning the house search and its effect on the credibility of the police.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:68:\"<p>Defence evidence – whether error in approach in summing-up</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:21:\"HKSAR v So Suet Chung\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:21:\"HKSAR v So Suet Chung\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-10-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:233:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744d064000001502795baa21336c237&docguid=I028196235FD24A94AD41322641CEAA8E&hitguid=I028196235FD24A94AD41322641CEAA8E&spos=3&epos=3&td=30&crumb-action=append&context=21\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1358\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"26 June 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"26 June 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:17:\"Criminal Evidence\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:17:\"Criminal Evidence\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:21:\"HKSAR v So Suet Chung\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8788','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8788\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:15:\"HKSAR v Harjani\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8788\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450249307\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8788\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450249307\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2573:\"Appeal — magistracy appeal — whether to be argued before Court of Appeal – nature and seriousness of issues involved warranted referral to Court of Appeal – Magistrates Ordinance (Cap.227) s. 118(1)(d)<p>\n	HKSAR v Harjani</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d05f0000015027967205e8a14d98&amp;docguid=I70140384A4464DFA88A6A32FE694C5CA&amp;hitguid=I70140384A4464DFA88A6A32FE694C5CA&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=3&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=23\">[2015] HKEC 1490</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Magistracy Appeals Nos. 685 of 2013 &amp; 425 of 2014<br />\n	Zervos J in Chambers<br />\n	27 July 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D appealed against his conviction in the Magistrate&rsquo;s Court for indecent assault, alleging serious improper conduct by his trial counsel, B, who himself appealed against a wasted costs order imposed on him by the Magistrate. At the present directions hearing, D and B agreed that the two appeals should be consolidated and referred to the Court of Appeal for determination; and that B&rsquo;s application for an anonymity order also be reserved for determination by the Court of Appeal.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, directing that the two appeals be argued before the Court of Appeal, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		A direction that a magistracy appeal should be argued before the Court of Appeal under s. 118(1)(d) of the Magistrates Ordinance (Cap. 227) should be made sparingly and in circumstances where the appeal raised an important issue of fact or law which warranted the determination of the Court of Appeal. Here, the two appeals arose from the same subject matter and raised common and similar issues that undoubtedly would be based on the same matters and material. It made abundant sense for their efficient and economic disposal that they be heard together.</li>\n	<li>\n		Further, the nature and seriousness of the issues and matters in the two appeals warranted the determination of the Court of Appeal, given that they related to the conduct of counsel during the trial process and the impact such conduct might have on a defendant&rsquo;s right to a fair trial.</li>\n	<li>\n		Accordingly, pursuant to s. 118(1)(d) of the Ordinance, the Court directed that the two appeals be argued before the Court of Appeal, which was left to direct whether the appeals should be consolidated or heard together. B&rsquo;s application for any anonymity order would also be reserved for that Court: it concerned the important principle that justice must be open and visible.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:209:\"Appeal — magistracy appeal — whether to be argued before Court of Appeal – nature and seriousness of issues involved warranted referral to Court of Appeal – Magistrates Ordinance (Cap.227) s. 118(1)(d)\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2560:\"<p>Appeal — magistracy appeal — whether to be argued before Court of Appeal – nature and seriousness of issues involved warranted referral to Court of Appeal – Magistrates Ordinance (Cap.227) s. 118(1)(d)\n</p><p>\n	HKSAR v Harjani</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d05f0000015027967205e8a14d98&amp;docguid=I70140384A4464DFA88A6A32FE694C5CA&amp;hitguid=I70140384A4464DFA88A6A32FE694C5CA&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=3&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=23\">[2015] HKEC 1490</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Magistracy Appeals Nos. 685 of 2013 &amp; 425 of 2014<br />\n	Zervos J in Chambers<br />\n	27 July 2015</p>\n<p>\n	D appealed against his conviction in the Magistrate’s Court for indecent assault, alleging serious improper conduct by his trial counsel, B, who himself appealed against a wasted costs order imposed on him by the Magistrate. At the present directions hearing, D and B agreed that the two appeals should be consolidated and referred to the Court of Appeal for determination; and that B’s application for an anonymity order also be reserved for determination by the Court of Appeal.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, directing that the two appeals be argued before the Court of Appeal, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		A direction that a magistracy appeal should be argued before the Court of Appeal under s. 118(1)(d) of the Magistrates Ordinance (Cap. 227) should be made sparingly and in circumstances where the appeal raised an important issue of fact or law which warranted the determination of the Court of Appeal. Here, the two appeals arose from the same subject matter and raised common and similar issues that undoubtedly would be based on the same matters and material. It made abundant sense for their efficient and economic disposal that they be heard together.</li>\n<li>\n		Further, the nature and seriousness of the issues and matters in the two appeals warranted the determination of the Court of Appeal, given that they related to the conduct of counsel during the trial process and the impact such conduct might have on a defendant’s right to a fair trial.</li>\n<li>\n		Accordingly, pursuant to s. 118(1)(d) of the Ordinance, the Court directed that the two appeals be argued before the Court of Appeal, which was left to direct whether the appeals should be consolidated or heard together. B’s application for any anonymity order would also be reserved for that Court: it concerned the important principle that justice must be open and visible.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:217:\"<p>Appeal — magistracy appeal — whether to be argued before Court of Appeal – nature and seriousness of issues involved warranted referral to Court of Appeal – Magistrates Ordinance (Cap.227) s. 118(1)(d)</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"HKSAR v Harjani\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"HKSAR v Harjani\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"101\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-10-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744d05f0000015027967205e8a14d98&docguid=I70140384A4464DFA88A6A32FE694C5CA&hitguid=I70140384A4464DFA88A6A32FE694C5CA&spos=2&epos=2&td=3&crumb-action=append&context=23\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1490\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"27 July 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"27 July 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"Criminal Procedure\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"Criminal Procedure\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:15:\"HKSAR v Harjani\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8790','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8790\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:25:\"Chan Po Kin v Yau Wai Yin\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8790\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450249307\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8790\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450249307\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2072:\"Co-ownership – tenants-in-common – one tenant-in-common entitled to bring possession proceedings without joining other tenants-in-common as<p>\n	Chan Po Kin v Yau Wai Yin</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d05e0000015027a04f96979d884a&amp;docguid=I8502C790C15649508FDDAD60A8195EA6&amp;hitguid=I8502C790C15649508FDDAD60A8195EA6&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=31\">[2015] HKEC 1283</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Civil Appeal No. 119 of 2014<br />\n	Lam V-P, Kwan and Chu JJA<br />\n	30 June 2015</p>\n<p>\n	X and Y were two of four tenants-in-common of land who leased it as landlords to R. As R did not exercise her option to renew the tenancy before it expired, X brought successful proceedings against R in the Lands Tribunal to recover vacant possession of the property and <em>mesne profits</em>. R appealed, arguing that X acting alone had no <em>locus standi</em> to sue.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Each tenant-in-common had a separate and distinct interest in the property and could deal with his own undivided share as he liked. He could lease it or dispose of his right to possession to a stranger without the concurrence of the other tenants-in-common. Similarly, he could enforce his interest in the land on his own without joining the other co-tenants.</li>\n	<li>\n		Here, R had no right to remain in occupation after the tenancy expired by the effluxion of time. There was no renewal of the tenancy, no statutory holding over or periodic tenancy. There was also no evidence that R had permission from the other co-owners to remain in occupation.</li>\n	<li>\n		Accordingly, X was entitled, in the exercise of her right and interest to possession as a tenant-in-common, to claim possession from R, who was a trespasser after the tenancy expired, and <em>mesne profits</em> based on R&rsquo;s occupation and use of the property, without joining the other tenants-in-common as parties to the proceedings.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:143:\"Co-ownership – tenants-in-common – one tenant-in-common entitled to bring possession proceedings without joining other tenants-in-common as\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2071:\"<p>Co-ownership – tenants-in-common – one tenant-in-common entitled to bring possession proceedings without joining other tenants-in-common as\n</p><p>\n	Chan Po Kin v Yau Wai Yin</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744d05e0000015027a04f96979d884a&amp;docguid=I8502C790C15649508FDDAD60A8195EA6&amp;hitguid=I8502C790C15649508FDDAD60A8195EA6&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=31\">[2015] HKEC 1283</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Civil Appeal No. 119 of 2014<br />\n	Lam V-P, Kwan and Chu JJA<br />\n	30 June 2015</p>\n<p>\n	X and Y were two of four tenants-in-common of land who leased it as landlords to R. As R did not exercise her option to renew the tenancy before it expired, X brought successful proceedings against R in the Lands Tribunal to recover vacant possession of the property and <em>mesne profits</em>. R appealed, arguing that X acting alone had no <em>locus standi</em> to sue.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		Each tenant-in-common had a separate and distinct interest in the property and could deal with his own undivided share as he liked. He could lease it or dispose of his right to possession to a stranger without the concurrence of the other tenants-in-common. Similarly, he could enforce his interest in the land on his own without joining the other co-tenants.</li>\n<li>\n		Here, R had no right to remain in occupation after the tenancy expired by the effluxion of time. There was no renewal of the tenancy, no statutory holding over or periodic tenancy. There was also no evidence that R had permission from the other co-owners to remain in occupation.</li>\n<li>\n		Accordingly, X was entitled, in the exercise of her right and interest to possession as a tenant-in-common, to claim possession from R, who was a trespasser after the tenancy expired, and <em>mesne profits</em> based on R’s occupation and use of the property, without joining the other tenants-in-common as parties to the proceedings.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:151:\"<p>Co-ownership – tenants-in-common – one tenant-in-common entitled to bring possession proceedings without joining other tenants-in-common as</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:25:\"Chan Po Kin v Yau Wai Yin\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:25:\"Chan Po Kin v Yau Wai Yin\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"112\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-10-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744d05e0000015027a04f96979d884a&docguid=I8502C790C15649508FDDAD60A8195EA6&hitguid=I8502C790C15649508FDDAD60A8195EA6&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=31\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1283\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"30 June 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"30 June 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:8:\"Land Law\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:8:\"Land Law\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:25:\"Chan Po Kin v Yau Wai Yin\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8792','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8792\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:42:\"Wynn Resorts Holdings, LLC v Hiroki Kanoya\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8792\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252662\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8792\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252662\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:5118:\"Intellectual Property – Application of ICANN Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (UDRP) to New gTLD Dispute – The Panel’s Decision on language issue in favour of the Complainant to use English rather than the default Japanese as the Language of the Proceeding<p>\n	Wynn Resorts Holdings, LLC v Hiroki Kanoya</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500760_Decision.pdf\">HK-1500760</a> &quot;wynn.tokyo&quot;<br />\n	Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)<br />\n	Ho-Hyun Nahm (Panelist)<br />\n	22 July 2015</p>\n<p>\n	Complainant (hereinafter &ldquo;C&rdquo;) was the holder of a number of registered trademarks incorporating the mark of &ldquo;WYNN&rdquo; (the &ldquo;Mark&rdquo;). Respondent (hereinafter &ldquo;R&rdquo;) was an individual domiciled in Japan who registered the domain name <wynn.tokyo>(the &ldquo;Disputed Domain Name&rdquo;) under the new generic Top-Level Domain (&ldquo;gTLD&rdquo;) &ldquo;.TOKYO&rdquo;.</wynn.tokyo></p>\n<p>\n	<wynn.tokyo>\n	<p>\n		On 11 June 2015, C filed an UDRP complaint against R with the Hong Kong Office of the Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (the &ldquo;Centre&rdquo;), seeking transfer of the Disputed Domain Name based on the grounds specified below:-</p>\n	<ul>\n		<li>\n			C was a famous American-based international gaming entertainment company and hotel gaming resorts developer founded by a veteran Las Vegas gaming mogul Mr. Steve Wynn and its predecessor from 1973 to 2000. The prominent and distinctive part of the Disputed Domain Name &ldquo;wynn&rdquo; was identical to C&rsquo;s Mark and the new gTLD &ldquo;.tokyo&rdquo; placed after the Mark gave a strong visual similarity to other domain names registered by C like <wynnlasvegas.com>.</wynnlasvegas.com></li>\n		<li>\n			C and its Group companies had not authorised or otherwise permitted R to use the Mark or any other name/mark of C&rsquo;s Group. The Disputed Domain Name was resolved to a parking page which gave no connection with a bona fide offering of goods or services. In addition, there was no evidence showing that R was commonly known by the Disputed Domain Name.</li>\n		<li>\n			R adopted an uncooperative and unresponsive attitude in respect of C&rsquo;s complaint on the Disputed Domain Name and failed to respond to the cease and desist letter sent by C&rsquo;s Representative. R intended to cause confusion to the public and ride on C&rsquo;s reputation in Asia. Furthermore, R&rsquo;s passive holding of the Disputed Domain Name was indeed a registration and usage in bad faith of the Disputed Domain Name as stated in the landmark Telstra case.</li>\n	</ul>\n	<wynnlasvegas.com>\n	<p>\n		As the Disputed Domain Name was registered under a registration agreement in Japanese, the default language of the proceeding should be Japanese in accordance with UDRP unless otherwise agreed by the parties or determined by the Panel. C requested to use English as the language of proceeding on the ground that C cannot understand Japanese, and English was widely spoken around the world.</p>\n	<p>\n		The Centre served the Written Notice to R bilingually in both English and Japanese and invited R to comment on C&rsquo;s request on the language of proceeding. Within the required period of time, R filed no Response.</p>\n	<p>\n		<strong>Held</strong>, granting the remedy sought, that:</p>\n	<p>\n		Having considered that R raised no objection to C&rsquo;s request for using English as the language of proceeding and the Commencement Notification served by ADNDRC was made to the parties in both Japanese and English, the Panel determined that the rest of the proceeding be conducted in English.</p>\n	<p>\n		The Panel agreed that the new gTLD &ldquo;tokyo&rdquo; did not reduce the similarity between the Disputed Domain Name and C&rsquo;s Mark, and held that the Disputed Domain Name was confusingly similar to C&rsquo;s Mark.</p>\n	<p>\n		The Panel found that R had no rights to or legitimate interests in the Disputed Domain Name, based on the fact that C had not authorisesd, licensed or permitted R to use the Mark, and that R had no connection with a bona fide offering of goods and services and was not known by the Disputed Domain Name.</p>\n	<p>\n		The Panel was of the view that due to the well-known status of C&rsquo;s Mark in Asia including Japan where R resided, R should have actual knowledge of the Mark. In addition, the Panel also took into account that R provided no evidence whatsoever of any actual or contemplated good faith use by it of the Disputed Domain Name. The Panel held that R&rsquo;s passive holding of the Disputed Domain Name constituted bad faith registration and usage of the Disputed Domain Name.<br />\n		In accordance with para. 4(i) of the UDRP, the Panel granted the relief sought by ordering the transfer of the Disputed Domain Name to C.</p>\n	<hr />\n	<p>\n		The full decision can be downloaded in the website of ADNDRC at <a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500760_Decision.pdf\">http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500760_Decision.pdf</a>.</p>\n	</wynnlasvegas.com></wynn.tokyo></p>\";s:7:\"summary\";s:275:\"Intellectual Property – Application of ICANN Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (UDRP) to New gTLD Dispute – The Panel’s Decision on language issue in favour of the Complainant to use English rather than the default Japanese as the Language of the Proceeding\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:4974:\"<p>Intellectual Property – Application of ICANN Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (UDRP) to New gTLD Dispute – The Panel’s Decision on language issue in favour of the Complainant to use English rather than the default Japanese as the Language of the Proceeding\n</p><p>\n	Wynn Resorts Holdings, LLC v Hiroki Kanoya</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500760_Decision.pdf\">HK-1500760</a> \"wynn.tokyo\"<br />\n	Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)<br />\n	Ho-Hyun Nahm (Panelist)<br />\n	22 July 2015</p>\n<p>\n	Complainant (hereinafter “C”) was the holder of a number of registered trademarks incorporating the mark of “WYNN” (the “Mark”). Respondent (hereinafter “R”) was an individual domiciled in Japan who registered the domain name <wynn.tokyo>(the “Disputed Domain Name”) under the new generic Top-Level Domain (“gTLD”) “.TOKYO”.</wynn.tokyo></p>\n<p>\n	<wynn.tokyo></wynn.tokyo></p>\n<p>\n		On 11 June 2015, C filed an UDRP complaint against R with the Hong Kong Office of the Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (the “Centre”), seeking transfer of the Disputed Domain Name based on the grounds specified below:-</p>\n<ul><li>\n			C was a famous American-based international gaming entertainment company and hotel gaming resorts developer founded by a veteran Las Vegas gaming mogul Mr. Steve Wynn and its predecessor from 1973 to 2000. The prominent and distinctive part of the Disputed Domain Name “wynn” was identical to C’s Mark and the new gTLD “.tokyo” placed after the Mark gave a strong visual similarity to other domain names registered by C like <wynnlasvegas.com>.</wynnlasvegas.com></li>\n<li>\n			C and its Group companies had not authorised or otherwise permitted R to use the Mark or any other name/mark of C’s Group. The Disputed Domain Name was resolved to a parking page which gave no connection with a bona fide offering of goods or services. In addition, there was no evidence showing that R was commonly known by the Disputed Domain Name.</li>\n<li>\n			R adopted an uncooperative and unresponsive attitude in respect of C’s complaint on the Disputed Domain Name and failed to respond to the cease and desist letter sent by C’s Representative. R intended to cause confusion to the public and ride on C’s reputation in Asia. Furthermore, R’s passive holding of the Disputed Domain Name was indeed a registration and usage in bad faith of the Disputed Domain Name as stated in the landmark Telstra case.</li>\n</ul><p>	<wynnlasvegas.com></wynnlasvegas.com></p>\n<p>\n		As the Disputed Domain Name was registered under a registration agreement in Japanese, the default language of the proceeding should be Japanese in accordance with UDRP unless otherwise agreed by the parties or determined by the Panel. C requested to use English as the language of proceeding on the ground that C cannot understand Japanese, and English was widely spoken around the world.</p>\n<p>\n		The Centre served the Written Notice to R bilingually in both English and Japanese and invited R to comment on C’s request on the language of proceeding. Within the required period of time, R filed no Response.</p>\n<p>\n		<strong>Held</strong>, granting the remedy sought, that:</p>\n<p>\n		Having considered that R raised no objection to C’s request for using English as the language of proceeding and the Commencement Notification served by ADNDRC was made to the parties in both Japanese and English, the Panel determined that the rest of the proceeding be conducted in English.</p>\n<p>\n		The Panel agreed that the new gTLD “tokyo” did not reduce the similarity between the Disputed Domain Name and C’s Mark, and held that the Disputed Domain Name was confusingly similar to C’s Mark.</p>\n<p>\n		The Panel found that R had no rights to or legitimate interests in the Disputed Domain Name, based on the fact that C had not authorisesd, licensed or permitted R to use the Mark, and that R had no connection with a bona fide offering of goods and services and was not known by the Disputed Domain Name.</p>\n<p>\n		The Panel was of the view that due to the well-known status of C’s Mark in Asia including Japan where R resided, R should have actual knowledge of the Mark. In addition, the Panel also took into account that R provided no evidence whatsoever of any actual or contemplated good faith use by it of the Disputed Domain Name. The Panel held that R’s passive holding of the Disputed Domain Name constituted bad faith registration and usage of the Disputed Domain Name.<br />\n		In accordance with para. 4(i) of the UDRP, the Panel granted the relief sought by ordering the transfer of the Disputed Domain Name to C.</p>\n<hr /><p>\n		The full decision can be downloaded in the website of ADNDRC at <a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500760_Decision.pdf\">http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500760_Decision.pdf</a>.</p>\n<p>	</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:283:\"<p>Intellectual Property – Application of ICANN Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (UDRP) to New gTLD Dispute – The Panel’s Decision on language issue in favour of the Complainant to use English rather than the default Japanese as the Language of the Proceeding</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:62:\"Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:62:\"Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:42:\"Wynn Resorts Holdings, LLC v Hiroki Kanoya\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:42:\"Wynn Resorts Holdings, LLC v Hiroki Kanoya\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-10-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:63:\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500760_Decision.pdf\";s:5:\"title\";s:10:\"HK-1500760\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"22 July 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"22 July 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"Dispute Resolution\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"Dispute Resolution\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:42:\"Wynn Resorts Holdings, LLC v Hiroki Kanoya\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1444694400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8794','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8794\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:69:\"Park Lomen Inn Ltd v Appeal Board (Hotel and Guesthouse Accommodation\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8794\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1447113600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252662\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8794\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252662\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3434:\"<p>Court of Appeal – appeal – ex parte appeals – observations for Rules Committee to consider in revising rules on reckoning of time in ex parte appeals</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Park Lomen Inn Ltd v Appeal Board (Hotel and Guesthouse Accommodation)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e00000150b7af40c2e2e29c66&amp;docguid=IB7B95F144C294F829A3F07C4F5221E99&amp;hitguid=IB7B95F144C294F829A3F07C4F5221E99&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=8\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 506</a><br />\r\nCourt of Appeal<br />\r\nCivil Appeal No. 171 of 2015 &amp; Miscellaneous Proceedings No. 486 of 2015<br />\r\nLam V-P, Cheung and Kwan JJA<br />\r\n4 August 2015</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Hotel Superintendent (the “Superintendent”) cancelled X’s licence for the operation of a guesthouse based on a conviction for having operated a guesthouse in premises other than the licensed premises. On 10 February 2015, the Judge refused X’s <em>ex parte</em> application for leave to judicially review the decision of the Appeal Board (Hotel and Guesthouse Accommodation) (the “Board”) to uphold the Superintendent’s decision (the “Order”). On 24 February 2015, X attempted to “file” a notice of appeal (the “Notice”), which the Appeal Registry refused because the Order had not been sealed. However, the Registry staff said that the Notice could be served and the Order sealed and perfected within seven days. On the same day, X served the Notice, which sought an interim stay of the cancellation of the licence pending appeal, on the Board as “proposed respondent”. On 25 February 2015, the Order was perfected. On 26February 2015, X attempted to “file” the Notice and sealed Order but was told that it was filed out of time and an extension of time was required. On 2 March 2015, X issued the present application for an extension of time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, granting an extension of time, but dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The appeal against an <em>ex parte</em> refusal of leave to apply for judicial review, could, depending on circumstances, be proceeded with on an <em>inter partes</em> or <em>ex parte</em> basis. Given the application for an interim stay, X was justified in serving the Notice in accordance with the Registry staff’s suggestion. Once this was done, the appeal became <em>inter partes</em>. In the circumstances, X had served the Notice within time under O. 53 r. 3(4) read together with O. 59 r. 3 of the RHC. Pursuant to O. 59 r. 5(1), X had seven days from 24 February 2015 to lodge the sealed Order. The attempt by X’s solicitors to do so on 26 February 2015 was within time, but because the Registry refused it, the documents were not in fact lodged and the prescribed fee was not paid. X therefore needed an extension of time to comply with O. 59 r. 5(1). Given the unusual circumstances leading to such delay through no fault of X, the proper course was to grant an extension to 23 July 2015 irrespective of the merits.</li>\r\n	<li>The Judge had correctly refused leave. X’s grounds of appeal were not reasonably arguable. Inter alia, as the administration of the licensing regime, the Superintendent and the Board were entitled to take a serious view of the safety risks associated with unlicensed premises and to adopt a more stringent policy of enforcement after an incident in 2009.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:164:\"<p>Court of Appeal – appeal – ex parte appeals – observations for Rules Committee to consider in revising rules on reckoning of time in ex parte appeals</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3407:\"<p>Court of Appeal – appeal – ex parte appeals – observations for Rules Committee to consider in revising rules on reckoning of time in ex parte appeals</p>\n<p>Park Lomen Inn Ltd v Appeal Board (Hotel and Guesthouse Accommodation)</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e00000150b7af40c2e2e29c66&amp;docguid=IB7B95F144C294F829A3F07C4F5221E99&amp;hitguid=IB7B95F144C294F829A3F07C4F5221E99&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=8\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 506</a><br />\nCourt of Appeal<br />\nCivil Appeal No. 171 of 2015 &amp; Miscellaneous Proceedings No. 486 of 2015<br />\nLam V-P, Cheung and Kwan JJA<br />\n4 August 2015</p>\n<p>The Hotel Superintendent (the “Superintendent”) cancelled X’s licence for the operation of a guesthouse based on a conviction for having operated a guesthouse in premises other than the licensed premises. On 10 February 2015, the Judge refused X’s <em>ex parte</em> application for leave to judicially review the decision of the Appeal Board (Hotel and Guesthouse Accommodation) (the “Board”) to uphold the Superintendent’s decision (the “Order”). On 24 February 2015, X attempted to “file” a notice of appeal (the “Notice”), which the Appeal Registry refused because the Order had not been sealed. However, the Registry staff said that the Notice could be served and the Order sealed and perfected within seven days. On the same day, X served the Notice, which sought an interim stay of the cancellation of the licence pending appeal, on the Board as “proposed respondent”. On 25 February 2015, the Order was perfected. On 26February 2015, X attempted to “file” the Notice and sealed Order but was told that it was filed out of time and an extension of time was required. On 2 March 2015, X issued the present application for an extension of time.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, granting an extension of time, but dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\n<ul><li>The appeal against an <em>ex parte</em> refusal of leave to apply for judicial review, could, depending on circumstances, be proceeded with on an <em>inter partes</em> or <em>ex parte</em> basis. Given the application for an interim stay, X was justified in serving the Notice in accordance with the Registry staff’s suggestion. Once this was done, the appeal became <em>inter partes</em>. In the circumstances, X had served the Notice within time under O. 53 r. 3(4) read together with O. 59 r. 3 of the RHC. Pursuant to O. 59 r. 5(1), X had seven days from 24 February 2015 to lodge the sealed Order. The attempt by X’s solicitors to do so on 26 February 2015 was within time, but because the Registry refused it, the documents were not in fact lodged and the prescribed fee was not paid. X therefore needed an extension of time to comply with O. 59 r. 5(1). Given the unusual circumstances leading to such delay through no fault of X, the proper course was to grant an extension to 23 July 2015 irrespective of the merits.</li>\n<li>The Judge had correctly refused leave. X’s grounds of appeal were not reasonably arguable. Inter alia, as the administration of the licensing regime, the Superintendent and the Board were entitled to take a serious view of the safety risks associated with unlicensed premises and to adopt a more stringent policy of enforcement after an incident in 2009.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:163:\"<p>Court of Appeal – appeal – ex parte appeals – observations for Rules Committee to consider in revising rules on reckoning of time in ex parte appeals</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:69:\"Park Lomen Inn Ltd v Appeal Board (Hotel and Guesthouse Accommodation\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:69:\"Park Lomen Inn Ltd v Appeal Board (Hotel and Guesthouse Accommodation\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-11-01 00:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:231:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad69f8e00000150b7af40c2e2e29c66&docguid=IB7B95F144C294F829A3F07C4F5221E99&hitguid=IB7B95F144C294F829A3F07C4F5221E99&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=8\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 4 HKLRD 506\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:13:\"4 August 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:13:\"4 August 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:69:\"Park Lomen Inn Ltd v Appeal Board (Hotel and Guesthouse Accommodation\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1447113600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8796','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8796\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:55:\"SNE Engineering Co Ltd v Hsin Chong Construction Co Ltd\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8796\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1447113600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252664\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8796\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252664\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3249:\"Patents – infringement – joint tortfeasor – whether defendant acted in way which furthered commission of tort by another pursuant to common design – no evidence of knowledge or intention of infringement<p>\n	SNE Engineering Co Ltd v Hsin Chong Construction Co Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6400000150b7b525e58793155c&amp;docguid=I457DE2C6BC9C485BA250ED2ED9C76F09&amp;hitguid=I457DE2C6BC9C485BA250ED2ED9C76F09&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=22&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=25\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 517</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Civil Appeal No. 88 of 2014<br />\n	Lam V-P, Cheung and Kwan JJA<br />\n	6 August 2015</p>\n<p>\n	P was engaged by D1, a contractor for pile removal works at a site for a railway project, as a subcontractor for the works. P engaged D2 to supply machinery and operators for the works. The works did not progress at the rate anticipated and D1 considered terminating P&rsquo;s subcontract. P then successfully applied for the registration of a Hong Kong short-term patent (the &ldquo;Patent&rdquo;) under Pt.XV of the Patents Ordinance (Cap.514) (the &ldquo;Ordinance&rdquo;) for a &ldquo;rotator and wedge&rdquo; method of extracting building piles from the ground (the &ldquo;Method&rdquo;). D1 terminated the subcontract and P commenced proceedings against Ds, claiming that the key concepts of the Method were the use of a wedge as a jamming and immobilising device between the pile and the internal surface of a steel casing; and the trapping of the pile inside the casing, which rotated causing the pile to twist and to break at a predetermined point. P contended that D1 used the Method to continue with the works at the site without P&rsquo;s permission and D2 participated in such infringement. The Judge dismissed P&rsquo;s claims, holding that the specification of the Patent did not disclose the invention in a manner sufficiently clear and complete for it to be performed by a person skilled in the art; and alternatively, the Method had been made available to the public and was not new. P appealed.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		P had to plead a case of common design if it wished to make D2 a secondary party as a joint tortfeasor, and had failed to do so. In any event, the Judge was right in rejecting such contention. To establish accessory liability in tort, a defendant must have acted in a way which furthered the commission of the tort by another pursuant to a common design to do or secure the doing of the acts which constituted the tort. The required limitation on the scope of liability, founded on a pragmatic concern to limit the propensity of the law of tort to interfere with a person&rsquo;s right to things which were in themselves entirely lawful, was achieved by the combination of active cooperation and commonality of intention. D2 was a supplier of equipment and operators. There was no evidence that D2 knew the equipment and operators were being used to commit an infringement of the Patent or that D1 was infringing the Patent. The mere supply of equipment which was known to be capable of being used to commit a tort did not suggest intent.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:210:\"Patents – infringement – joint tortfeasor – whether defendant acted in way which furthered commission of tort by another pursuant to common design – no evidence of knowledge or intention of infringement\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3206:\"<p>Patents – infringement – joint tortfeasor – whether defendant acted in way which furthered commission of tort by another pursuant to common design – no evidence of knowledge or intention of infringement\n</p><p>\n	SNE Engineering Co Ltd v Hsin Chong Construction Co Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6400000150b7b525e58793155c&amp;docguid=I457DE2C6BC9C485BA250ED2ED9C76F09&amp;hitguid=I457DE2C6BC9C485BA250ED2ED9C76F09&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=22&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=25\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 517</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Civil Appeal No. 88 of 2014<br />\n	Lam V-P, Cheung and Kwan JJA<br />\n	6 August 2015</p>\n<p>\n	P was engaged by D1, a contractor for pile removal works at a site for a railway project, as a subcontractor for the works. P engaged D2 to supply machinery and operators for the works. The works did not progress at the rate anticipated and D1 considered terminating P’s subcontract. P then successfully applied for the registration of a Hong Kong short-term patent (the “Patent”) under Pt.XV of the Patents Ordinance (Cap.514) (the “Ordinance”) for a “rotator and wedge” method of extracting building piles from the ground (the “Method”). D1 terminated the subcontract and P commenced proceedings against Ds, claiming that the key concepts of the Method were the use of a wedge as a jamming and immobilising device between the pile and the internal surface of a steel casing; and the trapping of the pile inside the casing, which rotated causing the pile to twist and to break at a predetermined point. P contended that D1 used the Method to continue with the works at the site without P’s permission and D2 participated in such infringement. The Judge dismissed P’s claims, holding that the specification of the Patent did not disclose the invention in a manner sufficiently clear and complete for it to be performed by a person skilled in the art; and alternatively, the Method had been made available to the public and was not new. P appealed.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		P had to plead a case of common design if it wished to make D2 a secondary party as a joint tortfeasor, and had failed to do so. In any event, the Judge was right in rejecting such contention. To establish accessory liability in tort, a defendant must have acted in a way which furthered the commission of the tort by another pursuant to a common design to do or secure the doing of the acts which constituted the tort. The required limitation on the scope of liability, founded on a pragmatic concern to limit the propensity of the law of tort to interfere with a person’s right to things which were in themselves entirely lawful, was achieved by the combination of active cooperation and commonality of intention. D2 was a supplier of equipment and operators. There was no evidence that D2 knew the equipment and operators were being used to commit an infringement of the Patent or that D1 was infringing the Patent. The mere supply of equipment which was known to be capable of being used to commit a tort did not suggest intent.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:218:\"<p>Patents – infringement – joint tortfeasor – whether defendant acted in way which furthered commission of tort by another pursuant to common design – no evidence of knowledge or intention of infringement</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:55:\"SNE Engineering Co Ltd v Hsin Chong Construction Co Ltd\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:55:\"SNE Engineering Co Ltd v Hsin Chong Construction Co Ltd\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"110\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-11-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:233:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744cc6400000150b7b525e58793155c&docguid=I457DE2C6BC9C485BA250ED2ED9C76F09&hitguid=I457DE2C6BC9C485BA250ED2ED9C76F09&spos=1&epos=1&td=22&crumb-action=append&context=25\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 4 HKLRD 517\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:13:\"6 August 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:13:\"6 August 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:21:\"Intellectual Property\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:21:\"Intellectual Property\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:55:\"SNE Engineering Co Ltd v Hsin Chong Construction Co Ltd\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1447113600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8798','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8798\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:32:\"Re Estate of Au Kong Tim (No. 2)\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8798\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1447113600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252662\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8798\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252662\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:1763:\"<p>Interrogatories – setting aside – duty to answer interrogatories lay on parties, not potential witnesses – interrogatories relating to credibility not allowed</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Re Estate of Au Kong Tim (No. 2)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e00000150b7b043252d84ad34&amp;docguid=I51CEF823C4D6428EB7D7B502D91BB88C&amp;hitguid=I51CEF823C4D6428EB7D7B502D91BB88C&amp;spos=3&amp;epos=3&amp;td=44&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=11\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 471</a><br />\r\nCourt of First Instance<br />\r\nProbate Action No. 7 of 2010<br />\r\nAndrew Chung J in Chambers<br />\r\n24 July 2015</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In contentious probate proceedings, D alleged that he was appointed as an executor under a will made by the deceased and witnessed by two solicitors (Ss). P1–2 served interrogatories on D, but intended that Ss answer the interrogatories on affidavit. D applied to set aside the interrogatories.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, granting the application, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The Rules of the High Court (Cap.4A, Sub. Leg.) (the “RHC”) did not provide for potential witnesses to be compelled to answer interrogatories by affidavit. Order 26 r. 1(1) of the RHC stipulates that interrogatories had to be served on parties, not witnesses or third parties. Under O. 26 r. 2(2), the duty to answer interrogatories lay with parties, not witnesses or third parties; and this could also be discerned from rr. 5(2), 5(3), 6(1) and 6(2).</li>\r\n	<li>In any event, interrogatories must be necessary either for: (a) disposing fairly of the cause or matter; or (b) saving costs. Here, they were not allowed because they related to matters for cross-examination on credibility or they were irrelevant.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:173:\"<p>Interrogatories – setting aside – duty to answer interrogatories lay on parties, not potential witnesses – interrogatories relating to credibility not allowed</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:1736:\"<p>Interrogatories – setting aside – duty to answer interrogatories lay on parties, not potential witnesses – interrogatories relating to credibility not allowed</p>\n<p>Re Estate of Au Kong Tim (No. 2)</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e00000150b7b043252d84ad34&amp;docguid=I51CEF823C4D6428EB7D7B502D91BB88C&amp;hitguid=I51CEF823C4D6428EB7D7B502D91BB88C&amp;spos=3&amp;epos=3&amp;td=44&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=11\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 471</a><br />\nCourt of First Instance<br />\nProbate Action No. 7 of 2010<br />\nAndrew Chung J in Chambers<br />\n24 July 2015</p>\n<p>In contentious probate proceedings, D alleged that he was appointed as an executor under a will made by the deceased and witnessed by two solicitors (Ss). P1–2 served interrogatories on D, but intended that Ss answer the interrogatories on affidavit. D applied to set aside the interrogatories.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, granting the application, that:</p>\n<ul><li>The Rules of the High Court (Cap.4A, Sub. Leg.) (the “RHC”) did not provide for potential witnesses to be compelled to answer interrogatories by affidavit. Order 26 r. 1(1) of the RHC stipulates that interrogatories had to be served on parties, not witnesses or third parties. Under O. 26 r. 2(2), the duty to answer interrogatories lay with parties, not witnesses or third parties; and this could also be discerned from rr. 5(2), 5(3), 6(1) and 6(2).</li>\n<li>In any event, interrogatories must be necessary either for: (a) disposing fairly of the cause or matter; or (b) saving costs. Here, they were not allowed because they related to matters for cross-examination on credibility or they were irrelevant.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:172:\"<p>Interrogatories – setting aside – duty to answer interrogatories lay on parties, not potential witnesses – interrogatories relating to credibility not allowed</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:32:\"Re Estate of Au Kong Tim (No. 2)\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:32:\"Re Estate of Au Kong Tim (No. 2)\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-11-01 00:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:233:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad69f8e00000150b7b043252d84ad34&docguid=I51CEF823C4D6428EB7D7B502D91BB88C&hitguid=I51CEF823C4D6428EB7D7B502D91BB88C&spos=3&epos=3&td=44&crumb-action=append&context=11\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 4 HKLRD 471\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"24 July 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"24 July 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:32:\"Re Estate of Au Kong Tim (No. 2)\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1447113600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8800','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8800\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:28:\"HKSAR v Lam Yat Fung Timothy\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8800\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1447113600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252662\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8800\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252662\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3815:\"<p>Witness — informer — whether prosecution obliged to disclose whether prosecution witness was informer — whether, without such disclosure, defendant’s innocence would be at stake, so as to justify departure from “informer privilege” rule</p>\r\n\r\n<p>HKSAR v Lam Yat Fung Timothy</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/search/run?ao=o.I05F65DF0BB8E44E2958F911CF8D0E23D&amp;srguid=&amp;context=13&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;crumb-label=Search+Results&amp;ntocview=I05F65DF0BB8E44E2958F911CF8D0E23D&amp;frt=HKSAR+v+Lam+Yat+Fung+timothy&amp;pty=&amp;cit=&amp;snippets=true&amp;buttonSearch=Search\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 679</a><br />\r\nCourt of Appeal<br />\r\nCriminal Appeal No. 178 of 2013<br />\r\nCheung, Kwan JJA and Derek Pang J<br />\r\n14 July 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>D was convicted of trafficking in a dangerous drug, namely 1.46 kg of ketamine. Acting on intelligence, police conducted an anti-drugs operation targeting PW1 and intercepted him leaving his flat with D and another man (“T”). Traces of ketamine were found on an electronic scale and two spoons inside two boxes which PW1 was carrying and one of three rubbish bags which D was holding. T was carrying a box containing eights packets of ketamine and a bag containing 23 packets of ketamine. Police seized a thermosealer from the flat. Traces of ketamine were found on the three men’s hands, but none on D’s fingernails. D, PW1 and T were charged with trafficking in a dangerous drug. PW1 pleaded guilty and gave evidence against D as a prosecution witness, stating that he had no previous experience of drugs or trafficking, he had been solicited by D and T to participate in the trafficking and let them use his flat to pack the drugs in exchange for money. D testified that he went to PW1’s home, played computer games and then went to sleep. He denied knowledge of the ketamine and asserted that his hands became contaminated with traces of it from touching a table there. D applied for leave to appeal against conviction. Before dealing with that application, the Court dealt with D’s application for the prosecution to disclose whether PW1 was an informer who had provided information about dangerous drugs to any law enforcement authority. D argued that such disclosure came under the “innocence at stake” exception to the informer privilege as: (a) the prosecution relied on PW1’s evidence to prove D’s knowledge of and participation in packing the ketamine; and (b) that if PW1 had previously been an informer in such a case, it would directly contradict his testimony that he had never before trafficked in drugs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>D had failed to prove that whether PW1 had previously provided intelligence on dangerous drugs was sufficient to prove his innocence.</li>\r\n	<li>This was not a usual case of an informer setting up a trap for the accused. Whether PW1 was an informer was not relevant to D’s defence, much less of any essential relevance. Taken at its highest, D only used this ground to attack PW1’s integrity, but the inconsistencies in his evidence did not prove D’s innocence. Unless the privileged information went directly to one of the elements of the offence, it would not be sufficient to show that disclosure was necessary to demonstrate the defendant’s innocence. Simply advancing ancillary attacks on the prosecution case (eg by impugning the credibility of a prosecution witness or providing evidence suggesting that certain prosecution evidence was obtained unconstitutionally) would very seldom be sufficient.</li>\r\n	<li>Further, D had adduced at trial other evidence of contradictions in PW1’s evidence and it was not necessary to rely on any other information to perfect his defence.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:257:\"<p>Witness — informer — whether prosecution obliged to disclose whether prosecution witness was informer — whether, without such disclosure, defendant’s innocence would be at stake, so as to justify departure from “informer privilege” rule</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3786:\"<p>Witness — informer — whether prosecution obliged to disclose whether prosecution witness was informer — whether, without such disclosure, defendant’s innocence would be at stake, so as to justify departure from “informer privilege” rule</p>\n<p>HKSAR v Lam Yat Fung Timothy</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/search/run?ao=o.I05F65DF0BB8E44E2958F911CF8D0E23D&amp;srguid=&amp;context=13&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;crumb-label=Search+Results&amp;ntocview=I05F65DF0BB8E44E2958F911CF8D0E23D&amp;frt=HKSAR+v+Lam+Yat+Fung+timothy&amp;pty=&amp;cit=&amp;snippets=true&amp;buttonSearch=Search\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 679</a><br />\nCourt of Appeal<br />\nCriminal Appeal No. 178 of 2013<br />\nCheung, Kwan JJA and Derek Pang J<br />\n14 July 2014</p>\n<p>D was convicted of trafficking in a dangerous drug, namely 1.46 kg of ketamine. Acting on intelligence, police conducted an anti-drugs operation targeting PW1 and intercepted him leaving his flat with D and another man (“T”). Traces of ketamine were found on an electronic scale and two spoons inside two boxes which PW1 was carrying and one of three rubbish bags which D was holding. T was carrying a box containing eights packets of ketamine and a bag containing 23 packets of ketamine. Police seized a thermosealer from the flat. Traces of ketamine were found on the three men’s hands, but none on D’s fingernails. D, PW1 and T were charged with trafficking in a dangerous drug. PW1 pleaded guilty and gave evidence against D as a prosecution witness, stating that he had no previous experience of drugs or trafficking, he had been solicited by D and T to participate in the trafficking and let them use his flat to pack the drugs in exchange for money. D testified that he went to PW1’s home, played computer games and then went to sleep. He denied knowledge of the ketamine and asserted that his hands became contaminated with traces of it from touching a table there. D applied for leave to appeal against conviction. Before dealing with that application, the Court dealt with D’s application for the prosecution to disclose whether PW1 was an informer who had provided information about dangerous drugs to any law enforcement authority. D argued that such disclosure came under the “innocence at stake” exception to the informer privilege as: (a) the prosecution relied on PW1’s evidence to prove D’s knowledge of and participation in packing the ketamine; and (b) that if PW1 had previously been an informer in such a case, it would directly contradict his testimony that he had never before trafficked in drugs.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\n<ul><li>D had failed to prove that whether PW1 had previously provided intelligence on dangerous drugs was sufficient to prove his innocence.</li>\n<li>This was not a usual case of an informer setting up a trap for the accused. Whether PW1 was an informer was not relevant to D’s defence, much less of any essential relevance. Taken at its highest, D only used this ground to attack PW1’s integrity, but the inconsistencies in his evidence did not prove D’s innocence. Unless the privileged information went directly to one of the elements of the offence, it would not be sufficient to show that disclosure was necessary to demonstrate the defendant’s innocence. Simply advancing ancillary attacks on the prosecution case (eg by impugning the credibility of a prosecution witness or providing evidence suggesting that certain prosecution evidence was obtained unconstitutionally) would very seldom be sufficient.</li>\n<li>Further, D had adduced at trial other evidence of contradictions in PW1’s evidence and it was not necessary to rely on any other information to perfect his defence.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:256:\"<p>Witness — informer — whether prosecution obliged to disclose whether prosecution witness was informer — whether, without such disclosure, defendant’s innocence would be at stake, so as to justify departure from “informer privilege” rule</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:28:\"HKSAR v Lam Yat Fung Timothy\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:28:\"HKSAR v Lam Yat Fung Timothy\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"101\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-11-01 00:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:276:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/search/run?ao=o.I05F65DF0BB8E44E2958F911CF8D0E23D&srguid=&context=13&crumb-action=append&crumb-label=Search+Results&ntocview=I05F65DF0BB8E44E2958F911CF8D0E23D&frt=HKSAR+v+Lam+Yat+Fung+timothy&pty=&cit=&snippets=true&buttonSearch=Search\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 4 HKLRD 679\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"14 July 2014\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"14 July 2014\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:17:\"Criminal Evidence\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:17:\"Criminal Evidence\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:28:\"HKSAR v Lam Yat Fung Timothy\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1447113600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8802','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8802\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:21:\"HKSAR v Lau Chun Pong\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8802\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1447113600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252662\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8802\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252662\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:4987:\"<p>Theft – joint charge – inference of common design – whether only reasonable and irresistible inference to be drawn – whether requisite mens rea established</p>\r\n\r\n<p>HKSAR v Lau Chun Pong</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/search/run?ao=o.I05F65DF0BB8E44E2958F911CF8D0E23D&amp;srguid=&amp;context=15&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;crumb-label=Search+Results&amp;ntocview=I05F65DF0BB8E44E2958F911CF8D0E23D&amp;frt=hksar+v+lau+chun+pong&amp;pty=&amp;cit=&amp;snippets=true&amp;buttonSearch=Search\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 583</a><br />\r\nCourt of First Instance<br />\r\nMagistracy Appeal No. 633 of 2013<br />\r\nAlbert Wong J<br />\r\n10 August 2015</p>\r\n\r\n<p>D was jointly charged with X, his girlfriend, of theft. X pleaded guilty while D was convicted after trial. The prosecution relied mainly on CCTV footage which showed D and X entering a McDonald’s restaurant together and sitting at the Entrance Table. D left his rucksack with X and went to the toilet, passing V seated at the Middle Table in a corridor. After leaving the toilet, all three corridor tables were unoccupied. D picked up V’s iPhone (the “iPhone”) from the Middle Table and returned to X at the Entrance Table. D showed the iPhone to X, they conversed, D put the iPhone in his bag and immediately left with X. On arrest and in court, D claimed that he took the iPhone because he thought it belonged to X. D testified that the iPhone was the same brand as X’s; she had a habit of leaving her belongings behind; she might have gone to the toilet and left her mobile telephone on the table; and when he asked X if the iPhone was hers, she said, “Yes” and put it in her handbag. In cross-examining D and in closing submissions, the prosecution seemingly suggested that it was sufficient to prove that D alone committed the offence. After the Deputy Magistrate repeatedly emphasised that D faced a joint charge, the prosecution submitted that when D took the iPhone and showed it to X, it became a “joint venture” between them and they treated the iPhone as their own. D appealed against conviction arguing that the Deputy Magistrate erred in: (a) holding that the only reasonable and irresistible inference was that “at all material time” both D and X knew the iPhone belonged to a third party and shared a common intention to steal it; and (b) rejecting D’s explanation, <em>inter alia</em>, on the basis that it was incredible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>At the present hearing, the prosecution drew the Court’s attention to the CCTV footage which showed that when D returned to X, she was speaking on a mobile telephone and, contrary to D’s testimony and the Deputy Magistrate’s finding, D placed the iPhone in his own bag and left with X. While an appeal court was entitled to take into account all the evidence adduced at trial, D was not cross-examined as to his state of mind when he saw X speaking on another mobile telephone. Accordingly, the Court was not in a proper position to assess the weight to be attached to such evidence or consider its effect on the case.</li>\r\n	<li>On all the evidence, in particular the CCTV footage, the Deputy Magistrate’s rejection of the exculpatory part of D’s testimony should not be disturbed. Notwithstanding that the Court had concerns about the Deputy Magistrate’s view on alleged discrepancies mentioned by him, his decision was not flawed. D’s claimed belief was unreasonable.</li>\r\n	<li>Further, it was clear the Deputy Magistrate knew throughout that the charge was a joint one and after repeatedly reminding the prosecution of this, the prosecution then put to D an allegation which sat well with the charge. There was nothing to indicate that the defence was misled or prejudiced, or that the Deputy Magistrate’s decision did not concern whether the offence was jointly committed with X.</li>\r\n	<li>While the prosecution had clarified the timing of the “joint venture”, its exact basis, in particular the role and mens rea of D and X, was less than clear. This case should be decided by reference to s. 4(1) of the Theft Ordinance (Cap. 210). There was no reason to think the Deputy Magistrate had not done so. Reading his statement of findings in context, in saying that a joint intent was formed “at all material time”, he must have meant it was formed when the couple met again after D had picked up the iPhone. This was the only time it was possible for D and X to have jointly dishonestly appropriated the iPhone in the restaurant knowing it belonged to someone else and shared a common intention to permanently deprive the owner of it.</li>\r\n	<li>On the whole of the evidence, and given the rejection of the exculpatory part of D’s testimony, the Deputy Magistrate properly drew the only and irresistible inference that when D rejoined X, he decided to assume the rights as owner of the iPhone and stole it jointly with X.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:172:\"<p>Theft – joint charge – inference of common design – whether only reasonable and irresistible inference to be drawn – whether requisite mens rea established</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:4954:\"<p>Theft – joint charge – inference of common design – whether only reasonable and irresistible inference to be drawn – whether requisite mens rea established</p>\n<p>HKSAR v Lau Chun Pong</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/search/run?ao=o.I05F65DF0BB8E44E2958F911CF8D0E23D&amp;srguid=&amp;context=15&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;crumb-label=Search+Results&amp;ntocview=I05F65DF0BB8E44E2958F911CF8D0E23D&amp;frt=hksar+v+lau+chun+pong&amp;pty=&amp;cit=&amp;snippets=true&amp;buttonSearch=Search\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 583</a><br />\nCourt of First Instance<br />\nMagistracy Appeal No. 633 of 2013<br />\nAlbert Wong J<br />\n10 August 2015</p>\n<p>D was jointly charged with X, his girlfriend, of theft. X pleaded guilty while D was convicted after trial. The prosecution relied mainly on CCTV footage which showed D and X entering a McDonald’s restaurant together and sitting at the Entrance Table. D left his rucksack with X and went to the toilet, passing V seated at the Middle Table in a corridor. After leaving the toilet, all three corridor tables were unoccupied. D picked up V’s iPhone (the “iPhone”) from the Middle Table and returned to X at the Entrance Table. D showed the iPhone to X, they conversed, D put the iPhone in his bag and immediately left with X. On arrest and in court, D claimed that he took the iPhone because he thought it belonged to X. D testified that the iPhone was the same brand as X’s; she had a habit of leaving her belongings behind; she might have gone to the toilet and left her mobile telephone on the table; and when he asked X if the iPhone was hers, she said, “Yes” and put it in her handbag. In cross-examining D and in closing submissions, the prosecution seemingly suggested that it was sufficient to prove that D alone committed the offence. After the Deputy Magistrate repeatedly emphasised that D faced a joint charge, the prosecution submitted that when D took the iPhone and showed it to X, it became a “joint venture” between them and they treated the iPhone as their own. D appealed against conviction arguing that the Deputy Magistrate erred in: (a) holding that the only reasonable and irresistible inference was that “at all material time” both D and X knew the iPhone belonged to a third party and shared a common intention to steal it; and (b) rejecting D’s explanation, <em>inter alia</em>, on the basis that it was incredible.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\n<ul><li>At the present hearing, the prosecution drew the Court’s attention to the CCTV footage which showed that when D returned to X, she was speaking on a mobile telephone and, contrary to D’s testimony and the Deputy Magistrate’s finding, D placed the iPhone in his own bag and left with X. While an appeal court was entitled to take into account all the evidence adduced at trial, D was not cross-examined as to his state of mind when he saw X speaking on another mobile telephone. Accordingly, the Court was not in a proper position to assess the weight to be attached to such evidence or consider its effect on the case.</li>\n<li>On all the evidence, in particular the CCTV footage, the Deputy Magistrate’s rejection of the exculpatory part of D’s testimony should not be disturbed. Notwithstanding that the Court had concerns about the Deputy Magistrate’s view on alleged discrepancies mentioned by him, his decision was not flawed. D’s claimed belief was unreasonable.</li>\n<li>Further, it was clear the Deputy Magistrate knew throughout that the charge was a joint one and after repeatedly reminding the prosecution of this, the prosecution then put to D an allegation which sat well with the charge. There was nothing to indicate that the defence was misled or prejudiced, or that the Deputy Magistrate’s decision did not concern whether the offence was jointly committed with X.</li>\n<li>While the prosecution had clarified the timing of the “joint venture”, its exact basis, in particular the role and mens rea of D and X, was less than clear. This case should be decided by reference to s. 4(1) of the Theft Ordinance (Cap. 210). There was no reason to think the Deputy Magistrate had not done so. Reading his statement of findings in context, in saying that a joint intent was formed “at all material time”, he must have meant it was formed when the couple met again after D had picked up the iPhone. This was the only time it was possible for D and X to have jointly dishonestly appropriated the iPhone in the restaurant knowing it belonged to someone else and shared a common intention to permanently deprive the owner of it.</li>\n<li>On the whole of the evidence, and given the rejection of the exculpatory part of D’s testimony, the Deputy Magistrate properly drew the only and irresistible inference that when D rejoined X, he decided to assume the rights as owner of the iPhone and stole it jointly with X.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:171:\"<p>Theft – joint charge – inference of common design – whether only reasonable and irresistible inference to be drawn – whether requisite mens rea established</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:21:\"HKSAR v Lau Chun Pong\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:21:\"HKSAR v Lau Chun Pong\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"101\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-11-01 00:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:269:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/search/run?ao=o.I05F65DF0BB8E44E2958F911CF8D0E23D&srguid=&context=15&crumb-action=append&crumb-label=Search+Results&ntocview=I05F65DF0BB8E44E2958F911CF8D0E23D&frt=hksar+v+lau+chun+pong&pty=&cit=&snippets=true&buttonSearch=Search\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 4 HKLRD 583\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:14:\"10 August 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:14:\"10 August 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"Criminal Law\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"Criminal Law\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:21:\"HKSAR v Lau Chun Pong\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1447113600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8804','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8804\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:20:\"HKSAR v Yik Man Ying\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"1\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8804\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1447113600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1453263652\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8804\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1453263652\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2528:\"<p>Theft – defendant-employee stole smartphone left by customer on chair in boutique – defendant of clear record, remorseful and suffering from depression – community service order appropriate</p>\r\n\r\n<p>HKSAR v Yik Man Ying</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e00000150b7b39dada6c15281&amp;docguid=I565C2CEAE1094E45B8E408D0FCA376B4&amp;hitguid=I565C2CEAE1094E45B8E408D0FCA376B4&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=5&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=18\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 700</a><br />\r\nCourt of First Instance<br />\r\nMagistracy Appeal No. 49 of 2014<br />\r\nDeputy Judge Albert Wong<br />\r\n1 September 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>D, a boutique employee, was convicted of theft. V, a customer, placed her iPhone on a chair and went into the fitting room. D took V’s iPhone, put it underneath the chair and then, two hours later, in her own handbag. D initially denied, but later admitted, stealing V’s iPhone. D was of clear record. A background report noted that D had an 18-month-old child and suffered from postnatal depression requiring out-patient treatment. The Deputy Magistrate considered the theft premeditated and sentenced D to six months’ imprisonment and ordered to pay restitution of $7,000. D appealed against sentence. A community service order (“CSO”) report was favourable but, because of her depression, doubted D’s ability to cope with stress and so a CSO was not recommended.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, allowing the appeal by substituting a community service order of 80 hours, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A custodial sentence was generally appropriate for stealing mobile telephones, especially smartphones. In determining sentence, apart from the particular facts and the value of the mobile telephone, the court should also take into account the data stored on the telephone and so the intrusion of privacy and considerable inconvenience to the victim.</li>\r\n	<li>Here, the six-month starting point was excessive. The offence was not premeditated and D’s <em>modus operandi</em> was not sophisticated. An appropriate sentence would usually be four-months’ imprisonment. However, a CSO of 80 hours was appropriate given the special circumstances, namely D’s clear record, remorse and the fact she had been detained for 28 days, she was working again while on bail pending appeal and a better result could be achieved if she received professional counselling and psychiatric treatment outside without worrying about her son.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:204:\"<p>Theft – defendant-employee stole smartphone left by customer on chair in boutique – defendant of clear record, remorseful and suffering from depression – community service order appropriate</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2501:\"<p>Theft – defendant-employee stole smartphone left by customer on chair in boutique – defendant of clear record, remorseful and suffering from depression – community service order appropriate</p>\n<p>HKSAR v Yik Man Ying</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e00000150b7b39dada6c15281&amp;docguid=I565C2CEAE1094E45B8E408D0FCA376B4&amp;hitguid=I565C2CEAE1094E45B8E408D0FCA376B4&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=5&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=18\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 700</a><br />\nCourt of First Instance<br />\nMagistracy Appeal No. 49 of 2014<br />\nDeputy Judge Albert Wong<br />\n1 September 2014</p>\n<p>D, a boutique employee, was convicted of theft. V, a customer, placed her iPhone on a chair and went into the fitting room. D took V’s iPhone, put it underneath the chair and then, two hours later, in her own handbag. D initially denied, but later admitted, stealing V’s iPhone. D was of clear record. A background report noted that D had an 18-month-old child and suffered from postnatal depression requiring out-patient treatment. The Deputy Magistrate considered the theft premeditated and sentenced D to six months’ imprisonment and ordered to pay restitution of $7,000. D appealed against sentence. A community service order (“CSO”) report was favourable but, because of her depression, doubted D’s ability to cope with stress and so a CSO was not recommended.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, allowing the appeal by substituting a community service order of 80 hours, that:</p>\n<ul><li>A custodial sentence was generally appropriate for stealing mobile telephones, especially smartphones. In determining sentence, apart from the particular facts and the value of the mobile telephone, the court should also take into account the data stored on the telephone and so the intrusion of privacy and considerable inconvenience to the victim.</li>\n<li>Here, the six-month starting point was excessive. The offence was not premeditated and D’s <em>modus operandi</em> was not sophisticated. An appropriate sentence would usually be four-months’ imprisonment. However, a CSO of 80 hours was appropriate given the special circumstances, namely D’s clear record, remorse and the fact she had been detained for 28 days, she was working again while on bail pending appeal and a better result could be achieved if she received professional counselling and psychiatric treatment outside without worrying about her son.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:203:\"<p>Theft – defendant-employee stole smartphone left by customer on chair in boutique – defendant of clear record, remorseful and suffering from depression – community service order appropriate</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:20:\"HKSAR v Yik Man Ying\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:20:\"HKSAR v Yik Man Ying\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"101\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-11-01 00:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad69f8e00000150b7b39dada6c15281&docguid=I565C2CEAE1094E45B8E408D0FCA376B4&hitguid=I565C2CEAE1094E45B8E408D0FCA376B4&spos=2&epos=2&td=5&crumb-action=append&context=18\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 4 HKLRD 700\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"1 September 2014\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"1 September 2014\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"Criminal Sentencing\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:19:\"Criminal Sentencing\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:32:\"Magistracy Appeal No. 49 of 2014\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:32:\"Magistracy Appeal No. 49 of 2014\";}}}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:24:\"Deputy Judge Albert Wong\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:24:\"Deputy Judge Albert Wong\";}}}s:14:\"title_original\";s:20:\"HKSAR v Yik Man Ying\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";s:1:\"0\";s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450249313\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";N;s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8806','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8806\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:42:\"Wide Power Corp Ltd v Manhattan Court (IO)\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8806\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1447113600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1450252662\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8806\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450252662\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:4206:\"<p>Registration – lis pendens – counterclaim for injunction requiring plaintiff to remove unauthorised building works within premises – not registrable as lis pendens</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wide Power Corp Ltd v Manhattan Court (IO)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad6290300000150b7b6756655d68238&amp;docguid=I574756690DC345AC8342FF938A22E2C5&amp;hitguid=I574756690DC345AC8342FF938A22E2C5&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=103&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=32\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 480</a><br />\r\nCourt of First Instance<br />\r\nHigh Court Action No. 1485 of 2013<br />\r\nLouis Chan J in Chambers<br />\r\n31 July 2015</p>\r\n\r\n<p>P, the owner of a flat in a building, claimed against D, the incorporated owners, for various reliefs. D’s defence and counterclaim (the “Counterclaim”) alleged that P or previous owners had erected unauthorised building works (“UBWs”) in the flat contrary to the deed of mutual covenant (the “DMC”). The Counterclaim sought, <em>inter alia</em>, an injunction against P to remove the UBWs and to restore the flat to its previous condition. D registered the Counterclaim as a <em>lis pendens</em> against the flat. P took steps to remove the UBWs and applied for an order to vacate the Counterclaim from the Land Registry. D claimed that the removal works were incomplete and refused to do so. Before the hearing of P’s application, P sold the flat to a third party. The Master then dismissed P’s application. P appealed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, allowing the appeal:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>If the Counterclaim were a claim <em>in personam</em>, as D now accepted, the judgment that it might establish would not bind a subsequent bona fide purchaser or mortgagee. Thus, there was no reason why it should be allowed to be registered. <em>Res judicata</em> did not apply as between D and a subsequent <em>bona fide</em> purchaser or mortgagee of the flat. The judgment was also not a matter of title although it might be evidence of a breach by the existing owner of the DMC. What bound the subsequent purchaser or mortgagee was the DMC which had been registered. Even if the Counterclaim was not registered as a <em>lis pendens</em>, no <em>bona fide</em> purchaser or mortgagee of the flat could obtain a title to it free of the DMC. It was for the subsequent purchaser or mortgagee to be satisfied of any breach of the DMC before completion. If the owners had covered up such breaches when conveying the premises to the purchaser, then the purchaser could resort to contractual remedies against the previous owner.</li>\r\n	<li>As for the issue of notice, pursuant to s. 4 of the LRO, if a judgment (or <em>lis pendens</em>) was not registered, then even if the subsequent purchaser had actual notice of it, the assignment of the subsequent purchaser would still have a higher priority over it. If the importance of the registration lay in the giving of notice of a claim to the subsequent purchaser and the claim was not for any proprietary interest in or charge on the property, then there was no reason to limit the mode of giving notice only to registration at the Land Registry and to compel such registration with the sanction of listing priority. There were many ways of giving notice of an infringement of the DMC to a potential purchaser. Hence, s. 4 should not be for compelling registration for such purposes, but to compel registration of a judgment (or lis pendens) that claimed an interest in or charge on the property in question. This would facilitate the tracing and ascertaining of title.</li>\r\n	<li>These and other provisions of the LRO, namely, ss. 2, 3(2), 5, 5A, 14, 16 and 17, provided for and regulated the registration of a lis pendens which claimed a proprietary interest or right in a real property. They also regulated the priority of the claim in the <em>lis pendens</em>. The need to re-register a lis pendens was to ensure that it was a live claim. Such registration was not to give notice to a subsequent purchaser or mortgagee of alleged breaches of a DMC committed in a property and the claim for restoration to be executed in the property as in the Counterclaim.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:178:\"<p>Registration – lis pendens – counterclaim for injunction requiring plaintiff to remove unauthorised building works within premises – not registrable as lis pendens</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:4177:\"<p>Registration – lis pendens – counterclaim for injunction requiring plaintiff to remove unauthorised building works within premises – not registrable as lis pendens</p>\n<p>Wide Power Corp Ltd v Manhattan Court (IO)</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad6290300000150b7b6756655d68238&amp;docguid=I574756690DC345AC8342FF938A22E2C5&amp;hitguid=I574756690DC345AC8342FF938A22E2C5&amp;spos=2&amp;epos=2&amp;td=103&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=32\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 480</a><br />\nCourt of First Instance<br />\nHigh Court Action No. 1485 of 2013<br />\nLouis Chan J in Chambers<br />\n31 July 2015</p>\n<p>P, the owner of a flat in a building, claimed against D, the incorporated owners, for various reliefs. D’s defence and counterclaim (the “Counterclaim”) alleged that P or previous owners had erected unauthorised building works (“UBWs”) in the flat contrary to the deed of mutual covenant (the “DMC”). The Counterclaim sought, <em>inter alia</em>, an injunction against P to remove the UBWs and to restore the flat to its previous condition. D registered the Counterclaim as a <em>lis pendens</em> against the flat. P took steps to remove the UBWs and applied for an order to vacate the Counterclaim from the Land Registry. D claimed that the removal works were incomplete and refused to do so. Before the hearing of P’s application, P sold the flat to a third party. The Master then dismissed P’s application. P appealed.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, allowing the appeal:</p>\n<ul><li>If the Counterclaim were a claim <em>in personam</em>, as D now accepted, the judgment that it might establish would not bind a subsequent bona fide purchaser or mortgagee. Thus, there was no reason why it should be allowed to be registered. <em>Res judicata</em> did not apply as between D and a subsequent <em>bona fide</em> purchaser or mortgagee of the flat. The judgment was also not a matter of title although it might be evidence of a breach by the existing owner of the DMC. What bound the subsequent purchaser or mortgagee was the DMC which had been registered. Even if the Counterclaim was not registered as a <em>lis pendens</em>, no <em>bona fide</em> purchaser or mortgagee of the flat could obtain a title to it free of the DMC. It was for the subsequent purchaser or mortgagee to be satisfied of any breach of the DMC before completion. If the owners had covered up such breaches when conveying the premises to the purchaser, then the purchaser could resort to contractual remedies against the previous owner.</li>\n<li>As for the issue of notice, pursuant to s. 4 of the LRO, if a judgment (or <em>lis pendens</em>) was not registered, then even if the subsequent purchaser had actual notice of it, the assignment of the subsequent purchaser would still have a higher priority over it. If the importance of the registration lay in the giving of notice of a claim to the subsequent purchaser and the claim was not for any proprietary interest in or charge on the property, then there was no reason to limit the mode of giving notice only to registration at the Land Registry and to compel such registration with the sanction of listing priority. There were many ways of giving notice of an infringement of the DMC to a potential purchaser. Hence, s. 4 should not be for compelling registration for such purposes, but to compel registration of a judgment (or lis pendens) that claimed an interest in or charge on the property in question. This would facilitate the tracing and ascertaining of title.</li>\n<li>These and other provisions of the LRO, namely, ss. 2, 3(2), 5, 5A, 14, 16 and 17, provided for and regulated the registration of a lis pendens which claimed a proprietary interest or right in a real property. They also regulated the priority of the claim in the <em>lis pendens</em>. The need to re-register a lis pendens was to ensure that it was a live claim. Such registration was not to give notice to a subsequent purchaser or mortgagee of alleged breaches of a DMC committed in a property and the claim for restoration to be executed in the property as in the Counterclaim.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:177:\"<p>Registration – lis pendens – counterclaim for injunction requiring plaintiff to remove unauthorised building works within premises – not registrable as lis pendens</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1