o8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1447113600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458184699,1),('8808','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"8808\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:48:\"Boehringer Ingelheim International GmbH v 晏松\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"1\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"8808\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1447113600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456727539\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"8808\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1453361333\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:4685:\"<p>Intellectual Property – Whether the procedures should be carried out bilingually – Cyberflying</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Boehringer Ingelheim International GmbH v晏松</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DCN-1500638 \"SYNJARDY.CN\"<br />\r\nAsian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)<br />\r\nFan Kun (Panelist)<br />\r\n24 September 2015</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On 22 July 2015, Complainant (hereinafter “C”) initiated a domain name dispute resolution proceeding concerning (the “Disputed Domain Name”) under the CNNIC ccTLD Dispute Resolution Policy (the “Policy”) by filing a complaint with the Hong Kong Arbitration Centre (the “Centre”) against段佐春 (“Prior Registrant”).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On 23 July 2015, the HKIAC sent a New Case Notification by email to the Registrar about the commencement of proceedings over the disputed Domain Name. The email was copied to the CNNIC and the HKIAC requested that the CNNIC keep the above disputed Domain Name locked until the proceeding was finalised. On the same day, the Registrar acknowledged the email notification but informed the HKIAC that the Prior Registrant was no longer the registrant/holder of the Domain Name. Shortly after the Registrar’s acknowledgment, the Respondent (hereinafter “R”) contacted the HKIAC by email, and requested all the documents be submitted in Chinese because he did not understand English. The HKIAC noted that the disputed Domain Name Registrant was transferred from the Prior Registrant to R within approximately 30 minutes of the New Case Notification sent to the Registrar.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Upon being informed by the HKIAC of the administrative deficiencies of the Complaint, C duly filed the amended Complaint in English naming R and further requesting that the proceedings be conducted in English, with reasons for such request.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the Complaint, C contended that the Disputed Domain Name was identical to the trademark consisting in the wording Synjardy® owned by C in several countries, especially China. C is also the owner of an important domain names portfolio including the trademark SYNJARDY®. Further, C contended that R had no rights and legitimate interests in respective of the Disputed Domain Name and had registered and was using the Disputed Domain Name in bad faith.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>R failed to file any response within the required period of time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, granting the remedy sought, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Having considered the overarching objectives of the Policy in terms of efficiency and economy and concerns on procedural fairness, the Panel is of the opinion that it is fair and just to conduct the proceedings in the dual-language of English and Chinese. The special circumstances of this case which were taken into account included the fact that C is located in Germany with no knowledge of Chinese. In order to carry out the proceedings in Chinese, C would have to retain specialised translation services at a cost likely to be higher than the cost of these proceedings. Furthermore, there was evidence that R had replied to C’s cease-and-desist letter in English and R’s default signature was in English in all his email communications to the HKIAC. The Panel believes that this would have been a sufficient basis that R is able to read and understand English, at least in the context of domain name disputes. In view of not depriving any party from its right to a fair opportunity to present its case, the Panel believes a bilingual arrangement would have the advantage of allowing both parties to articulate their arguments while avoiding unnecessary expenses and delays on translations.</li>\r\n	<li>As regards the change in R’s information shortly after the Notification was given the Registrar, the Panel finds that R’s actions were deliberate disruptions by way of transfer of the Domain Name during a pending administrative proceeding. (<em>NRG Scandinavia A/S v. RexRotary Inc</em>, WIPO Case D2014-0790). The Panel found that R’s conduct constituted “cyberflying” because R acted “with full knowledge of the [domain name system], and with an appreciation of how the [dispute resolution system] might be manipulated in an effort to avoid the mandatory [...] proceeding [that] the Respondent agreed to submit to as a necessary condition of its registration of the disputed domain names”. Under such circumstances, this Panel found R’s actions to be a deliberate attempt to disrupt these proceedings in order to evade the jurisdiction of the Panel.</li>\r\n	<li>Having found that other contentions raised by C were justifiable, the Panel ordered that the Disputed Domain Name be transferred from R to C.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:107:\"<p>Intellectual Property – Whether the procedures should be carried out bilingually – Cyberflying</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:4638:\"<p>Intellectual Property – Whether the procedures should be carried out bilingually – Cyberflying</p>\n<p>Boehringer Ingelheim International GmbH v晏松</p>\n<p>DCN-1500638 \"SYNJARDY.CN\"<br />\nAsian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)<br />\nFan Kun (Panelist)<br />\n24 September 2015</p>\n<p>On 22 July 2015, Complainant (hereinafter “C”) initiated a domain name dispute resolution proceeding concerning (the “Disputed Domain Name”) under the CNNIC ccTLD Dispute Resolution Policy (the “Policy”) by filing a complaint with the Hong Kong Arbitration Centre (the “Centre”) against段佐春 (“Prior Registrant”).</p>\n<p>On 23 July 2015, the HKIAC sent a New Case Notification by email to the Registrar about the commencement of proceedings over the disputed Domain Name. The email was copied to the CNNIC and the HKIAC requested that the CNNIC keep the above disputed Domain Name locked until the proceeding was finalised. On the same day, the Registrar acknowledged the email notification but informed the HKIAC that the Prior Registrant was no longer the registrant/holder of the Domain Name. Shortly after the Registrar’s acknowledgment, the Respondent (hereinafter “R”) contacted the HKIAC by email, and requested all the documents be submitted in Chinese because he did not understand English. The HKIAC noted that the disputed Domain Name Registrant was transferred from the Prior Registrant to R within approximately 30 minutes of the New Case Notification sent to the Registrar.</p>\n<p>Upon being informed by the HKIAC of the administrative deficiencies of the Complaint, C duly filed the amended Complaint in English naming R and further requesting that the proceedings be conducted in English, with reasons for such request.</p>\n<p>In the Complaint, C contended that the Disputed Domain Name was identical to the trademark consisting in the wording Synjardy® owned by C in several countries, especially China. C is also the owner of an important domain names portfolio including the trademark SYNJARDY®. Further, C contended that R had no rights and legitimate interests in respective of the Disputed Domain Name and had registered and was using the Disputed Domain Name in bad faith.</p>\n<p>R failed to file any response within the required period of time.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, granting the remedy sought, that:</p>\n<ul><li>Having considered the overarching objectives of the Policy in terms of efficiency and economy and concerns on procedural fairness, the Panel is of the opinion that it is fair and just to conduct the proceedings in the dual-language of English and Chinese. The special circumstances of this case which were taken into account included the fact that C is located in Germany with no knowledge of Chinese. In order to carry out the proceedings in Chinese, C would have to retain specialised translation services at a cost likely to be higher than the cost of these proceedings. Furthermore, there was evidence that R had replied to C’s cease-and-desist letter in English and R’s default signature was in English in all his email communications to the HKIAC. The Panel believes that this would have been a sufficient basis that R is able to read and understand English, at least in the context of domain name disputes. In view of not depriving any party from its right to a fair opportunity to present its case, the Panel believes a bilingual arrangement would have the advantage of allowing both parties to articulate their arguments while avoiding unnecessary expenses and delays on translations.</li>\n<li>As regards the change in R’s information shortly after the Notification was given the Registrar, the Panel finds that R’s actions were deliberate disruptions by way of transfer of the Domain Name during a pending administrative proceeding. (<em>NRG Scandinavia A/S v. RexRotary Inc</em>, WIPO Case D2014-0790). The Panel found that R’s conduct constituted “cyberflying” because R acted “with full knowledge of the [domain name system], and with an appreciation of how the [dispute resolution system] might be manipulated in an effort to avoid the mandatory [...] proceeding [that] the Respondent agreed to submit to as a necessary condition of its registration of the disputed domain names”. Under such circumstances, this Panel found R’s actions to be a deliberate attempt to disrupt these proceedings in order to evade the jurisdiction of the Panel.</li>\n<li>Having found that other contentions raised by C were justifiable, the Panel ordered that the Disputed Domain Name be transferred from R to C.</li>\n</ul><p> </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:106:\"<p>Intellectual Property – Whether the procedures should be carried out bilingually – Cyberflying</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:5:\"value\";s:14:\"FeaturedBlock1\";}}}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:48:\"Boehringer Ingelheim International GmbH v 晏松\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:48:\"Boehringer Ingelheim International GmbH v 晏松\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-11-01 00:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\