:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";s:1:\"0\";s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1452670482\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";N;s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458182632,1),('9057','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9061\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:56:\"One Step Closer to a Right to be Forgotten in Hong Kong?\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9057\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929167\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9057\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929167\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:4498:\"Mark Parsons, Eugene Low and Dominic Edmondson, Hogan Lovells<p>\n	The Administrative Appeals Board rejected an appeal from David Webb against an enforcement notice issued by the Privacy Commissioner for Personal Data requiring that Mr. Webb remove from his website (webb-site.com) the names of parties set out in court judgments of matrimonial proceedings published on the Hong Kong Judiciary&rsquo;s website over a decade earlier.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Background</strong></p>\n<p>\n	David Webb is a former investment banker turned activist who runs a website offering information on corporate and economic governance in Hong Kong, including the various roles that particular individuals play in the financial and public sectors.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>The Decision</strong></p>\n<p>\n	The AAB confirmed that Mr. Webb had contravened Data Protection Principle 3 (&ldquo;DPP3&rdquo;) of the Personal Data (Privacy) Ordinance (Cap. 486) by continuing to publish hyperlinks on webb-site.com to three judgments handed down between 2000 and 2002 by the Court of Appeal, each of which had been subsequently redacted by the Judiciary to remove the names of the parties.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Determining the Relevant Purpose of Data Collection</strong></p>\n<p>\n	DPP3 requires that personal data shall not (without consent of the data subject) be used except for the purpose at the time that the data was collected, or a directly related purpose.</p>\n<p>\n	The AAB held that DPP3 is directed against the misuse of personal data, regardless of whether the relevant personal data has been published elsewhere or was in the public domain.</p>\n<p>\n	The AAB considered that &ldquo;the purpose for which the data was to be used at the time of the collection of the data&rdquo; was to enable the Judiciary&rsquo;s judgments to be utilised as &ldquo;legal precedents on points of law, practice and procedure of the courts and of public interests&rdquo; and not to identify the parties in the judgments. Mr. Webb&rsquo;s purpose as a data user (held to be &ldquo;reporting and publication for general use&rdquo;) amounted to a new purpose inconsistent with that for which the personal data was collected, in contravention of DPP3.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Balance between Freedom of Expression and Personal Data Privacy</strong></p>\n<p>\n	The AAB determined that the balance between freedom of expression and data privacy protection struck by the Commissioner in its enforcement notice was not unreasonable. The Commissioner made a distinction between reporting facts capable of contributing to a debate of general public interest and making tawdry descriptions about an individual&rsquo;s private life.</p>\n<p>\n	The AAB also rejected Mr. Webb&rsquo;s arguments that open justice would exempt him from any breach of DPP3 and that DPP3 was disproportionate and unconstitutional.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Comment</strong></p>\n<p>\n	<em>Public Data is Still Personal Data</em></p>\n<p>\n	The main lesson is that personal data obtained from the public domain is still subject to the protection under DPP3.</p>\n<p>\n	The position in Hong Kong should be contrasted with Singapore, where the Personal Data Protection Act does not require organisations to obtain the consent of the individual when collecting personal data that is publicly available.</p>\n<p>\n	<em>But a Precedent Set for Matrimonial Case Reports Only?</em></p>\n<p>\n	One factor that appears to have led to the AAB&rsquo;s conclusion is the change of judicial practice to anonymise names of parties to matrimonial proceedings.</p>\n<p>\n	It would be interesting to know whether the AAB might have reached the same conclusion if the change in legal practice had not occurred.</p>\n<p>\n	<em>Public Interest: A Delicate Balance</em></p>\n<p>\n	Thirdly, public interest in disclosure is not a trump card, and the Commissioner will undertake a balancing exercise in each case between the right to privacy and the public interest.</p>\n<p>\n	Rather than establishing a blanket &ldquo;right to be forgotten&rdquo; (as some argued was the case with the ECJ&rsquo;s decision in <em>Google Spain</em>), the AAB&rsquo;s decision has been based squarely on DPP3, which concerns the original purpose for which personal data was collected. The AAB gave a narrow reading to that term. Given the specific context of this case, however, there may well be news disclosures in future that could force the Commissioner to make more challenging assessments as to where the balance lies between privacy and public interest.</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:61:\"Mark Parsons, Eugene Low and Dominic Edmondson, Hogan Lovells\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:4434:\"<p>Mark Parsons, Eugene Low and Dominic Edmondson, Hogan Lovells\n</p><p>\n	The Administrative Appeals Board rejected an appeal from David Webb against an enforcement notice issued by the Privacy Commissioner for Personal Data requiring that Mr. Webb remove from his website (webb-site.com) the names of parties set out in court judgments of matrimonial proceedings published on the Hong Kong Judiciary’s website over a decade earlier.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Background</strong></p>\n<p>\n	David Webb is a former investment banker turned activist who runs a website offering information on corporate and economic governance in Hong Kong, including the various roles that particular individuals play in the financial and public sectors.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>The Decision</strong></p>\n<p>\n	The AAB confirmed that Mr. Webb had contravened Data Protection Principle 3 (“DPP3”) of the Personal Data (Privacy) Ordinance (Cap. 486) by continuing to publish hyperlinks on webb-site.com to three judgments handed down between 2000 and 2002 by the Court of Appeal, each of which had been subsequently redacted by the Judiciary to remove the names of the parties.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Determining the Relevant Purpose of Data Collection</strong></p>\n<p>\n	DPP3 requires that personal data shall not (without consent of the data subject) be used except for the purpose at the time that the data was collected, or a directly related purpose.</p>\n<p>\n	The AAB held that DPP3 is directed against the misuse of personal data, regardless of whether the relevant personal data has been published elsewhere or was in the public domain.</p>\n<p>\n	The AAB considered that “the purpose for which the data was to be used at the time of the collection of the data” was to enable the Judiciary’s judgments to be utilised as “legal precedents on points of law, practice and procedure of the courts and of public interests” and not to identify the parties in the judgments. Mr. Webb’s purpose as a data user (held to be “reporting and publication for general use”) amounted to a new purpose inconsistent with that for which the personal data was collected, in contravention of DPP3.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Balance between Freedom of Expression and Personal Data Privacy</strong></p>\n<p>\n	The AAB determined that the balance between freedom of expression and data privacy protection struck by the Commissioner in its enforcement notice was not unreasonable. The Commissioner made a distinction between reporting facts capable of contributing to a debate of general public interest and making tawdry descriptions about an individual’s private life.</p>\n<p>\n	The AAB also rejected Mr. Webb’s arguments that open justice would exempt him from any breach of DPP3 and that DPP3 was disproportionate and unconstitutional.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Comment</strong></p>\n<p>\n	<em>Public Data is Still Personal Data</em></p>\n<p>\n	The main lesson is that personal data obtained from the public domain is still subject to the protection under DPP3.</p>\n<p>\n	The position in Hong Kong should be contrasted with Singapore, where the Personal Data Protection Act does not require organisations to obtain the consent of the individual when collecting personal data that is publicly available.</p>\n<p>\n	<em>But a Precedent Set for Matrimonial Case Reports Only?</em></p>\n<p>\n	One factor that appears to have led to the AAB’s conclusion is the change of judicial practice to anonymise names of parties to matrimonial proceedings.</p>\n<p>\n	It would be interesting to know whether the AAB might have reached the same conclusion if the change in legal practice had not occurred.</p>\n<p>\n	<em>Public Interest: A Delicate Balance</em></p>\n<p>\n	Thirdly, public interest in disclosure is not a trump card, and the Commissioner will undertake a balancing exercise in each case between the right to privacy and the public interest.</p>\n<p>\n	Rather than establishing a blanket “right to be forgotten” (as some argued was the case with the ECJ’s decision in <em>Google Spain</em>), the AAB’s decision has been based squarely on DPP3, which concerns the original purpose for which personal data was collected. The AAB gave a narrow reading to that term. Given the specific context of this case, however, there may well be news disclosures in future that could force the Commissioner to make more challenging assessments as to where the balance lies between privacy and public interest.</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:69:\"<p>Mark Parsons, Eugene Low and Dominic Edmondson, Hogan Lovells</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"483\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"102\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:56:\"One Step Closer to a Right to be Forgotten in Hong Kong?\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:56:\"One Step Closer to a Right to be Forgotten in Hong Kong?\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:56:\"One Step Closer to a Right to be Forgotten in Hong Kong?\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458127752,1),('9092','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9096\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:55:\"Hong Kong SFC Secures Court Orders against Maxim Trader\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9092\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1450224000\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929170\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9091\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929170\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2352:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence<p>\n	Hong Kong&#39;s Securities and Futures Commission (&ldquo;SFC&rdquo;) said on 11 December that it had obtained interim orders in the Court of First Instance to suspend the websites and restrain the activities of Maxim Trader, an unlicensed firm that the regulator claims has been soliciting investors. The SFC said the court orders would stay in place until the trial of the proceedings, the date of which has yet to be fixed. The orders were granted under s. 213 of the Securities and Futures Ordinance (&ldquo;SFO&rdquo;). <br />\n	<br />\n	As Maxim Trader is not a corporate entity capable of being sued, it has been named as the second defendant, described as &quot;an unknown person or persons purporting to carry on a securities dealing or asset management business known as MAXIM TRADER and using the websites www.maximtrader.com, www.maximtrader.biz, www.maximtaiwan.com and/or partner.maximtrader.com&quot;. <br />\n	<br />\n	In November, the SFC froze HK$23.5 million in assets belonging to Maxim, alleging that the firm operated in the territory without a license. <br />\n	<br />\n	At the time, the SFC said the firm, which is incorporated in the Seychelles, solicited over 130 investors to invest more than HK$111 million in a number of investment schemes since 2013, offering monthly returns of between 3 and 8 percent.<br />\n	<br />\n	Much like a Ponzi scheme, investors initially were able to receive monthly returns on their investments, but since July 2015 have not received further monthly returns. The SFC said the investors had been told by the firm that their investments had been converted into shares of a company &ndash; which appeared to the SFC to be worthless.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;Maxim Capital and Maxim Trader have contravened the SFO by holding out as carrying on a business in SFC regulated activities in Hong Kong without an SFC licence and issuing related advertisements,&quot; the regulator said.<br />\n	<br />\n	It also said the firm contravened the SFO by issuing advertisements inviting the public to enter into agreements to acquire interests in a collective investment scheme without SFC&#39;s authorization.<br />\n	<br />\n	The frozen HK$23.5 million is being held in an account maintained by Maxim Capital with a licensed money service operator in Hong Kong.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:36:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2382:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	Hong Kong\'s Securities and Futures Commission (“SFC”) said on 11 December that it had obtained interim orders in the Court of First Instance to suspend the websites and restrain the activities of Maxim Trader, an unlicensed firm that the regulator claims has been soliciting investors. The SFC said the court orders would stay in place until the trial of the proceedings, the date of which has yet to be fixed. The orders were granted under s. 213 of the Securities and Futures Ordinance (“SFO”). </p>\n<p>	As Maxim Trader is not a corporate entity capable of being sued, it has been named as the second defendant, described as \"an unknown person or persons purporting to carry on a securities dealing or asset management business known as MAXIM TRADER and using the websites <a href=\"http://www.maximtrader.com\">www.maximtrader.com</a>, <a href=\"http://www.maximtrader.biz\">www.maximtrader.biz</a>, <a href=\"http://www.maximtaiwan.com\">www.maximtaiwan.com</a> and/or partner.maximtrader.com\". </p>\n<p>	In November, the SFC froze HK$23.5 million in assets belonging to Maxim, alleging that the firm operated in the territory without a license. </p>\n<p>	At the time, the SFC said the firm, which is incorporated in the Seychelles, solicited over 130 investors to invest more than HK$111 million in a number of investment schemes since 2013, offering monthly returns of between 3 and 8 percent.</p>\n<p>	Much like a Ponzi scheme, investors initially were able to receive monthly returns on their investments, but since July 2015 have not received further monthly returns. The SFC said the investors had been told by the firm that their investments had been converted into shares of a company – which appeared to the SFC to be worthless.</p>\n<p>	\"Maxim Capital and Maxim Trader have contravened the SFO by holding out as carrying on a business in SFC regulated activities in Hong Kong without an SFC licence and issuing related advertisements,\" the regulator said.</p>\n<p>	It also said the firm contravened the SFO by issuing advertisements inviting the public to enter into agreements to acquire interests in a collective investment scheme without SFC\'s authorization.</p>\n<p>	The frozen HK$23.5 million is being held in an account maintained by Maxim Capital with a licensed money service operator in Hong Kong.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:44:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"661\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"576\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:55:\"Hong Kong SFC Secures Court Orders against Maxim Trader\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:55:\"Hong Kong SFC Secures Court Orders against Maxim Trader\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:55:\"Hong Kong SFC Secures Court Orders against Maxim Trader\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450224000\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183993,1),('9093','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9097\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:75:\"Hong Kong Bourse Urges Firms to Minimize Trading Halts, Communicate Clearly\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9093\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1450224000\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929170\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9093\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929170\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:1120:\"Michelle Price, Reuters<p>\n	The Hong Kong stock exchange issued regulatory guidance on 11 December outlining best practices for handling trading halts amid an uptick in share suspensions in the financial centre.<br />\n	<br />\n	The bourse urged firms to minimise the duration of halts, provide clear information on the reason for such halts and to communicate frequently with investors during suspensions.<br />\n	<br />\n	The notice followed a significant increase in the number of trading halts in the first half of 2015, at 522 compared with 309 in the same period of 2014, the exchange said.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;Under the rules, trading in securities should be halted only if it is necessary for the protection of investors or the maintenance of an orderly market,&quot; said HKEx Chief Regulatory Officer and Head of Listing David Graham.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;Issuers should use their best efforts to plan their affairs to avoid trading halts. Any trading halt should be kept to a period that is absolutely necessary to ensure investors are not denied reasonable access to the market.&quot;<br />\n	<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:23:\"Michelle Price, Reuters\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:1069:\"<p>Michelle Price, Reuters\n</p><p>\n	The Hong Kong stock exchange issued regulatory guidance on 11 December outlining best practices for handling trading halts amid an uptick in share suspensions in the financial centre.</p>\n<p>	The bourse urged firms to minimise the duration of halts, provide clear information on the reason for such halts and to communicate frequently with investors during suspensions.</p>\n<p>	The notice followed a significant increase in the number of trading halts in the first half of 2015, at 522 compared with 309 in the same period of 2014, the exchange said.</p>\n<p>	\"Under the rules, trading in securities should be halted only if it is necessary for the protection of investors or the maintenance of an orderly market,\" said HKEx Chief Regulatory Officer and Head of Listing David Graham.</p>\n<p>	\"Issuers should use their best efforts to plan their affairs to avoid trading halts. Any trading halt should be kept to a period that is absolutely necessary to ensure investors are not denied reasonable access to the market.\"</p>\n<p>	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:31:\"<p>Michelle Price, Reuters</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"662\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"114\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:75:\"Hong Kong Bourse Urges Firms to Minimize Trading Halts, Communicate Clearly\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:75:\"Hong Kong Bourse Urges Firms to Minimize Trading Halts, Communicate Clearly\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:75:\"Hong Kong Bourse Urges Firms to Minimize Trading Halts, Communicate Clearly\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1450224000\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458111751,1),('9095','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9099\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:70:\"Overseas Banks Struggling to Meet Tough New Deadline on Senior Bankers\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9095\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1450224000\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929170\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9095\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929170\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2536:\"Regulatory Intelligence news team<p>\n	Overseas banks with UK branches face a race against time to comply with new regulations requiring bank staff based outside of Europe to be held responsible for any failings that occur in the UK branch.<br />\n	<br />\n	Bovill, the specialist regulatory consultancy, said from March 2016, certain senior managers at banks based outside of the European Economic Area but which operate branches in the UK, could be made to be personally responsible or even criminally liable for regulatory problems that occur within their areas of responsibility.<br />\n	<br />\n	Bovill said senior managers based outside the UK branch would be accountable to the Prudential Regulation Authority and Financial Conduct Authority (&ldquo;FCA&rdquo;) if the individual is responsible for implementing the bank&#39;s strategy in the firm&#39;s UK branch.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;Overseas banks are working around the clock in order to be ready for the March 2016 deadline for these new regulations. To have a realistic chance of getting newly caught members of staff properly approved, applications are going to have be made in January,&quot; said Mark Spiers, head of banking, investments and lending at Bovill.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;What is causing real complexity is that if the UK branch structured in such a way that a senior manager based outside the UK still has an active role in the operations of the UK branch, then they will have to comply with the new rules, irrespective of where they live in the world.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;A senior manager based in South East Asia or the US caught under the regulations will want to assure themselves that the UK branch meets the regulators expectations on management and controls.&quot;<br />\n	<br />\n	Spiers said a vital reason why overseas banks may be taking longer to comply with the new senior managers regime (&ldquo;SMR&rdquo;) was because the UK branch managers were having to spend a significant amount of time educating their head offices on what the new rules meant in practice.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;UK branch managers are spending considerable time explaining to the head office what the new rules mean in reality, as well as feeding back to them on how the UK branch is being governed.&quot;<br />\n	<br />\n	Many banks operate UK branches rather than a full UK subsidiary to handle customer transactions in the UK, Bovill said.<br />\n	<br />\n	In October, the FCA announced the SMR would be extended to include all financial services firms in 2018.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:33:\"Regulatory Intelligence news team\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2418:\"<p>Regulatory Intelligence news team\n</p><p>\n	Overseas banks with UK branches face a race against time to comply with new regulations requiring bank staff based outside of Europe to be held responsible for any failings that occur in the UK branch.</p>\n<p>	Bovill, the specialist regulatory consultancy, said from March 2016, certain senior managers at banks based outside of the European Economic Area but which operate branches in the UK, could be made to be personally responsible or even criminally liable for regulatory problems that occur within their areas of responsibility.</p>\n<p>	Bovill said senior managers based outside the UK branch would be accountable to the Prudential Regulation Authority and Financial Conduct Authority (“FCA”) if the individual is responsible for implementing the bank\'s strategy in the firm\'s UK branch.</p>\n<p>	\"Overseas banks are working around the clock in order to be ready for the March 2016 deadline for these new regulations. To have a realistic chance of getting newly caught members of staff properly approved, applications are going to have be made in January,\" said Mark Spiers, head of banking, investments and lending at Bovill.</p>\n<p>	\"What is causing real complexity is that if the UK branch structured in such a way that a senior manager based outside the UK still has an active role in the operations of the UK branch, then they will have to comply with the new rules, irrespective of where they live in the world.</p>\n<p>	\"A senior manager based in South East Asia or the US caught under the regulations will want to assure themselves that the UK branch meets the regulators expectations on management and controls.\"</p>\n<p>	Spiers said a vital reason why overseas banks may be taking longer to comply with the new senior managers regime (“SMR”) was because the UK branch managers were having to spend a significant amount of time educating their head offices on what the new rules meant in practice.</p>\n<p>	\"UK branch managers are spending considerable time explaining to the head office what the new rules mean in reality, as well as feeding back to them on how the UK branch is being governed.\"</p>\n<p>	Many banks operate UK branches rather than a full UK subsidiary to handle customer transactions in the UK, Bovill said.</p>\n<p>	In October, the FCA announced the SMR would be extended to include all financial services firms in 2018.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:41:\"<p>Regulatory Intelligence news team</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\