<p>Regulatory Intelligence news team\n</p><p>\n	Overseas banks with UK branches face a race against time to comply with new regulations requiring bank staff based outside of Europe to be held responsible for any failings that occur in the UK branch.</p>\n<p>	Bovill, the specialist regulatory consultancy, said from March 2016, certain senior managers at banks based outside of the European Economic Area but which operate branches in the UK, could be made to be personally responsible or even criminally liable for regulatory problems that occur within their areas of responsibility.</p>\n<p>	Bovill said senior managers based outside the UK branch would be accountable to the Prudential Regulation Authority and Financial Conduct Authority (“FCA”) if the individual is responsible for implementing the bank\'s strategy in the firm\'s UK branch.</p>\n<p>	\"Overseas banks are working around the clock in order to be ready for the March 2016 deadline for these new regulations. To have a realistic chance of getting newly caught members of staff properly approved, applications are going to have be made in January,\" said Mark Spiers, head of banking, investments and lending at Bovill.</p>\n<p>	\"What is causing real complexity is that if the UK branch structured in such a way that a senior manager based outside the UK still has an active role in the operations of the UK branch, then they will have to comply with the new rules, irrespective of where they live in the world.</p>\n<p>	\"A senior manager based in South East Asia or the US caught under the regulations will want to assure themselves that the UK branch meets the regulators expectations on management and controls.\"</p>\n<p>	Spiers said a vital reason why overseas banks may be taking longer to comply with the new senior managers regime (“SMR”) was because the UK branch managers were having to spend a significant amount of time educating their head offices on what the new rules meant in practice.</p>\n<p>	\"UK branch managers are spending considerable time explaining to the head office what the new rules mean in reality, as well as feeding back to them on how the UK branch is being governed.\"</p>\n<p>	Many banks operate UK branches rather than a full UK subsidiary to handle customer transactions in the UK, Bovill said.</p>\n<p>	In October, the FCA announced the SMR would be extended to include all financial services firms in 2018.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:41:\"<p>Regulatory Intelligence news team</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"661\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"576\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:70:\"Overseas Banks Struggling to Meet Tough New Deadline on Senior Bankers\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:70:\"Overseas Banks Struggling to Meet Tough New Deadline on Senior Bankers\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:70:\"Overseas Banks Struggling to Meet Tough New Deadline on Senior Bankers\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTi