ameworks was consistent with the G20&#39;s aim for accounting standard setters to &quot;strengthen accounting recognition of loan loss provisions by incorporating a broader range of credit information&quot;.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:36:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:1313:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	The Hong Kong Monetary Authority (“HKMA”) has announced that it is planning to adopt the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\'s (“BCBS”) guidance on credit risk and accounting for expected credit losses, which was published on 18 December 2015. The new BCBS guidance replaces an earlier document on sound credit risk assessments and valuation for loans, issued in 2006, and sets out supervisory expectations for banks on sound credit risk practices associated with implementing and applying an expected credit loss (“ECL”) accounting framework.</p>\n<p>	In a recent circular, the HKMA said the move to ECL accounting frameworks by accounting standard setters was an important step forward in addressing weaknesses related to credit loss recognition, which were identified during the financial crisis.</p>\n<p>	The regulator said it encouraged all authorised institutions to review their credit risk management processes in light of the relevant principles set out in the BCBS guidance.</p>\n<p>	The HKMA said the development of ECL accounting frameworks was consistent with the G20\'s aim for accounting standard setters to \"strengthen accounting recognition of loan loss provisions by incorporating a broader range of credit information\".<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:44:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"661\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"576\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:44:\"HKMA to Follow Basel Guidance on Credit Risk\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:44:\"HKMA to Follow Basel Guidance on Credit Risk\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2014-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:44:\"HKMA to Follow Basel Guidance on Credit Risk\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451433600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183993,1),('9113','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9117\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:52:\"Deutsche Sanctioned in Japan as the FSA Gets Tougher\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9113\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451433600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929170\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9113\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929170\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:4416:\"Niall Coburn, Regulatory Intelligence<p>\n	An unidentified analyst at Deutsche bank&#39;s Japanese brokerage arm was recently accused by Japan&#39;s Financial Services Agency (&ldquo;FSA&rdquo;) of improperly providing unreleased and market sensitive information about a company to clients.<br />\n	<br />\n	The Securities Exchange Surveillance Commission (&ldquo;SESC&rdquo;) recommended that the FSA take &quot;administrative action&quot; against Deutsche Securities without specifying the type of penalty it is seeking. In Japan, the phrase &quot;administrative action&quot;, often implies a business improvement order or a temporary suspension from operations. Although the term has not been used, the analyst&#39;s actions would constitute insider dealing in the securities laws of Hong Kong and Australia, as he was providing undisclosed market sensitive information to a client.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Self-Reported<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	According to the SESC, the Deutsche equity analyst received information about a Japanese company&#39;s earnings before the official release of financial results in December 2014. The information was then shared with 21 people within the Deutsche sales division and a client. Following from these circumstances, two staff members passed information on to three other clients who then sold shares in the company, which was listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.<br />\n	<br />\n	Deutsche Securities self-identified the problem and reported the matter to the Japanese regulators. It said in an announcement to the market that it &quot;has determined and implemented thorough remedial action addressing the cause of the incident&quot;. There is no information about the how the information came about to be discovered within Deutsche or the compliance breakdown that led to the violation.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Other International Woes<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	The administration order follows a previous business improvement order, issued to Deutsche Securities by the FSA in 2013 to address improper client entertainment practices and investigations into Yen manipulation. The order also comes at a time when Deutsche Bank has been under intense scrutiny by the securities regulators in Europe and the US and continues to be under the public eye.<br />\n	<br />\n	In April this year, Deutsche Bank agreed to settle enforcement actions with international regulators and pay a total of $2.5 billion to four regulators in the US and UK and install an independent monitor as part of a settlement over claims that traders manipulated key interest rate benchmarks such as the London Interbank Offered Rate (&ldquo;LIBOR&rdquo;) and similar rates priced in Euros and Yen.<br />\n	<br />\n	This settlement included a ban on Deutsche Bank traders who engaged in interest rate manipulation in the US, including the firing of seven executives in Europe who remain employed by the bank. As a result of investigations in the US, ten Deutsche Bank employees were fired. However, four of those employees were later re-instated by German courts. There was an agreement that re-instated employees will not be allowed to hold compliance jobs, submit interbank offered rates or handle US Dollar transactions. There are currently criminal actions against Deutsche employees in London concerning the manipulation of LIBOR.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Crackdown by Japanese Regulators<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	Japanese regulators have intensified their investigations in relation to regulatory breaches after 2012 when several brokerage firms, including Nomura and Daiwa, were found to have leaked advance information of share offerings, allowing certain clients to profit before formal announcements were made to the market. Also, as further embarrassment to large Japanese corporations, securities regulators have recently issued a record fine of $59 million to Toshiba, which was caught falsifying financial documents in a $1.3 billion accounting scam.<br />\n	<br />\n	There is a wide perception that Japan needs to intensify regulatory control to be more like Hong Kong, Singapore and Australia. Recently the SESC and the FSA have been seen to be taking a tough line on a broad range of regulatory market violations. It appears there is a heightened emphasis by the Shinzo Abe government on corporate governance reforms as part of a growth strategy and wider reforms in financial services.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:37:\"Niall Coburn, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:4288:\"<p>Niall Coburn, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	An unidentified analyst at Deutsche bank\'s Japanese brokerage arm was recently accused by Japan\'s Financial Services Agency (“FSA”) of improperly providing unreleased and market sensitive information about a company to clients.</p>\n<p>	The Securities Exchange Surveillance Commission (“SESC”) recommended that the FSA take \"administrative action\" against Deutsche Securities without specifying the type of penalty it is seeking. In Japan, the phrase \"administrative action\", often implies a business improvement order or a temporary suspension from operations. Although the term has not been used, the analyst\'s actions would constitute insider dealing in the securities laws of Hong Kong and Australia, as he was providing undisclosed market sensitive information to a client.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Self-Reported<br /></strong><br />\n	According to the SESC, the Deutsche equity analyst received information about a Japanese company\'s earnings before the official release of financial results in December 2014. The information was then shared with 21 people within the Deutsche sales division and a client. Following from these circumstances, two staff members passed information on to three other clients who then sold shares in the company, which was listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.</p>\n<p>	Deutsche Securities self-identified the problem and reported the matter to the Japanese regulators. It said in an announcement to the market that it \"has determined and implemented thorough remedial action addressing the cause of the incident\". There is no information about the how the information came about to be discovered within Deutsche or the compliance breakdown that led to the violation.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Other International Woes<br /></strong><br />\n	The administration order follows a previous business improvement order, issued to Deutsche Securities by the FSA in 2013 to address improper client entertainment practices and investigations into Yen manipulation. The order also comes at a time when Deutsche Bank has been under intense scrutiny by the securities regulators in Europe and the US and continues to be under the public eye.</p>\n<p>	In April this year, Deutsche Bank agreed to settle enforcement actions with international regulators and pay a total of $2.5 billion to four regulators in the US and UK and install an independent monitor as part of a settlement over claims that traders manipulated key interest rate benchmarks such as the London Interbank Offered Rate (“LIBOR”) and similar rates priced in Euros and Yen.</p>\n<p>	This settlement included a ban on Deutsche Bank traders who engaged in interest rate manipulation in the US, including the firing of seven executives in Europe who remain employed by the bank. As a result of investigations in the US, ten Deutsche Bank employees were fired. However, four of those employees were later re-instated by German courts. There was an agreement that re-instated employees will not be allowed to hold compliance jobs, submit interbank offered rates or handle US Dollar transactions. There are currently criminal actions against Deutsche employees in London concerning the manipulation of LIBOR.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Crackdown by Japanese Regulators<br /></strong><br />\n	Japanese regulators have intensified their investigations in relation to regulatory breaches after 2012 when several brokerage firms, including Nomura and Daiwa, were found to have leaked advance information of share offerings, allowing certain clients to profit before formal announcements were made to the market. Also, as further embarrassment to large Japanese corporations, securities regulators have recently issued a record fine of $59 million to Toshiba, which was caught falsifying financial documents in a $1.3 billion accounting scam.</p>\n<p>	There is a wide perception that Japan needs to intensify regulatory control to be more like Hong Kong, Singapore and Australia. Recently the SESC and the FSA have been seen to be taking a tough line on a broad range of regulatory market violations. It appears there is a heightened emphasis by the Shinzo Abe government on corporate governance reforms as part of a growth strategy and wider reforms in financial services.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:45:\"<p>Niall Coburn, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"662\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"114\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:52:\"Deutsche Sanctioned in Japan as the FSA Gets Tougher\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:52:\"Deutsche Sanctioned in Japan as the FSA Gets Tougher\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:52:\"Deutsche Sanctioned in Japan as the FSA Gets Tougher\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"dataty