"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451433600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183993,1),('9117','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9121\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:66:\"Hong Kong SFC Suspends Former Trader who Took Orders over WhatsApp\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9117\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451433600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929174\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9117\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929174\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2730:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence<p>\n	Hong Kong&#39;s securities regulator has suspended a former securities dealer at broker BTIG for taking customer orders over phone messaging service WhatsApp, and for allowing a friend to operate his personal trading account. The Securities and Futures Commission (&ldquo;SFC&rdquo;) said Fabiano Hugues Joseph Mascolo&#39;s actions were in breach of the firm&#39;s internal policies and made it difficult to monitor his activity and compliance. Mascolo was suspended for three months until 20 March 2016.<br />\n	<br />\n	BTIG, a global financial services firm that specialises in institutional trading and brokerage, informed the SFC about the breach of its internal rules after learning that Mascolo had received a buy order from a US client and discussed it over the messaging service.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;Notwithstanding Mascolo&#39;s claim that he disclosed his entire saved WhatsApp messages to his supervisor at his request, BTIG has no control over the recording and retention of the WhatsApp messages,&quot; the SFC said. &quot;A WhatsApp message sent by Mascolo to the client to &#39;let&#39;s talk here, email monitored&#39; regarding the buy order showed Mascolo was clearly aware that BTIG prohibited WhatsApp messaging on mobile phones in relation to BTIG&#39;s business activities.&quot;<br />\n	<br />\n	The SFC said BTIG had in place a written electronic communication policy that strictly prohibited its employees from using electronic communication including text messaging on mobile phones that are not supported by BTIG&#39;s IT department and if the intended purpose was related to BTIG&#39;s business activities. It also said Mascolo&#39;s activities could have prevented BTIG from monitoring and complying with its regulatory requirements. <br />\n	<br />\n	The regulator also said Mascolo allowed a friend to operate his personal trading account at BTIG between April 2010 and September 2013. Although Mascolo knew his friend was a licensed representative he failed to obtain prior written consent from his friend&#39;s employer before allowing his friend to conduct personal trades in the securities account, the regulator said.<br />\n	<br />\n	During an interview with the SFC, Mascolo admitted the failure but said it was due to his ignorance of the relevant provisions in the SFC&#39;s Code of Conduct and not because he wished to conceal his friend&#39;s personal trades from his friend&#39;s employer. In doing so, Mascolo deprived his friend&#39;s employers the opportunity to monitor his friend&#39;s personal trades and assess whether there were any conflicts of interest, and breached paragraph 12.2(c) of the Code of Conduct, the SFC said.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:36:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2603:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	Hong Kong\'s securities regulator has suspended a former securities dealer at broker BTIG for taking customer orders over phone messaging service WhatsApp, and for allowing a friend to operate his personal trading account. The Securities and Futures Commission (“SFC”) said Fabiano Hugues Joseph Mascolo\'s actions were in breach of the firm\'s internal policies and made it difficult to monitor his activity and compliance. Mascolo was suspended for three months until 20 March 2016.</p>\n<p>	BTIG, a global financial services firm that specialises in institutional trading and brokerage, informed the SFC about the breach of its internal rules after learning that Mascolo had received a buy order from a US client and discussed it over the messaging service.</p>\n<p>	\"Notwithstanding Mascolo\'s claim that he disclosed his entire saved WhatsApp messages to his supervisor at his request, BTIG has no control over the recording and retention of the WhatsApp messages,\" the SFC said. \"A WhatsApp message sent by Mascolo to the client to \'let\'s talk here, email monitored\' regarding the buy order showed Mascolo was clearly aware that BTIG prohibited WhatsApp messaging on mobile phones in relation to BTIG\'s business activities.\"</p>\n<p>	The SFC said BTIG had in place a written electronic communication policy that strictly prohibited its employees from using electronic communication including text messaging on mobile phones that are not supported by BTIG\'s IT department and if the intended purpose was related to BTIG\'s business activities. It also said Mascolo\'s activities could have prevented BTIG from monitoring and complying with its regulatory requirements. </p>\n<p>	The regulator also said Mascolo allowed a friend to operate his personal trading account at BTIG between April 2010 and September 2013. Although Mascolo knew his friend was a licensed representative he failed to obtain prior written consent from his friend\'s employer before allowing his friend to conduct personal trades in the securities account, the regulator said.</p>\n<p>	During an interview with the SFC, Mascolo admitted the failure but said it was due to his ignorance of the relevant provisions in the SFC\'s Code of Conduct and not because he wished to conceal his friend\'s personal trades from his friend\'s employer. In doing so, Mascolo deprived his friend\'s employers the opportunity to monitor his friend\'s personal trades and assess whether there were any conflicts of interest, and breached paragraph 12.2(c) of the Code of Conduct, the SFC said.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:44:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"662\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"114\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:66:\"Hong Kong SFC Suspends Former Trader who Took Orders over WhatsApp\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:66:\"Hong Kong SFC Suspends Former Trader who Took Orders over WhatsApp\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:66:\"Hong Kong SFC Suspends Former Trader who Took Orders over WhatsApp\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:se