9;s business activities. It also said Mascolo&#39;s activities could have prevented BTIG from monitoring and complying with its regulatory requirements. <br />\n	<br />\n	The regulator also said Mascolo allowed a friend to operate his personal trading account at BTIG between April 2010 and September 2013. Although Mascolo knew his friend was a licensed representative he failed to obtain prior written consent from his friend&#39;s employer before allowing his friend to conduct personal trades in the securities account, the regulator said.<br />\n	<br />\n	During an interview with the SFC, Mascolo admitted the failure but said it was due to his ignorance of the relevant provisions in the SFC&#39;s Code of Conduct and not because he wished to conceal his friend&#39;s personal trades from his friend&#39;s employer. In doing so, Mascolo deprived his friend&#39;s employers the opportunity to monitor his friend&#39;s personal trades and assess whether there were any conflicts of interest, and breached paragraph 12.2(c) of the Code of Conduct, the SFC said.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:36:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2603:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	Hong Kong\'s securities regulator has suspended a former securities dealer at broker BTIG for taking customer orders over phone messaging service WhatsApp, and for allowing a friend to operate his personal trading account. The Securities and Futures Commission (“SFC”) said Fabiano Hugues Joseph Mascolo\'s actions were in breach of the firm\'s internal policies and made it difficult to monitor his activity and compliance. Mascolo was suspended for three months until 20 March 2016.</p>\n<p>	BTIG, a global financial services firm that specialises in institutional trading and brokerage, informed the SFC about the breach of its internal rules after learning that Mascolo had received a buy order from a US client and discussed it over the messaging service.</p>\n<p>	\"Notwithstanding Mascolo\'s claim that he disclosed his entire saved WhatsApp messages to his supervisor at his request, BTIG has no control over the recording and retention of the WhatsApp messages,\" the SFC said. \"A WhatsApp message sent by Mascolo to the client to \'let\'s talk here, email monitored\' regarding the buy order showed Mascolo was clearly aware that BTIG prohibited WhatsApp messaging on mobile phones in relation to BTIG\'s business activities.\"</p>\n<p>	The SFC said BTIG had in place a written electronic communication policy that strictly prohibited its employees from using electronic communication including text messaging on mobile phones that are not supported by BTIG\'s IT department and if the intended purpose was related to BTIG\'s business activities. It also said Mascolo\'s activities could have prevented BTIG from monitoring and complying with its regulatory requirements. </p>\n<p>	The regulator also said Mascolo allowed a friend to operate his personal trading account at BTIG between April 2010 and September 2013. Although Mascolo knew his friend was a licensed representative he failed to obtain prior written consent from his friend\'s employer before allowing his friend to conduct personal trades in the securities account, the regulator said.</p>\n<p>	During an interview with the SFC, Mascolo admitted the failure but said it was due to his ignorance of the relevant provisions in the SFC\'s Code of Conduct and not because he wished to conceal his friend\'s personal trades from his friend\'s employer. In doing so, Mascolo deprived his friend\'s employers the opportunity to monitor his friend\'s personal trades and assess whether there were any conflicts of interest, and breached paragraph 12.2(c) of the Code of Conduct, the SFC said.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:44:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"661\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"576\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:66:\"Hong Kong SFC Suspends Former Trader who Took Orders over WhatsApp\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:66:\"Hong Kong SFC Suspends Former Trader who Took Orders over WhatsApp\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:66:\"Hong Kong SFC Suspends Former Trader who Took Orders over WhatsApp\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451433600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183993,1),('9119','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9123\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:90:\"Full, Partial or Substituted: Compliance Challenges under the HKMA\'s new OTC Margin Module\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9119\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451433600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929174\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9119\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929174\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:6209:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence<p>\n	Recent proposals by the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (&ldquo;HKMA&rdquo;) to introduce margin requirements on non-centrally cleared over-the-counter (&ldquo;OTC&rdquo;) derivatives may prove to be a challenge for market participants ahead of the regime&#39;s planned implementation in September 2016, a law firm said. While the proposals were largely in line with standards set by international regulatory bodies, the HKMA&#39;s proposed regime contained some elements that would require significant preparation to comply with, according to law firm Clifford Chance.<br />\n	<br />\n	Some of the main challenges were determining to which degree financial institutions would be required to comply with the margin requirements, and in which circumstances they will apply, and ensuring firms have the resources in place to meet the requirements by 2016.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;The imposition of these regulatory margin requirements will be a significant change for the Hong Kong market; it will require a substantial build-out of operational and documentation infrastructure by market participants,&quot; said Francis Edwards, partner at Clifford Chance in Hong Kong.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Deep Market Impact<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	&quot;While implementation will be phased in over time, the economic consequences of the increased requirements to post collateral will be felt across the market.&quot;<br />\n	<br />\n	In a recently published client briefing, Clifford Chance said the proposed margin requirements were contained in a &quot;margin module&quot; that will become part of the HKMA&#39;s Supervisory Policy Manual when they become effective.<br />\n	<br />\n	It said the requirements would only apply to banks in Hong Kong when they trade with a &quot;covered entity&quot; &ndash; that is, another financial counterparty, a significant non-financial counterparty or any other firm designated by the HKMA.<br />\n	<br />\n	To complicate matters, there are three levels of compliance: full, partial or substituted:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Full compliance with the requirements will apply when Hong Kong-incorporated banks trade with other Hong Kong-incorporated firms, or covered entities.</li>\n	<li>\n		Where one of the parties is incorporated outside Hong Kong, only partial compliance with the requirements is needed.</li>\n	<li>\n		When a bank outside Hong Kong trades with a non-bank covered entity that is either in or out of Hong Kong, it may choose to comply with its local margin requirements instead &ndash; provided that the HKMA has deemed that jurisdiction &quot;comparable&quot;, thereby allowing for substituted compliance.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Local banks or a foreign regulator must apply to the HKMA in order to ensure a foreign jurisdiction is deemed comparable under the new regime, thus opening for partial or substituted compliance.<br />\n	<br />\n	The HKMA is also introducing risk mitigation standards, in line with those proposed by the International Organization of Securities Commission earlier this year, as the second jurisdiction in Asia to do so, following Singapore.<br />\n	<br />\n	These standards include requirements relating to trading relationship documentation, trade confirmation, portfolio reconciliation and dispute resolution. The regulator is proposing to introduce these on the same timetable as the introduction of margin requirements, over a four-year period starting in September 2016.<br />\n	<br />\n	Given that, unlike margin requirements, there is no international timetable for the introduction of risk mitigation standards, Clifford Chance said the HKMA might consider delaying them to allow market participants to first focus on compliance with the margin requirements under the new regime.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Tight Timetable<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	Hong Kong banks may already face a shortage of time and resources in managing all of the documentary and operational requirements involved in preparing for the introduction of mandatory clearing and margining during the course of 2016, it said.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;[Banks] need to appreciate the enormous amount of preparatory work involved in complying with the margin requirements being introduced in 2016,&quot; said Terry Yang, consultant at Clifford Chance. &quot;Not only do they need to classify each of their counterparties accurately, but they will also need to put in place new collateral documents &ndash; all within the span of about one year.&quot;<br />\n	<br />\n	The margin requirements do not need subsidiary legislation to be implemented, unlike the reporting and clearing rules for OTC derivatives transactions, as the HKMA has opted to publish them as a module under the Supervisory Policy Manual. This means there will be few options for market participants to comment on the new regime before it is finalized, the law firm said. It said the new module would likely be published in the first quarter of 2016 to allow banks time to prepare.<br />\n	<br />\n	The Securities and Futures Commission (&ldquo;SFC&rdquo;) was also likely to publish similar requirements for licensed corporations under its Code of Conduct, the law firm said. <br />\n	<br />\n	It outlined three major tasks for banks and licensed corporations to focus on in 2016:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Identify relevant foreign jurisdictions they want the HKMA to issue comparability determinations for, and coordinate with other regulators or market participants to ensure an application is lodged with the HKMA before September 2016.</li>\n	<li>\n		Classify their counterparties to identify which of them they need to exchange margin with under the new regime.</li>\n	<li>\n		Modify or enter new collateral and custody documentation with their counterparties to comply with the new margin requirements.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Organisations such as the International Swaps and Derivatives Association (&ldquo;ISDA&rdquo;) and some market participants may be working to prepare an industry-wide solution but it may still be a challenge in the Asia-Pacific region to persuade regional counterparties to adopt documentary solutions designed primarily for the US and European OTC derivatives markets, the law firm said.</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:36:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:5979:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	Recent proposals by the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (“HKMA”) to introduce margin requirements on non-centrally cleared over-the-counter (“OTC”) derivatives may prove to be a challenge for market participants ahead of the regime\'s planned implementation in September 2016, a law firm said. While the proposals were largely in line with standards set by international regulatory bodies, the HKMA\'s proposed regime contained some elements that would require significant preparation to comply with, according to law firm Clifford Chance.</p>\n<p>	Some of the main challenges were determining to which degree financial institutions would be required to comply with the margin requirements, and in which circumstances they will apply, and ensuring firms have the resources in place to meet the requirements by 2016.</p>\n<p>	\"The imposition of these regulatory margin requirements will be a significant change for the Hong Kong market; it will require a substantial build-out of operational and documentation infrastructure by market participants,\" said Francis Edwards, partner at Clifford Chance in Hong Kong.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Deep Market Impact<br /></strong><br />\n	\"While implementation will be phased in over time, the economic consequences of the increased requirements to post collateral will be felt across the market.\"</p>\n<p>	In a recently published client briefing, Clifford Chance said the proposed margin requirements were contained in a \"margin module\" that will become part of the HKMA\'s Supervisory Policy Manual when they become effective.</p>\n<p>	It said the requirements would only apply to banks in Hong Kong when they trade with a \"covered entity\" – that is, another financial counterparty, a significant non-financial counterparty or any other firm designated by the HKMA.</p>\n<p>	To complicate matters, there are three levels of compliance: full, partial or substituted:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		Full compliance with the requirements will apply when Hong Kong-incorporated banks trade with other Hong Kong-incorporated firms, or covered entities.</li>\n<li>\n		Where one of the parties is incorporated outside Hong Kong, only partial compliance with the requirements is needed.</li>\n<li>\n		When a bank outside Hong Kong trades with a non-bank covered entity that is either in or out of Hong Kong, it may choose to comply with its local margin requirements instead – provided that the HKMA has deemed that jurisdiction \"comparable\", thereby allowing for substituted compliance.</li>\n</ul><p>\n	Local banks or a foreign regulator must apply to the HKMA in order to ensure a foreign jurisdiction is deemed comparable under the new regime, thus opening for partial or substituted compliance.</p>\n<p>	The HKMA is also introducing risk mitigation standards, in line with those proposed by the International Organization of Securities Commission earlier this year, as the second jurisdiction in Asia to do so, following Singapore.</p>\n<p>	These standards include requirements relating to trading relationship documentation, trade confirmation, portfolio reconciliation and dispute resolution. The regulator is proposing to introduce these on the same timetable as the introduction of margin requirements, over a four-year period starting in September 2016.</p>\n<p>	Given that, unlike margin requirements, there is no international timetable for the introduction of risk mitigation standards, Clifford Chance said the HKMA might consider delaying them to allow market participants to first focus on compliance with the margin requirements under the new regime.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Tight Timetable<br /></strong><br />\n	Hong Kong banks may already face a shortage of time and resources in managing all of the documentary and operational requirements involved in preparing for the introduction of mandatory clearing and margining during the course of 2016, it said.</p>\n<p>	\"[Banks] need to appreciate the enormous amount of preparatory work involved in complying with the margin requirements being introduced in 2016,\" said Terry Yang, consultant at Clifford Chance. \"Not only do they need to classify each of their counterparties accurately, but they will also need to put in place new collateral documents – all within the span of about one year.\"</p>\n<p>	The margin requirements do not need subsidiary legislation to be implemented, unlike the reporting and clearing rules for OTC derivatives transactions, as the HKMA has opted to publish them as a module under the Supervisory Policy Manual. This means there will be few options for market participants to comment on the new regime before it is finalized, the law firm said. It said the new module would likely be published in the first quarter of 2016 to allow banks time to prepare.</p>\n<p>	The Securities and Futures Commission (“SFC”) was also likely to publish similar requirements for licensed corporations under its Code of Conduct, the law firm said. </p>\n<p>	It outlined three major tasks for banks and licensed corporations to focus on in 2016:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		Identify relevant foreign jurisdictions they want the HKMA to issue comparability determinations for, and coordinate with other regulators or market participants to ensure an application is lodged with the HKMA before September 2016.</li>\n<li>\n		Classify their counterparties to identify which of them they need to exchange margin with under the new regime.</li>\n<li>\n		Modify or enter new collateral and custody documentation with their counterparties to comply with the new margin requirements.</li>\n</ul><p>\n	Organisations such as the International Swaps and Derivatives Association (“ISDA”) and some market participants may be working to prepare an industry-wide solution but it may still be a challenge in the Asia-Pacific region to persuade regional counterparties to adopt documentary solutions designed primarily for the US and European OTC derivatives markets, the law firm said.</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:44:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"662\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"114\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:90:\"Full, Partial or Substituted: Compliance Challenges under the HKMA\'s new OTC Margin Module\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:95:\"Full, Partial or Substituted: Compliance Challenges under the HKMA&#039;s new OTC Margin Module\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:90:\"Full, Partial or Substituted: Compliance Challenges under the HKMA\'s new OTC Margin Module\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451433600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458111751,1),('9120','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9124\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:90:\"Full, Partial or Substituted: Compliance Challenges under the HKMA\'s new OTC Margin Module\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9120\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451433600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929174\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9119\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929174\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:6209:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence<p>\n	Recent proposals by the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (&ldquo;HKMA&rdquo;) to introduce margin requirements on non-centrally cleared over-the-counter (&ldquo;OTC&rdquo;) derivatives may prove to be a challenge for market participants ahead of the regime&#39;s planned implementation in September 2016, a law firm said. While the proposals were largely in line with standards set by international regulatory bodies, the HKMA&#39;s proposed regime contained some elements that would require significant preparation to comply with, according to law firm Clifford Chance.<br />\n	<br />\n	Some of the main challenges were determining to which degree financial institutions would be required to comply with the margin requirements, and in which circumstances they will apply, and ensuring firms have the resources in place to meet the requirements by 2016.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;The imposition of these regulatory margin requirements will be a significant change for the Hong Kong market; it will require a substantial build-out of operational and documentation infrastructure by market participants,&quot; said Francis Edwards, partner at Clifford Chance in Hong Kong.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Deep Market Impact<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	&quot;While implementation will be phased in over time, the economic consequences of the increased requirements to post collateral will be felt across the market.&quot;<br />\n	<br />\n	In a recently published client briefing, Clifford Chance said the proposed margin requirements were contained in a &quot;margin module&quot; that will become part of the HKMA&#39;s Supervisory Policy Manual when they become effective.<br />\n	<br />\n	It said the requirements would only apply to banks in Hong Kong when they trade with a &quot;covered entity&quot; &ndash; that is, another financial counterparty, a significant non-financial counterparty or any other firm designated by the HKMA.<br />\n	<br />\n	To complicate matters, there are three levels of compliance: full, partial or substituted:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Full compliance with the requirements will apply when Hong Kong-incorporated banks trade with other Hong Kong-incorporated firms, or covered entities.</li>\n	<li>\n		Where one of the parties is incorporated outside Hong Kong, only partial compliance with the requirements is needed.</li>\n	<li>\n		When a bank outside Hong Kong trades with a non-bank covered entity that is either in or out of Hong Kong, it may choose to comply with its local margin requirements instead &ndash; provided that the HKMA has deemed that jurisdiction &quot;comparable&quot;, thereby allowing for substituted compliance.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Local banks or a foreign regulator must apply to the HKMA in order to ensure a foreign jurisdiction is deemed comparable under the new regime, thus opening for partial or substituted compliance.<br />\n	<br />\n	The HKMA is also introducing risk mitigation standards, in line with those proposed by the International Organization of Securities Commission earlier this year, as the second jurisdiction in Asia to do so, following Singapore.<br />\n	<br />\n	These standards include requirements relating to trading relationship documentation, trade confirmation, portfolio reconciliation and dispute resolution. The regulator is proposing to introduce these on the same timetable as the introduction of margin requirements, over a four-year period starting in September 2016.<br />\n	<br />\n	Given that, unlike margin requirements, there is no international timetable for the introduction of risk mitigation standards, Clifford Chance said the HKMA might consider delaying them to allow market participants to first focus on compliance with the margin requirements under the new regime.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Tight Timetable<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	Hong Kong banks may already face a shortage of time and resources in managing all of the documentary and operational requirements involved in preparing for the introduction of mandatory clearing and margining during the course of 2016, it said.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;[Banks] need to appreciate the enormous amount of preparatory work involved in complying with the margin requirements being introduced in 2016,&quot; said Terry Yang, consultant at Clifford Chance. &quot;Not only do they need to classify each of their counterparties accurately, but they will also need to put in place new collateral documents &ndash; all within the span of about one year.&quot;<br />\n	<br />\n	The margin requirements do not need subsidiary legislation to be implemented, unlike the reporting and clearing rules for OTC derivatives transactions, as the HKMA has opted to publish them as a module under the Supervisory Policy Manual. This means there will be few options for market participants to comment on the new regime before it is finalized, the law firm said. It said the new module would likely be published in the first quarter of 2016 to allow banks time to prepare.<br />\n	<br />\n	The Securities and Futures Commission (&ldquo;SFC&rdquo;) was also likely to publish similar requirements for licensed corporations under its Code of Conduct, the law firm said. <br />\n	<br />\n	It outlined three major tasks for banks and licensed corporations to focus on in 2016:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Identify relevant foreign jurisdictions they want the HKMA to issue comparability determinations for, and coordinate with other regulators or market participants to ensure an application is lodged with the HKMA before September 2016.</li>\n	<li>\n		Classify their counterparties to identify which of them they need to exchange margin with under the new regime.</li>\n	<li>\n		Modify or enter new collateral and custody documentation with their counterparties to comply with the new margin requirements.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Organisations such as the International Swaps and Derivatives Association (&ldquo;ISDA&rdquo;) and some market participants may be working to prepare an industry-wide solution but it may still be a challenge in the Asia-Pacific region to persuade regional counterparties to adopt documentary solutions designed primarily for the US and European OTC derivatives markets, the law firm said.</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:36:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:5979:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	Recent proposals by the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (“HKMA”) to introduce margin requirements on non-centrally cleared over-the-counter (“OTC”) derivatives may prove to be a challenge for market participants ahead of the regime\'s planned implementation in September 2016, a law firm said. While the proposals were largely in line with standards set by international regulatory bodies, the HKMA\'s proposed regime contained some elements that would require significant preparation to comply with, according to law firm Clifford Chance.</p>\n<p>	Some of the main challenges were determining to which degree financial institutions would be required to comply with the margin requirements, and in which circumstances they will apply, and ensuring firms have the resources in place to meet the requirements by 2016.</p>\n<p>	\"The imposition of these regulatory margin requirements will be a significant change for the Hong Kong market; it will require a substantial build-out of operational and documentation infrastructure by market participants,\" said Francis Edwards, partner at Clifford Chance in Hong Kong.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Deep Market Impact<br /></strong><br />\n	\"While implementation will be phased in over time, the economic consequences of the increased requirements to post collateral will be felt across the market.\"</p>\n<p>	In a recently published client briefing, Clifford Chance said the proposed margin requirements were contained in a \"margin module\" that will become part of the HKMA\'s Supervisory Policy Manual when they become effective.</p>\n<p>	It said the requirements would only apply to banks in Hong Kong when they trade with a \"covered entity\" – that is, another financial counterparty, a significant non-financial counterparty or any other firm designated by the HKMA.</p>\n<p>	To complicate matters, there are three levels of compliance: full, partial or substituted:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		Full compliance with the requirements will apply when Hong Kong-incorporated banks trade with other Hong Kong-incorporated firms, or covered entities.</li>\n<li>\n		Where one of the parties is incorporated outside Hong Kong, only partial compliance with the requirements is needed.</li>\n<li>\n		When a bank outside Hong Kong trades with a non-bank covered entity that is either in or out of Hong Kong, it may choose to comply with its local margin requirements instead – provided that the HKMA has deemed that jurisdiction \"comparable\", thereby allowing for substituted compliance.</li>\n</ul><p>\n	Local banks or a foreign regulator must apply to the HKMA in order to ensure a foreign jurisdiction is deemed comparable under the new regime, thus opening for partial or substituted compliance.</p>\n<p>	The HKMA is also introducing risk mitigation standards, in line with those proposed by the International Organization of Securities Commission earlier this year, as the second jurisdiction in Asia to do so, following Singapore.</p>\n<p>	These standards include requirements relating to trading relationship documentation, trade confirmation, portfolio reconciliation and dispute resolution. The regulator is proposing to introduce these on the same timetable as the introduction of margin requirements, over a four-year period starting in September 2016.</p>\n<p>	Given that, unlike margin requirements, there is no international timetable for the introduction of risk mitigation standards, Clifford Chance said the HKMA might consider delaying them to allow market participants to first focus on compliance with the margin requirements under the new regime.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Tight Timetable<br /></strong><br />\n	Hong Kong banks may already face a shortage of time and resources in managing all of the documentary and operational requirements involved in preparing for the introduction of mandatory clearing and margining during the course of 2016, it said.</p>\n<p>	\"[Banks] need to appreciate the enormous amount of preparatory work involved in complying with the margin requirements being introduced in 2016,\" said Terry Yang, consultant at Clifford Chance. \"Not only do they need to classify each of their counterparties accurately, but they will also need to put in place new collateral documents – all within the span of about one year.\"</p>\n<p>	The margin requirements do not need subsidiary legislation to be implemented, unlike the reporting and clearing rules for OTC derivatives transactions, as the HKMA has opted to publish them as a module under the Supervisory Policy Manual. This means there will be few options for market participants to comment on the new regime before it is finalized, the law firm said. It said the new module would likely be published in the first quarter of 2016 to allow banks time to prepare.</p>\n<p>	The Securities and Futures Commission (“SFC”) was also likely to publish similar requirements for licensed corporations under its Code of Conduct, the law firm said. </p>\n<p>	It outlined three major tasks for banks and licensed corporations to focus on in 2016:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		Identify relevant foreign jurisdictions they want the HKMA to issue comparability determinations for, and coordinate with other regulators or market participants to ensure an application is lodged with the HKMA before September 2016.</li>\n<li>\n		Classify their counterparties to identify which of them they need to exchange margin with under the new regime.</li>\n<li>\n		Modify or enter new collateral and custody documentation with their counterparties to comply with the new margin requirements.</li>\n</ul><p>\n	Organisations such as the International Swaps and Derivatives Association (“ISDA”) and some market participants may be working to prepare an industry-wide solution but it may still be a challenge in the Asia-Pacific region to persuade regional counterparties to adopt documentary solutions designed primarily for the US and European OTC derivatives markets, the law firm said.</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:44:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"661\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"576\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:90:\"Full, Partial or Substituted: Compliance Challenges under the HKMA\'s new OTC Margin Module\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:95:\"Full, Partial or Substituted: Compliance Challenges under the HKMA&#039;s new OTC Margin Module\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:90:\"Full, Partial or Substituted: Compliance Challenges under the HKMA\'s new OTC Margin Module\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451433600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183993,1),('9121','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9125\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:51:\"Busy Year Ahead for Hong Kong\'s Insurance Regulator\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9121\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451433600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929174\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9121\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929174\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3192:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence<p>\n	As it enters its last year of service in its current incarnation, Hong Kong&#39;s insurance regulator can look forward to a 2016 packed with regulatory challenges, of which the main task will be the establishment of the Independent Insurance Authority in late 2016. However, there are also prudential, consumer protection and manpower issues to resolve, the regulator said.<br />\n	<br />\n	John Leung, the recently appointed Commissioner of Insurance, said the independent insurance regulator was expected to take over the work of the current Office of the Commissioner of Insurance in late 2016, and eventually be responsible for regulating insurance intermediaries in about two to three years&#39; time.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;As a financially independent statutory body, the independent insurance authority will have greater flexibility and a more powerful toolbox to carry out supervisory work while promoting the sustainable development of our insurance industry,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	He said a Provisional Insurance Authority would soon be set up to undertake essential preparatory work for the new regulator. <br />\n	<br />\n	In a recent newsletter to the industry, Leung also said the regulator had received general support from the industry for its proposed Risk-Based Capital Framework, which aims to make capital requirements more sensitive to the level of risk that insurance companies are bearing. <br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;We are proceeding to the next phase which involves developing the detailed rules and carrying out quantitative impact studies for different types of insurers, to be followed by another consultation exercise,&quot; he said. <br />\n	<br />\n	On the consumer protection front, Leung said the regulator would focus on implementing the Guidance Note on Underwriting Long Term Insurance Business (GN16) in 2016, following the implementation of a guidance note on underwriting Class C Business (such as Investment Linked Assurance Schemes) earlier this year.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;Both guidance notes have engraved the principle of Fair Treatment of Customers in prescribing the conduct of business by life insurers,&quot; he said. &quot;While such initiatives require changes to the culture and operations of our practitioners, public confidence in our insurance industry will be enhanced. Customers will buy more products as they have better understanding of their insurance needs and the products on offer. That will benefit the long-term growth of the industry.&quot;<br />\n	<br />\n	Leung also said proposals for a Policyholders&rsquo; Protection Fund would be introduced via enabling legislation into the Legislative Council in 2016.<br />\n	<br />\n	He also said the industry was concerned about a manpower shortage, in particular for back office jobs such as underwriting, claims, risk management, actuary, and compliance. In response to this, he noted that the government earlier this year allocated funding to launch a three-year pilot scheme to help expand the talent pool in the insurance and asset and wealth management services. The initiative will be launched in phases, starting early 2016.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:36:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3081:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	As it enters its last year of service in its current incarnation, Hong Kong\'s insurance regulator can look forward to a 2016 packed with regulatory challenges, of which the main task will be the establishment of the Independent Insurance Authority in late 2016. However, there are also prudential, consumer protection and manpower issues to resolve, the regulator said.</p>\n<p>	John Leung, the recently appointed Commissioner of Insurance, said the independent insurance regulator was expected to take over the work of the current Office of the Commissioner of Insurance in late 2016, and eventually be responsible for regulating insurance intermediaries in about two to three years\' time.</p>\n<p>	\"As a financially independent statutory body, the independent insurance authority will have greater flexibility and a more powerful toolbox to carry out supervisory work while promoting the sustainable development of our insurance industry,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	He said a Provisional Insurance Authority would soon be set up to undertake essential preparatory work for the new regulator. </p>\n<p>	In a recent newsletter to the industry, Leung also said the regulator had received general support from the industry for its proposed Risk-Based Capital Framework, which aims to make capital requirements more sensitive to the level of risk that insurance companies are bearing. </p>\n<p>	\"We are proceeding to the next phase which involves developing the detailed rules and carrying out quantitative impact studies for different types of insurers, to be followed by another consultation exercise,\" he said. </p>\n<p>	On the consumer protection front, Leung said the regulator would focus on implementing the Guidance Note on Underwriting Long Term Insurance Business (GN16) in 2016, following the implementation of a guidance note on underwriting Class C Business (such as Investment Linked Assurance Schemes) earlier this year.</p>\n<p>	\"Both guidance notes have engraved the principle of Fair Treatment of Customers in prescribing the conduct of business by life insurers,\" he said. \"While such initiatives require changes to the culture and operations of our practitioners, public confidence in our insurance industry will be enhanced. Customers will buy more products as they have better understanding of their insurance needs and the products on offer. That will benefit the long-term growth of the industry.\"</p>\n<p>	Leung also said proposals for a Policyholders’ Protection Fund would be introduced via enabling legislation into the Legislative Council in 2016.</p>\n<p>	He also said the industry was concerned about a manpower shortage, in particular for back office jobs such as underwriting, claims, risk management, actuary, and compliance. In response to this, he noted that the government earlier this year allocated funding to launch a three-year pilot scheme to help expand the talent pool in the insurance and asset and wealth management services. The initiative will be launched in phases, starting early 2016.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:44:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"662\";}}}s:20:\"fiel