cially independent statutory body, the independent insurance authority will have greater flexibility and a more powerful toolbox to carry out supervisory work while promoting the sustainable development of our insurance industry,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	He said a Provisional Insurance Authority would soon be set up to undertake essential preparatory work for the new regulator. <br />\n	<br />\n	In a recent newsletter to the industry, Leung also said the regulator had received general support from the industry for its proposed Risk-Based Capital Framework, which aims to make capital requirements more sensitive to the level of risk that insurance companies are bearing. <br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;We are proceeding to the next phase which involves developing the detailed rules and carrying out quantitative impact studies for different types of insurers, to be followed by another consultation exercise,&quot; he said. <br />\n	<br />\n	On the consumer protection front, Leung said the regulator would focus on implementing the Guidance Note on Underwriting Long Term Insurance Business (GN16) in 2016, following the implementation of a guidance note on underwriting Class C Business (such as Investment Linked Assurance Schemes) earlier this year.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;Both guidance notes have engraved the principle of Fair Treatment of Customers in prescribing the conduct of business by life insurers,&quot; he said. &quot;While such initiatives require changes to the culture and operations of our practitioners, public confidence in our insurance industry will be enhanced. Customers will buy more products as they have better understanding of their insurance needs and the products on offer. That will benefit the long-term growth of the industry.&quot;<br />\n	<br />\n	Leung also said proposals for a Policyholders&rsquo; Protection Fund would be introduced via enabling legislation into the Legislative Council in 2016.<br />\n	<br />\n	He also said the industry was concerned about a manpower shortage, in particular for back office jobs such as underwriting, claims, risk management, actuary, and compliance. In response to this, he noted that the government earlier this year allocated funding to launch a three-year pilot scheme to help expand the talent pool in the insurance and asset and wealth management services. The initiative will be launched in phases, starting early 2016.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:36:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3081:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	As it enters its last year of service in its current incarnation, Hong Kong\'s insurance regulator can look forward to a 2016 packed with regulatory challenges, of which the main task will be the establishment of the Independent Insurance Authority in late 2016. However, there are also prudential, consumer protection and manpower issues to resolve, the regulator said.</p>\n<p>	John Leung, the recently appointed Commissioner of Insurance, said the independent insurance regulator was expected to take over the work of the current Office of the Commissioner of Insurance in late 2016, and eventually be responsible for regulating insurance intermediaries in about two to three years\' time.</p>\n<p>	\"As a financially independent statutory body, the independent insurance authority will have greater flexibility and a more powerful toolbox to carry out supervisory work while promoting the sustainable development of our insurance industry,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	He said a Provisional Insurance Authority would soon be set up to undertake essential preparatory work for the new regulator. </p>\n<p>	In a recent newsletter to the industry, Leung also said the regulator had received general support from the industry for its proposed Risk-Based Capital Framework, which aims to make capital requirements more sensitive to the level of risk that insurance companies are bearing. </p>\n<p>	\"We are proceeding to the next phase which involves developing the detailed rules and carrying out quantitative impact studies for different types of insurers, to be followed by another consultation exercise,\" he said. </p>\n<p>	On the consumer protection front, Leung said the regulator would focus on implementing the Guidance Note on Underwriting Long Term Insurance Business (GN16) in 2016, following the implementation of a guidance note on underwriting Class C Business (such as Investment Linked Assurance Schemes) earlier this year.</p>\n<p>	\"Both guidance notes have engraved the principle of Fair Treatment of Customers in prescribing the conduct of business by life insurers,\" he said. \"While such initiatives require changes to the culture and operations of our practitioners, public confidence in our insurance industry will be enhanced. Customers will buy more products as they have better understanding of their insurance needs and the products on offer. That will benefit the long-term growth of the industry.\"</p>\n<p>	Leung also said proposals for a Policyholders’ Protection Fund would be introduced via enabling legislation into the Legislative Council in 2016.</p>\n<p>	He also said the industry was concerned about a manpower shortage, in particular for back office jobs such as underwriting, claims, risk management, actuary, and compliance. In response to this, he noted that the government earlier this year allocated funding to launch a three-year pilot scheme to help expand the talent pool in the insurance and asset and wealth management services. The initiative will be launched in phases, starting early 2016.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:44:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"661\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"576\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"