hrough ongoing informal consultations but also supplemented by more formal cooperation under certain circumstances.<br />\n	<br />\n	The regulators said they expected cooperation to be most useful in issues of common regulatory concern around applications for authorisation or licensing, or the ongoing supervision of the activities of entities that operate cross-border. <br />\n	<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:36:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:1842:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	Hong Kong securities regulator and United States Commodity Futures Trading Commission (“CFTC”) have agreed to boost cooperation on cross-border supervision, the two bodies said in a statement on Wednesday, 23 December.</p>\n<p>	Such agreements aim at make it easier for firms engaged in cross-border trading to comply with the myriad of rules governing markets that were brought in after the 2008 financial crisis. In particular, the agreement pledges the two bodies to cooperate closely when a systemically important institution in the two jurisdictions faces a financial crisis or emergency situation. It also cites a need to work together when an entity in one jurisdiction files a regulatory application in the other, when regulatory actions by one agency would materially affect the entity\'s operations in the other, and in continuing compliance supervision and oversight.</p>\n<p>	The agreement took effect on 21 December and covers regulated markets, trading platforms, central counterparties among others, the statement said, adding that it does not create any legally binding obligations or supersede domestic law.</p>\n<p>	\"No domestic secrecy or blocking laws or regulations should prevent an authority from providing assistance to the other authority,\" the statement added.</p>\n<p>	Under the Memorandum of Understanding, the two regulators have agreed on a process for information sharing, primarily through ongoing informal consultations but also supplemented by more formal cooperation under certain circumstances.</p>\n<p>	The regulators said they expected cooperation to be most useful in issues of common regulatory concern around applications for authorisation or licensing, or the ongoing supervision of the activities of entities that operate cross-border. </p>\n<p>	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:44:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"661\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"576\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:61:\"Hong Kong SFC and US CFTC Sign Agreement to Boost Supervision\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:61:\"Hong Kong SFC and US CFTC Sign Agreement to Boost Supervision\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:61:\"Hong Kong SFC and US CFTC Sign Agreement to Boost Supervision\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"pred