f the customer due diligence (“CDD”) requirements contained in Schedule 2 of the Anti-Money Laundering and Counter-Terrorist Financing (Financial Institutions) Ordinance (“AMLCTFO”), criminal cases are now beginning to come through the system*. The AMLCTFO came into force in April 2012.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Readers may recall that Schedule 2 of the AMLCTFO provides for stringent CDD and record-keeping requirements for financial institutions in Hong Kong, specified breaches of which can lead to criminal offences pursuant to s. 5 of the AMLCTFO. In the main, the financial institutions are the banks and licensed corporations regulated by the HKMA and SFC, respectively.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the AMLCTFO also regulates (among others) licensed money service operators, with their relevant regulator being Customs and Excise.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>HKSAR v Mak Kit Ping</em> <strong>(麥洁平)</strong> <a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6400000151f1b8eee89cba71cf&amp;docguid=IC2A0F89D92F34D9C96145BD11250CA98&amp;hitguid=IC2A0F89D92F34D9C96145BD11250CA98&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=2\">[2015] CHKEC 1501</a> is one of the first reported criminal prosecutions for breach of a specified provision in s. 5 of the AMLCTFO. The defendant was a money service operator (licensed to conduct remittance and currency exchange). The prosecutions followed investigations by Customs and Excise. The multiple summonses in the Magistrates court relate to alleged offences contrary to s.5(5) of the AMLCTFO, which are stated to have involved multiple “wire transfers” (exceeding HK$8000) and “occasional transactions” (exceeding HK$120,000) between 2013–14 (regulated by Schedule 2, Part 2, s. 3 of the AMLCTFO).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On summary conviction, a “s. 5(5)” offence carries a maximum fine set at level six (HK$100,000) and imprisonment for six months; on indictment, the same offence carries a fine of up to HK$1,000,000 and imprisonment for two years. The punishment is considerably more if a defendant commits a breach of a specified provision with “intent to defraud”.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In <em>HKSAR v Mak Kit Ping</em>, the defendant admitted to multiple offences contrary to s. 5(5) of the AMLCTFO and was fined a total of HK$428,000. Significantly, on the defendant’s appeal against sentence to the High Court, the amount of the total fine was reduced to HK$100,000.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Given the prevalence of small-scale remittance agents and currency changers in parts of Hong Kong, the convictions in this case (some three years after the commencement of the AMLCTFO) come as no surprise. More prosecutions are likely to follow.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>* See (i) <em>Hong Kong Lawyer Exclusively Online</em>, August 2015 (<a href=\"/content/hong-kong-fines-state-bank-india-anti-money-laundering-lapses#\">http://www.hk-lawyer.org/en/article.asp?articleid=3071&amp;c=144</a>) and November 2015 (<a href=\"/content/several-aml-investigations-pipeline-says-hkma-official\">http://www.hk-lawyer.org/en/article.asp?articleid=3311&amp;c=144</a>&nbsp;– <em>“Several AML Investigations in Pipeline, says HKMA Official”</em>); and (ii) s. 21 (“Relevant authorities may take disciplinary actions”) of the AMLCTFO.</p>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:83:\"<p>Jason Carmichael and Warren Ganesh, Smyth &amp; Co in association with RPC</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3413:\"<p>Jason Carmichael and Warren Ganesh, Smyth &amp; Co in association with RPC</p>\n<p>On the back of reports of the first regulatory fine for breaches of the customer due diligence (“CDD”) requirements contained in Schedule 2 of the Anti-Money Laundering and Counter-Terrorist Financing (Financial Institutions) Ordinance (“AMLCTFO”), criminal cases are now beginning to come through the system*. The AMLCTFO came into force in April 2012.</p>\n<p>Readers may recall that Schedule 2 of the AMLCTFO provides for stringent CDD and record-keeping requirements for financial institutions in Hong Kong, specified breaches of which can lead to criminal offences pursuant to s. 5 of the AMLCTFO. In the main, the financial institutions are the banks and licensed corporations regulated by the HKMA and SFC, respectively.</p>\n<p>However, the AMLCTFO also regulates (among others) licensed money service operators, with their relevant regulator being Customs and Excise.</p>\n<p><em>HKSAR v Mak Kit Ping</em> <strong>(麥洁平)</strong> <a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6400000151f1b8eee89cba71cf&amp;docguid=IC2A0F89D92F34D9C96145BD11250CA98&amp;hitguid=IC2A0F89D92F34D9C96145BD11250CA98&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=2\">[2015] CHKEC 1501</a> is one of the first reported criminal prosecutions for breach of a specified provision in s. 5 of the AMLCTFO. The defendant was a money service operator (licensed to conduct remittance and currency exchange). The prosecutions followed investigations by Customs and Excise. The multiple summonses in the Magistrates court relate to alleged offences contrary to s.5(5) of the AMLCTFO, which are stated to have involved multiple “wire transfers” (exceeding HK$8000) and “occasional transactions” (exceeding HK$120,000) between 2013–14 (regulated by Schedule 2, Part 2, s. 3 of the AMLCTFO).</p>\n<p>On summary conviction, a “s. 5(5)” offence carries a maximum fine set at level six (HK$100,000) and imprisonment for six months; on indictment, the same offence carries a fine of up to HK$1,000,000 and imprisonment for two years. The punishment is considerably more if a defendant commits a breach of a specified provision with “intent to defraud”.</p>\n<p>In <em>HKSAR v Mak Kit Ping</em>, the defendant admitted to multiple offences contrary to s. 5(5) of the AMLCTFO and was fined a total of HK$428,000. Significantly, on the defendant’s appeal against sentence to the High Court, the amount of the total fine was reduced to HK$100,000.</p>\n<p>Given the prevalence of small-scale remittance agents and currency changers in parts of Hong Kong, the convictions in this case (some three years after the commencement of the AMLCTFO) come as no surprise. More prosecutions are likely to follow.</p>\n<hr /><p>* See (i) <em>Hong Kong Lawyer Exclusively Online</em>, August 2015 (<a href=\"/content/hong-kong-fines-state-bank-india-anti-money-laundering-lapses#\">http://www.hk-lawyer.org/en/article.asp?articleid=3071&amp;c=144</a>) and November 2015 (<a href=\"/content/several-aml-investigations-pipeline-says-hkma-official\">http://www.hk-lawyer.org/en/article.asp?articleid=3311&amp;c=144</a> – <em>“Several AML Investigations in Pipeline, says HKMA Official”</em>); and (ii) s. 21 (“Relevant authorities may take disciplinary actions”) of the AMLCTFO.</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:82:\"<p>Jason Carmichael and Warren Ganesh, Smyth &amp; Co in association with RPC</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"483\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"114\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:46:\"Convictions for Lack of Customer Due Diligence\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:46:\"Convictions for Lack of Customer Due Diligence\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 00:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:46:\"Convictions for Lack of Customer Due Diligence\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";s:1:\"0\";s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929174\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";N;s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458111751,1),('9130','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9134\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:42:\"沒有執行客戶盡職審查而被定罪\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9130\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456223987\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9129\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1456223987\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3099:\"<p>夏禮豪及Warren Ganesh，Smyth &amp; Co與RPC聯營</p>\r\n\r\n<p>《打擊洗錢及恐怖分子資金籌集(金融機構)條例》(「《條例》」)附表2載有金融機構須執行客戶盡職審查的規定，監管機構早前首次對違反這項規定的金融機構判處罰款，現在，也就是這案件經報道後不久，涉及這規定的刑事案件開始出現*。《條例》於2012年4月生效。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>讀者大概記得《條例》附表2嚴格規定香港金融機構須執行客戶盡職審查及備存紀錄，根據《條例》第5條，違反指明的條文有可能導致刑事罪行。大部分金融機構都是分別受香港金管局及證監會監管的銀行及持牌法團。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>然而，《條例》亦規管(其中包括)持牌金錢服務經營者，現時相關的監管機構是海關。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>在<em>香港特別行政區訴麥洁平</em><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6400000151f1b8eee89cba71cf&amp;docguid=IC2A0F89D92F34D9C96145BD11250CA98&amp;hitguid=IC2A0F89D92F34D9C96145BD11250CA98&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=2\">[2015] CHKEC 1501</a>一案，被告人違反《條例》第5條指明的條文而被刑事檢控，是首批經彙報的同類案件之一。被告人是金錢服務經營者(獲發牌經營滙款及貨幣兌換的業務)。被告人被檢控之前被海關調查。多張傳召被告人到裁判法院出庭的傳票是根據《條例》第5(5)條發出，指被告人2013-14年間違反該條訂明的罪行，涉及多次「電滙轉帳」(超過港幣8,000元)及「非經常性交易」(超過港幣120,000元)(受《條例》附表2第2部第3條規管)。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>凡違反「第5(5)條」的罪行的，一經循簡易程序定罪，最高可處第6級罰款(港幣100,000元)及監禁六個月；凡違反同一罪行的，一經循公訴程序定罪，最高可處罰款港幣1,000,000元及監禁兩年。如果被告人觸犯某項指明的條文是出於詐騙意圖，懲罰會重得多。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>在香港特別行政區訴麥洁平一案中，被告人承認多次違反《條例》第5(5)條的罪行，被判處罰款合共港幣428,000元。被告人就判決向高等法院提出上訴，總罰款大幅減至港幣100,000元。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>由於小規模滙款代理人及貨幣兌換商在香港某些地區到處可見，本案定罪(《條例》生效之後三年多)並不令人意外。這類檢控有可能陸續有來。</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>* 見(i)《香港律師》2015年8月<em>Exclusively Online</em>(<a href=\"/tc/content/hong-kong-fines-state-bank-india-anti-money-laundering-lapses\">http://www.hk-lawyer.org/tc/article.asp?articleid=3071&amp;c=144</a>)及2015年11月Exclusively Online(<a href=\"/tc/content/several-aml-investigations-pipeline-says-hkma-official\">http://www.hk-lawyer.org/tc/article.asp?articleid=3311&amp;c=144</a> – <em>Several AML Investigations in Pipeline, says HKMA Official</em>)；及(ii)《條例》第21條(「有關當局可採取紀律行動」)。</p>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:63:\"<p>夏禮豪及Warren Ganesh，Smyth &amp; Co與RPC聯營</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3072:\"<p>夏禮豪及Warren Ganesh，Smyth &amp; Co與RPC聯營</p>\n<p>《打擊洗錢及恐怖分子資金籌集(金融機構)條例》(「《條例》」)附表2載有金融機構須執行客戶盡職審查的規定，監管機構早前首次對違反這項規定的金融機構判處罰款，現在，也就是這案件經報道後不久，涉及這規定的刑事案件開始出現*。《條例》於2012年4月生效。</p>\n<p>讀者大概記得《條例》附表2嚴格規定香港金融機構須執行客戶盡職審查及備存紀錄，根據《條例》第5條，違反指明的條文有可能導致刑事罪行。大部分金融機構都是分別受香港金管局及證監會監管的銀行及持牌法團。</p>\n<p>然而，《條例》亦規管(其中包括)持牌金錢服務經營者，現時相關的監管機構是海關。</p>\n<p>在<em>香港特別行政區訴麥洁平</em><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6400000151f1b8eee89cba71cf&amp;docguid=IC2A0F89D92F34D9C96145BD11250CA98&amp;hitguid=IC2A0F89D92F34D9C96145BD11250CA98&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=2\">[2015] CHKEC 1501</a>一案，被告人違反《條例》第5條指明的條文而被刑事檢控，是首批經彙報的同類案件之一。被告人是金錢服務經營者(獲發牌經營滙款及貨幣兌換的業務)。被告人被檢控之前被海關調查。多張傳召被告人到裁判法院出庭的傳票是根據《條例》第5(5)條發出，指被告人2013-14年間違反該條訂明的罪行，涉及多次「電滙轉帳」(超過港幣8,000元)及「非經常性交易」(超過港幣120,000元)(受《條例》附表2第2部第3條規管)。</p>\n<p>凡違反「第5(5)條」的罪行的，一經循簡易程序定罪，最高可處第6級罰款(港幣100,000元)及監禁六個月；凡違反同一罪行的，一經循公訴程序定罪，最高可處罰款港幣1,000,000元及監禁兩年。如果被告人觸犯某項指明的條文是出於詐騙意圖，懲罰會重得多。</p>\n<p>在香港特別行政區訴麥洁平一案中，被告人承認多次違反《條例》第5(5)條的罪行，被判處罰款合共港幣428,000元。被告人就判決向高等法院提出上訴，總罰款大幅減至港幣100,000元。</p>\n<p>由於小規模滙款代理人及貨幣兌換商在香港某些地區到處可見，本案定罪(《條例》生效之後三年多)並不令人意外。這類檢控有可能陸續有來。</p>\n<hr /><p>* 見(i)《香港律師》2015年8月<em>Exclusively Online</em>(<a href=\"/tc/content/hong-kong-fines-state-bank-india-anti-money-laundering-lapses\">http://www.hk-lawyer.org/tc/article.asp?articleid=3071&amp;c=144</a>)及2015年11月Exclusively Online(<a href=\"/tc/content/several-aml-investigations-pipeline-says-hkma-official\">http://www.hk-lawyer.org/tc/article.asp?articleid=3311&amp;c=144</a> – <em>Several AML Investigations in Pipeline, says HKMA Official</em>)；及(ii)《條例》第21條(「有關當局可採取紀律行動」)。</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:62:\"<p>夏禮豪及Warren Ganesh，Smyth &amp; Co與RPC聯營</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"520\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"576\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:42:\"沒有執行客戶盡職審查而被定罪\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:42:\"沒有執行客戶盡職審查而被定罪\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 00:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:42:\"沒有執行客戶盡職審查而被定罪\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";s:1:\"0\";s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929174\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";N;s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183993,1),('9179','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9183\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"\"Suitability Term\"\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9179\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9179\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3919:\"Regulatory Practice Group, Smyth & Co in association with RPC<p>\n	The Securities and Futures Commission&rsquo;s <em>&ldquo;Consultation Conclusions on the Client Agreement Requirements&rdquo;</em> for financial intermediaries was published in December 2015, a year or so after the end of the SFC&rsquo;s further consultation exercise. There were few surprises.</p>\n<p>\n	In short, the SFC has given financial intermediaries until 9 June 2017 to review and revise their client agreements to include:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		a new &ldquo;Suitability Term&rdquo; to be added as part of clause 6.2 of the SFC&rsquo;s Code of Conduct (the &ldquo;Suitability Term&rdquo;)*; and</li>\n	<li>\n		a new clause 6.5 of the Code of Conduct mandating that a licensed or registered person not include in a client agreement any provision which is inconsistent with its obligations under the Code of Conduct or which misdescribes the actual services to be provided to a client (&ldquo;clause 6.5&rdquo;).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	The wording of the Suitability Term is the same as proposed by the SFC in its consultation exercise between 2013&ndash;14. Therefore, the SFC has not been persuaded by respondents to the consultation exercise to withdraw or dilute this proposal. Following certain feedback from some respondents seeking clarification of the meaning of &ldquo;financial product&rdquo;, the SFC has added a note to the Suitability Term in order to define what this means (namely, &ldquo;any securities, futures contracts or leveraged foreign exchange contracts as defined under the Securities and Futures Ordinance&rdquo;).</p>\n<p>\n	The only other concession by the SFC appears to be that new provisions to the Code of Conduct will become mandatory as from 9 June 2017, rather than 25 March 2016 as previously mooted (the &ldquo;transitional period&rdquo;). However, the SFC&rsquo;s accompanying press release makes it clear that financial intermediaries are expected to get on with the task of revising their client agreements &ldquo;immediately&rdquo;, both with respect to new clients and existing clients*. In fairness, some financial intermediaries have already begun this process, recognising that the SFC was unlikely to budge during the final consultation exercise.</p>\n<p>\n	The Suitability Term and clause 6.5 are significant developments. They represent an attempt by the SFC to address the bargaining position between investors and financial intermediaries by shifting the legal focus to the services and/or the financial product provided through financial intermediaries (rather than, for example, on the operation and validity of their disclaimer clauses). In particular, these two new provisions are an attempt to prevent financial intermediaries from relying on exclusion and non-reliance clauses that state that services are &ldquo;execution-only&rdquo; in circumstances where (in fact) advice is given at the outset.</p>\n<p>\n	Going forward, aggrieved investors should not get carried away with the new provisions. There will still be a need for claimants to prove a breach; for example, that the financial product is not &ldquo;reasonably suitable&rdquo;. Just as importantly, claimants will need to establish and quantify their loss.</p>\n<hr />\n<p>\n	* <em>&ldquo;If we [the intermediary] solicit the sale of or recommend any financial product to you [the client], the financial product must be reasonably suitable for you having regard to your financial situation, investment experience and investment objectives. No other provision of this agreement or any other document we may ask you to sign and no statement we may ask you to make derogates from this clause&rdquo;</em>. See SFC Press Release, dated 8 December 2015 (<a href=\"http://www.sfc.hk/edistributionWeb/gateway/EN/news-and-announcements/news/doc?refNo=15PR120\">http://www.sfc.hk/edistributionWeb/gateway/EN/news-and-announcements/news/doc?refNo=15PR120</a>).</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:61:\"Regulatory Practice Group, Smyth & Co in association with RPC\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3818:\"<p>Regulatory Practice Group, Smyth &amp; Co in association with RPC\n</p><p>\n	The Securities and Futures Commission’s <em>“Consultation Conclusions on the Client Agreement Requirements”</em> for financial intermediaries was published in December 2015, a year or so after the end of the SFC’s further consultation exercise. There were few surprises.</p>\n<p>\n	In short, the SFC has given financial intermediaries until 9 June 2017 to review and revise their client agreements to include:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		a new “Suitability Term” to be added as part of clause 6.2 of the SFC’s Code of Conduct (the “Suitability Term”)*; and</li>\n<li>\n		a new clause 6.5 of the Code of Conduct mandating that a licensed or registered person not include in a client agreement any provision which is inconsistent with its obligations under the Code of Conduct or which misdescribes the actual services to be provided to a client (“clause 6.5”).</li>\n</ul><p>\n	The wording of the Suitability Term is the same as proposed by the SFC in its consultation exercise between 2013–14. Therefore, the SFC has not been persuaded by respondents to the consultation exercise to withdraw or dilute this proposal. Following certain feedback from some respondents seeking clarification of the meaning of “financial product”, the SFC has added a note to the Suitability Term in order to define what this means (namely, “any securities, futures contracts or leveraged foreign exchange contracts as defined under the Securities and Futures Ordinance”).</p>\n<p>\n	The only other concession by the SFC appears to be that new provisions to the Code of Conduct will become mandatory as from 9 June 2017, rather than 25 March 2016 as previously mooted (the “transitional period”). However, the SFC’s accompanying press release makes it clear that financial intermediaries are expected to get on with the task of revising their client agreements “immediately”, both with respect to new clients and existing clients*. In fairness, some financial intermediaries have already begun this process, recognising that the SFC was unlikely to budge during the final consultation exercise.</p>\n<p>\n	The Suitability Term and clause 6.5 are significant developments. They represent an attempt by the SFC to address the bargaining position between investors and financial intermediaries by shifting the legal focus to the services and/or the financial product provided through financial intermediaries (rather than, for example, on the operation and validity of their disclaimer clauses). In particular, these two new provisions are an attempt to prevent financial intermediaries from relying on exclusion and non-reliance clauses that state that services are “execution-only” in circumstances where (in fact) advice is given at the outset.</p>\n<p>\n	Going forward, aggrieved investors should not get carried away with the new provisions. There will still be a need for claimants to prove a breach; for example, that the financial product is not “reasonably suitable”. Just as importantly, claimants will need to establish and quantify their loss.</p>\n<hr /><p>\n	* <em>“If we [the intermediary] solicit the sale of or recommend any financial product to you [the client], the financial product must be reasonably suitable for you having regard to your financial situation, investment experience and investment objectives. No other provision of this agreement or any other document we may ask you to sign and no statement we may ask you to make derogates from this clause”</em>. See SFC Press Release, dated 8 December 2015 (<a href=\"http://www.sfc.hk/edistributionWeb/gateway/EN/news-and-announcements/news/doc?refNo=15PR120\">http://www.sfc.hk/edistributionWeb/gateway/EN/news-and-announcements/news/doc?refNo=15PR120</a>).</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:73:\"<p>Regulatory Practice Group, Smyth &amp; Co in association with RPC</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"483\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"114\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"\"Suitability Term\"\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:28:\"&quot;Suitability Term&quot;\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:18:\"\"Suitability Term\"\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458111751,1),('9180','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9184\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:21:\"「合適性規定」\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9180\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9179\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2996:\"監管執業組，Smyth & Co與RPC聯營<p>\n	證券及期貨事務監察委員會於2015年12月發表有關金融中介機構客戶協議規定的諮詢總結。該諮詢已於一年左右前結束。總結有幾個令人意外之處。</p>\n<p>\n	總括而言，證監會要求金融中介機構於2017年6月9日或之前檢視及修訂客戶協議，納入包括以下新條款：</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		在證券及期貨事務監察委員會《操守準則》第 6.2段加入「合適性規定」；及</li>\n	<li>\n		《操守準則》中新增第 6.5 段，禁止持牌人或註冊人在客戶協議加入與 《操守準則》下須予遵守的責任不符或對向客戶提供的實際服務構成失實描述的合約條款(第 6.5 段)。</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	「合適性規定」的用字與證監會在2013&ndash;14年諮詢內的建議相同。因此，證監會並沒有按諮詢回應者的意見，撤回或淡化本建議。鑑於有部份回應者要求澄清「金融產品」的定義，證監會在「合適性規定」加入一項註釋，以界定該詞的涵蓋範圍(即「《證券及期貨條例》所界定的任何證券、期貨合約或槓桿式外匯交易合約」)。</p>\n<p>\n	證監會另外唯一讓步似乎是必須於《操守準則》的新條款將由2017年6月9日起強制生效，而非之前建議的2016年3月25日(「過渡期」)。然而，證監會的新聞稿明確表示，金融中介機構應「即時」開始對其客戶協議作出檢討及修訂，無論是對於新客戶和現有客戶*。平心而論，一些金融中介機構在諮詢最後階段意識到證監會不大可能作出讓步，已開始這個過程。</p>\n<p>\n	「合適性規定」及第 6.5 段是重大進展，代表證監會試圖通過轉移法律焦點至金融中介機構提供的服務和／或金融產品(而非例如免責聲明條款的運作及效力)，來解決投資者與金融中介機構之間的議價地位。尤其是，這兩項新規定是為了防止金融中介機構利用例外及的非依賴條款聲明服務「只限執行」，而實際上從一開始就給予建議。</p>\n<p>\n	展望未來，受影響的投資者不應對新規定得意忘形，因為申索人仍需證明違反規定，例如，該金融產品不是「合理地適合」。同樣重要的是，申索人需要確立及量化其損失。</p>\n<hr />\n<p>\n	* 「假如我們[中介人]向閣下[客戶]招攬銷售或建議任何金融產品，該金融產品必須是我們經考慮閣下的財政狀況、投資經驗及投資目標後而認為合理地適合閣下的。本協議的其他條 文或任何其他我們可能要求閣下簽署的文件及我們可能要求閣下作出的聲明概不會減損本 條款的效力。」見證監會2015年12月8日新聞稿(<a href=\"http://www.sfc.hk/edistributionWeb/gateway/EN/news-and-announcements/news/doc?refNo=15PR120\">http://www.sfc.hk/edistributionWeb/gateway/EN/news-and-announcements/news/doc?refNo=15PR120</a>)。</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:40:\"監管執業組，Smyth & Co與RPC聯營\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2999:\"<p>監管執業組，Smyth &amp; Co與RPC聯營\n</p><p>\n	證券及期貨事務監察委員會於2015年12月發表有關金融中介機構客戶協議規定的諮詢總結。該諮詢已於一年左右前結束。總結有幾個令人意外之處。</p>\n<p>\n	總括而言，證監會要求金融中介機構於2017年6月9日或之前檢視及修訂客戶協議，納入包括以下新條款：</p>\n<ul><li>\n		在證券及期貨事務監察委員會《操守準則》第 6.2段加入「合適性規定」；及</li>\n<li>\n		《操守準則》中新增第 6.5 段，禁止持牌人或註冊人在客戶協議加入與 《操守準則》下須予遵守的責任不符或對向客戶提供的實際服務構成失實描述的合約條款(第 6.5 段)。</li>\n</ul><p>\n	「合適性規定」的用字與證監會在2013–14年諮詢內的建議相同。因此，證監會並沒有按諮詢回應者的意見，撤回或淡化本建議。鑑於有部份回應者要求澄清「金融產品」的定義，證監會在「合適性規定」加入一項註釋，以界定該詞的涵蓋範圍(即「《證券及期貨條例》所界定的任何證券、期貨合約或槓桿式外匯交易合約」)。</p>\n<p>\n	證監會另外唯一讓步似乎是必須於《操守準則》的新條款將由2017年6月9日起強制生效，而非之前建議的2016年3月25日(「過渡期」)。然而，證監會的新聞稿明確表示，金融中介機構應「即時」開始對其客戶協議作出檢討及修訂，無論是對於新客戶和現有客戶*。平心而論，一些金融中介機構在諮詢最後階段意識到證監會不大可能作出讓步，已開始這個過程。</p>\n<p>\n	「合適性規定」及第 6.5 段是重大進展，代表證監會試圖通過轉移法律焦點至金融中介機構提供的服務和／或金融產品(而非例如免責聲明條款的運作及效力)，來解決投資者與金融中介機構之間的議價地位。尤其是，這兩項新規定是為了防止金融中介機構利用例外及的非依賴條款聲明服務「只限執行」，而實際上從一開始就給予建議。</p>\n<p>\n	展望未來，受影響的投資者不應對新規定得意忘形，因為申索人仍需證明違反規定，例如，該金融產品不是「合理地適合」。同樣重要的是，申索人需要確立及量化其損失。</p>\n<hr /><p>\n	* 「假如我們[中介人]向閣下[客戶]招攬銷售或建議任何金融產品，該金融產品必須是我們經考慮閣下的財政狀況、投資經驗及投資目標後而認為合理地適合閣下的。本協議的其他條 文或任何其他我們可能要求閣下簽署的文件及我們可能要求閣下作出的聲明概不會減損本 條款的效力。」見證監會2015年12月8日新聞稿(<a href=\"http://www.sfc.hk/edistributionWeb/gateway/EN/news-and-announcements/news/doc?refNo=15PR120\">http://www.sfc.hk/edistributionWeb/gateway/EN/news-and-announcements/news/doc?refNo=15PR120</a>)。</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:52:\"<p>監管執業組，Smyth &amp; Co與RPC聯營</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"520\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"576\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:21:\"「合適性規定」\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:21:\"「合適性規定」\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:21:\"「合適性規定」\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183993,1),('9203','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9207\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:62:\"IOSCO Looks at New Risks Emerging from OTC Derivatives Reforms\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9203\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1453939200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9203\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:7382:\"Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence<p>\n	The International Organisation of Securities Commissions (&ldquo;IOSCO&rdquo;) is now looking at a number of new issues and risks that have emerged in the over-the-counter derivatives markets following six years of reforms. Amongst the issues being considered include whether the G20 remit of mandatory reporting and clearing has achieved its intended purpose.<br />\n	<br />\n	At the Pittsburgh Summit in September 2009, the G20 agreed that all standardised OTC derivatives contracts should be traded on exchanges or electronic trading platforms, where appropriate; cleared through central counterparties to reduce counterparty risk; and reported to trade repositories to increase transparency. Non-centrally cleared derivatives should be subject to higher capital requirements.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>New Issues on OTC Derivatives Reforms<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	David Wright, secretary-general of IOSCO, said that although considerable progress had been made on the derivatives market reform &ndash; for example, the majority of interest rate swaps are being cleared through CCPs, and OTC derivatives are becoming subject to higher capital requirements &ndash; much remained to be done.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;By and large, the ship has been steadied. That&#39;s not to say the job is done. There are new risks emerging and regulators still have significant challenges before them.&quot;<br />\n	<br />\n	The robustness of CCPs is another area that is now under intensive examination, according to Wright. He said the Committee on Payments and Market Infrastructures (&ldquo;CPMI&rdquo;) and the International Organization of Securities Commissions&#39; standards for CCPs are working closely together on analysing the Principles for Financial Market Infrastructures (&ldquo;PFMI&rdquo;) under different conditions.<br />\n	<br />\n	Some of the PFMI requirements relate to the financial risk management practices of CCPs regarding governance, stress-testing, margin, liquidity, collateral and recovery. Other areas that are now being examined include whether the default mechanism is able to deal appropriately with a default situation and whether CCPs have sufficient capital should a counterparty fail.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Lack of Data Harmonization<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	The mandatory trade reporting of OTC derivatives trade data which was intended to increase transparency might not have achieved its intended purpose. Wright said what started off as a simple idea of having globally aggregated trade data, particularly on derivatives, has regrettably burgeoned into 29 trade repositories worldwide. He said this has presented a different set of challenges, including the difficulty in harmonising and aggregating trade data, which has made it difficult for regulators to have a full picture of trading pattern. Regulators worldwide are now working on harmonising data based on products and transaction pattern.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;Regulators are working on common data standards but this is going to take some time,&rdquo; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Mandatory Clearing<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	Despite the new issues that have emerged, the main financial centres in the Asia-Pacific region, namely Australia, Hong Kong, Japan and Singapore, are pressing ahead with their respective OTC derivatives reforms. Hong Kong and Singapore began voluntary clearing of OTC derivatives trades at the end of 2014, and mandatory clearing in those two jurisdictions is expected to go into full swing this year, said Kishore Ramakrishnan, director, consulting at PwC in Hong Kong.<br />\n	<br />\n	Ramakrishnan said Singapore is likely to begin mandatory clearing of certain derivatives products, mainly interest rate swaps, foreign exchange products and non-deliverable forwards, during the second and third quarters of this year. He said Hong Kong was widely expected to enforce mandatory clearing in the third quarter after it has gone through the legislative process in the first quarter of 2016.<br />\n	<br />\n	Ramakrishnan said most jurisdictions in the Asia-Pacific region will begin with interbank clearing, whereas buy-side clearing, which applies to derivatives users such as assets managers, hedge funds, insurance firms and corporates, is not expected to happen until 2017.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;In fact, buy-side clearing may not take place until 2018, largely because of the lack of liquidity for some derivatives products,&quot; he said. <br />\n	<br />\n	As banks operating in the OTC derivatives markets work toward compliance with the liquidity coverage ratio and the net stable funding ratio, both of which have been slated for implementation in 2018, preparation work is now underway. <br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Margin Requirements for Non-Centrally Cleared Trades<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	The implementation of margin requirements for non-centrally cleared trades is set to take place on 1 September 2016, and more Asian jurisdictions will publish their respective consultation papers in the first quarter of this year. Ramakrishnan said he expected to see Japan and Singapore finalise their rules in the first quarter, while Hong Kong could be next, following the release of its consultation paper in December 2015.<br />\n	<br />\n	The fact that Asian jurisdictions are all at such different stages of progress in terms of their rule-making has made it much harder for financial institutions to prepare for rule implementation.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Substituted Compliance and Risk Mitigation<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	Tom Jenkins, partner at KPMG China, said that if regulators were able to finalise the substituted compliance determination before the 1 September 2016 implementation date, it would reduce the complex tasks that financial institutions need to do.<br />\n	<br />\n	Jenkins said regulators are likely to expect banks which enter into non-centrally cleared derivatives with covered entities to comply with risk mitigation requirements. The Hong Kong Monetary Authority, for instance, proposed such requirements in its December consultation paper. These risk mitigation requirements cover areas such as trading relationship documentation and trade confirmation. Banks would be required to examine their policy processes to ensure that they meet these requirements, Jenkins said.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Netting<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	The netting concept, which falls under the banner of margin requirements for bilateral trades, will be one of the main concerns for market participants this year, according to Jenkins. Under the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision&#39;s framework, banks are allowed to net off contracts that are profitable against those which are in loss-making positions. Regulations in the European Union and the United States allow netting to apply only if there is a valid netting agreement in place. <br />\n	<br />\n	In Asia, where many jurisdictions have no valid netting opinions, netting becomes an issue, Jenkins said. &quot;If your counterparty is in a jurisdiction with no netting opinions, margin will be calculated on a gross basis, which is likely to be higher,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	Jenkins said the HKMA and the Monetary Authority of Singapore are considering whether to introduce a threshold on transactions with counterparties in non-netting jurisdictions.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:37:\"Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:7158:\"<p>Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	The International Organisation of Securities Commissions (“IOSCO”) is now looking at a number of new issues and risks that have emerged in the over-the-counter derivatives markets following six years of reforms. Amongst the issues being considered include whether the G20 remit of mandatory reporting and clearing has achieved its intended purpose.</p>\n<p>	At the Pittsburgh Summit in September 2009, the G20 agreed that all standardised OTC derivatives contracts should be traded on exchanges or electronic trading platforms, where appropriate; cleared through central counterparties to reduce counterparty risk; and reported to trade repositories to increase transparency. Non-centrally cleared derivatives should be subject to higher capital requirements.</p>\n<p>	<strong>New Issues on OTC Derivatives Reforms<br /></strong><br />\n	David Wright, secretary-general of IOSCO, said that although considerable progress had been made on the derivatives market reform – for example, the majority of interest rate swaps are being cleared through CCPs, and OTC derivatives are becoming subject to higher capital requirements – much remained to be done.</p>\n<p>	\"By and large, the ship has been steadied. That\'s not to say the job is done. There are new risks emerging and regulators still have significant challenges before them.\"</p>\n<p>	The robustness of CCPs is another area that is now under intensive examination, according to Wright. He said the Committee on Payments and Market Infrastructures (“CPMI”) and the International Organization of Securities Commissions\' standards for CCPs are working closely together on analysing the Principles for Financial Market Infrastructures (“PFMI”) under different conditions.</p>\n<p>	Some of the PFMI requirements relate to the financial risk management practices of CCPs regarding governance, stress-testing, margin, liquidity, collateral and recovery. Other areas that are now being examined include whether the default mechanism is able to deal appropriately with a default situation and whether CCPs have sufficient capital should a counterparty fail.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Lack of Data Harmonization<br /></strong><br />\n	The mandatory trade reporting of OTC derivatives trade data which was intended to increase transparency might not have achieved its intended purpose. Wright said what started off as a simple idea of having globally aggregated trade data, particularly on derivatives, has regrettably burgeoned into 29 trade repositories worldwide. He said this has presented a different set of challenges, including the difficulty in harmonising and aggregating trade data, which has made it difficult for regulators to have a full picture of trading pattern. Regulators worldwide are now working on harmonising data based on products and transaction pattern.</p>\n<p>	\"Regulators are working on common data standards but this is going to take some time,” he said.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Mandatory Clearing<br /></strong><br />\n	Despite the new issues that have emerged, the main financial centres in the Asia-Pacific region, namely Australia, Hong Kong, Japan and Singapore, are pressing ahead with their respective OTC derivatives reforms. Hong Kong and Singapore began voluntary clearing of OTC derivatives trades at the end of 2014, and mandatory clearing in those two jurisdictions is expected to go into full swing this year, said Kishore Ramakrishnan, director, consulting at PwC in Hong Kong.</p>\n<p>	Ramakrishnan said Singapore is likely to begin mandatory clearing of certain derivatives products, mainly interest rate swaps, foreign exchange products and non-deliverable forwards, during the second and third quarters of this year. He said Hong Kong was widely expected to enforce mandatory clearing in the third quarter after it has gone through the legislative process in the first quarter of 2016.</p>\n<p>	Ramakrishnan said most jurisdictions in the Asia-Pacific region will begin with interbank clearing, whereas buy-side clearing, which applies to derivatives users such as assets managers, hedge funds, insurance firms and corporates, is not expected to happen until 2017.</p>\n<p>	\"In fact, buy-side clearing may not take place until 2018, largely because of the lack of liquidity for some derivatives products,\" he said. </p>\n<p>	As banks operating in the OTC derivatives markets work toward compliance with the liquidity coverage ratio and the net stable funding ratio, both of which have been slated for implementation in 2018, preparation work is now underway. </p>\n<p>	<strong>Margin Requirements for Non-Centrally Cleared Trades<br /></strong><br />\n	The implementation of margin requirements for non-centrally cleared trades is set to take place on 1 September 2016, and more Asian jurisdictions will publish their respective consultation papers in the first quarter of this year. Ramakrishnan said he expected to see Japan and Singapore finalise their rules in the first quarter, while Hong Kong could be next, following the release of its consultation paper in December 2015.</p>\n<p>	The fact that Asian jurisdictions are all at such different stages of progress in terms of their rule-making has made it much harder for financial institutions to prepare for rule implementation.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Substituted Compliance and Risk Mitigation<br /></strong><br />\n	Tom Jenkins, partner at KPMG China, said that if regulators were able to finalise the substituted compliance determination before the 1 September 2016 implementation date, it would reduce the complex tasks that financial institutions need to do.</p>\n<p>	Jenkins said regulators are likely to expect banks which enter into non-centrally cleared derivatives with covered entities to comply with risk mitigation requirements. The Hong Kong Monetary Authority, for instance, proposed such requirements in its December consultation paper. These risk mitigation requirements cover areas such as trading relationship documentation and trade confirmation. Banks would be required to examine their policy processes to ensure that they meet these requirements, Jenkins said.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Netting<br /></strong><br />\n	The netting concept, which falls under the banner of margin requirements for bilateral trades, will be one of the main concerns for market participants this year, according to Jenkins. Under the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\'s framework, banks are allowed to net off contracts that are profitable against those which are in loss-making positions. Regulations in the European Union and the United States allow netting to apply only if there is a valid netting agreement in place. </p>\n<p>	In Asia, where many jurisdictions have no valid netting opinions, netting becomes an issue, Jenkins said. \"If your counterparty is in a jurisdiction with no netting opinions, margin will be calculated on a gross basis, which is likely to be higher,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	Jenkins said the HKMA and the Monetary Authority of Singapore are considering whether to introduce a threshold on transactions with counterparties in non-netting jurisdictions.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:45:\"<p>Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"662\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"114\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:62:\"IOSCO Looks at New Risks Emerging from OTC Derivatives Reforms\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:62:\"IOSCO Looks at New Risks Emerging from OTC Derivatives Reforms\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:62:\"IOSCO Looks at New Risks Emerging from OTC Derivatives Reforms\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1453939200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458111751,1),('9204','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9208\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:62:\"IOSCO Looks at New Risks Emerging from OTC Derivatives Reforms\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9204\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1453939200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9203\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:7382:\"Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence<p>\n	The International Organisation of Securities Commissions (&ldquo;IOSCO&rdquo;) is now looking at a number of new issues and risks that have emerged in the over-the-counter derivatives markets following six years of reforms. Amongst the issues being considered include whether the G20 remit of mandatory reporting and clearing has achieved its intended purpose.<br />\n	<br />\n	At the Pittsburgh Summit in September 2009, the G20 agreed that all standardised OTC derivatives contracts should be traded on exchanges or electronic trading platforms, where appropriate; cleared through central counterparties to reduce counterparty risk; and reported to trade repositories to increase transparency. Non-centrally cleared derivatives should be subject to higher capital requirements.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>New Issues on OTC Derivatives Reforms<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	David Wright, secretary-general of IOSCO, said that although considerable progress had been made on the derivatives market reform &ndash; for example, the majority of interest rate swaps are being cleared through CCPs, and OTC derivatives are becoming subject to higher capital requirements &ndash; much remained to be done.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;By and large, the ship has been steadied. That&#39;s not to say the job is done. There are new risks emerging and regulators still have significant challenges before them.&quot;<br />\n	<br />\n	The robustness of CCPs is another area that is now under intensive examination, according to Wright. He said the Committee on Payments and Market Infrastructures (&ldquo;CPMI&rdquo;) and the International Organization of Securities Commissions&#39; standards for CCPs are working closely together on analysing the Principles for Financial Market Infrastructures (&ldquo;PFMI&rdquo;) under different conditions.<br />\n	<br />\n	Some of the PFMI requirements relate to the financial risk management practices of CCPs regarding governance, stress-testing, margin, liquidity, collateral and recovery. Other areas that are now being examined include whether the default mechanism is able to deal appropriately with a default situation and whether CCPs have sufficient capital should a counterparty fail.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Lack of Data Harmonization<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	The mandatory trade reporting of OTC derivatives trade data which was intended to increase transparency might not have achieved its intended purpose. Wright said what started off as a simple idea of having globally aggregated trade data, particularly on derivatives, has regrettably burgeoned into 29 trade repositories worldwide. He said this has presented a different set of challenges, including the difficulty in harmonising and aggregating trade data, which has made it difficult for regulators to have a full picture of trading pattern. Regulators worldwide are now working on harmonising data based on products and transaction pattern.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;Regulators are working on common data standards but this is going to take some time,&rdquo; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Mandatory Clearing<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	Despite the new issues that have emerged, the main financial centres in the Asia-Pacific region, namely Australia, Hong Kong, Japan and Singapore, are pressing ahead with their respective OTC derivatives reforms. Hong Kong and Singapore began voluntary clearing of OTC derivatives trades at the end of 2014, and mandatory clearing in those two jurisdictions is expected to go into full swing this year, said Kishore Ramakrishnan, director, consulting at PwC in Hong Kong.<br />\n	<br />\n	Ramakrishnan said Singapore is likely to begin mandatory clearing of certain derivatives products, mainly interest rate swaps, foreign exchange products and non-deliverable forwards, during the second and third quarters of this year. He said Hong Kong was widely expected to enforce mandatory clearing in the third quarter after it has gone through the legislative process in the first quarter of 2016.<br />\n	<br />\n	Ramakrishnan said most jurisdictions in the Asia-Pacific region will begin with interbank clearing, whereas buy-side clearing, which applies to derivatives users such as assets managers, hedge funds, insurance firms and corporates, is not expected to happen until 2017.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;In fact, buy-side clearing may not take place until 2018, largely because of the lack of liquidity for some derivatives products,&quot; he said. <br />\n	<br />\n	As banks operating in the OTC derivatives markets work toward compliance with the liquidity coverage ratio and the net stable funding ratio, both of which have been slated for implementation in 2018, preparation work is now underway. <br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Margin Requirements for Non-Centrally Cleared Trades<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	The implementation of margin requirements for non-centrally cleared trades is set to take place on 1 September 2016, and more Asian jurisdictions will publish their respective consultation papers in the first quarter of this year. Ramakrishnan said he expected to see Japan and Singapore finalise their rules in the first quarter, while Hong Kong could be next, following the release of its consultation paper in December 2015.<br />\n	<br />\n	The fact that Asian jurisdictions are all at such different stages of progress in terms of their rule-making has made it much harder for financial institutions to prepare for rule implementation.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Substituted Compliance and Risk Mitigation<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	Tom Jenkins, partner at KPMG China, said that if regulators were able to finalise the substituted compliance determination before the 1 September 2016 implementation date, it would reduce the complex tasks that financial institutions need to do.<br />\n	<br />\n	Jenkins said regulators are likely to expect banks which enter into non-centrally cleared derivatives with covered entities to comply with risk mitigation requirements. The Hong Kong Monetary Authority, for instance, proposed such requirements in its December consultation paper. These risk mitigation requirements cover areas such as trading relationship documentation and trade confirmation. Banks would be required to examine their policy processes to ensure that they meet these requirements, Jenkins said.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Netting<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	The netting concept, which falls under the banner of margin requirements for bilateral trades, will be one of the main concerns for market participants this year, according to Jenkins. Under the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision&#39;s framework, banks are allowed to net off contracts that are profitable against those which are in loss-making positions. Regulations in the European Union and the United States allow netting to apply only if there is a valid netting agreement in place. <br />\n	<br />\n	In Asia, where many jurisdictions have no valid netting opinions, netting becomes an issue, Jenkins said. &quot;If your counterparty is in a jurisdiction with no netting opinions, margin will be calculated on a gross basis, which is likely to be higher,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	Jenkins said the HKMA and the Monetary Authority of Singapore are considering whether to introduce a threshold on transactions with counterparties in non-netting jurisdictions.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:37:\"Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:7158:\"<p>Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	The International Organisation of Securities Commissions (“IOSCO”) is now looking at a number of new issues and risks that have emerged in the over-the-counter derivatives markets following six years of reforms. Amongst the issues being considered include whether the G20 remit of mandatory reporting and clearing has achieved its intended purpose.</p>\n<p>	At the Pittsburgh Summit in September 2009, the G20 agreed that all standardised OTC derivatives contracts should be traded on exchanges or electronic trading platforms, where appropriate; cleared through central counterparties to reduce counterparty risk; and reported to trade repositories to increase transparency. Non-centrally cleared derivatives should be subject to higher capital requirements.</p>\n<p>	<strong>New Issues on OTC Derivatives Reforms<br /></strong><br />\n	David Wright, secretary-general of IOSCO, said that although considerable progress had been made on the derivatives market reform – for example, the majority of interest rate swaps are being cleared through CCPs, and OTC derivatives are becoming subject to higher capital requirements – much remained to be done.</p>\n<p>	\"By and large, the ship has been steadied. That\'s not to say the job is done. There are new risks emerging and regulators still have significant challenges before them.\"</p>\n<p>	The robustness of CCPs is another area that is now under intensive examination, according to Wright. He said the Committee on Payments and Market Infrastructures (“CPMI”) and the International Organization of Securities Commissions\' standards for CCPs are working closely together on analysing the Principles for Financial Market Infrastructures (“PFMI”) under different conditions.</p>\n<p>	Some of the PFMI requirements relate to the financial risk management practices of CCPs regarding governance, stress-testing, margin, liquidity, collateral and recovery. Other areas that are now being examined include whether the default mechanism is able to deal appropriately with a default situation and whether CCPs have sufficient capital should a counterparty fail.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Lack of Data Harmonization<br /></strong><br />\n	The mandatory trade reporting of OTC derivatives trade data which was intended to increase transparency might not have achieved its intended purpose. Wright said what started off as a simple idea of having globally aggregated trade data, particularly on derivatives, has regrettably burgeoned into 29 trade repositories worldwide. He said this has presented a different set of challenges, including the difficulty in harmonising and aggregating trade data, which has made it difficult for regulators to have a full picture of trading pattern. Regulators worldwide are now working on harmonising data based on products and transaction pattern.</p>\n<p>	\"Regulators are working on common data standards but this is going to take some time,” he said.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Mandatory Clearing<br /></strong><br />\n	Despite the new issues that have emerged, the main financial centres in the Asia-Pacific region, namely Australia, Hong Kong, Japan and Singapore, are pressing ahead with their respective OTC derivatives reforms. Hong Kong and Singapore began voluntary clearing of OTC derivatives trades at the end of 2014, and mandatory clearing in those two jurisdictions is expected to go into full swing this year, said Kishore Ramakrishnan, director, consulting at PwC in Hong Kong.</p>\n<p>	Ramakrishnan said Singapore is likely to begin mandatory clearing of certain derivatives products, mainly interest rate swaps, foreign exchange products and non-deliverable forwards, during the second and third quarters of this year. He said Hong Kong was widely expected to enforce mandatory clearing in the third quarter after it has gone through the legislative process in the first quarter of 2016.</p>\n<p>	Ramakrishnan said most jurisdictions in the Asia-Pacific region will begin with interbank clearing, whereas buy-side clearing, which applies to derivatives users such as assets managers, hedge funds, insurance firms and corporates, is not expected to happen until 2017.</p>\n<p>	\"In fact, buy-side clearing may not take place until 2018, largely because of the lack of liquidity for some derivatives products,\" he said. </p>\n<p>	As banks operating in the OTC derivatives markets work toward compliance with the liquidity coverage ratio and the net stable funding ratio, both of which have been slated for implementation in 2018, preparation work is now underway. </p>\n<p>	<strong>Margin Requirements for Non-Centrally Cleared Trades<br /></strong><br />\n	The implementation of margin requirements for non-centrally cleared trades is set to take place on 1 September 2016, and more Asian jurisdictions will publish their respective consultation papers in the first quarter of this year. Ramakrishnan said he expected to see Japan and Singapore finalise their rules in the first quarter, while Hong Kong could be next, following the release of its consultation paper in December 2015.</p>\n<p>	The fact that Asian jurisdictions are all at such different stages of progress in terms of their rule-making has made it much harder for financial institutions to prepare for rule implementation.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Substituted Compliance and Risk Mitigation<br /></strong><br />\n	Tom Jenkins, partner at KPMG China, said that if regulators were able to finalise the substituted compliance determination before the 1 September 2016 implementation date, it would reduce the complex tasks that financial institutions need to do.</p>\n<p>	Jenkins said regulators are likely to expect banks which enter into non-centrally cleared derivatives with covered entities to comply with risk mitigation requirements. The Hong Kong Monetary Authority, for instance, proposed such requirements in its December consultation paper. These risk mitigation requirements cover areas such as trading relationship documentation and trade confirmation. Banks would be required to examine their policy processes to ensure that they meet these requirements, Jenkins said.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Netting<br /></strong><br />\n	The netting concept, which falls under the banner of margin requirements for bilateral trades, will be one of the main concerns for market participants this year, according to Jenkins. Under the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\'s framework, banks are allowed to net off contracts that are profitable against those which are in loss-making positions. Regulations in the European Union and the United States allow netting to apply only if there is a valid netting agreement in place. </p>\n<p>	In Asia, where many jurisdictions have no valid netting opinions, netting becomes an issue, Jenkins said. \"If your counterparty is in a jurisdiction with no netting opinions, margin will be calculated on a gross basis, which is likely to be higher,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	Jenkins said the HKMA and the Monetary Authority of Singapore are considering whether to introduce a threshold on transactions with counterparties in non-netting jurisdictions.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:45:\"<p>Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"661\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"576\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:62:\"IOSCO Looks at New Risks Emerging from OTC Derivatives Reforms\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:62:\"IOSCO Looks at New Risks Emerging from OTC Derivatives Reforms\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:62:\"IOSCO Looks at New Risks Emerging from OTC Derivatives Reforms\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1453939200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183993,1),('9207','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9211\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:68:\"Implementing Prudential Regulations and New Issues Key Focus in 2016\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9207\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1453939200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9207\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:6828:\"Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence<p>\n	Eight years after the financial crisis, regulators will now focus on the implementation of prudential regulations, and this is likely to continue for at least another two years, officials said.<br />\n	<br />\n	Mark Carney, Governor of the Bank of England, said in a recent speech that the series of international reforms which followed the crisis had reached a plateau. Regulatory reforms are far from complete, however, as regulators now begin to deal with the consequences of implementing the various initiatives, and make legislative changes in the domestic markets to facilitate rule implementation over the next few years, according to Keith Pogson, partner at EY in Hong Kong.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;That&#39;s what most regulators&#39; agenda is going to be. It&#39;s not just catching up, but it&#39;s implementing locally what&#39;s going on globally, and making [the changes] happen. Basel III, total loss-absorbing capacity (&ldquo;TLAC&rdquo;), and recovery and resolution plans, OTC derivatives reforms, CCPs, FATCA, all of this stuff has been coming for a long time,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Policy Formulation Far from Complete<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	Simon Topping, head of regulations for Asia Pacific at KPMG China, said that although regulators had completed most of the policy formulation and were moving toward implementation, some aspects of policy formulation were far from complete.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;You have the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision [BCBS], the Financial Stability Board [FSB] and Mr. Carney saying they have finalised the policy formulation stage. That&#39;s largely true but there are important issues that are not resolved,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	Topping said the standardised approach to credit risk is an example of a piece of regulation which has a number of unresolved issues. He said the second consultation paper issued by the BCBS in December last year would present considerable challenges to banks, particularly to Asian banks.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;Banks who will use the new standardised approach fear that it will result in higher risk-weighted assets and hence lower capital ratios. Moreover, there will also be an indirect effect on those banks using the internal ratings-based (&ldquo;IRB&rdquo;) approach, as the capital savings they can make will be constrained by the introduction of a floor calculated relative to the new standardised approach,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	Basel III is another area where implementation is expected to continue until 2018, according to Topping. Changes to Basel III are likely as the BCBS now attempts to evaluate it in a holistic manner and one of the possible changes is the removal of some of the capital buffers, he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	Basel III requires banks to maintain a number of capital buffers, which some banks have considered duplicative. Topping said banks were hoping that BCBS would remove some of them.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;BCBS is looking at whether there is a need to re-calibrate capital and banks are hoping that there will be a good outcome,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	The asset management sector could see important regulatory developments this year, said David Wright, secretary-general of the International Organisation of Securities Commissions. Some banking regulators at the FSB are concerned about the risks posed by asset managers and whether the bigger players should be required to put in place specific measures, he said. Some feel that the new regulations on banks have shifted risks to asset managers and the shadow banking sector.<br />\n	<br />\n	Wright said the FSB-IOSCO technical work group is carrying out in-depth analysis on the market activities of asset managers and no conclusions have so far been made.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;The main &#39;activity&#39; issues are well known: looking primarily at liquidity and leverage issues. These are complex subjects that have to be very carefully thought through. Asset managers are not banks; it&#39;s a very different sector from banks. A consultation paper on the main issues concerning the asset management industry might be expected sometime in the middle of this year,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>New Areas, New Issues<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	Over the next year or two the focus is likely to shift from the prudential issues on which the BCBS has traditionally focused to areas such as technology risk and cyber crime, conduct risk, and financial crime, all areas where regulators other than the BCBS are involved in setting the standards, Topping said.<br />\n	<br />\n	At the 2016 World Economic Forum, held in Davos, Switzerland earlier this month, a panel session talked about combating cyber crime through public-private partnerships. Loretta Lynch, attorney-general of the United States pointed out the importance of collaboration between industries and governments in identifying, predicting and preventing cyber threats. She said the United States has begun implementing some of the recommendations by the World Economic Forum aimed at addressing cyber crime.<br />\n	<br />\n	The World Economic Forum in 2015 launched a cyber crime project, a multi-year engagement with the aim to find practical ways to combat cyber crime through public-private cooperation and a framework for establishing more globally applicable cyber crime legislation.<br />\n	<br />\n	Technology, according to Topping, is now regarded as discrete risk, rather than as part of operational risk. As technology and mobile banking change the pattern of intermediation and enable non-banks providers to offer deposit substitutes and transaction services, regulators will be focusing on the prudential regulation of such providers, he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	Pogson pointed to a new concept called extended enterprise which requires banks to be concerned about the data which reside at vendors and third-parties and the controls the latter put in place when services are being outsourced. For example, banks need to ensure that customers&#39; data is protected when they engage a vendor to manufacture the chip for credit cards.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;Today the focus of regulations has been on the banks themselves, but now it is making sure that the banks are protecting the data when it goes outside the bank to third-party vendors,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Financial Crime</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	Recent terrorist events in France and Indonesia have led regulators to put a sharp focus on terrorist financing. Regulators are also concerned about broader financial crime issues including money laundering, sanctions and fraud. Topping said he expected to see more guidelines for banks on how to deal with sanctions and terrorist financing over the next few years.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:37:\"Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:6572:\"<p>Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	Eight years after the financial crisis, regulators will now focus on the implementation of prudential regulations, and this is likely to continue for at least another two years, officials said.</p>\n<p>	Mark Carney, Governor of the Bank of England, said in a recent speech that the series of international reforms which followed the crisis had reached a plateau. Regulatory reforms are far from complete, however, as regulators now begin to deal with the consequences of implementing the various initiatives, and make legislative changes in the domestic markets to facilitate rule implementation over the next few years, according to Keith Pogson, partner at EY in Hong Kong.</p>\n<p>	\"That\'s what most regulators\' agenda is going to be. It\'s not just catching up, but it\'s implementing locally what\'s going on globally, and making [the changes] happen. Basel III, total loss-absorbing capacity (“TLAC”), and recovery and resolution plans, OTC derivatives reforms, CCPs, FATCA, all of this stuff has been coming for a long time,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Policy Formulation Far from Complete<br /></strong><br />\n	Simon Topping, head of regulations for Asia Pacific at KPMG China, said that although regulators had completed most of the policy formulation and were moving toward implementation, some aspects of policy formulation were far from complete.</p>\n<p>	\"You have the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision [BCBS], the Financial Stability Board [FSB] and Mr. Carney saying they have finalised the policy formulation stage. That\'s largely true but there are important issues that are not resolved,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	Topping said the standardised approach to credit risk is an example of a piece of regulation which has a number of unresolved issues. He said the second consultation paper issued by the BCBS in December last year would present considerable challenges to banks, particularly to Asian banks.</p>\n<p>	\"Banks who will use the new standardised approach fear that it will result in higher risk-weighted assets and hence lower capital ratios. Moreover, there will also be an indirect effect on those banks using the internal ratings-based (“IRB”) approach, as the capital savings they can make will be constrained by the introduction of a floor calculated relative to the new standardised approach,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	Basel III is another area where implementation is expected to continue until 2018, according to Topping. Changes to Basel III are likely as the BCBS now attempts to evaluate it in a holistic manner and one of the possible changes is the removal of some of the capital buffers, he said.</p>\n<p>	Basel III requires banks to maintain a number of capital buffers, which some banks have considered duplicative. Topping said banks were hoping that BCBS would remove some of them.</p>\n<p>	\"BCBS is looking at whether there is a need to re-calibrate capital and banks are hoping that there will be a good outcome,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	The asset management sector could see important regulatory developments this year, said David Wright, secretary-general of the International Organisation of Securities Commissions. Some banking regulators at the FSB are concerned about the risks posed by asset managers and whether the bigger players should be required to put in place specific measures, he said. Some feel that the new regulations on banks have shifted risks to asset managers and the shadow banking sector.</p>\n<p>	Wright said the FSB-IOSCO technical work group is carrying out in-depth analysis on the market activities of asset managers and no conclusions have so far been made.</p>\n<p>	\"The main \'activity\' issues are well known: looking primarily at liquidity and leverage issues. These are complex subjects that have to be very carefully thought through. Asset managers are not banks; it\'s a very different sector from banks. A consultation paper on the main issues concerning the asset management industry might be expected sometime in the middle of this year,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	<strong>New Areas, New Issues<br /></strong><br />\n	Over the next year or two the focus is likely to shift from the prudential issues on which the BCBS has traditionally focused to areas such as technology risk and cyber crime, conduct risk, and financial crime, all areas where regulators other than the BCBS are involved in setting the standards, Topping said.</p>\n<p>	At the 2016 World Economic Forum, held in Davos, Switzerland earlier this month, a panel session talked about combating cyber crime through public-private partnerships. Loretta Lynch, attorney-general of the United States pointed out the importance of collaboration between industries and governments in identifying, predicting and preventing cyber threats. She said the United States has begun implementing some of the recommendations by the World Economic Forum aimed at addressing cyber crime.</p>\n<p>	The World Economic Forum in 2015 launched a cyber crime project, a multi-year engagement with the aim to find practical ways to combat cyber crime through public-private cooperation and a framework for establishing more globally applicable cyber crime legislation.</p>\n<p>	Technology, according to Topping, is now regarded as discrete risk, rather than as part of operational risk. As technology and mobile banking change the pattern of intermediation and enable non-banks providers to offer deposit substitutes and transaction services, regulators will be focusing on the prudential regulation of such providers, he said.</p>\n<p>	Pogson pointed to a new concept called extended enterprise which requires banks to be concerned about the data which reside at vendors and third-parties and the controls the latter put in place when services are being outsourced. For example, banks need to ensure that customers\' data is protected when they engage a vendor to manufacture the chip for credit cards.</p>\n<p>	\"Today the focus of regulations has been on the banks themselves, but now it is making sure that the banks are protecting the data when it goes outside the bank to third-party vendors,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Financial Crime</strong></p>\n<p>	Recent terrorist events in France and Indonesia have led regulators to put a sharp focus on terrorist financing. Regulators are also concerned about broader financial crime issues including money laundering, sanctions and fraud. Topping said he expected to see more guidelines for banks on how to deal with sanctions and terrorist financing over the next few years.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:45:\"<p>Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"662\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"114\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:68:\"Implementing Prudential Regulations and New Issues Key Focus in 2016\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:68:\"Implementing Prudential Regulations and New Issues Key Focus in 2016\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:68:\"Implementing Prudential Regulations and New Issues Key Focus in 2016\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12: