INSERT INTO `cache_entity_node` VALUES ('9208','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9212\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:68:\"Implementing Prudential Regulations and New Issues Key Focus in 2016\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9208\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1453939200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9207\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:6828:\"Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence<p>\n	Eight years after the financial crisis, regulators will now focus on the implementation of prudential regulations, and this is likely to continue for at least another two years, officials said.<br />\n	<br />\n	Mark Carney, Governor of the Bank of England, said in a recent speech that the series of international reforms which followed the crisis had reached a plateau. Regulatory reforms are far from complete, however, as regulators now begin to deal with the consequences of implementing the various initiatives, and make legislative changes in the domestic markets to facilitate rule implementation over the next few years, according to Keith Pogson, partner at EY in Hong Kong.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;That&#39;s what most regulators&#39; agenda is going to be. It&#39;s not just catching up, but it&#39;s implementing locally what&#39;s going on globally, and making [the changes] happen. Basel III, total loss-absorbing capacity (&ldquo;TLAC&rdquo;), and recovery and resolution plans, OTC derivatives reforms, CCPs, FATCA, all of this stuff has been coming for a long time,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Policy Formulation Far from Complete<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	Simon Topping, head of regulations for Asia Pacific at KPMG China, said that although regulators had completed most of the policy formulation and were moving toward implementation, some aspects of policy formulation were far from complete.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;You have the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision [BCBS], the Financial Stability Board [FSB] and Mr. Carney saying they have finalised the policy formulation stage. That&#39;s largely true but there are important issues that are not resolved,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	Topping said the standardised approach to credit risk is an example of a piece of regulation which has a number of unresolved issues. He said the second consultation paper issued by the BCBS in December last year would present considerable challenges to banks, particularly to Asian banks.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;Banks who will use the new standardised approach fear that it will result in higher risk-weighted assets and hence lower capital ratios. Moreover, there will also be an indirect effect on those banks using the internal ratings-based (&ldquo;IRB&rdquo;) approach, as the capital savings they can make will be constrained by the introduction of a floor calculated relative to the new standardised approach,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	Basel III is another area where implementation is expected to continue until 2018, according to Topping. Changes to Basel III are likely as the BCBS now attempts to evaluate it in a holistic manner and one of the possible changes is the removal of some of the capital buffers, he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	Basel III requires banks to maintain a number of capital buffers, which some banks have considered duplicative. Topping said banks were hoping that BCBS would remove some of them.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;BCBS is looking at whether there is a need to re-calibrate capital and banks are hoping that there will be a good outcome,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	The asset management sector could see important regulatory developments this year, said David Wright, secretary-general of the International Organisation of Securities Commissions. Some banking regulators at the FSB are concerned about the risks posed by asset managers and whether the bigger players should be required to put in place specific measures, he said. Some feel that the new regulations on banks have shifted risks to asset managers and the shadow banking sector.<br />\n	<br />\n	Wright said the FSB-IOSCO technical work group is carrying out in-depth analysis on the market activities of asset managers and no conclusions have so far been made.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;The main &#39;activity&#39; issues are well known: looking primarily at liquidity and leverage issues. These are complex subjects that have to be very carefully thought through. Asset managers are not banks; it&#39;s a very different sector from banks. A consultation paper on the main issues concerning the asset management industry might be expected sometime in the middle of this year,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>New Areas, New Issues<br />\n	</strong><br />\n	Over the next year or two the focus is likely to shift from the prudential issues on which the BCBS has traditionally focused to areas such as technology risk and cyber crime, conduct risk, and financial crime, all areas where regulators other than the BCBS are involved in setting the standards, Topping said.<br />\n	<br />\n	At the 2016 World Economic Forum, held in Davos, Switzerland earlier this month, a panel session talked about combating cyber crime through public-private partnerships. Loretta Lynch, attorney-general of the United States pointed out the importance of collaboration between industries and governments in identifying, predicting and preventing cyber threats. She said the United States has begun implementing some of the recommendations by the World Economic Forum aimed at addressing cyber crime.<br />\n	<br />\n	The World Economic Forum in 2015 launched a cyber crime project, a multi-year engagement with the aim to find practical ways to combat cyber crime through public-private cooperation and a framework for establishing more globally applicable cyber crime legislation.<br />\n	<br />\n	Technology, according to Topping, is now regarded as discrete risk, rather than as part of operational risk. As technology and mobile banking change the pattern of intermediation and enable non-banks providers to offer deposit substitutes and transaction services, regulators will be focusing on the prudential regulation of such providers, he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	Pogson pointed to a new concept called extended enterprise which requires banks to be concerned about the data which reside at vendors and third-parties and the controls the latter put in place when services are being outsourced. For example, banks need to ensure that customers&#39; data is protected when they engage a vendor to manufacture the chip for credit cards.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;Today the focus of regulations has been on the banks themselves, but now it is making sure that the banks are protecting the data when it goes outside the bank to third-party vendors,&quot; he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Financial Crime</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	Recent terrorist events in France and Indonesia have led regulators to put a sharp focus on terrorist financing. Regulators are also concerned about broader financial crime issues including money laundering, sanctions and fraud. Topping said he expected to see more guidelines for banks on how to deal with sanctions and terrorist financing over the next few years.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:37:\"Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:6572:\"<p>Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	Eight years after the financial crisis, regulators will now focus on the implementation of prudential regulations, and this is likely to continue for at least another two years, officials said.</p>\n<p>	Mark Carney, Governor of the Bank of England, said in a recent speech that the series of international reforms which followed the crisis had reached a plateau. Regulatory reforms are far from complete, however, as regulators now begin to deal with the consequences of implementing the various initiatives, and make legislative changes in the domestic markets to facilitate rule implementation over the next few years, according to Keith Pogson, partner at EY in Hong Kong.</p>\n<p>	\"That\'s what most regulators\' agenda is going to be. It\'s not just catching up, but it\'s implementing locally what\'s going on globally, and making [the changes] happen. Basel III, total loss-absorbing capacity (“TLAC”), and recovery and resolution plans, OTC derivatives reforms, CCPs, FATCA, all of this stuff has been coming for a long time,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Policy Formulation Far from Complete<br /></strong><br />\n	Simon Topping, head of regulations for Asia Pacific at KPMG China, said that although regulators had completed most of the policy formulation and were moving toward implementation, some aspects of policy formulation were far from complete.</p>\n<p>	\"You have the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision [BCBS], the Financial Stability Board [FSB] and Mr. Carney saying they have finalised the policy formulation stage. That\'s largely true but there are important issues that are not resolved,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	Topping said the standardised approach to credit risk is an example of a piece of regulation which has a number of unresolved issues. He said the second consultation paper issued by the BCBS in December last year would present considerable challenges to banks, particularly to Asian banks.</p>\n<p>	\"Banks who will use the new standardised approach fear that it will result in higher risk-weighted assets and hence lower capital ratios. Moreover, there will also be an indirect effect on those banks using the internal ratings-based (“IRB”) approach, as the capital savings they can make will be constrained by the introduction of a floor calculated relative to the new standardised approach,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	Basel III is another area where implementation is expected to continue until 2018, according to Topping. Changes to Basel III are likely as the BCBS now attempts to evaluate it in a holistic manner and one of the possible changes is the removal of some of the capital buffers, he said.</p>\n<p>	Basel III requires banks to maintain a number of capital buffers, which some banks have considered duplicative. Topping said banks were hoping that BCBS would remove some of them.</p>\n<p>	\"BCBS is looking at whether there is a need to re-calibrate capital and banks are hoping that there will be a good outcome,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	The asset management sector could see important regulatory developments this year, said David Wright, secretary-general of the International Organisation of Securities Commissions. Some banking regulators at the FSB are concerned about the risks posed by asset managers and whether the bigger players should be required to put in place specific measures, he said. Some feel that the new regulations on banks have shifted risks to asset managers and the shadow banking sector.</p>\n<p>	Wright said the FSB-IOSCO technical work group is carrying out in-depth analysis on the market activities of asset managers and no conclusions have so far been made.</p>\n<p>	\"The main \'activity\' issues are well known: looking primarily at liquidity and leverage issues. These are complex subjects that have to be very carefully thought through. Asset managers are not banks; it\'s a very different sector from banks. A consultation paper on the main issues concerning the asset management industry might be expected sometime in the middle of this year,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	<strong>New Areas, New Issues<br /></strong><br />\n	Over the next year or two the focus is likely to shift from the prudential issues on which the BCBS has traditionally focused to areas such as technology risk and cyber crime, conduct risk, and financial crime, all areas where regulators other than the BCBS are involved in setting the standards, Topping said.</p>\n<p>	At the 2016 World Economic Forum, held in Davos, Switzerland earlier this month, a panel session talked about combating cyber crime through public-private partnerships. Loretta Lynch, attorney-general of the United States pointed out the importance of collaboration between industries and governments in identifying, predicting and preventing cyber threats. She said the United States has begun implementing some of the recommendations by the World Economic Forum aimed at addressing cyber crime.</p>\n<p>	The World Economic Forum in 2015 launched a cyber crime project, a multi-year engagement with the aim to find practical ways to combat cyber crime through public-private cooperation and a framework for establishing more globally applicable cyber crime legislation.</p>\n<p>	Technology, according to Topping, is now regarded as discrete risk, rather than as part of operational risk. As technology and mobile banking change the pattern of intermediation and enable non-banks providers to offer deposit substitutes and transaction services, regulators will be focusing on the prudential regulation of such providers, he said.</p>\n<p>	Pogson pointed to a new concept called extended enterprise which requires banks to be concerned about the data which reside at vendors and third-parties and the controls the latter put in place when services are being outsourced. For example, banks need to ensure that customers\' data is protected when they engage a vendor to manufacture the chip for credit cards.</p>\n<p>	\"Today the focus of regulations has been on the banks themselves, but now it is making sure that the banks are protecting the data when it goes outside the bank to third-party vendors,\" he said.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Financial Crime</strong></p>\n<p>	Recent terrorist events in France and Indonesia have led regulators to put a sharp focus on terrorist financing. Regulators are also concerned about broader financial crime issues including money laundering, sanctions and fraud. Topping said he expected to see more guidelines for banks on how to deal with sanctions and terrorist financing over the next few years.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:45:\"<p>Patricia Lee, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"661\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"576\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:68:\"Implementing Prudential Regulations and New Issues Key Focus in 2016\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:68:\"Implementing Prudential Regulations and New Issues Key Focus in 2016\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:68:\"Implementing Prudential Regulations and New Issues Key Focus in 2016\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1453939200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183993,1),('9209','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9213\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:80:\"Hong Kong Flags Changes to Market Risk Capital Framework after New BCBS Guidance\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9209\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1453939200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9209\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3915:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence<p>\n	Hong Kong&#39;s banking regulator has urged banks to begin studying the revised market risk capital framework that was released by the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision (&ldquo;BCBS&rdquo;) in early January, saying the new framework will have a significant impact on rules in the territory. The Hong Kong Monetary Authority (&ldquo;HKMA&rdquo;) said it intended to implement the revised market risk capital framework in accordance with the BCBS timetable and would be consulting the industry on its implementation proposals for Hong Kong in due course.<br />\n	<br />\n	The new market risk standards are scheduled to be implemented by national supervisors across the world by 1 January 2019, with banks required to start regulatory reporting based on the revised standardised approach or internal models approach from 31 December 2019.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;As the revised market risk capital framework in effect represents a significant overhaul of the current market risk capital framework, it is likely to have impacts on, among other things, the capital requirements, systems, data and resources of locally incorporated authorized institutions, particularly for those with material market risk exposures,&quot; said Karen Kemp, executive director of banking policy at the HKMA, in a circular to the industry. &quot;All relevant authorized institutions are therefore strongly recommended to familiarise themselves with the new market risk capital standards in advance of any HKMA consultations, consider the implications of implementation for their institutions, and start preparing, to the extent practicable, for the local implementation of the revised framework.&quot;<br />\n	<br />\n	The revised market risk capital framework builds on the BCBS&#39; reform of global regulatory standards in response to the global financial crisis, which were contained in the &quot;Basel 2.5&quot; market risk reforms issued in 2009. While these addressed the most pressing deficiencies at the time, the new set of standards addresses outstanding structural shortcomings in the market risk capital framework.<br />\n	<br />\n	The HKMA said the BCBS expects a number of aspects of its ongoing work may have an impact on the revised market risk capital framework. These include a proposal for incorporating criteria for simple, transparent and comparable securitisations into the Basel capital framework, the application of the market risk capital framework to credit valuation adjustments, and the ongoing review of capital treatment for credit risk and the treatment of interest rate risk in the banking book.<br />\n	<br />\n	The regulator said the key features of the new risk capital framework included a revised boundary between the regulatory trading book and banking book, which has been revised to reduce incentives for arbitrage of regulatory capital requirements between the two books. The new framework contains stricter limits and applies capital disincentives to the transfer of risk positions between the banking book and trading book.<br />\n	<br />\n	The new regime also includes a revised internal models approach, replacing the value-at-risk-based approach in the current framework with one that is based on expected shortfall designed to better capture &quot;tail risks&quot; and market illiquidity risks, the HKMA said. <br />\n	<br />\n	The new framework also includes a revised standardised approach, which has been made sufficiently risk-sensitive to serve as a credible fallback as well as a floor to the revised internal models approach, the HKMA said. It added that the revised standardised approach involves a more extensive use of risk sensitivities as inputs to market risk calculations and has three main components: a sensitivities-based method for capturing risk sensitivities, a standardised default risk charge and a residual risk add-on.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:36:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3806:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	Hong Kong\'s banking regulator has urged banks to begin studying the revised market risk capital framework that was released by the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision (“BCBS”) in early January, saying the new framework will have a significant impact on rules in the territory. The Hong Kong Monetary Authority (“HKMA”) said it intended to implement the revised market risk capital framework in accordance with the BCBS timetable and would be consulting the industry on its implementation proposals for Hong Kong in due course.</p>\n<p>	The new market risk standards are scheduled to be implemented by national supervisors across the world by 1 January 2019, with banks required to start regulatory reporting based on the revised standardised approach or internal models approach from 31 December 2019.</p>\n<p>	\"As the revised market risk capital framework in effect represents a significant overhaul of the current market risk capital framework, it is likely to have impacts on, among other things, the capital requirements, systems, data and resources of locally incorporated authorized institutions, particularly for those with material market risk exposures,\" said Karen Kemp, executive director of banking policy at the HKMA, in a circular to the industry. \"All relevant authorized institutions are therefore strongly recommended to familiarise themselves with the new market risk capital standards in advance of any HKMA consultations, consider the implications of implementation for their institutions, and start preparing, to the extent practicable, for the local implementation of the revised framework.\"</p>\n<p>	The revised market risk capital framework builds on the BCBS\' reform of global regulatory standards in response to the global financial crisis, which were contained in the \"Basel 2.5\" market risk reforms issued in 2009. While these addressed the most pressing deficiencies at the time, the new set of standards addresses outstanding structural shortcomings in the market risk capital framework.</p>\n<p>	The HKMA said the BCBS expects a number of aspects of its ongoing work may have an impact on the revised market risk capital framework. These include a proposal for incorporating criteria for simple, transparent and comparable securitisations into the Basel capital framework, the application of the market risk capital framework to credit valuation adjustments, and the ongoing review of capital treatment for credit risk and the treatment of interest rate risk in the banking book.</p>\n<p>	The regulator said the key features of the new risk capital framework included a revised boundary between the regulatory trading book and banking book, which has been revised to reduce incentives for arbitrage of regulatory capital requirements between the two books. The new framework contains stricter limits and applies capital disincentives to the transfer of risk positions between the banking book and trading book.</p>\n<p>	The new regime also includes a revised internal models approach, replacing the value-at-risk-based approach in the current framework with one that is based on expected shortfall designed to better capture \"tail risks\" and market illiquidity risks, the HKMA said. </p>\n<p>	The new framework also includes a revised standardised approach, which has been made sufficiently risk-sensitive to serve as a credible fallback as well as a floor to the revised internal models approach, the HKMA said. It added that the revised standardised approach involves a more extensive use of risk sensitivities as inputs to market risk calculations and has three main components: a sensitivities-based method for capturing risk sensitivities, a standardised default risk charge and a residual risk add-on.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:44:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"662\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"114\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:80:\"Hong Kong Flags Changes to Market Risk Capital Framework after New BCBS Guidance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:80:\"Hong Kong Flags Changes to Market Risk Capital Framework after New BCBS Guidance\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:80:\"Hong Kong Flags Changes to Market Risk Capital Framework after New BCBS Guidance\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1453939200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458111751,1),('9210','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9214\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:80:\"Hong Kong Flags Changes to Market Risk Capital Framework after New BCBS Guidance\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9210\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1453939200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9209\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3915:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence<p>\n	Hong Kong&#39;s banking regulator has urged banks to begin studying the revised market risk capital framework that was released by the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision (&ldquo;BCBS&rdquo;) in early January, saying the new framework will have a significant impact on rules in the territory. The Hong Kong Monetary Authority (&ldquo;HKMA&rdquo;) said it intended to implement the revised market risk capital framework in accordance with the BCBS timetable and would be consulting the industry on its implementation proposals for Hong Kong in due course.<br />\n	<br />\n	The new market risk standards are scheduled to be implemented by national supervisors across the world by 1 January 2019, with banks required to start regulatory reporting based on the revised standardised approach or internal models approach from 31 December 2019.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;As the revised market risk capital framework in effect represents a significant overhaul of the current market risk capital framework, it is likely to have impacts on, among other things, the capital requirements, systems, data and resources of locally incorporated authorized institutions, particularly for those with material market risk exposures,&quot; said Karen Kemp, executive director of banking policy at the HKMA, in a circular to the industry. &quot;All relevant authorized institutions are therefore strongly recommended to familiarise themselves with the new market risk capital standards in advance of any HKMA consultations, consider the implications of implementation for their institutions, and start preparing, to the extent practicable, for the local implementation of the revised framework.&quot;<br />\n	<br />\n	The revised market risk capital framework builds on the BCBS&#39; reform of global regulatory standards in response to the global financial crisis, which were contained in the &quot;Basel 2.5&quot; market risk reforms issued in 2009. While these addressed the most pressing deficiencies at the time, the new set of standards addresses outstanding structural shortcomings in the market risk capital framework.<br />\n	<br />\n	The HKMA said the BCBS expects a number of aspects of its ongoing work may have an impact on the revised market risk capital framework. These include a proposal for incorporating criteria for simple, transparent and comparable securitisations into the Basel capital framework, the application of the market risk capital framework to credit valuation adjustments, and the ongoing review of capital treatment for credit risk and the treatment of interest rate risk in the banking book.<br />\n	<br />\n	The regulator said the key features of the new risk capital framework included a revised boundary between the regulatory trading book and banking book, which has been revised to reduce incentives for arbitrage of regulatory capital requirements between the two books. The new framework contains stricter limits and applies capital disincentives to the transfer of risk positions between the banking book and trading book.<br />\n	<br />\n	The new regime also includes a revised internal models approach, replacing the value-at-risk-based approach in the current framework with one that is based on expected shortfall designed to better capture &quot;tail risks&quot; and market illiquidity risks, the HKMA said. <br />\n	<br />\n	The new framework also includes a revised standardised approach, which has been made sufficiently risk-sensitive to serve as a credible fallback as well as a floor to the revised internal models approach, the HKMA said. It added that the revised standardised approach involves a more extensive use of risk sensitivities as inputs to market risk calculations and has three main components: a sensitivities-based method for capturing risk sensitivities, a standardised default risk charge and a residual risk add-on.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:36:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3806:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	Hong Kong\'s banking regulator has urged banks to begin studying the revised market risk capital framework that was released by the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision (“BCBS”) in early January, saying the new framework will have a significant impact on rules in the territory. The Hong Kong Monetary Authority (“HKMA”) said it intended to implement the revised market risk capital framework in accordance with the BCBS timetable and would be consulting the industry on its implementation proposals for Hong Kong in due course.</p>\n<p>	The new market risk standards are scheduled to be implemented by national supervisors across the world by 1 January 2019, with banks required to start regulatory reporting based on the revised standardised approach or internal models approach from 31 December 2019.</p>\n<p>	\"As the revised market risk capital framework in effect represents a significant overhaul of the current market risk capital framework, it is likely to have impacts on, among other things, the capital requirements, systems, data and resources of locally incorporated authorized institutions, particularly for those with material market risk exposures,\" said Karen Kemp, executive director of banking policy at the HKMA, in a circular to the industry. \"All relevant authorized institutions are therefore strongly recommended to familiarise themselves with the new market risk capital standards in advance of any HKMA consultations, consider the implications of implementation for their institutions, and start preparing, to the extent practicable, for the local implementation of the revised framework.\"</p>\n<p>	The revised market risk capital framework builds on the BCBS\' reform of global regulatory standards in response to the global financial crisis, which were contained in the \"Basel 2.5\" market risk reforms issued in 2009. While these addressed the most pressing deficiencies at the time, the new set of standards addresses outstanding structural shortcomings in the market risk capital framework.</p>\n<p>	The HKMA said the BCBS expects a number of aspects of its ongoing work may have an impact on the revised market risk capital framework. These include a proposal for incorporating criteria for simple, transparent and comparable securitisations into the Basel capital framework, the application of the market risk capital framework to credit valuation adjustments, and the ongoing review of capital treatment for credit risk and the treatment of interest rate risk in the banking book.</p>\n<p>	The regulator said the key features of the new risk capital framework included a revised boundary between the regulatory trading book and banking book, which has been revised to reduce incentives for arbitrage of regulatory capital requirements between the two books. The new framework contains stricter limits and applies capital disincentives to the transfer of risk positions between the banking book and trading book.</p>\n<p>	The new regime also includes a revised internal models approach, replacing the value-at-risk-based approach in the current framework with one that is based on expected shortfall designed to better capture \"tail risks\" and market illiquidity risks, the HKMA said. </p>\n<p>	The new framework also includes a revised standardised approach, which has been made sufficiently risk-sensitive to serve as a credible fallback as well as a floor to the revised internal models approach, the HKMA said. It added that the revised standardised approach involves a more extensive use of risk sensitivities as inputs to market risk calculations and has three main components: a sensitivities-based method for capturing risk sensitivities, a standardised default risk charge and a residual risk add-on.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:44:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"661\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"576\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:80:\"Hong Kong Flags Changes to Market Risk Capital Framework after New BCBS Guidance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:80:\"Hong Kong Flags Changes to Market Risk Capital Framework after New BCBS Guidance\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"