\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183993,1),('9211','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9215\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:66:\"Hong Kong will Not Impose Stamp Duty on Derivatives, Says Official\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9211\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1453939200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9211\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2589:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence<p>\n	Hong Kong&#39;s government has ruled out imposing stamp duty on derivatives transactions, saying it would render the territory uncompetitive against other major markets. The territory&#39;s Secretary for Financial Services and the Treasury, KC Chan, told the Legislative Council on Wednesday, 20 January, that derivatives transactions would only be charged stamp duty if they were settled by physical delivery, involving a share transfer. Chan was responding to a question by the Hon. Sin Chung-kai on whether the authorities would consider imposing stamp duty evenly across all asset classes.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;It is a common practice in international financial markets that derivative products are not subject to stamp duty. Major international derivative markets ... do not levy stamp duty on trading of derivative products,&quot; Chan said. &quot;As an international financial centre, Hong Kong must provide a competitive trading environment, including competitive transaction costs.&quot;<br />\n	<br />\n	Chan said the nature and trading purpose were different between stocks and derivatives. Unlike stock investors, derivative product investors do not have rights such as dividend payment and voting rights, he said.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;Generally speaking, if the holder of a derivative has no right to the underlying stock, the derivative will not be a &#39;Hong Kong stock&#39; as defined under the Stamp Duty Ordinance (&ldquo;SDO&rdquo;), and its transfer will not be subject to stamp duty,&quot; Chan said. He added that the trading of derivatives in the markets of the Hong Kong Exchanges and Clearing Limited (&ldquo;HKEx&rdquo;) was cash-settled, and thus not subject to stamp duty.<br />\n	<br />\n	Under the SDO, the buyer and the seller each has to pay stamp duty in respect of instruments for transfer of Hong Kong stock. &quot;Hong Kong stock&quot; is defined in the SDO to mean stock where the transfer is required to be registered in Hong Kong, including any right, option or interest in respect of such stock. If derivative products are settled by physical delivery, share transfers will be involved, and will therefore be chargeable to stamp duties.<br />\n	<br />\n	The stamp duty exemption has made some derivatives, such as warrants and callable bull/bear contracts, a popular investment product in Hong Kong. According to figures from HKEx, the turnover of derivative warrants and callable bull/bear contracts in 2015 accounted for 17 percent and 7 percent of the securities market&#39;s total turnover.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:36:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2482:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	Hong Kong\'s government has ruled out imposing stamp duty on derivatives transactions, saying it would render the territory uncompetitive against other major markets. The territory\'s Secretary for Financial Services and the Treasury, KC Chan, told the Legislative Council on Wednesday, 20 January, that derivatives transactions would only be charged stamp duty if they were settled by physical delivery, involving a share transfer. Chan was responding to a question by the Hon. Sin Chung-kai on whether the authorities would consider imposing stamp duty evenly across all asset classes.</p>\n<p>	\"It is a common practice in international financial markets that derivative products are not subject to stamp duty. Major international derivative markets ... do not levy stamp duty on trading of derivative products,\" Chan said. \"As an international financial centre, Hong Kong must provide a competitive trading environment, including competitive transaction costs.\"</p>\n<p>	Chan said the nature and trading purpose were different between stocks and derivatives. Unlike stock investors, derivative product investors do not have rights such as dividend payment and voting rights, he said.</p>\n<p>	\"Generally speaking, if the holder of a derivative has no right to the underlying stock, the derivative will not be a \'Hong Kong stock\' as defined under the Stamp Duty Ordinance (“SDO”), and its transfer will not be subject to stamp duty,\" Chan said. He added that the trading of derivatives in the markets of the Hong Kong Exchanges and Clearing Limited (“HKEx”) was cash-settled, and thus not subject to stamp duty.</p>\n<p>	Under the SDO, the buyer and the seller each has to pay stamp duty in respect of instruments for transfer of Hong Kong stock. \"Hong Kong stock\" is defined in the SDO to mean stock where the transfer is required to be registered in Hong Kong, including any right, option or interest in respect of such stock. If derivative products are settled by physical delivery, share transfers will be involved, and will therefore be chargeable to stamp duties.</p>\n<p>	The stamp duty exemption has made some derivatives, such as warrants and callable bull/bear contracts, a popular investment product in Hong Kong. According to figures from HKEx, the turnover of derivative warrants and callable bull/bear contracts in 2015 accounted for 17 percent and 7 percent of the securities market\'s total turnover.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:44:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"662\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"114\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:66:\"Hong Kong will Not Impose Stamp Duty on Derivatives, Says Official\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:66:\"Hong Kong will Not Impose Stamp Duty on Derivatives, Says Official\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:66:\"Hong Kong will Not Impose Stamp Duty on Derivatives, Says Official\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_repli