l turnover.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:36:\"Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2482:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	Hong Kong\'s government has ruled out imposing stamp duty on derivatives transactions, saying it would render the territory uncompetitive against other major markets. The territory\'s Secretary for Financial Services and the Treasury, KC Chan, told the Legislative Council on Wednesday, 20 January, that derivatives transactions would only be charged stamp duty if they were settled by physical delivery, involving a share transfer. Chan was responding to a question by the Hon. Sin Chung-kai on whether the authorities would consider imposing stamp duty evenly across all asset classes.</p>\n<p>	\"It is a common practice in international financial markets that derivative products are not subject to stamp duty. Major international derivative markets ... do not levy stamp duty on trading of derivative products,\" Chan said. \"As an international financial centre, Hong Kong must provide a competitive trading environment, including competitive transaction costs.\"</p>\n<p>	Chan said the nature and trading purpose were different between stocks and derivatives. Unlike stock investors, derivative product investors do not have rights such as dividend payment and voting rights, he said.</p>\n<p>	\"Generally speaking, if the holder of a derivative has no right to the underlying stock, the derivative will not be a \'Hong Kong stock\' as defined under the Stamp Duty Ordinance (“SDO”), and its transfer will not be subject to stamp duty,\" Chan said. He added that the trading of derivatives in the markets of the Hong Kong Exchanges and Clearing Limited (“HKEx”) was cash-settled, and thus not subject to stamp duty.</p>\n<p>	Under the SDO, the buyer and the seller each has to pay stamp duty in respect of instruments for transfer of Hong Kong stock. \"Hong Kong stock\" is defined in the SDO to mean stock where the transfer is required to be registered in Hong Kong, including any right, option or interest in respect of such stock. If derivative products are settled by physical delivery, share transfers will be involved, and will therefore be chargeable to stamp duties.</p>\n<p>	The stamp duty exemption has made some derivatives, such as warrants and callable bull/bear contracts, a popular investment product in Hong Kong. According to figures from HKEx, the turnover of derivative warrants and callable bull/bear contracts in 2015 accounted for 17 percent and 7 percent of the securities market\'s total turnover.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:44:\"<p>Trond Vagen, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"661\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"576\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:66:\"Hong Kong will Not Impose Stamp Duty on Derivatives, Says Official\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:66:\"Hong Kong will Not Impose Stamp Duty on Derivatives, Says Official\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:66:\"Hong Kong will Not Impose Stamp Duty on Derivatives, Says Official\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1453939200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183993,1),('9213','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9217\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:88:\"Nation-States will Crack Down Hard on Bitcoin because of Criminal Element, says Bernanke\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9213\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1453939200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9213\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454929177\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3054:\"Ajay Shamdasani, Regulatory Intelligence<p>\n	National governments will crack down hard on Bitcoin and other crypto-currencies because of concerns such technologies can more easily facilitate terrorist financing and other criminal activities, said Ben Bernanke, former US Federal Reserve chairman. Speaking at the annual Asian Financial Forum in Hong Kong on Tuesday, 19 January, he also said emerging markets such as China should be cautious as it liberalised its financial systems.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;There have been enormous advances in financial technology and [the blockchain] is an extremely impressive programme. Bitcoin is an alternative currency &hellip; but it would not be successful as currency because in the world we live in today, there is a lot of concern amongst governments of terrorist financing, drug financing and other kinds of illicit activities that can be easily financed through a Bitcoin type of technology. I think [nation-states] are going to crack down hard; I do not think Bitcoin will become a global currency,&quot; Bernanke told a global audience of regulators, policymakers and industry participants during a lunch-time interview on stage.<br />\n	<br />\n	Bernanke&#39;s interviewer, Andrew Sheng, a distinguished fellow at the University of Hong Kong&#39;s (&ldquo;HKU&rdquo;) Asia Global Institute, said the rise of blockchain and Bitcoin could disintermediate central banks. &quot;The threat is to central banking, not just conventional banking,&quot; he said. However, Bernanke said he was not sold on Bitcoin and the blockchain technology creating a global standard for transactions.<br />\n	<br />\n	The former Fed chair also said mainland China should be cautious in moving ahead with market reforms. <br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;You need the right institutional and legal framework before you liberalise. There is a process by which you liberalise financial markets and liberalise [your] currency. Ultimately, you will get to an open and convertible currency: in the process of doing that, you have got to make sure you have got good banking regulations and well-functioning asset markets and bond markets and that you have mechanisms for trading currencies. China is making good progress on those things,&quot; Bernanke said.<br />\n	<br />\n	He said that Zhou Xiaochuan, the governor of the People&#39;s Bank of China, was gradually ushering in the requisite reforms for a full-scale opening up of the mainland&#39;s financial markets and its ultimate goal of making the yuan freely tradable and convertible.<br />\n	<br />\n	&quot;You do not want to go too slow and put off those reforms forever. On other hand, you must be sure you are ready to take large steps. You need the right institutional, legal and accounting infrastructure before you go into that. China has been cautious,&quot; Bernanke said, reflecting on the 2008 global financial crisis in the West. &quot;If the banking system is not secure, if there is a shock from, say, sub-prime loans, that could bring down the entire system.&quot;<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:40:\"Ajay Shamdasani, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2937:\"<p>Ajay Shamdasani, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	National governments will crack down hard on Bitcoin and other crypto-currencies because of concerns such technologies can more easily facilitate terrorist financing and other criminal activities, said Ben Bernanke, former US Federal Reserve chairman. Speaking at the annual Asian Financial Forum in Hong Kong on Tuesday, 19 January, he also said emerging markets such as China should be cautious as it liberalised its financial systems.</p>\n<p>	\"There have been enormous advances in financial technology and [the blockchain] is an extremely impressive programme. Bitcoin is an alternative currency … but it would not be successful as currency because in the world we live in today, there is a lot of concern amongst governments of terrorist financing, drug financing and other kinds of illicit activities that can be easily financed through a Bitcoin type of technology. I think [nation-states] are going to crack down hard; I do not think Bitcoin will become a global currency,\" Bernanke told a global audience of regulators, policymakers and industry participants during a lunch-time interview on stage.</p>\n<p>	Bernanke\'s interviewer, Andrew Sheng, a distinguished fellow at the University of Hong Kong\'s (“HKU”) Asia Global Institute, said the rise of blockchain and Bitcoin could disintermediate central banks. \"The threat is to central banking, not just conventional banking,\" he said. However, Bernanke said he was not sold on Bitcoin and the blockchain technology creating a global standard for transactions.</p>\n<p>	The former Fed chair also said mainland China should be cautious in moving ahead with market reforms. </p>\n<p>	\"You need the right institutional and legal framework before you liberalise. There is a process by which you liberalise financial markets and liberalise [your] currency. Ultimately, you will get to an open and convertible currency: in the process of doing that, you have got to make sure you have got good banking regulations and well-functioning asset markets and bond markets and that you have mechanisms for trading currencies. China is making good progress on those things,\" Bernanke said.</p>\n<p>	He said that Zhou Xiaochuan, the governor of the People\'s Bank of China, was gradually ushering in the requisite reforms for a full-scale opening up of the mainland\'s financial markets and its ultimate goal of making the yuan freely tradable and convertible.</p>\n<p>	\"You do not want to go too slow and put off those reforms forever. On other hand, you must be sure you are ready to take large steps. You need the right institutional, legal and accounting infrastructure before you go into that. China has been cautious,\" Bernanke said, reflecting on the 2008 global financial crisis in the West. \"If the banking system is not secure, if there is a shock from, say, sub-prime loans, that could bring down the entire system.\"<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:48:\"<p>Ajay Shamdasani, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"662\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"114\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:88:\"Nation-States will Crack Down Hard on Bitcoin because of Criminal Element, says Bernanke\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:88:\"Nation-States will Crack Down Hard on Bitcoin because of Criminal Element, says Bernanke\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:88:\"Nation-States will Crack Down Hard on Bitcoin because of Criminal Element, says Bernanke\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s