\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458115031,1),('9306','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9310\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:48:\"Antwerp Diamond Bank NV v Brink’s, Inc (No. 2)\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9306\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9305\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3640:\"訟費 — 附帶條款的和解提議或付款 — 原告人是否有權就原審和上訴而獲判給按彌償基準計算的訟費<p>\n	Antwerp Diamond Bank NV v Brink&rsquo;s, Inc (No. 2)</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e000001519fa6e426adfbe36e&amp;docguid=I0E908818A4B84E67BAF58785F46FAC98&amp;hitguid=I0E908818A4B84E67BAF58785F46FAC98&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 628</a><br />\n	上訴法庭<br />\n	上訴法庭民事上訴案2012年第282號<br />\n	上訴法庭副庭長林文瀚及倫明高，上訴法庭法官鮑晏明<br />\n	2015年8月14日</p>\n<p>\n	本案原告人(下稱P)向第三被告人(下稱D3)提出申索，理由為D3交付貨物時出錯，構成挪佔貨物。2011年7月8日，P提出附帶條款和解提議，表示願意接受850,000美元(未計利息)以和解上述申索(下稱「涉案提議」)。法庭裁定D3勝訴。然而，上訴法庭裁定P上訴得直，並下令D3向P支付﹕(一)損害賠償852,399美元連帶利息，利率為商業息率(最優惠利率加一厘)，自錯誤交付貨物之日起計﹔及(二)原審和上訴的訟費。P現申請更改上述命令，根據《高等法院規則》 (第4章，附屬法例A)(下稱「《規則》」)第22號命令第24(2)及(3)條規則，要求法庭判給P﹕(一)P於2011年8月6日(即D3本可無需法庭許可而接受涉案提議的最後日期)或之後招致的按彌償基準計算的原審和上訴訟費﹔及(二)損害賠償額的利息，利率為最優惠利率加六厘，以及於2011年8月6日或之後招致的訟費的利息，利率為5.5%(最優惠利率加六厘的一半)。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &mdash; 批准延展時限，但駁回上訴﹕</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		根據《規則》第22號命令第24(2)及(3)條規則而下令D3支付P於2011年8月6日或之後招致的按彌償基準計算的原審訟費，並非不公正。P大可真誠地認為其申索勝算極高。雖然P所提出的和解金額只略為低於申索額(兩者只相差0.27%)，但這本身不足以令到涉案提議「純屬訴訟策略」或「有欠真誠」，從而令作出P所尋求的命令變得不公正。即使附帶條款和解提議所提出的和解金額與申索額所差無幾，收到該提議的與訟方也應認真考慮該提議、提出切實的附帶條款和解反提議，以及促使雙方認真和切實地考慮進行敵對式訴訟以外的各種和解方案。</li>\n	<li>\n		至於上訴的訟費，即使有可能在上訴期間提出附帶條款和解提議，本案與訟雙方都沒有重新提出附帶條款和解提議，因此並不產生根據《規則》第22號命令第24(3)條規則而下令支付按彌償基準計算的訟費或額外訟費利息的問題。故此，涉案提議只會被視為可能影響本庭如何就上訴訟費行使酌情權的相關因素。D3不接納涉案提議，不能說是不合理。D3承受進行原審所帶來的敗訴風險，且獲判勝訴，但最終經P提出上訴而被判敗訴。因此，適當的做法是不干預關乎上訴訟費的暫准令，並在有需要時按對訟當事人基準評定訟費。</li>\n	<li>\n		雖然P是一家銀行，但這本身不能令下述命令變得不公正，即根據《規則》第22號命令第24(4)條規則下令D3支付P的訟費，而所有訟費的利息息率為最優惠利率加四厘的一半(這有助避免就每個項目所招致的訟費而計算利息)，以及下令D3就P獲判給的損害賠償支付按上述經提高息率計算的利息。</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:133:\"訟費 — 附帶條款的和解提議或付款 — 原告人是否有權就原審和上訴而獲判給按彌償基準計算的訟費\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3635:\"<p>訟費 — 附帶條款的和解提議或付款 — 原告人是否有權就原審和上訴而獲判給按彌償基準計算的訟費\n</p><p>\n	Antwerp Diamond Bank NV v Brink’s, Inc (No. 2)</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e000001519fa6e426adfbe36e&amp;docguid=I0E908818A4B84E67BAF58785F46FAC98&amp;hitguid=I0E908818A4B84E67BAF58785F46FAC98&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 628</a><br />\n	上訴法庭<br />\n	上訴法庭民事上訴案2012年第282號<br />\n	上訴法庭副庭長林文瀚及倫明高，上訴法庭法官鮑晏明<br />\n	2015年8月14日</p>\n<p>\n	本案原告人(下稱P)向第三被告人(下稱D3)提出申索，理由為D3交付貨物時出錯，構成挪佔貨物。2011年7月8日，P提出附帶條款和解提議，表示願意接受850,000美元(未計利息)以和解上述申索(下稱「涉案提議」)。法庭裁定D3勝訴。然而，上訴法庭裁定P上訴得直，並下令D3向P支付﹕(一)損害賠償852,399美元連帶利息，利率為商業息率(最優惠利率加一厘)，自錯誤交付貨物之日起計﹔及(二)原審和上訴的訟費。P現申請更改上述命令，根據《高等法院規則》 (第4章，附屬法例A)(下稱「《規則》」)第22號命令第24(2)及(3)條規則，要求法庭判給P﹕(一)P於2011年8月6日(即D3本可無需法庭許可而接受涉案提議的最後日期)或之後招致的按彌償基準計算的原審和上訴訟費﹔及(二)損害賠償額的利息，利率為最優惠利率加六厘，以及於2011年8月6日或之後招致的訟費的利息，利率為5.5%(最優惠利率加六厘的一半)。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> — 批准延展時限，但駁回上訴﹕</p>\n<ul><li>\n		根據《規則》第22號命令第24(2)及(3)條規則而下令D3支付P於2011年8月6日或之後招致的按彌償基準計算的原審訟費，並非不公正。P大可真誠地認為其申索勝算極高。雖然P所提出的和解金額只略為低於申索額(兩者只相差0.27%)，但這本身不足以令到涉案提議「純屬訴訟策略」或「有欠真誠」，從而令作出P所尋求的命令變得不公正。即使附帶條款和解提議所提出的和解金額與申索額所差無幾，收到該提議的與訟方也應認真考慮該提議、提出切實的附帶條款和解反提議，以及促使雙方認真和切實地考慮進行敵對式訴訟以外的各種和解方案。</li>\n<li>\n		至於上訴的訟費，即使有可能在上訴期間提出附帶條款和解提議，本案與訟雙方都沒有重新提出附帶條款和解提議，因此並不產生根據《規則》第22號命令第24(3)條規則而下令支付按彌償基準計算的訟費或額外訟費利息的問題。故此，涉案提議只會被視為可能影響本庭如何就上訴訟費行使酌情權的相關因素。D3不接納涉案提議，不能說是不合理。D3承受進行原審所帶來的敗訴風險，且獲判勝訴，但最終經P提出上訴而被判敗訴。因此，適當的做法是不干預關乎上訴訟費的暫准令，並在有需要時按對訟當事人基準評定訟費。</li>\n<li>\n		雖然P是一家銀行，但這本身不能令下述命令變得不公正，即根據《規則》第22號命令第24(4)條規則下令D3支付P的訟費，而所有訟費的利息息率為最優惠利率加四厘的一半(這有助避免就每個項目所招致的訟費而計算利息)，以及下令D3就P獲判給的損害賠償支付按上述經提高息率計算的利息。</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:141:\"<p>訟費 — 附帶條款的和解提議或付款 — 原告人是否有權就原審和上訴而獲判給按彌償基準計算的訟費</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"上訴法庭\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"上訴法庭\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:48:\"Antwerp Diamond Bank NV v Brink’s, Inc (No. 2)\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:48:\"Antwerp Diamond Bank NV v Brink’s, Inc (No. 2)\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"565\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"638\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:231:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad69f8e000001519fa6e426adfbe36e&docguid=I0E908818A4B84E67BAF58785F46FAC98&hitguid=I0E908818A4B84E67BAF58785F46FAC98&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=4\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 4 HKLRD 628\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"2015年8月14日\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"2015年8月14日\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"民事訴訟程序\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"民事訴訟程序\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:48:\"Antwerp Diamond Bank NV v Brink’s, Inc (No. 2)\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183919,1),('9307','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9311\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:39:\"Fong Meng Sung John v Luk Man Lok Rocky\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9307\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456675528\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9307\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3335:\"<p><em>Discontinuance of proceedings – notice of discontinuance by plaintiff against those defendants invalid – leave to discontinue required</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>P commenced proceedings in 2009 by way of originating summons under O.88 r. 1 of the Rules of the High Court (Cap. 4A, Sub. Leg.) (the “RHC”), but did not file any affidavit evidence pursuant to O. 28 r. 1A(4). Only D1 filed an acknowledgment of service; and in May 2011, by consent between P and D1 (with D2–3 being absent), the proceedings were ordered to be continued as if the same had been begun by writ and directions were given for the filing of pleadings. D1 filed his defence and counterclaim in July 2011. Default judgment was initially obtained against D2–3 in August 2011, but was set aside in July 2013 on the ground that service on D2–3 was irregular and that they had a meritorious defence. P then served a notice of discontinuance (the “Notice”) on D2–3. Notwithstanding, D2–3 filed a defence and counterclaim in August 2013. D2–3, who wished to have their counterclaim tried in these proceedings, contended that the Notice was invalid as P could not discontinue the proceedings against them without leave. The Master held that the Notice was effective and expunged D2–3’s defence and counterclaim. D2–3 appealed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, allowing the appeal, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The statutory code of discontinuance was enacted to fetter the otherwise unqualified option of a plaintiff in a common law action to discontinue the action at any time and leave it to the court to decide whether a plaintiff could still discontinue after his action had reached a certain stage, and if so, whether he should be allowed to do so only on terms.</li>\r\n	<li>Order 21 rr. 2(1) and (3) of the RHC did not apply to originating summons proceedings that were ordered to continue as if begun by writ. The right to discontinue without leave could be exercised only within a very narrow window from commencement of proceedings. In relation to such proceedings, O. 21 rr. 2(3A), (3B) and 3 drew the line at the service of affidavit evidence by the defendant. It would be inconsistent with the legislative intention underlying the leave requirement if a plaintiff, not having discontinued the proceedings under O. 21 r. 2(3A) within 14 days after being served with the defendant’s affidavit evidence, were given another option to discontinue without leave through the application of O. 21 r. 2(1) and (3) to proceedings directed to continue as if begun by writ under O. 28 r. 8. It did not matter that neither party served affidavit evidence pursuant to O. 28 as happened here.</li>\r\n	<li>It was doubtful whether the time limit under O. 21 r.2(1) and (3) could be “reset” by the timetable laid down by the Court for D2–3 to serve their defences after setting aside the default judgment. This was particularly so when the default judgment was set aside also on merits. It would be inconsistent with the principle underlying the requirement for leave to discontinue if P could, after opposing D2–3’s application to set aside the default judgment, discontinue without leave under O. 21 r. 2(1) or (3). Order 21 r. 2(1) should be confined to cases where the defence was served within the time laid down by O. 18 r. 2.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:147:\"<p>Discontinuance of proceedings – notice of discontinuance by plaintiff against those defendants invalid – leave to discontinue required</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3316:\"<p><em>Discontinuance of proceedings – notice of discontinuance by plaintiff against those defendants invalid – leave to discontinue required</em></p>\n<p>P commenced proceedings in 2009 by way of originating summons under O.88 r. 1 of the Rules of the High Court (Cap. 4A, Sub. Leg.) (the “RHC”), but did not file any affidavit evidence pursuant to O. 28 r. 1A(4). Only D1 filed an acknowledgment of service; and in May 2011, by consent between P and D1 (with D2–3 being absent), the proceedings were ordered to be continued as if the same had been begun by writ and directions were given for the filing of pleadings. D1 filed his defence and counterclaim in July 2011. Default judgment was initially obtained against D2–3 in August 2011, but was set aside in July 2013 on the ground that service on D2–3 was irregular and that they had a meritorious defence. P then served a notice of discontinuance (the “Notice”) on D2–3. Notwithstanding, D2–3 filed a defence and counterclaim in August 2013. D2–3, who wished to have their counterclaim tried in these proceedings, contended that the Notice was invalid as P could not discontinue the proceedings against them without leave. The Master held that the Notice was effective and expunged D2–3’s defence and counterclaim. D2–3 appealed.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, allowing the appeal, that:</p>\n<ul><li>The statutory code of discontinuance was enacted to fetter the otherwise unqualified option of a plaintiff in a common law action to discontinue the action at any time and leave it to the court to decide whether a plaintiff could still discontinue after his action had reached a certain stage, and if so, whether he should be allowed to do so only on terms.</li>\n<li>Order 21 rr. 2(1) and (3) of the RHC did not apply to originating summons proceedings that were ordered to continue as if begun by writ. The right to discontinue without leave could be exercised only within a very narrow window from commencement of proceedings. In relation to such proceedings, O. 21 rr. 2(3A), (3B) and 3 drew the line at the service of affidavit evidence by the defendant. It would be inconsistent with the legislative intention underlying the leave requirement if a plaintiff, not having discontinued the proceedings under O. 21 r. 2(3A) within 14 days after being served with the defendant’s affidavit evidence, were given another option to discontinue without leave through the application of O. 21 r. 2(1) and (3) to proceedings directed to continue as if begun by writ under O. 28 r. 8. It did not matter that neither party served affidavit evidence pursuant to O. 28 as happened here.</li>\n<li>It was doubtful whether the time limit under O. 21 r.2(1) and (3) could be “reset” by the timetable laid down by the Court for D2–3 to serve their defences after setting aside the default judgment. This was particularly so when the default judgment was set aside also on merits. It would be inconsistent with the principle underlying the requirement for leave to discontinue if P could, after opposing D2–3’s application to set aside the default judgment, discontinue without leave under O. 21 r. 2(1) or (3). Order 21 r. 2(1) should be confined to cases where the defence was served within the time laid down by O. 18 r. 2.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:146:\"<p>Discontinuance of proceedings – notice of discontinuance by plaintiff against those defendants invalid – leave to discontinue required</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:39:\"Fong Meng Sung John v Luk Man Lok Rocky\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:39:\"Fong Meng Sung John v Luk Man Lok Rocky\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:231:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744cc64000001519fac058cd1ffe493&docguid=IE88DB906395548BB9201744F2936D69F&hitguid=IE88DB906395548BB9201744F2936D69F&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=7\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1852\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"7 September 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"7 September 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:39:\"Fong Meng Sung John v Luk Man Lok Rocky\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458115031,1),('9308','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9312\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:39:\"Fong Meng Sung John v Luk Man Lok Rocky\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9308\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9307\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3713:\"中止訴訟 — 原告人中止針對被告人的法律程序的通知書無效 — 需要取得中止訴訟的許可<p>\n	Fong Meng Sung John v Luk Man Lok Rocky</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc64000001519fac058cd1ffe493&amp;docguid=IE88DB906395548BB9201744F2936D69F&amp;hitguid=IE88DB906395548BB9201744F2936D69F&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=7\">[2015] HKEC 1852</a><br />\n	原訟法庭<br />\n	雜項案件2009年第1959號<br />\n	特委法官黃國瑛資深大律師內庭聆訊<br />\n	2015年9月7日</p>\n<p>\n	原告人於2009年根據《高等法院規則》(第4A章，附屬法例)(「《規則》」)第88號命令第1條規則，藉原訴傳票展開法律程序，但沒有根據第28號命令第1A(4)條規則送交誓章證據存檔。只有第一被告人送交送達認收書存檔；2011年5月，聆案官按原告人與第一被告人同意(第二及第三被告人缺席)，命令繼續進行法律程序，猶如是藉令狀開展一樣，並指示送交狀書存檔。第一被告人於2011年7月提交抗辯書及反申索書存檔。原告人最初於2011年8月獲得判決第二及第三被告人敗訴的怠誤判決，但聆案官於2013年7月將判決作廢，理由是向第二及第三被告人的文件送達有問題，且二人有一個值得考慮的抗辯理由。之後，原告人向第二及第三被告人送達中止訴訟通知書(「該通知書」)。儘管如此，第二及第三被告人還是於2013年8月提交抗辯書及反申索書存檔。他倆想自己的反申索在法律程序中被審理，因而以原告人不能未經許可便中止針對他倆提起的法律程序為由，指稱該通知書沒有法律效力。聆案官裁定該通知書有效，並且剔除第二及第三被告人的抗辯及反申索。第二及第三被告人上訴。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &ndash; 上訴得直：</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		制定中止訴訟的法定條文是要束縛普通法訴訟的原告人(不然原告人便不受限制，可隨時選擇中止訴訟)及交由法庭決定，當訴訟達到某階段之後，原告人是否還能中止訴訟，如果能夠，他是否應先符合某些條款才獲准中止。</li>\n	<li>\n		如藉原訴傳票開展的法律程序被命令繼續進行，猶如是藉令狀開展一樣，《規則》第21號命令第2(1)及(3)條規則不適用。法律程序展開以後，一方只能在極短時間之內無許可而行使中止訴訟的權利。對這類法律程序，第21號命令第2(3A)、2(3B)及3條規則以被告人誓章證據的送達為起點定出期限。沒有在被告人的誓章證據送達之後14天內根據第21號命令第2(3A)條規則中止訴訟的原告人，如果可選擇將第21號命令第2(1)及(3)條規則，應用到根據第28號命令第8條規則被指示猶如是藉令狀開展一樣繼續進行的法律程序，便會與許可規定背後的立法原意不相符。兩方都不根據第28號命令送達誓章證據也沒關係，就如本案一樣。</li>\n	<li>\n		聆案官在撤銷怠誤判決之後，給第二及第三被告人規定送達抗辯書的時限，但第21號命令第2(1)及(3)條規則所定的期限未必因此能「重設」，在撤銷怠誤判決是有法律依據的時候，更是一個大疑問。如原告人在反對第二及第三被告人申請撤銷怠誤判決之後，能根據第21號命令第2(1)或(3)條規則，在未經許可的情況下中止訴訟，便會與許可規定背後的原則不相符。第21號命令第2(1)條規則應局限於在第18號命令第2條規則規定的時間內送達抗辯書的案件。</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:118:\"中止訴訟 — 原告人中止針對被告人的法律程序的通知書無效 — 需要取得中止訴訟的許可\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3712:\"<p>中止訴訟 — 原告人中止針對被告人的法律程序的通知書無效 — 需要取得中止訴訟的許可\n</p><p>\n	Fong Meng Sung John v Luk Man Lok Rocky</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc64000001519fac058cd1ffe493&amp;docguid=IE88DB906395548BB9201744F2936D69F&amp;hitguid=IE88DB906395548BB9201744F2936D69F&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=7\">[2015] HKEC 1852</a><br />\n	原訟法庭<br />\n	雜項案件2009年第1959號<br />\n	特委法官黃國瑛資深大律師內庭聆訊<br />\n	2015年9月7日</p>\n<p>\n	原告人於2009年根據《高等法院規則》(第4A章，附屬法例)(「《規則》」)第88號命令第1條規則，藉原訴傳票展開法律程序，但沒有根據第28號命令第1A(4)條規則送交誓章證據存檔。只有第一被告人送交送達認收書存檔；2011年5月，聆案官按原告人與第一被告人同意(第二及第三被告人缺席)，命令繼續進行法律程序，猶如是藉令狀開展一樣，並指示送交狀書存檔。第一被告人於2011年7月提交抗辯書及反申索書存檔。原告人最初於2011年8月獲得判決第二及第三被告人敗訴的怠誤判決，但聆案官於2013年7月將判決作廢，理由是向第二及第三被告人的文件送達有問題，且二人有一個值得考慮的抗辯理由。之後，原告人向第二及第三被告人送達中止訴訟通知書(「該通知書」)。儘管如此，第二及第三被告人還是於2013年8月提交抗辯書及反申索書存檔。他倆想自己的反申索在法律程序中被審理，因而以原告人不能未經許可便中止針對他倆提起的法律程序為由，指稱該通知書沒有法律效力。聆案官裁定該通知書有效，並且剔除第二及第三被告人的抗辯及反申索。第二及第三被告人上訴。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> – 上訴得直：</p>\n<ul><li>\n		制定中止訴訟的法定條文是要束縛普通法訴訟的原告人(不然原告人便不受限制，可隨時選擇中止訴訟)及交由法庭決定，當訴訟達到某階段之後，原告人是否還能中止訴訟，如果能夠，他是否應先符合某些條款才獲准中止。</li>\n<li>\n		如藉原訴傳票開展的法律程序被命令繼續進行，猶如是藉令狀開展一樣，《規則》第21號命令第2(1)及(3)條規則不適用。法律程序展開以後，一方只能在極短時間之內無許可而行使中止訴訟的權利。對這類法律程序，第21號命令第2(3A)、2(3B)及3條規則以被告人誓章證據的送達為起點定出期限。沒有在被告人的誓章證據送達之後14天內根據第21號命令第2(3A)條規則中止訴訟的原告人，如果可選擇將第21號命令第2(1)及(3)條規則，應用到根據第28號命令第8條規則被指示猶如是藉令狀開展一樣繼續進行的法律程序，便會與許可規定背後的立法原意不相符。兩方都不根據第28號命令送達誓章證據也沒關係，就如本案一樣。</li>\n<li>\n		聆案官在撤銷怠誤判決之後，給第二及第三被告人規定送達抗辯書的時限，但第21號命令第2(1)及(3)條規則所定的期限未必因此能「重設」，在撤銷怠誤判決是有法律依據的時候，更是一個大疑問。如原告人在反對第二及第三被告人申請撤銷怠誤判決之後，能根據第21號命令第2(1)或(3)條規則，在未經許可的情況下中止訴訟，便會與許可規定背後的原則不相符。第21號命令第2(1)條規則應局限於在第18號命令第2條規則規定的時間內送達抗辯書的案件。</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:126:\"<p>中止訴訟 — 原告人中止針對被告人的法律程序的通知書無效 — 需要取得中止訴訟的許可</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"原訟法庭\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"原訟法庭\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:39:\"Fong Meng Sung John v Luk Man Lok Rocky\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:39:\"Fong Meng Sung John v Luk Man Lok Rocky\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"565\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"638\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:231:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744cc64000001519fac058cd1ffe493&docguid=IE88DB906395548BB9201744F2936D69F&hitguid=IE88DB906395548BB9201744F2936D69F&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=7\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1852\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"2015年9月7日\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"2015年9月7日\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"民事訴訟程序\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"民事訴訟程序\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:39:\"Fong Meng Sung John v Luk Man Lok Rocky\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183919,1),('9309','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9313\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:37:\"Tong Cun Ming v Cheung Sun Ling Sanny\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9309\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9309\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3702:\"Religious institution incorporated as company – expulsion of members – whether rules of natural justice applied in terminating membership of religious charitable trust and incorporated company limited by guarantee<p>\n	Tong Cun Ming v Cheung Sun Ling Sanny</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad62903000001519fb116b22ae09b0f&amp;docguid=I42ED3241FEF14FE298FEF0967AF82747&amp;hitguid=I42ED3241FEF14FE298FEF0967AF82747&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=10\">[2015] HKEC 1834</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Miscellaneous Proceedings Nos. 143, 1013 &amp; 2477 of 2011<br />\n	David Lok J<br />\n	2 September 2015</p>\n<p>\n	X was a religious institution, a religious charitable trust and an incorporated company. X was divided into two rival camps: the Traditionalists&rsquo; Camp, including Ds, on one side and the Reformists&rsquo; Camp, including Ps, on the other. On 15 October 2011, without giving prior notification of a proposal to expel Ps, the charges against them or an opportunity to present their respective cases, the Board passed a resolution terminating their membership of X (the &ldquo;Termination Resolution&rdquo;) for breach of charitable objects in art.3 of the memorandum of association (the &ldquo;Memorandum&rdquo;) and breach of the religious oath. On 11 November 2011, notices of the decision were issued to Ps, who brought proceedings against 15 councillors of the Board and X challenging the validity of the Termination Resolution, which was one of three actions between the parties. Article 9.2 of X&rsquo;s articles of association stipulated that a member could be expelled only if the councillors were satisfied that a member had failed or refused to abide by any of the articles and/or rules or regulations made under art. 8.1; and he had a right to appeal against the decision. The present hearing was a trial of certain preliminary issues in the three actions, including whether the purported expulsion of Ps from X&rsquo;s membership was invalid for breach of the rules of natural justice.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		The principles of natural justice applied to the expulsion of members of an incorporated company unless the circumstances indicated the contrary. This was the case here. Article 9.2 did not provide for an absolute and unrestricted power to expel members from X, but one subject to conditions. Further, various factors, including that certain members of the Reformist Camp had donated substantial sums to X, suggested that Ps had substantial interests in its operation and future development. Accordingly, the Termination Resolution was unlawful.</li>\n	<li>\n		An expelled member should be notified of disciplinary proceedings and charges against him. It was no answer that, given the circumstances leading to the dispute, the member should have known about such charges. Although an appeal procedure was provided for by the Articles, there would not have been a fair result reached by fair methods. The Traditionalists&rsquo; Camp wished to crush the opposition once and for all. Even if Ps had appealed, the board hearing it would not be a properly constituted one, much less a fair and impartial tribunal because the two other members of the appeal committee were not selected by the honorary legal adviser in accordance with art. 9.2, but by the Board. Moreover, under art. 17, the Termination Resolution stripped Ps&rsquo; of their right to stand for election as councillors even if they appealed against the decision and so natural justice demanded that they be given the right to be heard before it was passed.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:217:\"Religious institution incorporated as company – expulsion of members – whether rules of natural justice applied in terminating membership of religious charitable trust and incorporated company limited by guarantee\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3666:\"<p>Religious institution incorporated as company – expulsion of members – whether rules of natural justice applied in terminating membership of religious charitable trust and incorporated company limited by guarantee\n</p><p>\n	Tong Cun Ming v Cheung Sun Ling Sanny</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad62903000001519fb116b22ae09b0f&amp;docguid=I42ED3241FEF14FE298FEF0967AF82747&amp;hitguid=I42ED3241FEF14FE298FEF0967AF82747&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=10\">[2015] HKEC 1834</a><br />\n	Court of First Instance<br />\n	Miscellaneous Proceedings Nos. 143, 1013 &amp; 2477 of 2011<br />\n	David Lok J<br />\n	2 September 2015</p>\n<p>\n	X was a religious institution, a religious charitable trust and an incorporated company. X was divided into two rival camps: the Traditionalists’ Camp, including Ds, on one side and the Reformists’ Camp, including Ps, on the other. On 15 October 2011, without giving prior notification of a proposal to expel Ps, the charges against them or an opportunity to present their respective cases, the Board passed a resolution terminating their membership of X (the “Termination Resolution”) for breach of charitable objects in art.3 of the memorandum of association (the “Memorandum”) and breach of the religious oath. On 11 November 2011, notices of the decision were issued to Ps, who brought proceedings against 15 councillors of the Board and X challenging the validity of the Termination Resolution, which was one of three actions between the parties. Article 9.2 of X’s articles of association stipulated that a member could be expelled only if the councillors were satisfied that a member had failed or refused to abide by any of the articles and/or rules or regulations made under art. 8.1; and he had a right to appeal against the decision. The present hearing was a trial of certain preliminary issues in the three actions, including whether the purported expulsion of Ps from X’s membership was invalid for breach of the rules of natural justice.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		The principles of natural justice applied to the expulsion of members of an incorporated company unless the circumstances indicated the contrary. This was the case here. Article 9.2 did not provide for an absolute and unrestricted power to expel members from X, but one subject to conditions. Further, various factors, including that certain members of the Reformist Camp had donated substantial sums to X, suggested that Ps had substantial interests in its operation and future development. Accordingly, the Termination Resolution was unlawful.</li>\n<li>\n		An expelled member should be notified of disciplinary proceedings and charges against him. It was no answer that, given the circumstances leading to the dispute, the member should have known about such charges. Although an appeal procedure was provided for by the Articles, there would not have been a fair result reached by fair methods. The Traditionalists’ Camp wished to crush the opposition once and for all. Even if Ps had appealed, the board hearing it would not be a properly constituted one, much less a fair and impartial tribunal because the two other members of the appeal committee were not selected by the honorary legal adviser in accordance with art. 9.2, but by the Board. Moreover, under art. 17, the Termination Resolution stripped Ps’ of their right to stand for election as councillors even if they appealed against the decision and so natural justice demanded that they be given the right to be heard before it was passed.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:225:\"<p>Religious institution incorporated as company – expulsion of members – whether rules of natural justice applied in terminating membership of religious charitable trust and incorporated company limited by guarantee</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:37:\"Tong Cun Ming v Cheung Sun Ling Sanny\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:37:\"Tong Cun Ming v Cheung Sun Ling Sanny\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:2:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"100\";}i:1;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad62903000001519fb116b22ae09b0f&docguid=I42ED3241FEF14FE298FEF0967AF82747&hitguid=I42ED3241FEF14FE298FEF0967AF82747&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=10\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1834\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"2 September 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"2 September 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:11:\"Company Law\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:11:\"Company Law\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:37:\"Tong Cun Ming v Cheung Sun Ling Sanny\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458115031,1),('9311','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9315\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:37:\"Secretary for Justice v Cheng Kam Mun\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9311\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456675400\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9311\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1455866109\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2769:\"<p><em>Application for order of committal after leave to apply granted – failure to enter originating summons for hearing within 14 days under O. 52 r. 3(2) – court had no inherent jurisdiction to extend time for compliance with O. 52 r. 3(2) in criminal contempt case</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Secretary for Justice (the “SJ”) obtained leave to apply for an order of committal against Xs, in respect of conduct which allegedly constituted criminal contempt. The SJ then issued originating summonses (the “OS”) for orders of committal for criminal contempt of court against Xs, but failed to enter the OS for hearing within 14days so that the leave lapsed under O.52 r. 3(2) of the Rules of the High Court (Cap. 4A, Sub. Leg.) (the “RHC”). The SJ therefore applied under O. 3 r. 5 of the RHC for an extension of time to issue a notice of appointment to hear the OS in compliance with O. 52 r. 3(2). At the hearing, the SJ conceded that the Court had no power to extend time under O. 3 r. 5 as the application for committal was for criminal contempt, but argued that the Court had an inherent jurisdiction to extend time. Alternatively, the SJ argued that the decision of the Court of Appeal in the case of <em>Effiscient Ltd v Lehman</em>, insofar as it held that for the purpose of O. 52 r. 3(2), entering an originating summons for hearing meant issuing a notice of appointment to hear the originating summons, was <em>per incuriam</em> and not binding on the Court.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The Court was bound by <em>Effiscient Ltd v Lehman</em>. The doctrine of <em>per incuriam</em> could not be relied on by a judge at first instance to refuse to follow a directly relevant decision of the Court of Appeal. The only way to reverse the decision would be to take the matter to the Court of Appeal (or the Court of Final Appeal) or amend the RHC.</li>\r\n	<li>The Court had no inherent jurisdiction to extend the time to comply with the requirement of O. 52 r. 3(2). The consequence of non-compliance, namely that “the leave <em>shall lapse</em>”, was unequivocal and the legislature’s intention was clear. Such jurisdiction could not extend to laying down any procedure which was inconsistent with an express statutory rule. In this respect, <em>Effiscient Ltd v Lehman</em> was distinguishable because it was a civil contempt case, where there was no dispute that a power to extend time under O. 3 r. 5(1) was available.</li>\r\n	<li>Further, various foreign decisions, while not binding on the Court, supported the view that the time limit under O. 52 r. 3(2) was mandatory and any default in compliance could not be cured by a court extending time in a criminal contempt case.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:270:\"<p>Application for order of committal after leave to apply granted – failure to enter originating summons for hearing within 14 days under O.52 r.3(2) – court had no inherent jurisdiction to extend time for compliance with O.52 r.3(2) in criminal contempt case</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2750:\"<p><em>Application for order of committal after leave to apply granted – failure to enter originating summons for hearing within 14 days under O. 52 r. 3(2) – court had no inherent jurisdiction to extend time for compliance with O. 52 r. 3(2) in criminal contempt case</em></p>\n<p>The Secretary for Justice (the “SJ”) obtained leave to apply for an order of committal against Xs, in respect of conduct which allegedly constituted criminal contempt. The SJ then issued originating summonses (the “OS”) for orders of committal for criminal contempt of court against Xs, but failed to enter the OS for hearing within 14days so that the leave lapsed under O.52 r. 3(2) of the Rules of the High Court (Cap. 4A, Sub. Leg.) (the “RHC”). The SJ therefore applied under O. 3 r. 5 of the RHC for an extension of time to issue a notice of appointment to hear the OS in compliance with O. 52 r. 3(2). At the hearing, the SJ conceded that the Court had no power to extend time under O. 3 r. 5 as the application for committal was for criminal contempt, but argued that the Court had an inherent jurisdiction to extend time. Alternatively, the SJ argued that the decision of the Court of Appeal in the case of <em>Effiscient Ltd v Lehman</em>, insofar as it held that for the purpose of O. 52 r. 3(2), entering an originating summons for hearing meant issuing a notice of appointment to hear the originating summons, was <em>per incuriam</em> and not binding on the Court.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\n<ul><li>The Court was bound by <em>Effiscient Ltd v Lehman</em>. The doctrine of <em>per incuriam</em> could not be relied on by a judge at first instance to refuse to follow a directly relevant decision of the Court of Appeal. The only way to reverse the decision would be to take the matter to the Court of Appeal (or the Court of Final Appeal) or amend the RHC.</li>\n<li>The Court had no inherent jurisdiction to extend the time to comply with the requirement of O. 52 r. 3(2). The consequence of non-compliance, namely that “the leave <em>shall lapse</em>”, was unequivocal and the legislature’s intention was clear. Such jurisdiction could not extend to laying down any procedure which was inconsistent with an express statutory rule. In this respect, <em>Effiscient Ltd v Lehman</em> was distinguishable because it was a civil contempt case, where there was no dispute that a power to extend time under O. 3 r. 5(1) was available.</li>\n<li>Further, various foreign decisions, while not binding on the Court, supported the view that the time limit under O. 52 r. 3(2) was mandatory and any default in compliance could not be cured by a court extending time in a criminal contempt case.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:269:\"<p>Application for order of committal after leave to apply granted – failure to enter originating summons for hearing within 14 days under O.52 r.3(2) – court had no inherent jurisdiction to extend time for compliance with O.52 r.3(2) in criminal contempt case</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:37:\"Secretary for Justice v Cheng Kam Mun\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:37:\"Secretary for Justice v Cheng Kam Mun\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:2:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}i:1;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"483\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"101\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 00:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad69f8e000001519fbd761f3f77340f&docguid=IE03DDBCACD2041A2861A28389D391F5D&hitguid=IE03DDBCACD2041A2861A28389D391F5D&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=15\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1836\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"1 September 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"1 September 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:17:\"Criminal Contempt\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:17:\"Criminal Contempt\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:37:\"Secretary for Justice v Cheng Kam Mun\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";s:1:\"0\";s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";N;s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458115031,1),('9312','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9316\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:37:\"Secretary for Justice v Cheng Kam Mun\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9312\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1455866159\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9311\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1455866159\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3241:\"<p>在獲給予所需許可後，申請交付羈押令 — 未有按照第52號命令第3(2)條規則的規定，於14天內登錄原訴傳票以待聆訊 — 在涉及刑事藐視法庭的案件中，法庭不具有固有司法管轄權把遵守第52號命令第3(2)條規則的時限延展</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Secretary for Justice v Cheng Kam Mun</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e000001519fbd761f3f77340f&amp;docguid=IE03DDBCACD2041A2861A28389D391F5D&amp;hitguid=IE03DDBCACD2041A2861A28389D391F5D&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=15\">[2015] HKEC 1836</a><br />\r\n原訟法庭<br />\r\n高院雜項案件2012年第488、490至492及494至506號<br />\r\n原訟法庭法官周家明內庭聆訊<br />\r\n2015年9月1日</p>\r\n\r\n<p>律政司司長(下稱「司長」)獲批予許可，申請命令把被指曾作出構成刑事藐視法庭的行為的各名答辯人(下稱Xs)交付羈押。司長繼而發出原訴傳票，要求法庭以Xs刑事藐視法庭為由而下令把他們交付羈押。不過，司長未有於14天內登錄該原訴傳票以待聆訊，因此，根據《高等法院規則》(第4章，附屬法例A)(下稱「《規則》」)第52號命令第3(2)條規則，上述許可即告失效。司長於是根據《規則》第3號命令第5條規則，申請延展時限，讓司長可依照第52號命令第3(2)條規則，發出通知書預約時間聆訊該原訴傳票。在該申請的聆訊中，司長承認，由於交付羈押令的申請乃建基於刑事藐視法庭，故原訟法庭無權根據第3號命令第5條規則延展時限。然而，司長辯稱原訟法庭具有固有司法管轄權延展時限。司長亦提出交替辯據，指上訴法庭在<em>Effiscient Ltd v Lehman</em>一案的裁決中表示第52號命令第3(2)條規則下「登錄原訴傳票以待聆訊」意指發出通知書預約時間聆訊該原訴傳票的部份乃屬判決中的錯誤評論，對原訟法庭沒有約束力。</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>裁決</strong> — 駁回申請﹕</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>原訟法庭受<em>Effiscient Ltd v Lehman</em>一案約束。原審法官不能倚賴「判決中的錯誤評論」法則，以拒絕依循與案件直接相關的上訴法庭裁決。推翻該裁決的方法，就只有把事情提呈上訴法庭(或終審法院)，又或尋求修訂 《規則》。</li>\r\n	<li>原訟法庭不具有固有司法管轄權把遵守第52號命令第3(2)條規則的時限延展。不遵守該規則的後果已毫不含糊地訂明為「許可即告失效」，這方面的立法意願亦清楚不過。固有司法管轄權不能延伸至包括訂立任何與明文法規互不一致的程序。就此而言，<em>Effiscient Ltd v Lehman</em>一案與本案有別，因為該案涉及民事藐視法庭，而不受爭議的是法庭在該類案件中有權根據第3號命令第5(1)條規則延展時限。</li>\r\n	<li>此外，各項海外裁決雖然對原訟法庭沒有約束力，但支持以下說法，即第52號命令第3(2)條規則下的時限屬強制性，以及在涉及刑事藐視法庭的案件中，遵守該規則方面的缺失不能透過法庭延展時限來補救。</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:297:\"<p>在獲給予所需許可後，申請交付羈押令 — 未有按照第52號命令第3(2)條規則的規定，於14天內登錄原訴傳票以待聆訊 — 在涉及刑事藐視法庭的案件中，法庭不具有固有司法管轄權把遵守第52號命令第3(2)條規則的時限延展</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3212:\"<p>在獲給予所需許可後，申請交付羈押令 — 未有按照第52號命令第3(2)條規則的規定，於14天內登錄原訴傳票以待聆訊 — 在涉及刑事藐視法庭的案件中，法庭不具有固有司法管轄權把遵守第52號命令第3(2)條規則的時限延展</p>\n<p>Secretary for Justice v Cheng Kam Mun</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e000001519fbd761f3f77340f&amp;docguid=IE03DDBCACD2041A2861A28389D391F5D&amp;hitguid=IE03DDBCACD2041A2861A28389D391F5D&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=15\">[2015] HKEC 1836</a><br />\n原訟法庭<br />\n高院雜項案件2012年第488、490至492及494至506號<br />\n原訟法庭法官周家明內庭聆訊<br />\n2015年9月1日</p>\n<p>律政司司長(下稱「司長」)獲批予許可，申請命令把被指曾作出構成刑事藐視法庭的行為的各名答辯人(下稱Xs)交付羈押。司長繼而發出原訴傳票，要求法庭以Xs刑事藐視法庭為由而下令把他們交付羈押。不過，司長未有於14天內登錄該原訴傳票以待聆訊，因此，根據《高等法院規則》(第4章，附屬法例A)(下稱「《規則》」)第52號命令第3(2)條規則，上述許可即告失效。司長於是根據《規則》第3號命令第5條規則，申請延展時限，讓司長可依照第52號命令第3(2)條規則，發出通知書預約時間聆訊該原訴傳票。在該申請的聆訊中，司長承認，由於交付羈押令的申請乃建基於刑事藐視法庭，故原訟法庭無權根據第3號命令第5條規則延展時限。然而，司長辯稱原訟法庭具有固有司法管轄權延展時限。司長亦提出交替辯據，指上訴法庭在<em>Effiscient Ltd v Lehman</em>一案的裁決中表示第52號命令第3(2)條規則下「登錄原訴傳票以待聆訊」意指發出通知書預約時間聆訊該原訴傳票的部份乃屬判決中的錯誤評論，對原訟法庭沒有約束力。</p>\n<p><strong>裁決</strong> — 駁回申請﹕</p>\n<ul><li>原訟法庭受<em>Effiscient Ltd v Lehman</em>一案約束。原審法官不能倚賴「判決中的錯誤評論」法則，以拒絕依循與案件直接相關的上訴法庭裁決。推翻該裁決的方法，就只有把事情提呈上訴法庭(或終審法院)，又或尋求修訂 《規則》。</li>\n<li>原訟法庭不具有固有司法管轄權把遵守第52號命令第3(2)條規則的時限延展。不遵守該規則的後果已毫不含糊地訂明為「許可即告失效」，這方面的立法意願亦清楚不過。固有司法管轄權不能延伸至包括訂立任何與明文法規互不一致的程序。就此而言，<em>Effiscient Ltd v Lehman</em>一案與本案有別，因為該案涉及民事藐視法庭，而不受爭議的是法庭在該類案件中有權根據第3號命令第5(1)條規則延展時限。</li>\n<li>此外，各項海外裁決雖然對原訟法庭沒有約束力，但支持以下說法，即第52號命令第3(2)條規則下的時限屬強制性，以及在涉及刑事藐視法庭的案件中，遵守該規則方面的缺失不能透過法庭延展時限來補救。</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:296:\"<p>在獲給予所需許可後，申請交付羈押令 — 未有按照第52號命令第3(2)條規則的規定，於14天內登錄原訴傳票以待聆訊 — 在涉及刑事藐視法庭的案件中，法庭不具有固有司法管轄權把遵守第52號命令第3(2)條規則的時限延展</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"原訟法庭\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"原訟法庭\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:37:\"Secretary for Justice v Cheng Kam Mun\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:37:\"Secretary for Justice v Cheng Kam Mun\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:2:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}i:1;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"520\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"563\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"638\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 00:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad69f8e000001519fbd761f3f77340f&docguid=IE03DDBCACD2041A2861A28389D391F5D&hitguid=IE03DDBCACD2041A2861A28389D391F5D&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=15\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1836\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"2015年9月1日\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"2015年9月1日\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"刑事藐視法庭\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"刑事藐視法庭\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:37:\"Secretary for Justice v Cheng Kam Mun\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";s:1:\"0\";s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";N;s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183919,1),('9313','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9317\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:22:\"HKSAR v Cherif Mohamed\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9313\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456675439\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9313\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:1745:\"<p><em>Dangerous drugs – trafficking – appropriate enhancement for international element – family circumstances not mitigation</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>D, a Guinean national, pleaded guilty to trafficking in dangerous drugs. He was intercepted on arrival at Hong Kong airport from Nigeria and, while in custody, discharged 82 pellets containing 0.79 kg of cocaine. D admitted under caution that he had swallowed the pellets in Lagos and received a reward of US$4,000 for importing them into Hong Kong. The Judge adopted a starting point of 20½years, enhanced it by 1½ years for the international factor and reduced it for plea to 14 years and eight months’ imprisonment. Almost four years later, D sought leave to appeal out of time against sentence, explaining the delay in his application by saying his wife, W, was recently diagnosed with breast cancer, she required surgery and wished him to be by her side; and W could no longer care for their young daughter, nor could D’s aged parents. D argued that as the sole breadwinner, his lengthy imprisonment had caused his family financial hardship.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>D’s application was badly out of time and without merit. Contrary to D’s contention, the 1½-year enhancement for the international element was well within the range available to the Judge.</li>\r\n	<li>Even accepting the circumstances of D’s wife and family, they played virtually no part in the mitigation of drug offences. In any event, a reduction in sentence, on a purely humanitarian basis, would not assist D unless the Court anticipated his immediate release which, having regard to the seriousness of the offence, was inconceivable.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:134:\"<p>Dangerous drugs – trafficking – appropriate enhancement for international element – family circumstances not mitigation</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:1728:\"<p><em>Dangerous drugs – trafficking – appropriate enhancement for international element – family circumstances not mitigation</em></p>\n<p>D, a Guinean national, pleaded guilty to trafficking in dangerous drugs. He was intercepted on arrival at Hong Kong airport from Nigeria and, while in custody, discharged 82 pellets containing 0.79 kg of cocaine. D admitted under caution that he had swallowed the pellets in Lagos and received a reward of US$4,000 for importing them into Hong Kong. The Judge adopted a starting point of 20½years, enhanced it by 1½ years for the international factor and reduced it for plea to 14 years and eight months’ imprisonment. Almost four years later, D sought leave to appeal out of time against sentence, explaining the delay in his application by saying his wife, W, was recently diagnosed with breast cancer, she required surgery and wished him to be by her side; and W could no longer care for their young daughter, nor could D’s aged parents. D argued that as the sole breadwinner, his lengthy imprisonment had caused his family financial hardship.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\n<ul><li>D’s application was badly out of time and without merit. Contrary to D’s contention, the 1½-year enhancement for the international element was well within the range available to the Judge.</li>\n<li>Even accepting the circumstances of D’s wife and family, they played virtually no part in the mitigation of drug offences. In any event, a reduction in sentence, on a purely humanitarian basis, would not assist D unless the Court anticipated his immediate release which, having regard to the seriousness of the offence, was inconceivable.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:133:\"<p>Dangerous drugs – trafficking – appropriate enhancement for international element – family circumstances not mitigation</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:22:\"HKSAR v Cherif Mohamed\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:22:\"HKSAR v Cherif Mohamed\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"101\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744c097000001519fc437b588051c87&docguid=I1D07A969705E4C4388B5A255B178928F&hitguid=I1D07A969705E4C4388B5A255B178928F&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=18\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 4 HKLRD 604\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:14:\"12 August 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:14:\"12 August 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"Criminal Sentencing\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:19:\"Criminal Sentencing\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:22:\"HKSAR v Cherif Mohamed\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458115031,1),('9314','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9318\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:22:\"HKSAR v Cherif Mohamed\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9314\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9313\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2270:\"危險藥物 — 販運罪 — 基於跨國販毒元素而作出的恰當加刑幅度 — 家庭狀況並非減刑因素<p>\n	HKSAR v Cherif Mohamed<br />\n	<br />\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744c097000001519fc437b588051c87&amp;docguid=I1D07A969705E4C4388B5A255B178928F&amp;hitguid=I1D07A969705E4C4388B5A255B178928F&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=18\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 604</a><br />\n	上訴法庭<br />\n	上訴法庭刑事上訴案2015年第95號<br />\n	上訴法庭法官麥機智，原訟法庭法官彭偉昌<br />\n	2015年8月12日</p>\n<p>\n	本案被告人是西非幾內亞國民，承認一項「販運危險藥物」罪。案情指出，被告人乘搭航機從尼日利亞來港，到步後在香港機場被截查和羈押。羈押期間，被告人從體內排出82粒內含共重0.79公斤可卡因的丸狀物。他在警誡下承認曾在尼日利亞拉各斯市吞下該批丸狀物，並收取4,000美元作為把涉案毒品帶進香港的報酬。原審法官採納監禁20年半為量刑基準，基於跨國販毒元素而把刑期提高一年半，然後因應被告人認罪而把刑期扣減至14年8個月。事隔近四年後，被告人現申請許可逾期針對判刑提出上訴。對於為何延誤提出該申請，被告人解釋說其妻子(下稱W)最近被診斷患有乳癌，須接受手術，並希望被告人陪伴身旁，而W和被告人的年老雙親均無法照顧被告人和W的年幼女兒。被告人辯稱自己是其家庭的唯一經濟支柱，而其家庭已因他被判長期監禁而陷入財政困境。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &mdash; 駁回申請﹕</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		被告人的申請嚴重過期，且無理可據。與被告人的辯據相反，建基於跨國販毒元素的一年半刑期增幅，絕無超越可供原審法官考慮和採納的幅度。</li>\n	<li>\n		即使本庭接納被告人妻子和家庭的狀況，這基本上也不構成涉及毒品的罪行的減刑因素。不論如何，純粹基於人道理由而給予的減刑不會對被告人有任何幫助，除非本庭有意讓他即時獲釋，但考慮到涉案罪行的嚴重性質，本庭根本不可能持該種想法。</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:120:\"危險藥物 — 販運罪 — 基於跨國販毒元素而作出的恰當加刑幅度 — 家庭狀況並非減刑因素\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2263