";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183919,1),('9315','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9319\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:9:\"QMY v GSS\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9315\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456675501\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9315\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3765:\"<p><em>Proceedings under Guardianship of Minors Ordinance – whether Family Court had jurisdiction where child not habitually residing or present in Hong Kong – whether inherent jurisdiction over child, founded on nationality prior to 1997, continued after 1997 on basis of permanent residence</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>M and F, the mother and father of G, never married. M was a mainland Chinese resident and F was a Hong Kong permanent resident. G was a permanent resident of Hong Kong by birth. Shortly after G was born, M and G moved to the Mainland. M and G were currently residing in Guangzhou, but had previously resided in Siming District, Xiamen and Fujian. In July 2012, M applied in Hong Kong under s. 10 of the Guardianship of Minors Ordinance (Cap. 13) (“GMO”) for F to pay maintenance for G (the “Hong Kong Proceedings”). Within one month, F then commenced proceedings on the Mainland in the Siming District seeking custody of G and an order that M pay him maintenance for G. In September 2012, F applied to stay the Hong Kong Proceedings on the ground of <em>forum non conveniens </em>in favour of the mainland Court. In January 2013, the Siming Court dismissed F’s claim. F then applied for the Hong Kong Proceedings to be dismissed on the basis that the Hong Kong Court had no jurisdiction to deal with M’s application because G was not an ordinary or habitual resident of Hong Kong or physically present here. On 27May 2013, the Hong Kong Family Court dismissed F’s jurisdictional challenge and application to stay the Hong Kong proceedings. In October 2013, F’s appeal against the decision of the Siming Court was dismissed. In November 2013, F commenced other mainland proceedings in the Tianhe District, Guangzhou, again for custody of G and payment of maintenance for her by M. In March 2014, the Tianhe Court granted custody of G to M and ordered F to pay maintenance. The Guangzhou Court dismissed F’s appeal against that decision, but varied it by <em>inter alia</em> removing the custody order in favour of M. F now appealed against the 27 May decision of the Family Court.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, allowing the appeal:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>While there was no express provision in the GMO on whether the child must be habitually resident or physically present in Hong Kong at the time proceedings were commenced before the court’s jurisdiction could be invoked, in the absence of restrictions, the court should be prepared to proceed on the basis that it had such jurisdiction. However, it was not necessary for the purpose of this appeal to give a determinative answer because the Hong Kong Court also had inherent jurisdiction over children which might be exercised beyond its territorial limits.</li>\r\n	<li>The Hong Kong courts had inherent jurisdiction over children both before and after the resumption of exercise of sovereignty by mainland China on 1 July 1997. It was difficult to transpose the concept of jurisdiction founded on the original basis of nationality to one founded on the status as a permanent resident of Hong Kong. Irrespective of its original basis, this inherent jurisdiction was so well entrenched in Hong Kong in relation to children matters that one should proceed on the basis that in appropriate situations which involved a child who was a permanent resident of Hong Kong, the court would step in and exercise its traditional protective role over the child even if he or she was not physically present in Hong Kong at the time of the application. It was unthinkable that such inherent jurisdiction over children would suddenly disappear simply because of the change in 1997. Any contrary view would leave too large a <em>lacuna</em> in the practice and operation of family law.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:298:\"<p>Proceedings under Guardianship of Minors Ordinance – whether Family Court had jurisdiction where child not habitually residing or present in Hong Kong – whether inherent jurisdiction over child, founded on nationality prior to 1997, continued after 1997 on basis of permanent residence</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3748:\"<p><em>Proceedings under Guardianship of Minors Ordinance – whether Family Court had jurisdiction where child not habitually residing or present in Hong Kong – whether inherent jurisdiction over child, founded on nationality prior to 1997, continued after 1997 on basis of permanent residence</em></p>\n<p>M and F, the mother and father of G, never married. M was a mainland Chinese resident and F was a Hong Kong permanent resident. G was a permanent resident of Hong Kong by birth. Shortly after G was born, M and G moved to the Mainland. M and G were currently residing in Guangzhou, but had previously resided in Siming District, Xiamen and Fujian. In July 2012, M applied in Hong Kong under s. 10 of the Guardianship of Minors Ordinance (Cap. 13) (“GMO”) for F to pay maintenance for G (the “Hong Kong Proceedings”). Within one month, F then commenced proceedings on the Mainland in the Siming District seeking custody of G and an order that M pay him maintenance for G. In September 2012, F applied to stay the Hong Kong Proceedings on the ground of <em>forum non conveniens </em>in favour of the mainland Court. In January 2013, the Siming Court dismissed F’s claim. F then applied for the Hong Kong Proceedings to be dismissed on the basis that the Hong Kong Court had no jurisdiction to deal with M’s application because G was not an ordinary or habitual resident of Hong Kong or physically present here. On 27May 2013, the Hong Kong Family Court dismissed F’s jurisdictional challenge and application to stay the Hong Kong proceedings. In October 2013, F’s appeal against the decision of the Siming Court was dismissed. In November 2013, F commenced other mainland proceedings in the Tianhe District, Guangzhou, again for custody of G and payment of maintenance for her by M. In March 2014, the Tianhe Court granted custody of G to M and ordered F to pay maintenance. The Guangzhou Court dismissed F’s appeal against that decision, but varied it by <em>inter alia</em> removing the custody order in favour of M. F now appealed against the 27 May decision of the Family Court.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, allowing the appeal:</p>\n<ul><li>While there was no express provision in the GMO on whether the child must be habitually resident or physically present in Hong Kong at the time proceedings were commenced before the court’s jurisdiction could be invoked, in the absence of restrictions, the court should be prepared to proceed on the basis that it had such jurisdiction. However, it was not necessary for the purpose of this appeal to give a determinative answer because the Hong Kong Court also had inherent jurisdiction over children which might be exercised beyond its territorial limits.</li>\n<li>The Hong Kong courts had inherent jurisdiction over children both before and after the resumption of exercise of sovereignty by mainland China on 1 July 1997. It was difficult to transpose the concept of jurisdiction founded on the original basis of nationality to one founded on the status as a permanent resident of Hong Kong. Irrespective of its original basis, this inherent jurisdiction was so well entrenched in Hong Kong in relation to children matters that one should proceed on the basis that in appropriate situations which involved a child who was a permanent resident of Hong Kong, the court would step in and exercise its traditional protective role over the child even if he or she was not physically present in Hong Kong at the time of the application. It was unthinkable that such inherent jurisdiction over children would suddenly disappear simply because of the change in 1997. Any contrary view would leave too large a <em>lacuna</em> in the practice and operation of family law.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:297:\"<p>Proceedings under Guardianship of Minors Ordinance – whether Family Court had jurisdiction where child not habitually residing or present in Hong Kong – whether inherent jurisdiction over child, founded on nationality prior to 1997, continued after 1997 on basis of permanent residence</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:9:\"QMY v GSS\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:9:\"QMY v GSS\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"106\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744c097000001519fcf82a11aae0195&docguid=IE24A6BCA719B4AACAF8DF3EB9D469AC7&hitguid=IE24A6BCA719B4AACAF8DF3EB9D469AC7&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=21\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 4 HKLRD 641\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:14:\"19 August 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:14:\"19 August 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:10:\"Family Law\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:10:\"Family Law\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:9:\"QMY v GSS\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458115031,1),('9316','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9320\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:9:\"QMY v GSS\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9316\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9315\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3626:\"根據《未成年人監護條例》進行的法律程序 — 子女不是慣常住在香港或不是身在香港，家事法庭有沒有司法管轄權 — 對兒童的固有司法管轄權，1997年之前以國籍為基礎，1997年之後是否以永久性居留地為基礎<p>\n	QMY v GSS</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744c097000001519fcf82a11aae0195&amp;docguid=IE24A6BCA719B4AACAF8DF3EB9D469AC7&amp;hitguid=IE24A6BCA719B4AACAF8DF3EB9D469AC7&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=21\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 641<br />\n	</a>上訴法庭<br />\n	民事上訴案件2014年第68號<br />\n	林文瀚副庭長，上訴法庭法官張澤祐及上訴法庭法官袁家寧<br />\n	2015年8月19日</p>\n<p>\n	M和F是G的父母，二人從來沒有結婚。M是中國內地居民，F是香港永久性居民。G是在香港出生的香港永久性居民。G出生後不久，M和G搬到內地居住。M和G現時住在廣州，之前住過思明區、廈門、福建。2012年7月，M在香港根據《未成年人監護條例》(第13章)(「《條例》」)第10條提出申請，要求法庭命令F支付G的贍養費(「香港法律程序」)。F於之後一個月內，在內地思明區展開法律程序，要求法院判給他G的管養權及命令M付給他G的贍養費。2012年9月，F申請擱置香港法律程序，理由是香港法庭並非便利公堂(<em>forum non conveniens</em>)，內地法院才是。2013年1月，思明區人民法院駁回F的申索。之後，F申請撤銷香港法律程序，理由是G不是通常或慣常住在香港，也不是身在香港，香港法庭因而沒有司法管轄權處理M的申請。2013年5月27日，香港家事法庭駁回F對司法管轄權的異議及他擱置香港法律程序的申請。2013年10月，F針對思明區人民法院的判決而提出的上訴被駁回。2013年11月，F在廣州天河區展開另一次法律程序，再次要求法院判給他G的管養權及命令M支付G的贍養費。2014年3月，天河區人民法院將G的管養權判給M，命令F支付贍養費。廣州市中級人民法院駁回F針對該判決的上訴，但更改判決，包括撤銷判給M管養權的命令。F現針對家事法庭5月27日的判決提出上訴。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &ndash;上訴得直：</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		《條例》沒有明文規定子女是否必須在法律程序展開時慣常住在香港或身在香港，法庭的司法管轄權才能被援引，但雖然《條例》不作限制，法庭理應基於其具有司法管轄權而準備處理案件。不過無需要為了這宗上訴案而一錘定音，因為香港法庭對兒童亦具有可在香港領土範圍以外地區行使的固有司法管轄權。</li>\n	<li>\n		不論是1997年7月1日中國恢復行使主權之前還是之後，香港法庭都對兒童具有固有司法管轄權。司法管轄權的概念原本以國籍為基礎，要將這概念變為以香港永久性居民身分為基礎，殊不容易。不論原本的基礎為何，就涉及兒童的案件而言，這固有司法管轄權在香港是那麽的根深蒂固，在合適的情況中，即案件涉及香港永久性居民子女時，法庭都會介入，發揮其保護兒童的傳統作用，即使涉案子女在申請提出之時並非身在香港亦然，而任何人都應基於此而進行訴訟。難以想像這種對兒童的固有司法管轄權會純粹因為1997年香港回歸中國而突然消失。任何相反意見都會使家事法的實踐和施行出現極大漏洞。</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:276:\"根據《未成年人監護條例》進行的法律程序 — 子女不是慣常住在香港或不是身在香港，家事法庭有沒有司法管轄權 — 對兒童的固有司法管轄權，1997年之前以國籍為基礎，1997年之後是否以永久性居留地為基礎\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3624:\"<p>根據《未成年人監護條例》進行的法律程序 — 子女不是慣常住在香港或不是身在香港，家事法庭有沒有司法管轄權 — 對兒童的固有司法管轄權，1997年之前以國籍為基礎，1997年之後是否以永久性居留地為基礎\n</p><p>\n	QMY v GSS</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744c097000001519fcf82a11aae0195&amp;docguid=IE24A6BCA719B4AACAF8DF3EB9D469AC7&amp;hitguid=IE24A6BCA719B4AACAF8DF3EB9D469AC7&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=21\">[2015] 4 HKLRD 641<br /></a>上訴法庭<br />\n	民事上訴案件2014年第68號<br />\n	林文瀚副庭長，上訴法庭法官張澤祐及上訴法庭法官袁家寧<br />\n	2015年8月19日</p>\n<p>\n	M和F是G的父母，二人從來沒有結婚。M是中國內地居民，F是香港永久性居民。G是在香港出生的香港永久性居民。G出生後不久，M和G搬到內地居住。M和G現時住在廣州，之前住過思明區、廈門、福建。2012年7月，M在香港根據《未成年人監護條例》(第13章)(「《條例》」)第10條提出申請，要求法庭命令F支付G的贍養費(「香港法律程序」)。F於之後一個月內，在內地思明區展開法律程序，要求法院判給他G的管養權及命令M付給他G的贍養費。2012年9月，F申請擱置香港法律程序，理由是香港法庭並非便利公堂(<em>forum non conveniens</em>)，內地法院才是。2013年1月，思明區人民法院駁回F的申索。之後，F申請撤銷香港法律程序，理由是G不是通常或慣常住在香港，也不是身在香港，香港法庭因而沒有司法管轄權處理M的申請。2013年5月27日，香港家事法庭駁回F對司法管轄權的異議及他擱置香港法律程序的申請。2013年10月，F針對思明區人民法院的判決而提出的上訴被駁回。2013年11月，F在廣州天河區展開另一次法律程序，再次要求法院判給他G的管養權及命令M支付G的贍養費。2014年3月，天河區人民法院將G的管養權判給M，命令F支付贍養費。廣州市中級人民法院駁回F針對該判決的上訴，但更改判決，包括撤銷判給M管養權的命令。F現針對家事法庭5月27日的判決提出上訴。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> –上訴得直：</p>\n<ul><li>\n		《條例》沒有明文規定子女是否必須在法律程序展開時慣常住在香港或身在香港，法庭的司法管轄權才能被援引，但雖然《條例》不作限制，法庭理應基於其具有司法管轄權而準備處理案件。不過無需要為了這宗上訴案而一錘定音，因為香港法庭對兒童亦具有可在香港領土範圍以外地區行使的固有司法管轄權。</li>\n<li>\n		不論是1997年7月1日中國恢復行使主權之前還是之後，香港法庭都對兒童具有固有司法管轄權。司法管轄權的概念原本以國籍為基礎，要將這概念變為以香港永久性居民身分為基礎，殊不容易。不論原本的基礎為何，就涉及兒童的案件而言，這固有司法管轄權在香港是那麽的根深蒂固，在合適的情況中，即案件涉及香港永久性居民子女時，法庭都會介入，發揮其保護兒童的傳統作用，即使涉案子女在申請提出之時並非身在香港亦然，而任何人都應基於此而進行訴訟。難以想像這種對兒童的固有司法管轄權會純粹因為1997年香港回歸中國而突然消失。任何相反意見都會使家事法的實踐和施行出現極大漏洞。</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:284:\"<p>根據《未成年人監護條例》進行的法律程序 — 子女不是慣常住在香港或不是身在香港，家事法庭有沒有司法管轄權 — 對兒童的固有司法管轄權，1997年之前以國籍為基礎，1997年之後是否以永久性居留地為基礎</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"上訴法庭\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"上訴法庭\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:9:\"QMY v GSS\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:9:\"QMY v GSS\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"568\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"638\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744c097000001519fcf82a11aae0195&docguid=IE24A6BCA719B4AACAF8DF3EB9D469AC7&hitguid=IE24A6BCA719B4AACAF8DF3EB9D469AC7&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=21\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"[2015] 4 HKLRD 641\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"2015年8月19日\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"2015年8月19日\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:9:\"家庭法\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:9:\"家庭法\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:9:\"QMY v GSS\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183919,1),('9317','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9321\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:42:\"VPOWER Engineering (Shenzhen) Ltd v VPOWER\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9317\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9317\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:4344:\"Intellectual Property – Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy for .hk and .香港domain names (DNDRP) – domain name registered prior to Claimant acquiring interest in the trade mark in Hong Kong – bare assertions of bad faith against Respondent’s actions<p>\n	VPOWER Engineering (Shenzhen) Ltd v VPOWER<br />\n	<br />\n	<a href=\"http://www.hkiac.org/images/stories/domain_name/hk/decision/DHK-1500124_Decision.pdf\">DHK-1500124</a> &quot;vpower.hk&quot; <br />\n	Hong Kong International Arbitration Centre<br />\n	Eugene Low (Panelist)<br />\n	28 August 2015</p>\n<p>\n	Complainant, (hereinafter &ldquo;C&rdquo;) a group carrying on the business as a power provider in Greater China and Southern Asia, submitted a Complaint concerning the Disputed Domain Name &ldquo;vpower.hk&rdquo; registered by Respondent (hereinafter &ldquo;R&rdquo;), pursuant to the Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy for .hk and .香港 domain names (&ldquo;DNDRP&rdquo;). C contended that R registered and was using the Disputed Domain Name with intent to confuse users.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the Complaint, that, <em>inter alia</em>:</p>\n<p>\n	Under para. 4a of DNDRP, C has the burden of providing that &ldquo;the Disputed Domain Name is identical or confusingly similar to a trade mark or service mark <em>in Hong Kong</em> in which the Complainant has right&rdquo; (<em>emphasis added</em>).</p>\n<p>\n	C satisfied this limb by identifying a Hong Kong trade mark registration for a composite mark containing the mark &ldquo;VPOWER&rdquo; in question.</p>\n<p>\n	However, in respect of a number of other trade marks and domain names apparently held in the names of C&rsquo;s affiliated companies, C failed to explain how those trade mark registrations and domain names would amount to or be relevant to <em>&ldquo;a trade mark or service mark in Hong Kong in which the Complainant has rights&rdquo;</em>. In particular, ownership of a domain name incorporating the trade mark in question <em>per se</em> does not prove or constitute the requisite rights to that trade mark in Hong Kong.</p>\n<p>\n	The Panel was unable to conclude that R had rights or legitimate interests in the Disputed Domain Name. There was inconclusive evidence as to R&rsquo;s business status. C made out a <em>prima facie</em> case and R failed to submit evidence on whether &ldquo;VPOWER&rdquo; is R&rsquo;s trade name or trade mark or whether R has been commonly known by the Disputed Domain Name.</p>\n<p>\n	C failed to prove registration and use of the Disputed Domain Name in bad faith because:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		None of C&rsquo;s cited trade mark applications and registrations preceded the date of registration of the Disputed Domain Name.</li>\n	<li>\n		The Panel concluded this was a case where the Disputed Domain Name was registered before C had acquired rights to a trade mark or service mark in Hong Kong. While this conclusion by itself does not preclude a finding of bad faith, in such circumstances it would generally require stronger evidence to prove that the domain name was registered in bad faith (eg, see &ldquo;WIPO Overview 2.0&rdquo;) because normally R could not have contemplated C&rsquo;s then non-existent rights. To overcome this, C would have to adduce clear evidence to show that at the time of registration of the Disputed Domain Name, R was somehow aware of C and such rights to a trade mark or service mark that C is going to acquire.</li>\n	<li>\n		C did not adduce evidence of any unregistered rights in C&rsquo;s trade mark in Hong Kong prior to registration of the Disputed Domain Name.</li>\n	<li>\n		C did not adduce evidence that R was aware of C and its relevant trade mark rights in Hong Kong when the Disputed Domain Name was registered.</li>\n	<li>\n		C also failed to prove that R was using the Disputed Domain Name in bad faith. C only made bare assertions that R&rsquo;s use of the Disputed Domain Name would create a likelihood of confusion.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Since C failed to prove all the required elements under para. 4(a) of the DNDRP, the Complaint was dismissed.</p>\n<hr />\n<p>\n	The full decision can be downloaded in the website of ADNDRC at <a href=\"http://www.hkiac.org/images/stories/domain_name/hk/decision/DHK-1500124_Decision.pdf\">http://www.hkiac.org/images/stories/domain_name/hk/decision/DHK-1500124_Decision.pdf</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:262:\"Intellectual Property – Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy for .hk and .香港domain names (DNDRP) – domain name registered prior to Claimant acquiring interest in the trade mark in Hong Kong – bare assertions of bad faith against Respondent’s actions\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:4227:\"<p>Intellectual Property – Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy for .hk and .香港domain names (DNDRP) – domain name registered prior to Claimant acquiring interest in the trade mark in Hong Kong – bare assertions of bad faith against Respondent’s actions\n</p><p>\n	VPOWER Engineering (Shenzhen) Ltd v VPOWER</p>\n<p>	<a href=\"http://www.hkiac.org/images/stories/domain_name/hk/decision/DHK-1500124_Decision.pdf\">DHK-1500124</a> \"vpower.hk\" <br />\n	Hong Kong International Arbitration Centre<br />\n	Eugene Low (Panelist)<br />\n	28 August 2015</p>\n<p>\n	Complainant, (hereinafter “C”) a group carrying on the business as a power provider in Greater China and Southern Asia, submitted a Complaint concerning the Disputed Domain Name “vpower.hk” registered by Respondent (hereinafter “R”), pursuant to the Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy for .hk and .香港 domain names (“DNDRP”). C contended that R registered and was using the Disputed Domain Name with intent to confuse users.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the Complaint, that, <em>inter alia</em>:</p>\n<p>\n	Under para. 4a of DNDRP, C has the burden of providing that “the Disputed Domain Name is identical or confusingly similar to a trade mark or service mark <em>in Hong Kong</em> in which the Complainant has right” (<em>emphasis added</em>).</p>\n<p>\n	C satisfied this limb by identifying a Hong Kong trade mark registration for a composite mark containing the mark “VPOWER” in question.</p>\n<p>\n	However, in respect of a number of other trade marks and domain names apparently held in the names of C’s affiliated companies, C failed to explain how those trade mark registrations and domain names would amount to or be relevant to <em>“a trade mark or service mark in Hong Kong in which the Complainant has rights”</em>. In particular, ownership of a domain name incorporating the trade mark in question <em>per se</em> does not prove or constitute the requisite rights to that trade mark in Hong Kong.</p>\n<p>\n	The Panel was unable to conclude that R had rights or legitimate interests in the Disputed Domain Name. There was inconclusive evidence as to R’s business status. C made out a <em>prima facie</em> case and R failed to submit evidence on whether “VPOWER” is R’s trade name or trade mark or whether R has been commonly known by the Disputed Domain Name.</p>\n<p>\n	C failed to prove registration and use of the Disputed Domain Name in bad faith because:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		None of C’s cited trade mark applications and registrations preceded the date of registration of the Disputed Domain Name.</li>\n<li>\n		The Panel concluded this was a case where the Disputed Domain Name was registered before C had acquired rights to a trade mark or service mark in Hong Kong. While this conclusion by itself does not preclude a finding of bad faith, in such circumstances it would generally require stronger evidence to prove that the domain name was registered in bad faith (eg, see “WIPO Overview 2.0”) because normally R could not have contemplated C’s then non-existent rights. To overcome this, C would have to adduce clear evidence to show that at the time of registration of the Disputed Domain Name, R was somehow aware of C and such rights to a trade mark or service mark that C is going to acquire.</li>\n<li>\n		C did not adduce evidence of any unregistered rights in C’s trade mark in Hong Kong prior to registration of the Disputed Domain Name.</li>\n<li>\n		C did not adduce evidence that R was aware of C and its relevant trade mark rights in Hong Kong when the Disputed Domain Name was registered.</li>\n<li>\n		C also failed to prove that R was using the Disputed Domain Name in bad faith. C only made bare assertions that R’s use of the Disputed Domain Name would create a likelihood of confusion.</li>\n</ul><p>\n	Since C failed to prove all the required elements under para. 4(a) of the DNDRP, the Complaint was dismissed.</p>\n<hr /><p>\n	The full decision can be downloaded in the website of ADNDRC at <a href=\"http://www.hkiac.org/images/stories/domain_name/hk/decision/DHK-1500124_Decision.pdf\">http://www.hkiac.org/images/stories/domain_name/hk/decision/DHK-1500124_Decision.pdf</a>.</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:270:\"<p>Intellectual Property – Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy for .hk and .香港domain names (DNDRP) – domain name registered prior to Claimant acquiring interest in the trade mark in Hong Kong – bare assertions of bad faith against Respondent’s actions</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:42:\"Hong Kong International Arbitration Centre\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:42:\"Hong Kong International Arbitration Centre\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:42:\"VPOWER Engineering (Shenzhen) Ltd v VPOWER\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:42:\"VPOWER Engineering (Shenzhen) Ltd v VPOWER\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:84:\"http://www.hkiac.org/images/stories/domain_name/hk/decision/DHK-1500124_Decision.pdf\";s:5:\"title\";s:11:\"DHK-1500124\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:14:\"28 August 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:14:\"28 August 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"Dispute Resolution\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"Dispute Resolution\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:42:\"VPOWER Engineering (Shenzhen) Ltd v VPOWER\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458182632,1),('9318','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9322\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:42:\"VPOWER Engineering (Shenzhen) Ltd v VPOWER\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9318\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9317\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3486:\"知識產權 — 適用於.hk及.香港域名的域名爭議解決政策(「爭議解決政策」) — 在申請人於香港取得商標權益之前已經註冊的域名 — 單單堅稱被申請人有惡意地行事<p>\n	VPOWER Engineering (Shenzhen) Ltd v VPOWER<br />\n	<br />\n	<a href=\"http://www.hkiac.org/images/stories/domain_name/hk/decision/DHK-1500124_Decision.pdf\">DHK-1500124</a> &quot;vpower.hk&quot; <br />\n	香港國際仲裁中心<br />\n	Eugene Low(專家組成員)<br />\n	2015年8月28日</p>\n<p>\n	投訴人所屬集團在大中華及南亞地區經營供電業務。投訴人根據適用於.hk及.香港域名的域名爭議解決政策(「爭議解決政策」)提交投訴書，投訴內容與被投訴人已經註冊的爭議域名vpower.hk有關。投訴人聲稱被投訴人註冊及正使用爭議域名，目的是在使用者中造成混淆。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &ndash; 駁回投訴，裁決重點如下：</p>\n<p>\n	根據爭議解決政策第4a段，投訴人有責任證明「爭議域名和投訴人於香港具權利的商標或服務商標完全相同或容易造成混淆」。</p>\n<p>\n	投訴人找到一個已在香港註冊且包含爭議標記VPOWER的複合商標為證據，證明了這點。</p>\n<p>\n	不過，投訴人沒有解釋多個明顯以投訴人的聯繫公司名義持有的商標及域名怎樣與「投訴人於香港具權利的商標或服務商標相同或相關。特別一提，擁有包含爭議商標的域名在本質上並不證明或構成於香港具有所需的商標權。</p>\n<p>\n	專家組無法斷定被投訴人對於爭議域名具有使用權或享有合法權益。證明被投訴人業務狀況的論據不具決定性。投訴人想證實一項表面證據，而被投訴人則沒有提交證據證明VPOWER是否被投訴人的商品名稱或商標，或者被投訴人對爭議域名的使用是否已為大眾所知。</p>\n<p>\n	投訴人未能證明爭議域名已被惡意註冊及使用，因為：</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		投訴人列舉的商標，沒有一項是在爭議域名註冊日期之前申請及註冊的。</li>\n	<li>\n		專家組斷定，爭議域名在投訴人於香港取得商標或服務商標權之前已經註冊。這結論本身不排除被投訴人有惡意，而在這情況中，因為被投訴人在正常情況下不可能預見投訴人其時不存在的權利，專家組通常要求更有力的證據來證明域名被惡意註冊(參見WIPO Overview 2.0 )。投訴人要解決這點，就必須清楚證明被投訴人在爭議域名註冊之時，不管怎麽樣，總之就是對投訴人及投訴人將要得到的商標或服務商標權有認識。</li>\n	<li>\n		投訴人沒有用投訴人任何在爭議域名註冊之前未有於香港註冊的商標權作為證據。</li>\n	<li>\n		投訴人沒有提出證據證明，被投訴人在註冊爭議域名之時，已對投訴人及投訴人相關的香港商標權有認識。</li>\n	<li>\n		投訴人未能證明被投訴人惡意使用爭議域名。投訴人單單堅稱被投訴人使用爭議域名有可能引起混淆。</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	由於投訴人未能證明爭議解決政策第4(a)段列明的所有行為，投訴被駁回。</p>\n<hr />\n<p>\n	裁決全文在亞洲域名爭議解決中心的網頁可供下載：<a href=\"http://www.hkiac.org/images/stories/domain_name/hk/decision/DHK-1500124_Decision.pdf\">http://www.hkiac.org/images/stories/domain_name/hk/decision/DHK-1500124_Decision.pdf</a>。</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:216:\"知識產權 — 適用於.hk及.香港域名的域名爭議解決政策(「爭議解決政策」) — 在申請人於香港取得商標權益之前已經註冊的域名 — 單單堅稱被申請人有惡意地行事\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3465:\"<p>知識產權 — 適用於.hk及.香港域名的域名爭議解決政策(「爭議解決政策」) — 在申請人於香港取得商標權益之前已經註冊的域名 — 單單堅稱被申請人有惡意地行事\n</p><p>\n	VPOWER Engineering (Shenzhen) Ltd v VPOWER</p>\n<p>	<a href=\"http://www.hkiac.org/images/stories/domain_name/hk/decision/DHK-1500124_Decision.pdf\">DHK-1500124</a> \"vpower.hk\" <br />\n	香港國際仲裁中心<br />\n	Eugene Low(專家組成員)<br />\n	2015年8月28日</p>\n<p>\n	投訴人所屬集團在大中華及南亞地區經營供電業務。投訴人根據適用於.hk及.香港域名的域名爭議解決政策(「爭議解決政策」)提交投訴書，投訴內容與被投訴人已經註冊的爭議域名vpower.hk有關。投訴人聲稱被投訴人註冊及正使用爭議域名，目的是在使用者中造成混淆。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> – 駁回投訴，裁決重點如下：</p>\n<p>\n	根據爭議解決政策第4a段，投訴人有責任證明「爭議域名和投訴人於香港具權利的商標或服務商標完全相同或容易造成混淆」。</p>\n<p>\n	投訴人找到一個已在香港註冊且包含爭議標記VPOWER的複合商標為證據，證明了這點。</p>\n<p>\n	不過，投訴人沒有解釋多個明顯以投訴人的聯繫公司名義持有的商標及域名怎樣與「投訴人於香港具權利的商標或服務商標相同或相關。特別一提，擁有包含爭議商標的域名在本質上並不證明或構成於香港具有所需的商標權。</p>\n<p>\n	專家組無法斷定被投訴人對於爭議域名具有使用權或享有合法權益。證明被投訴人業務狀況的論據不具決定性。投訴人想證實一項表面證據，而被投訴人則沒有提交證據證明VPOWER是否被投訴人的商品名稱或商標，或者被投訴人對爭議域名的使用是否已為大眾所知。</p>\n<p>\n	投訴人未能證明爭議域名已被惡意註冊及使用，因為：</p>\n<ul><li>\n		投訴人列舉的商標，沒有一項是在爭議域名註冊日期之前申請及註冊的。</li>\n<li>\n		專家組斷定，爭議域名在投訴人於香港取得商標或服務商標權之前已經註冊。這結論本身不排除被投訴人有惡意，而在這情況中，因為被投訴人在正常情況下不可能預見投訴人其時不存在的權利，專家組通常要求更有力的證據來證明域名被惡意註冊(參見WIPO Overview 2.0 )。投訴人要解決這點，就必須清楚證明被投訴人在爭議域名註冊之時，不管怎麽樣，總之就是對投訴人及投訴人將要得到的商標或服務商標權有認識。</li>\n<li>\n		投訴人沒有用投訴人任何在爭議域名註冊之前未有於香港註冊的商標權作為證據。</li>\n<li>\n		投訴人沒有提出證據證明，被投訴人在註冊爭議域名之時，已對投訴人及投訴人相關的香港商標權有認識。</li>\n<li>\n		投訴人未能證明被投訴人惡意使用爭議域名。投訴人單單堅稱被投訴人使用爭議域名有可能引起混淆。</li>\n</ul><p>\n	由於投訴人未能證明爭議解決政策第4(a)段列明的所有行為，投訴被駁回。</p>\n<hr /><p>\n	裁決全文在亞洲域名爭議解決中心的網頁可供下載：<a href=\"http://www.hkiac.org/images/stories/domain_name/hk/decision/DHK-1500124_Decision.pdf\">http://www.hkiac.org/images/stories/domain_name/hk/decision/DHK-1500124_Decision.pdf</a>。</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:224:\"<p>知識產權 — 適用於.hk及.香港域名的域名爭議解決政策(「爭議解決政策」) — 在申請人於香港取得商標權益之前已經註冊的域名 — 單單堅稱被申請人有惡意地行事</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:24:\"香港國際仲裁中心\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:24:\"香港國際仲裁中心\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:42:\"VPOWER Engineering (Shenzhen) Ltd v VPOWER\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:42:\"VPOWER Engineering (Shenzhen) Ltd v VPOWER\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"565\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2015-12-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:84:\"http://www.hkiac.org/images/stories/domain_name/hk/decision/DHK-1500124_Decision.pdf\";s:5:\"title\";s:11:\"DHK-1500124\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"2015年8月28日\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"2015年8月28日\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"解決糾紛\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"解決糾紛\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:42:\"VPOWER Engineering (Shenzhen) Ltd v VPOWER\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1449446400\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183919,1),('9319','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9323\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:75:\"Bar Council of Hong Kong Bar Association v Barristers Disciplinary Tribunal\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9319\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456675196\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9319\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2381:\"<p><em>Judicial review – withdrawal of application by consent – importance of complying with Practice Direction SL3 and need to consider public interest in light of subject matter of review</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Bar Council was granted leave to judicially review the decision of a Barristers Disciplinary Tribunal dismissing a complaint of D, a defendant in a criminal trial, against his barrister (“B”). D’s conviction was quashed on appeal and he accused B of flagrant incompetence in failing to call a witness without consulting first D (see <a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e00000151f204e4f13f7cfd97&amp;docguid=IED2C1C0C421E44AF944921A4E63CFAD3&amp;hitguid=IED2C1C0C421E44AF944921A4E63CFAD3&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] 2HKLRD 150</a>). The parties now sought an order by consent that the judicial review be withdrawn with no order as to costs. The Judge directed the parties to comply with para. 23(1) of Practice Direction SL3 (the “PD”). This requires the solicitors involved to file <em>inter alia</em> a short statement setting out the matters relied on as justifying the consent order sought and citing any relevant authorities and statutory provisions. Short statements were submitted stating that the Bar Council had accepted B’s representations that he had been vindicated by the Court of Appeal which held that the decision of another barrister, who was involved in the same case as B, not to call a witness was correct in law, so that it could not be said that B’s decision was negligent or had caused injustice to D.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, granting the order sought, that the Court was not a rubber stamp. It was for the Court, in the exercise of its discretionary jurisdiction, to satisfy itself that the order sought could be made on the case established, even though it was effectively unopposed. Hence, a short statement should provide sufficient reasons and circumstances that would justify and legitimise the order. The short statement served to ensure that the disposal order was just and appropriate taking into account the parties’ interests and any wider public interest which might be relevant to the case, where the subject matter of the review involved the professional conduct of a barrister in a criminal trial.</p>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:195:\"<p>Judicial review – withdrawal of application by consent – importance of complying with Practice Direction SL3 and need to consider public interest in light of subject matter of review</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2374:\"<p><em>Judicial review – withdrawal of application by consent – importance of complying with Practice Direction SL3 and need to consider public interest in light of subject matter of review</em></p>\n<p>The Bar Council was granted leave to judicially review the decision of a Barristers Disciplinary Tribunal dismissing a complaint of D, a defendant in a criminal trial, against his barrister (“B”). D’s conviction was quashed on appeal and he accused B of flagrant incompetence in failing to call a witness without consulting first D (see <a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e00000151f204e4f13f7cfd97&amp;docguid=IED2C1C0C421E44AF944921A4E63CFAD3&amp;hitguid=IED2C1C0C421E44AF944921A4E63CFAD3&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] 2HKLRD 150</a>). The parties now sought an order by consent that the judicial review be withdrawn with no order as to costs. The Judge directed the parties to comply with para. 23(1) of Practice Direction SL3 (the “PD”). This requires the solicitors involved to file <em>inter alia</em> a short statement setting out the matters relied on as justifying the consent order sought and citing any relevant authorities and statutory provisions. Short statements were submitted stating that the Bar Council had accepted B’s representations that he had been vindicated by the Court of Appeal which held that the decision of another barrister, who was involved in the same case as B, not to call a witness was correct in law, so that it could not be said that B’s decision was negligent or had caused injustice to D.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, granting the order sought, that the Court was not a rubber stamp. It was for the Court, in the exercise of its discretionary jurisdiction, to satisfy itself that the order sought could be made on the case established, even though it was effectively unopposed. Hence, a short statement should provide sufficient reasons and circumstances that would justify and legitimise the order. The short statement served to ensure that the disposal order was just and appropriate taking into account the parties’ interests and any wider public interest which might be relevant to the case, where the subject matter of the review involved the professional conduct of a barrister in a criminal trial.</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:194:\"<p>Judicial review – withdrawal of application by consent – importance of complying with Practice Direction SL3 and need to consider public interest in light of subject matter of review</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:75:\"Bar Council of Hong Kong Bar Association v Barristers Disciplinary Tribunal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:75:\"Bar Council of Hong Kong Bar Association v Barristers Disciplinary Tribunal\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:2:\"93\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:231:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744cc6400000151ebcb69bc5739fac9&docguid=IDD932ED0289E4DBBAA9763397CED97A4&hitguid=IDD932ED0289E4DBBAA9763397CED97A4&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=4\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2163\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"16 October 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"16 October 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"Administrative Law\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"Administrative Law\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:75:\"Bar Council of Hong Kong Bar Association v Barristers Disciplinary Tribunal\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458115031,1),('9320','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9324\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:75:\"Bar Council of Hong Kong Bar Association v Barristers Disciplinary Tribunal\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9320\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9319\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2636:\"司法覆核 — 在與訟各方同意下撤回申請 — 遵守《實務指示SL3》的重要性，以及有需要因應涉案標的事項而考慮公眾利益<p>\n	Bar Council of Hong Kong Bar Association v Barristers Disciplinary Tribunal</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6400000151ebcb69bc5739fac9&amp;docguid=IDD932ED0289E4DBBAA9763397CED97A4&amp;hitguid=IDD932ED0289E4DBBAA9763397CED97A4&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] HKEC 2163</a><br />\n	原訟法庭<br />\n	高院憲法及行政訴訟2014年第159號<br />\n	原訟法庭法官薛偉成<br />\n	2015年10月16日</p>\n<p>\n	大律師公會理事會獲給予許可，針對大律師紀律審裁組的一項裁決提出司法覆核申請。該項裁決駁回一名刑案被告人(下稱D)針對其代表大律師(下稱B)的投訴。D的定罪經上訴後獲撤銷，而他指控B嚴重不稱職，理由為B未先諮詢他而不傳召一名證人出庭作供(詳見<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e00000151f204e4f13f7cfd97&amp;docguid=IED2C1C0C421E44AF944921A4E63CFAD3&amp;hitguid=IED2C1C0C421E44AF944921A4E63CFAD3&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] 2HKLRD 150</a>)。與訟各方現要求法庭頒下同意令，即撤回上述司法覆核申請及不作出訟費令。法官指示各方遵守《實務指示SL3》第23(1)段，其要求相關律師提交文件，包括一份簡短陳述書，述明根據何等理據要求法庭作出同意令，以及引述任何相關的案例典據及法例條文。各方遂提交簡短陳述書，述明大律師公會理事會已接納B的申述，即上訴法庭已證明他無辜，而上訴法庭曾裁定同一刑案中另一名大律師作出不傳召一名證人出庭作供的決定在法律上正確，因此B的決定不能說是疏忽或曾令D蒙受不公。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &mdash; 頒下同意令﹕</p>\n<p>\n	法庭並不是「橡皮圖章」，而是要行使司法酌情權，信納自己可在已確立的案情下頒發各方所尋求的命令，即使與訟各方實際上沒有反對作出該命令，情況亦然。因此，簡短陳述書應提述充分理由和情況，以支持法庭作出該命令和使之合法。簡短陳述書有助確保以下一點﹕當司法覆核所針對的標的事項涉及一名大律師在刑案審訊中的專業行為時，法庭在顧及各方權益和可能與案有關的更廣泛公眾利益後，作出公正和恰當的命令以處置案件。</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:160:\"司法覆核 — 在與訟各方同意下撤回申請 — 遵守《實務指示SL3》的重要性，以及有需要因應涉案標的事項而考慮公眾利益\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2640:\"<p>司法覆核 — 在與訟各方同意下撤回申請 — 遵守《實務指示SL3》的重要性，以及有需要因應涉案標的事項而考慮公眾利益\n</p><p>\n	Bar Council of Hong Kong Bar Association v Barristers Disciplinary Tribunal</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6400000151ebcb69bc5739fac9&amp;docguid=IDD932ED0289E4DBBAA9763397CED97A4&amp;hitguid=IDD932ED0289E4DBBAA9763397CED97A4&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] HKEC 2163</a><br />\n	原訟法庭<br />\n	高院憲法及行政訴訟2014年第159號<br />\n	原訟法庭法官薛偉成<br />\n	2015年10月16日</p>\n<p>\n	大律師公會理事會獲給予許可，針對大律師紀律審裁組的一項裁決提出司法覆核申請。該項裁決駁回一名刑案被告人(下稱D)針對其代表大律師(下稱B)的投訴。D的定罪經上訴後獲撤銷，而他指控B嚴重不稱職，理由為B未先諮詢他而不傳召一名證人出庭作供(詳見<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e00000151f204e4f13f7cfd97&amp;docguid=IED2C1C0C421E44AF944921A4E63CFAD3&amp;hitguid=IED2C1C0C421E44AF944921A4E63CFAD3&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] 2HKLRD 150</a>)。與訟各方現要求法庭頒下同意令，即撤回上述司法覆核申請及不作出訟費令。法官指示各方遵守《實務指示SL3》第23(1)段，其要求相關律師提交文件，包括一份簡短陳述書，述明根據何等理據要求法庭作出同意令，以及引述任何相關的案例典據及法例條文。各方遂提交簡短陳述書，述明大律師公會理事會已接納B的申述，即上訴法庭已證明他無辜，而上訴法庭曾裁定同一刑案中另一名大律師作出不傳召一名證人出庭作供的決定在法律上正確，因此B的決定不能說是疏忽或曾令D蒙受不公。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> — 頒下同意令﹕</p>\n<p>\n	法庭並不是「橡皮圖章」，而是要行使司法酌情權，信納自己可在已確立的案情下頒發各方所尋求的命令，即使與訟各方實際上沒有反對作出該命令，情況亦然。因此，簡短陳述書應提述充分理由和情況，以支持法庭作出該命令和使之合法。簡短陳述書有助確保以下一點﹕當司法覆核所針對的標的事項涉及一名大律師在刑案審訊中的專業行為時，法庭在顧及各方權益和可能與案有關的更廣泛公眾利益後，作出公正和恰當的命令以處置案件。</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:168:\"<p>司法覆核 — 在與訟各方同意下撤回申請 — 遵守《實務指示SL3》的重要性，以及有需要因應涉案標的事項而考慮公眾利益</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"原訟法庭\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"原訟法庭\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:75:\"Bar Council of Hong Kong Bar Association v Barristers Disciplinary Tribunal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:75:\"Bar Council of Hong Kong Bar Association v Barristers Disciplinary Tribunal\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"555\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"638\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:231:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744cc6400000151ebcb69bc5739fac9&docguid=IDD932ED0289E4DBBAA9763397CED97A4&hitguid=IDD932ED0289E4DBBAA9763397CED97A4&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=4\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2163\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:17:\"2015年10月16日\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:17:\"2015年10月16日\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:9:\"行政法\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:9:\"行政法\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:75:\"Bar Council of Hong Kong Bar Association v Barristers Disciplinary Tribunal\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183919,1),('9321','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9325\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:23:\"Lai Yi v Tsui Kin Chung\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9321\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456675261\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9321\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:1346:\"<p><em>Parties – anonymity – causing of embarrassment or inconvenience or emotional disturbance to party, even though with medical condition, was insufficient for granting of anonymity order</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In proceedings before the Lands Tribunal, T sought an anonymity order, claiming he suffered from chronic depression and that the publication of a judgment would inevitably reveal his identity and affect his medical condition.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, in dismissing the application, that causing embarrassment or inconvenience or emotional disturbance to a party, even one with a medical condition, was an insufficient basis to grant an anonymity order, as these were the normal incidents of litigation. Whether the effect would be so severe as to endanger one’s life or seriously affect one’s health to the extent of justifying an anonymity order depended entirely on the seriousness of one’s medical condition. Here, T had failed to establish the need for an anonymity order. His claim that he was vulnerable and overreacted was unsupported by medical evidence. Further, whether his condition was being adequately managed by medication was also an important consideration, but evidence in this respect was lacking. The seriousness of T’s problem and the likely impact of publicity of the order on him was unknown.</p>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:196:\"<p>Parties – anonymity – causing of embarrassment or inconvenience or emotional disturbance to party, even though with medical condition, was insufficient for granting of anonymity order</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:1339:\"<p><em>Parties – anonymity – causing of embarrassment or inconvenience or emotional disturbance to party, even though with medical condition, was insufficient for granting of anonymity order</em></p>\n<p>In proceedings before the Lands Tribunal, T sought an anonymity order, claiming he suffered from chronic depression and that the publication of a judgment would inevitably reveal his identity and affect his medical condition.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, in dismissing the application, that causing embarrassment or inconvenience or emotional disturbance to a party, even one with a medical condition, was an insufficient basis to grant an anonymity order, as these were the normal incidents of litigation. Whether the effect would be so severe as to endanger one’s life or seriously affect one’s health to the extent of justifying an anonymity order depended entirely on the seriousness of one’s medical condition. Here, T had failed to establish the need for an anonymity order. His claim that he was vulnerable and overreacted was unsupported by medical evidence. Further, whether his condition was being adequately managed by medication was also an important consideration, but evidence in this respect was lacking. The seriousness of T’s problem and the likely impact of publicity of the order on him was unknown.</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:195:\"<p>Parties – anonymity – causing of embarrassment or inconvenience or emotional disturbance to party, even though with medical condition, was insufficient for granting of anonymity order</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:14:\"Lands Tribunal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:14:\"Lands Tribunal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Lai Yi v Tsui Kin Chung\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Lai Yi v Tsui Kin Chung\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"112\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:231:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744cc6300000151ebcbee8416329bb7&docguid=I01EBB1358DEE4E85B9A290F94C07F687&hitguid=I01EBB1358DEE4E85B9A290F94C07F687&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=7\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2064\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:14:\"5 October 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:14:\"5 October 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:23:\"Lai Yi v Tsui Kin Chung\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458115031,1),('9322','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9326\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:23:\"Lai Yi v Tsui Kin Chung\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9322\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9321\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:1870:\"與訟方 — 姓名保密 — 指披露姓名將令與訟方感到尷尬、蒙受不便或受到精神困擾，並不足以支持法庭頒予姓名保密令，即使與訟方健康狀況受影響，情況亦然<p>\n	Lai Yi v Tsui Kin Chung&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6300000151ebcbee8416329bb7&amp;docguid=I01EBB1358DEE4E85B9A290F94C07F687&amp;hitguid=I01EBB1358DEE4E85B9A290F94C07F687&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=7\">[2015] HKEC 2064</a><br />\n	土地審裁處<br />\n	條例第IV部收回管有申請2015年<br />\n	第1406號<br />\n	黃敬華法官內庭聆訊<br />\n	2015年10月5日</p>\n<p>\n	在土地審裁處席前進行的法律程序中，與訟其中一方(下稱T)向審裁處申請姓名保密令，聲稱自己患有長期抑鬱症，又指公布判決必會令自己的身份公諸於世，對自身健康狀況造成影響。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &mdash; 駁回申請﹕<br />\n	<br />\n	指披露姓名將令與訟方感到尷尬、蒙受不便或受到精神困擾，並不足以支持法庭頒予姓名保密令，即使與訟方健康狀況受影響，情況亦然。究其原因，披露與訟方姓名乃為附隨着訴訟的正常情況。披露姓名的後果會否嚴重至危及與訟方的性命或嚴重影響與訟方的健康、以致支持法庭頒予姓名保密令，須完全取決於與訟方健康狀況的嚴重程度。在本案中，T未能證明其有需要獲頒予姓名保密令。他指自己易受傷害和反應異常敏感，但這未獲醫學證據支持。此外，另一項重要考慮因素是他的健康狀況已否妥為受到藥物控制，但案中缺乏這方面的證據。法庭無從知悉T的問題何等嚴重或姓名保密令受公眾關注一事對他可能造成何等影響。</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:211:\"與訟方 — 姓名保密 — 指披露姓名將令與訟方感到尷尬、蒙受不便或受到精神困擾，並不足以支持法庭頒予姓名保密令，即使與訟方健康狀況受影響，情況亦然\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:1863:\"<p>與訟方 — 姓名保密 — 指披露姓名將令與訟方感到尷尬、蒙受不便或受到精神困擾，並不足以支持法庭頒予姓名保密令，即使與訟方健康狀況受影響，情況亦然\n</p><p>\n	Lai Yi v Tsui Kin Chung </p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6300000151ebcbee8416329bb7&amp;docguid=I01EBB1358DEE4E85B9A290F94C07F687&amp;hitguid=I01EBB1358DEE4E85B9A290F94C07F687&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=7\">[2015] HKEC 2064</a><br />\n	土地審裁處<br />\n	條例第IV部收回管有申請2015年<br />\n	第1406號<br />\n	黃敬華法官內庭聆訊<br />\n	2015年10月5日</p>\n<p>\n	在土地審裁處席前進行的法律程序中，與訟其中一方(下稱T)向審裁處申請姓名保密令，聲稱自己患有長期抑鬱症，又指公布判決必會令自己的身份公諸於世，對自身健康狀況造成影響。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> — 駁回申請﹕</p>\n<p>	指披露姓名將令與訟方感到尷尬、蒙受不便或受到精神困擾，並不足以支持法庭頒予姓名保密令，即使與訟方健康狀況受影響，情況亦然。究其原因，披露與訟方姓名乃為附隨着訴訟的正常情況。披露姓名的後果會否嚴重至危及與訟方的性命或嚴重影響與訟方的健康、以致支持法庭頒予姓名保密令，須完全取決於與訟方健康狀況的嚴重程度。在本案中，T未能證明其有需要獲頒予姓名保密令。他指自己易受傷害和反應異常敏感，但這未獲醫學證據支持。此外，另一項重要考慮因素是他的健康狀況已否妥為受到藥物控制，但案中缺乏這方面的證據。法庭無從知悉T的問題何等嚴重或姓名保密令受公眾關注一事對他可能造成何等影響。</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:219:\"<p>與訟方 — 姓名保密 — 指披露姓名將令與訟方感到尷尬、蒙受不便或受到精神困擾，並不足以支持法庭頒予姓名保密令，即使與訟方健康狀況受影響，情況亦然</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"土地審裁處\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"土地審裁處\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Lai Yi v Tsui Kin Chung\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Lai Yi v Tsui Kin Chung\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"574\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"638\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:231:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744cc6300000151ebcbee8416329bb7&docguid=I01EBB1358DEE4E85B9A290F94C07F687&hitguid=I01EBB1358DEE4E85B9A290F94C07F687&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=7\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2064\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"2015年10月5日\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"2015年10月5日\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"民事訴訟程序\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"民事訴訟程序\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:23:\"Lai Yi v Tsui Kin Chung\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183919,1),('9323','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9327\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:45:\"Re First China Financial Network Holdings Ltd\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9323\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456675326\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9323\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2833:\"<p><em>Directors – listed company – disqualification – three directors made false claim so that company assets wrongly paid to company owned by one of directors – appropriate length of disqualification</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In proceedings brought by the Securities and Futures Commission (the “SFC”), D1–3 were found liable for having wronged C, a company, by dishonestly presenting a non-existent Mutual Understanding and Agreement (“MUA”), resulting in assets of C worth RMB18,692,000 (the “Sum”) being wrongly paid to a company owned by D3 (see <a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc64000001520b6f3018573c2ec0&amp;docguid=IE012E0E855934FA0AEB797E758D8EFAA&amp;hitguid=IE012E0E855934FA0AEB797E758D8EFAA&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] HKEC 86</a>). The Judge found that Ds had acted in breach of trust. D3 was the instigator; D2 yielded to D3’s pressure without carefully considering C’s interest, while D1 was the least culpable because he did try to resist pressure from D3 and find a legitimate way of returning the windfall to him. The SFC now sought disqualification orders under s. 214(2)(d) of the Securities and Futures Ordinance (Cap. 571) (the “SFO”).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, ruling that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Disqualification was not mandatory but entirely within the discretion of the court. There was no statutory minimum period of disqualification in Hong Kong under s.214(2)(d) of the Securities and Futures Ordinance (Cap.571). It was therefore more appropriate to define the minimum bracket as “below 5 years” instead of “2 to 5 years”.</li>\r\n	<li>Ds’ conduct merited a starting point for disqualification in the middle bracket of 6 to 10 years. As regards mitigation, D3 had repaid the Sum to C. Neither D1 nor D2 had derived any financial benefit from the dishonest enterprise. All of Ds had acted out of character. However, no credit would be given for D2–3’s very late expression of remorse; or D1’s attempt to resolve the petition by way of the<em> Carecraft </em>procedure because he denied his conduct was dishonest.</li>\r\n	<li>There was no real risk of similar misconduct by Ds should they become directors again. Erring on the side of leniency in favour of Ds, the disqualification periods for D3, D2 and D1 should be 7 years, 5 years and 4 years respectively. No exception would be made for D3 to enable him to work as a manager in a mainland company which held shares in a Hong Kong company during this time.</li>\r\n	<li><em>(Obiter)</em> The delay in the hearing of over 8 months after the handing down of the judgment allowed D2–3 to continue to manage C in the meantime. This kind of delay was unacceptable and hopefully, would not be repeated.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:211:\"<p>Directors – listed company – disqualification – three directors made false claim so that company assets wrongly paid to company owned by one of directors – appropriate length of disqualification</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2812:\"<p><em>Directors – listed company – disqualification – three directors made false claim so that company assets wrongly paid to company owned by one of directors – appropriate length of disqualification</em></p>\n<p>In proceedings brought by the Securities and Futures Commission (the “SFC”), D1–3 were found liable for having wronged C, a company, by dishonestly presenting a non-existent Mutual Understanding and Agreement (“MUA”), resulting in assets of C worth RMB18,692,000 (the “Sum”) being wrongly paid to a company owned by D3 (see <a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc64000001520b6f3018573c2ec0&amp;docguid=IE012E0E855934FA0AEB797E758D8EFAA&amp;hitguid=IE012E0E855934FA0AEB797E758D8EFAA&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] HKEC 86</a>). The Judge found that Ds had acted in breach of trust. D3 was the instigator; D2 yielded to D3’s pressure without carefully considering C’s interest, while D1 was the least culpable because he did try to resist pressure from D3 and find a legitimate way of returning the windfall to him. The SFC now sought disqualification orders under s. 214(2)(d) of the Securities and Futures Ordinance (Cap. 571) (the “SFO”).</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, ruling that:</p>\n<ul><li>Disqualification was not mandatory but entirely within the discretion of the court. There was no statutory minimum period of disqualification in Hong Kong under s.214(2)(d) of the Securities and Futures Ordinance (Cap.571). It was therefore more appropriate to define the minimum bracket as “below 5 years” instead of “2 to 5 years”.</li>\n<li>Ds’ conduct merited a starting point for disqualification in the middle bracket of 6 to 10 years. As regards mitigation, D3 had repaid the Sum to C. Neither D1 nor D2 had derived any financial benefit from the dishonest enterprise. All of Ds had acted out of character. However, no credit would be given for D2–3’s very late expression of remorse; or D1’s attempt to resolve the petition by way of the<em> Carecraft </em>procedure because he denied his conduct was dishonest.</li>\n<li>There was no real risk of similar misconduct by Ds should they become directors again. Erring on the side of leniency in favour of Ds, the disqualification periods for D3, D2 and D1 should be 7 years, 5 years and 4 years respectively. No exception would be made for D3 to enable him to work as a manager in a mainland company which held shares in a Hong Kong company during this time.</li>\n<li><em>(Obiter)</em> The delay in the hearing of over 8 months after the handing down of the judgment allowed D2–3 to continue to manage C in the meantime. This kind of delay was unacceptable and hopefully, would not be repeated.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:210:\"<p>Directors – listed company – disqualification – three directors made false claim so that company assets wrongly paid to company owned by one of directors – appropriate length of disqualification</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:45:\"Re First China Financial Network Holdings Ltd\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:45:\"Re First China Financial Network Holdings Ltd\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:2:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"100\";}i:1;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad6290300000151ebcc512fabc7db83&docguid=ICFD1525D1B7943B9B4419235E2722D7B&hitguid=ICFD1525D1B7943B9B4419235E2722D7B&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=10\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2101\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:17:\"30 September 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:17:\"30 September 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:11:\"Company Law\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:11:\"Company Law\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:45:\"Re First China Financial Network Holdings Ltd\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458115031,1),('9324','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9328\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:45:\"Re First China Financial Network Holdings Ltd\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9324\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9323\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3406:\"董事 — 上市公司 — 取消資格 — 三名董事提出虛假的聲稱，以致公司資產被不當地支付給由其中一名董事擁有的公司 — 合適的取消資格期<p>\n	Re First China Financial Network Holdings Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad6290300000151ebcc512fabc7db83&amp;docguid=ICFD1525D1B7943B9B4419235E2722D7B&amp;hitguid=ICFD1525D1B7943B9B4419235E2722D7B&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=10\">[2015] HKEC 2101</a><br />\n	原訟法庭<br />\n	雜項案件2012年第2502號<br />\n	原訟法庭法官陳健強<br />\n	2015年9月30日</p>\n<p>\n	第一至第三被告人不誠實地提說一份不存在的共識協議，導致一間公司(「該公司」)價值人民幣18,692,000元的資產(「該筆款項」)被不當地支付給一間由第三被告人擁有的公司，證券及期貨事務監察委員會(「證監會」)就此提起法律程序，第一至第三被告人被裁定對該公司作出失當行為，須就此承擔法律責任(見<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc64000001520b6f3018573c2ec0&amp;docguid=IE012E0E855934FA0AEB797E758D8EFAA&amp;hitguid=IE012E0E855934FA0AEB797E758D8EFAA&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] HKEC 86</a>)。法官裁斷三名被告人的行為違反了作為受託人應負的責任。第三被告人是教唆者；第二被告人屈服於第三被告人施加的壓力，沒有仔細考慮該公司的利益，而第一被告人該負的責任最少，因為他確實有嘗試反抗第三被告人向他施加的壓力，並且尋找合法途徑將意外之財交還給他。證監會現根據《證券及期貨條例》(第571章)(「《條例》」)第214(2)(d)條，要求法庭作出取消資格令。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &ndash; 裁定：</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		法庭不是必須取消擔任董事的資格，而是完全有酌情決定權作出這處分。《條例》第214(2)(d)條沒有規定取消在香港資格的最短期間。因此較為合宜的做法是將年期最少的一級界定為「5年以下」，而不是「2至5年」。</li>\n	<li>\n		根據三名被告人的行為，他們被取消資格的年期應以6至10年這個中間級別為起點。至於年期的寬減，第三被告人已將該筆款項償還該公司。第一被告人和第二被告人都沒有從不誠實的行動中得到經濟得益。三名被告人的行為全是料想不到的。然而，第二和第三被告人很遲才表達悔意，法官無法相信他們；第一被告人嘗試循<em>Carecraft</em>程序解決呈請，但法官也不大相信他，因為他否認自己的行為不誠實。</li>\n	<li>\n		如果三名被告人再做董事，也不存在他們作出類似的不當行為的實在風險。法官對三名被告人處以較為寬宏的取消資格期：第三被告人、第二被告人及第一被告人的年期應分別為7年、5年及4年。第三被告人的情況不作特殊處理，他不能在取消資格期間於持有香港公司股份的內地公司擔任經理。</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>(附帶意見)</em>發下判案書後延誤超過8個月才進行聆訊，讓第二及第三被告人可在這段期間繼續管理該公司。這種延誤不可接受，但願以後不再發生。</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:185:\"董事 — 上市公司 — 取消資格 — 三名董事提出虛假的聲稱，以致公司資產被不當地支付給由其中一名董事擁有的公司 — 合適的取消資格期\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3404:\"<p>董事 — 上市公司 — 取消資格 — 三名董事提出虛假的聲稱，以致公司資產被不當地支付給由其中一名董事擁有的公司 — 合適的取消資格期\n</p><p>\n	Re First China Financial Network Holdings Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad6290300000151ebcc512fabc7db83&amp;docguid=ICFD1525D1B7943B9B4419235E2722D7B&amp;hitguid=ICFD1525D1B7943B9B4419235E2722D7B&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=10\">[2015] HKEC 2101</a><br />\n	原訟法庭<br />\n	雜項案件2012年第2502號<br />\n	原訟法庭法官陳健強<br />\n	2015年9月30日</p>\n<p>\n	第一至第三被告人不誠實地提說一份不存在的共識協議，導致一間公司(「該公司」)價值人民幣18,692,000元的資產(「該筆款項」)被不當地支付給一間由第三被告人擁有的公司，證券及期貨事務監察委員會(「證監會」)就此提起法律程序，第一至第三被告人被裁定對該公司作出失當行為，須就此承擔法律責任(見<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc64000001520b6f3018573c2ec0&amp;docguid=IE012E0E855934FA0AEB797E758D8EFAA&amp;hitguid=IE012E0E855934FA0AEB797E758D8EFAA&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=4\">[2015] HKEC 86</a>)。法官裁斷三名被告人的行為違反了作為受託人應負的責任。第三被告人是教唆者；第二被告人屈服於第三被告人施加的壓力，沒有仔細考慮該公司的利益，而第一被告人該負的責任最少，因為他確實有嘗試反抗第三被告人向他施加的壓力，並且尋找合法途徑將意外之財交還給他。證監會現根據《證券及期貨條例》(第571章)(「《條例》」)第214(2)(d)條，要求法庭作出取消資格令。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> – 裁定：</p>\n<ul><li>\n		法庭不是必須取消擔任董事的資格，而是完全有酌情決定權作出這處分。《條例》第214(2)(d)條沒有規定取消在香港資格的最短期間。因此較為合宜的做法是將年期最少的一級界定為「5年以下」，而不是「2至5年」。</li>\n<li>\n		根據三名被告人的行為，他們被取消資格的年期應以6至10年這個中間級別為起點。至於年期的寬減，第三被告人已將該筆款項償還該公司。第一被告人和第二被告人都沒有從不誠實的行動中得到經濟得益。三名被告人的行為全是料想不到的。然而，第二和第三被告人很遲才表達悔意，法官無法相信他們；第一被告人嘗試循<em>Carecraft</em>程序解決呈請，但法官也不大相信他，因為他否認自己的行為不誠實。</li>\n<li>\n		如果三名被告人再做董事，也不存在他們作出類似的不當行為的實在風險。法官對三名被告人處以較為寬宏的取消資格期：第三被告人、第二被告人及第一被告人的年期應分別為7年、5年及4年。第三被告人的情況不作特殊處理，他不能在取消資格期間於持有香港公司股份的內地公司擔任經理。</li>\n<li>\n		<em>(附帶意見)</em>發下判案書後延誤超過8個月才進行聆訊，讓第二及第三被告人可在這段期間繼續管理該公司。這種延誤不可接受，但願以後不再發生。</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:193:\"<p>董事 — 上市公司 — 取消資格 — 三名董事提出虛假的聲稱，以致公司資產被不當地支付給由其中一名董事擁有的公司 — 合適的取消資格期</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"原訟法庭\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"原訟法庭\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:45:\"Re First China Financial Network Holdings Ltd\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:45:\"Re First China Financial Network Holdings Ltd\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:2:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"562\";}i:1;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"565\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"638\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad6290300000151ebcc512fabc7db83&docguid=ICFD1525D1B7943B9B4419235E2722D7B&hitguid=ICFD1525D1B7943B9B4419235E2722D7B&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=10\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2101\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"2015年9月30日\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"2015年9月30日\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:9:\"公司法\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:9:\"公司法\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:45:\"Re First China Financial Network Holdings Ltd\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183919,1),('9325','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9329\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:23:\"HKSAR v Ip Wai Ho Micky\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9325\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456676117\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9325\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:1696:\"<p><em>Appeal – abandonment of appeal – whether to be treated as nullity – whether applicant knew meaning and effect of signing notice of abandonment</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>D was convicted of trafficking in dangerous drugs and applied for leave to appeal against both conviction and sentence. On 8 January 2009, D abandoned his application relating to sentence and it was dismissed. D’s application for leave to appeal against conviction was dismissed in September 2010. On 5 May 2015, D sought to treat his notice of abandonment as a nullity. He stated that <em>inter alia</em> his elderly mother was suffering from terminal cancer and he wished to be a filial son in her last days; and he had not known the significance or consequence of signing the notice of abandonment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>There was no credible evidence that D did not understand the nature or effect of the notice of abandonment when he signed it. His assertion that he was wrongly advised by counsel that he could seek a reduction of sentence after his application for leave to appeal against conviction was decided was belated and unsubstantiated. Had D really been so advised, it was improbable he would have waited 6 years to revive the application regarding sentence. Whatever his true reasons for signing the notice, it was clearly a deliberate and informed decision.</li>\r\n	<li>D had not shown with credible evidence why his abandonment should be treated as a nullity. As the jurisdiction of the Court was not revived, it was functus officio and would not entertain arguments on the merits of the abandoned appeal in respect of sentence.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:157:\"<p>Appeal – abandonment of appeal – whether to be treated as nullity – whether applicant knew meaning and effect of signing notice of abandonment</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:1679:\"<p><em>Appeal – abandonment of appeal – whether to be treated as nullity – whether applicant knew meaning and effect of signing notice of abandonment</em></p>\n<p>D was convicted of trafficking in dangerous drugs and applied for leave to appeal against both conviction and sentence. On 8 January 2009, D abandoned his application relating to sentence and it was dismissed. D’s application for leave to appeal against conviction was dismissed in September 2010. On 5 May 2015, D sought to treat his notice of abandonment as a nullity. He stated that <em>inter alia</em> his elderly mother was suffering from terminal cancer and he wished to be a filial son in her last days; and he had not known the significance or consequence of signing the notice of abandonment.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\n<ul><li>There was no credible evidence that D did not understand the nature or effect of the notice of abandonment when he signed it. His assertion that he was wrongly advised by counsel that he could seek a reduction of sentence after his application for leave to appeal against conviction was decided was belated and unsubstantiated. Had D really been so advised, it was improbable he would have waited 6 years to revive the application regarding sentence. Whatever his true reasons for signing the notice, it was clearly a deliberate and informed decision.</li>\n<li>D had not shown with credible evidence why his abandonment should be treated as a nullity. As the jurisdiction of the Court was not revived, it was functus officio and would not entertain arguments on the merits of the abandoned appeal in respect of sentence.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:156:\"<p>Appeal – abandonment of appeal – whether to be treated as nullity – whether applicant knew meaning and effect of signing notice of abandonment</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"HKSAR v Ip Wai Ho Micky\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"HKSAR v Ip Wai Ho Micky\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"101\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad6290300000151ebcd067f9133a950&docguid=IE1F129EE386F44C7B5CCAD249BD80348&hitguid=IE1F129EE386F44C7B5CCAD249BD80348&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=13\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2086\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:14:\"7 October 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:14:\"7 October 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"Criminal Procedure\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"Criminal Procedure\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:23:\"HKSAR v Ip Wai Ho Micky\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458115031,1),('9326','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9330\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:23:\"HKSAR v Ip Wai Ho Micky\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9326\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9325\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2037:\"上訴 — 放棄上訴 — 應否被視為無效 — 申請人是否知悉簽署放棄上訴通知書的涵義和後果<p>\n	HKSAR v Ip Wai Ho Micky</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad6290300000151ebcd067f9133a950&amp;docguid=IE1F129EE386F44C7B5CCAD249BD80348&amp;hitguid=IE1F129EE386F44C7B5CCAD249BD80348&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=13\">[2015] HKEC 2086</a><br />\n	上訴法庭<br />\n	上訴法庭刑事上訴案2008年第218號<br />\n	上訴法庭法官關淑馨及麥偉德<br />\n	2015年9月30日，10月7日</p>\n<p>\n	本案被告人經原審後被裁定「販運危險藥物」罪成立。他不服定罪和判刑，申請許可提出上訴。2009年1月8日，他放棄判刑方面的上訴，該上訴亦被駁回。2010年10月，他的定罪上訴許可申請被駁回。2015年5月5日，他提出申請，要求法庭把他的放棄上訴通知書視作無效，其中兩項理由為﹕(一)他的母親年事已高且患有末期癌症而他希望在她的餘生一盡孝子之責﹔及(二)他不知悉簽署放棄上訴通知書的意義和後果。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &mdash; 駁回申請﹕</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		案中缺乏可信的證據以證明被告人在簽署放棄上訴通知書時並不明白其性質和後果。他聲稱曾接獲大律師的錯誤意見，即他的定罪上訴許可申請獲法庭定奪後，他可尋求減刑。這項聲稱過遲提出，且缺乏理據支持。假如他確曾接獲上述意見，則他不大可能等侯六年後才恢復進行其判刑上訴申請。不論他簽署放棄上訴通知書的真正理由為何，他都是在知情下刻意決定簽署該通知書。</li>\n	<li>\n		被告人未能提出可信的證據，以解釋他放棄上訴的行為為何應被視為無效。由於本庭在本案中的司法管轄權未獲重新啟動，本庭在本案中的職份已完，不會聽取關於已放棄的判刑上訴是否有理可據的論據。</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:120:\"上訴 — 放棄上訴 — 應否被視為無效 — 申請人是否知悉簽署放棄上訴通知書的涵義和後果\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2037:\"<p>上訴 — 放棄上訴 — 應否被視為無效 — 申請人是否知悉簽署放棄上訴通知書的涵義和後果\n</p><p>\n	HKSAR v Ip Wai Ho Micky</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=i0ad6290300000151ebcd067f9133a950&amp;docguid=IE1F129EE386F44C7B5CCAD249BD80348&amp;hitguid=IE1F129EE386F44C7B5CCAD249BD80348&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=13\">[2015] HKEC 2086</a><br />\n	上訴法庭<br />\n	上訴法庭刑事上訴案2008年第218號<br />\n	上訴法庭法官關淑馨及麥偉德<br />\n	2015年9月30日，10月7日</p>\n<p>\n	本案被告人經原審後被裁定「販運危險藥物」罪成立。他不服定罪和判刑，申請許可提出上訴。2009年1月8日，他放棄判刑方面的上訴，該上訴亦被駁回。2010年10月，他的定罪上訴許可申請被駁回。2015年5月5日，他提出申請，要求法庭把他的放棄上訴通知書視作無效，其中兩項理由為﹕(一)他的母親年事已高且患有末期癌症而他希望在她的餘生一盡孝子之責﹔及(二)他不知悉簽署放棄上訴通知書的意義和後果。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> — 駁回申請﹕</p>\n<ul><li>\n		案中缺乏可信的證據以證明被告人在簽署放棄上訴通知書時並不明白其性質和後果。他聲稱曾接獲大律師的錯誤意見，即他的定罪上訴許可申請獲法庭定奪後，他可尋求減刑。這項聲稱過遲提出，且缺乏理據支持。假如他確曾接獲上述意見，則他不大可能等侯六年後才恢復進行其判刑上訴申請。不論他簽署放棄上訴通知書的真正理由為何，他都是在知情下刻意決定簽署該通知書。</li>\n<li>\n		被告人未能提出可信的證據，以解釋他放棄上訴的行為為何應被視為無效。由於本庭在本案中的司法管轄權未獲重新啟動，本庭在本案中的職份已完，不會聽取關於已放棄的判刑上訴是否有理可據的論據。</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:128:\"<p>上訴 — 放棄上訴 — 應否被視為無效 — 申請人是否知悉簽署放棄上訴通知書的涵義和後果</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"上訴法庭\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"上訴法庭\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"HKSAR v Ip Wai Ho Micky\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"HKSAR v Ip Wai Ho Micky\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"563\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"638\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=i0ad6290300000151ebcd067f9133a950&docguid=IE1F129EE386F44C7B5CCAD249BD80348&hitguid=IE1F129EE386F44C7B5CCAD249BD80348&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=13\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2086\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"2015年10月7日\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"2015年10月7日\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"刑事訴訟程序\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"刑事訴訟程序\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:23:\"HKSAR v Ip Wai Ho Micky\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183919,1),('9327','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9331\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:39:\"Cartier International AG v Peng Hai Kun\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9327\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456675226\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9327\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3482:\"<p><em>Intellectual Property – Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy – Record of ‘Way-back Machine’ proves use of domain name in bad faith – Attempts to attract internet traffic by riding on the Complainant’s reputation constitutes use of domain name in bad faith</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Complainant, (hereinafter “C”), holder of registered trademark of “Cartier” in many countries for its products in precious metals (including jewellery, clocks and watches), submitted a Complaint concerning the Disputed Domain Name “cartierr.com” registered by Respondent (hereinafter “R”), pursuant to the ICANN Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (“UDRP”).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C contended that R registered and used the Disputed Domain Name for the purpose of attracting Internet traffic to its website for commercial gain and to disrupt C’s businesses. Although the Disputed Domain Name did not resolve to any active website at the time C submitted its complaint, C adduced evidence from a ‘way-back machine’ demonstrating that the Disputed Domain Name was pointing to a website of a jewellery company in Shenzhen which advertised products of C and its competitors, Tiffany and Swarovski.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>R submitted a response within the required period of time, arguing that the website was launched only for testing purposes during a very short period of time, and no records of the website could be found by common search engines, such as Baidu and Google. Therefore it did not harm C’s rights and interests.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, granting the remedy sought, that, inter alia:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The Panel accepted C’s contention that C had legitimate rights and interests in C’s trademark which enjoyed a high reputation in Mainland China’s and overseas’ markets, and found that inclusion of an additional “r” to C’s trademark would not reduce the confusion between C’s trademark and the Disputed Domain Name.</li>\r\n	<li>Noting that R did not contend that it had rights to and legitimate interests in the Disputed Domain Name, the Panel accepted C’s contention that R had no rights and legitimate interests in respect of the Disputed Domain Name.</li>\r\n	<li>The Panel found that R’s argument that its temporary use of domain name for website testing purposes would not harm C’s operations and reputation was groundless. It accepted C’s evidence produced by the ‘way-back machine’, and was of the view that once the website was published, its contents became public information that could have been viewed by public Internet users. In view of the fact that both C and R were in the same industry, the Panel inferred that R must have known about C’s trademark before its registration of the Disputed Domain Name. Also, setting up a website selling products similar to C’s under a domain name which was confusingly similar to C’s trademark would constitute use of domain name in bad faith. The Panel also emphasised that whether R had caused any actual harm to C was irrelevant to its finding of bad faith.</li>\r\n	<li>With C’s ability to establish all the required elements under para. 4(a) of the UDRP, the Panel ordered that the Disputed Domain Name be transferred to C.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>The full decision can be downloaded in the website of ADNDRC at <a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500782_Decision.pdf\">http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500782_Decision.pdf</a>.</p>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:285:\"<p>Intellectual Property – Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy – Record of ‘Way-back Machine’ proves use of domain name in bad faith – Attempts to attract internet traffic by riding on the Complainant’s reputation constitutes use of domain name in bad faith</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3450:\"<p><em>Intellectual Property – Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy – Record of ‘Way-back Machine’ proves use of domain name in bad faith – Attempts to attract internet traffic by riding on the Complainant’s reputation constitutes use of domain name in bad faith</em></p>\n<p>Complainant, (hereinafter “C”), holder of registered trademark of “Cartier” in many countries for its products in precious metals (including jewellery, clocks and watches), submitted a Complaint concerning the Disputed Domain Name “cartierr.com” registered by Respondent (hereinafter “R”), pursuant to the ICANN Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (“UDRP”).</p>\n<p>C contended that R registered and used the Disputed Domain Name for the purpose of attracting Internet traffic to its website for commercial gain and to disrupt C’s businesses. Although the Disputed Domain Name did not resolve to any active website at the time C submitted its complaint, C adduced evidence from a ‘way-back machine’ demonstrating that the Disputed Domain Name was pointing to a website of a jewellery company in Shenzhen which advertised products of C and its competitors, Tiffany and Swarovski.</p>\n<p>R submitted a response within the required period of time, arguing that the website was launched only for testing purposes during a very short period of time, and no records of the website could be found by common search engines, such as Baidu and Google. Therefore it did not harm C’s rights and interests.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, granting the remedy sought, that, inter alia:</p>\n<ul><li>The Panel accepted C’s contention that C had legitimate rights and interests in C’s trademark which enjoyed a high reputation in Mainland China’s and overseas’ markets, and found that inclusion of an additional “r” to C’s trademark would not reduce the confusion between C’s trademark and the Disputed Domain Name.</li>\n<li>Noting that R did not contend that it had rights to and legitimate interests in the Disputed Domain Name, the Panel accepted C’s contention that R had no rights and legitimate interests in respect of the Disputed Domain Name.</li>\n<li>The Panel found that R’s argument that its temporary use of domain name for website testing purposes would not harm C’s operations and reputation was groundless. It accepted C’s evidence produced by the ‘way-back machine’, and was of the view that once the website was published, its contents became public information that could have been viewed by public Internet users. In view of the fact that both C and R were in the same industry, the Panel inferred that R must have known about C’s trademark before its registration of the Disputed Domain Name. Also, setting up a website selling products similar to C’s under a domain name which was confusingly similar to C’s trademark would constitute use of domain name in bad faith. The Panel also emphasised that whether R had caused any actual harm to C was irrelevant to its finding of bad faith.</li>\n<li>With C’s ability to establish all the required elements under para. 4(a) of the UDRP, the Panel ordered that the Disputed Domain Name be transferred to C.</li>\n</ul><hr /><p>The full decision can be downloaded in the website of ADNDRC at <a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500782_Decision.pdf\">http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500782_Decision.pdf</a>.</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:284:\"<p>Intellectual Property – Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy – Record of ‘Way-back Machine’ proves use of domain name in bad faith – Attempts to attract internet traffic by riding on the Complainant’s reputation constitutes use of domain name in bad faith</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:62:\"Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:62:\"Asian Domain Name Dispute Resolution Centre (Hong Kong Office)\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:39:\"Cartier International AG v Peng Hai Kun\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:39:\"Cartier International AG v Peng Hai Kun\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:63:\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500782_Decision.pdf\";s:5:\"title\";s:10:\"HK-1500782\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:17:\"30 September 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:17:\"30 September 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"Dispute Resolution\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"Dispute Resolution\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:39:\"Cartier International AG v Peng Hai Kun\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458115031,1),('9328','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9332\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:39:\"卡地亞國際有限公司對彭海昆\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9328\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9327\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3297:\"知識產權 — 《統一域名爭議解決政策》 — Way-back Machine的記錄證明惡意使用域名 – 試圖利用投訴人的知名度增加互聯網流量，此舉構成惡意使用域名<p>\n	卡地亞國際有限公司對彭海昆</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500782_Decision.pdf\">HK-1500782</a> &quot;cartierr.com&quot;<br />\n	亞洲域名爭議解決中心<br />\n	<br />\n	李桃(專家組成員)<br />\n	<br />\n	2015年9月30日</p>\n<p>\n	投訴人就其珠寶、鐘表等貴金屬產品在多個國家註冊了Cartier商標。投訴人根據互聯網名稱與數字地址分配機構的《統一域名爭議解決政策》(「《政策》」)提交投訴書，投訴內容與已被被投訴人註冊的爭議域名cartierr.com有關。</p>\n<p>\n	投訴人提出爭議，指被投訴人註冊及使用爭議域名的目的，是吸引互聯網用戶訪問其網站以獲得商業利益及干擾投訴人的業務。雖然投訴人提交投訴書之時，爭議域名並不解析至任何可用的網站，但投訴人提出來自way-back machine的證據，證明爭議域名當時是指向深圳一家珠寶公司的網站，該網站曾宣傳投訴人及其競爭對手Tiffany(蒂芙尼)和Swarovski(施華洛世奇)的產品。</p>\n<p>\n	被投訴人在規定期限內提交答辯書，辯稱開設網站只為在極短時間內作調試之用，而且百度及Google等常用的搜索引擎都發現不到該網站的訊息記錄，因此沒有損害投訴人的權利和利益。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &ndash; 批給索求的解決方法，其中包括：</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		專家組接納投訴人的論點，認同投訴人對投訴人的商標享有合法權利和利益，且投訴人的商標在中國內地及海外市場享有極高知名度，因而認定，在投訴人的商標多增一個r不會減低投訴人的商標與爭議域名產生混淆的程度。</li>\n	<li>\n		專家組注意到，被投訴人沒有主張其對爭議域名擁有任何權利或合法權益，所以接納投訴人指被投訴人對爭議域名不享有任何權利或合法權益。</li>\n	<li>\n		對於被投訴人辯稱自己是為調試網站而臨時使用域名，因此不會損害投訴人的業務及知名度，專家組認定這論點毫無根據。專家組接納投訴人由way-back machine提供的證據，並且認為網站一經公布，網站內容便成為公開訊息，廣大互聯網用戶皆可瀏覽。由於投訴人與被投訴人從事相同業務，專家組推斷被投訴人在註冊爭議域名之前，一定已經熟悉投訴人的商標。此外，建設網站銷售與投訴人的產品相似的產品，而相關域名與投訴人的商標極其相似，容易引起混淆，會構成惡意使用域名。專家組亦強調，對於專家組是否認定惡意存在，被投訴人有否對投訴人造成實際損害是無關宏旨的。</li>\n	<li>\n		投訴人的投訴符合《政策》第4(a)條規定的所有條件，專家組命令將爭議域名轉移給投訴人。</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<p>\n	裁決全文在亞洲域名爭議解決中心的網頁可供下載：<a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500782_Decision.pdf\">http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500782_Decision.pdf</a>。</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:199:\"知識產權 — 《統一域名爭議解決政策》 — Way-back Machine的記錄證明惡意使用域名 – 試圖利用投訴人的知名度增加互聯網流量，此舉構成惡意使用域名\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3270:\"<p>知識產權 — 《統一域名爭議解決政策》 — Way-back Machine的記錄證明惡意使用域名 – 試圖利用投訴人的知名度增加互聯網流量，此舉構成惡意使用域名\n</p><p>\n	卡地亞國際有限公司對彭海昆</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500782_Decision.pdf\">HK-1500782</a> \"cartierr.com\"<br />\n	亞洲域名爭議解決中心</p>\n<p>	李桃(專家組成員)</p>\n<p>	2015年9月30日</p>\n<p>\n	投訴人就其珠寶、鐘表等貴金屬產品在多個國家註冊了Cartier商標。投訴人根據互聯網名稱與數字地址分配機構的《統一域名爭議解決政策》(「《政策》」)提交投訴書，投訴內容與已被被投訴人註冊的爭議域名cartierr.com有關。</p>\n<p>\n	投訴人提出爭議，指被投訴人註冊及使用爭議域名的目的，是吸引互聯網用戶訪問其網站以獲得商業利益及干擾投訴人的業務。雖然投訴人提交投訴書之時，爭議域名並不解析至任何可用的網站，但投訴人提出來自way-back machine的證據，證明爭議域名當時是指向深圳一家珠寶公司的網站，該網站曾宣傳投訴人及其競爭對手Tiffany(蒂芙尼)和Swarovski(施華洛世奇)的產品。</p>\n<p>\n	被投訴人在規定期限內提交答辯書，辯稱開設網站只為在極短時間內作調試之用，而且百度及Google等常用的搜索引擎都發現不到該網站的訊息記錄，因此沒有損害投訴人的權利和利益。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> – 批給索求的解決方法，其中包括：</p>\n<ul><li>\n		專家組接納投訴人的論點，認同投訴人對投訴人的商標享有合法權利和利益，且投訴人的商標在中國內地及海外市場享有極高知名度，因而認定，在投訴人的商標多增一個r不會減低投訴人的商標與爭議域名產生混淆的程度。</li>\n<li>\n		專家組注意到，被投訴人沒有主張其對爭議域名擁有任何權利或合法權益，所以接納投訴人指被投訴人對爭議域名不享有任何權利或合法權益。</li>\n<li>\n		對於被投訴人辯稱自己是為調試網站而臨時使用域名，因此不會損害投訴人的業務及知名度，專家組認定這論點毫無根據。專家組接納投訴人由way-back machine提供的證據，並且認為網站一經公布，網站內容便成為公開訊息，廣大互聯網用戶皆可瀏覽。由於投訴人與被投訴人從事相同業務，專家組推斷被投訴人在註冊爭議域名之前，一定已經熟悉投訴人的商標。此外，建設網站銷售與投訴人的產品相似的產品，而相關域名與投訴人的商標極其相似，容易引起混淆，會構成惡意使用域名。專家組亦強調，對於專家組是否認定惡意存在，被投訴人有否對投訴人造成實際損害是無關宏旨的。</li>\n<li>\n		投訴人的投訴符合《政策》第4(a)條規定的所有條件，專家組命令將爭議域名轉移給投訴人。</li>\n</ul><hr /><p>\n	裁決全文在亞洲域名爭議解決中心的網頁可供下載：<a href=\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500782_Decision.pdf\">http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500782_Decision.pdf</a>。</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:207:\"<p>知識產權 — 《統一域名爭議解決政策》 — Way-back Machine的記錄證明惡意使用域名 – 試圖利用投訴人的知名度增加互聯網流量，此舉構成惡意使用域名</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:51:\"亞洲域名爭議解決中心（香港秘書處）\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:51:\"亞洲域名爭議解決中心（香港秘書處）\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:39:\"卡地亞國際有限公司對彭海昆\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:39:\"卡地亞國際有限公司對彭海昆\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"565\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:63:\"http://www.adndrc.org/diymodule/docUDRP/HK-1500782_Decision.pdf\";s:5:\"title\";s:10:\"HK-1500782\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"2015年9月30日\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"2015年9月30日\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"解決糾紛\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"解決糾紛\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:39:\"卡地亞國際有限公司對彭海昆\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183919,1),('9329','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9333\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:27:\"Li Kam Ling v Tse Wai Keung\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9329\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456675288\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9329\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3534:\"<p><em>Employees’ compensation – permanent partial incapacity – special circumstances of employee stipulated in s. 9(1A)(b) applied – compensation for permanent partial incapacity assessed under s. 9(1A) – quantum</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>X was injured while working as an automobile mechanic for D who ran a repair garage. On 14 July 2012, X was using a highly pressurised gun to inject grease via a plastic hose into a lorry, when the hose suddenly burst and grease punctured his left hand. X was aged 59 at the time of the accident. He had received only primary school education and had worked for many years only as a garage mechanic. X’s work was physically demanding. He used hand tools and lifted/moved objects weighing over 100–200 lbs. Joint orthopaedic experts agreed that X had sustained an injection injury/grease gun injury to the left hand and the residual impairment was severe. He had lost his fine motor skills and strength in his left hand. X was not fit to return to his pre-accident job or any work requiring a strong handgrip and dexterity or medium to heavy manual labour. Suitable alternative occupations included a security guard, for which the average monthly salary was HK$9,117 in September 2012. One expert estimated the total loss of earning capacity at 21 percent, another at 10 percent. X’s pre-accident monthly earnings were HK$16,900. Based on X’s left hand injury resulting in left hand scar and left thumb interphalangeal joint and metacarpophalangeal joint stiffness, the Employees’ Compensation (Ordinary Assessment) Board (the “Board”), assessed a permanent loss of earning capacity (“PLEC”) of 12 percent, which was subsequently reassessed at 15percent. X appealed under s. 18 of the Employees’ Compensation Ordinance (Cap. 282) (the “ECO”), seeking an assessment under s. 9(1A) of the ECO of the percentage of compensation which would have been payable in case of permanent total incapacity as was proportionate to the loss of earning capacity permanently caused by the injury in any employment which, having regard to the special circumstances set out in s. 9(1A)(b), the employee was capable of undertaking at that time. P’s injury did not fall within the First Schedule to the ECO.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, finding that D was liable to pay compensation to P under the ECO, allowing the appeal and assessing compensation for permanent partial incapacity under s. 9(1A), that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The nature of X’s injuries, his qualifications, previous training and experience constituted the “special circumstances” stipulated in s. 9(1A)(b) of the ECO.</li>\r\n	<li>A post-accident monthly salary as a security guard of HK$9,117 involved a 46percent actual reduction in earnings [(HK$16,900 – HK$9,117) ÷ HK$16,900 x 100%], which was significantly more than the 15 percent loss of earning capacity assessed by the Board. In the circumstances, the <em>Paper Mills</em> formula would be applied and the appeal allowed by substituting 15 percent with 46percent pursuant to s. 18(3) of the ECO. Under s. 7(1)(c) of the ECO, the compensation for permanent total incapacity resulting from the injury, in the case of an employee aged 56 or over at the time of the accident, was a lump sum equal to 48 months’ earnings or 48 times the amount specified in the second column of Sch. 6 opposite s.7(1)(c) in the first column, whichever was less. Thus here, the award under s. 9 was HK$373,584 [(HK$16,900 – HK$9,117) ÷ HK$16,900 x HK$811,200].</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:225:\"<p>Employees’ compensation – permanent partial incapacity – special circumstances of employee stipulated in s. 9(1A)(b) applied – compensation for permanent partial incapacity assessed under s. 9(1A) – quantum</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3517:\"<p><em>Employees’ compensation – permanent partial incapacity – special circumstances of employee stipulated in s. 9(1A)(b) applied – compensation for permanent partial incapacity assessed under s. 9(1A) – quantum</em></p>\n<p>X was injured while working as an automobile mechanic for D who ran a repair garage. On 14 July 2012, X was using a highly pressurised gun to inject grease via a plastic hose into a lorry, when the hose suddenly burst and grease punctured his left hand. X was aged 59 at the time of the accident. He had received only primary school education and had worked for many years only as a garage mechanic. X’s work was physically demanding. He used hand tools and lifted/moved objects weighing over 100–200 lbs. Joint orthopaedic experts agreed that X had sustained an injection injury/grease gun injury to the left hand and the residual impairment was severe. He had lost his fine motor skills and strength in his left hand. X was not fit to return to his pre-accident job or any work requiring a strong handgrip and dexterity or medium to heavy manual labour. Suitable alternative occupations included a security guard, for which the average monthly salary was HK$9,117 in September 2012. One expert estimated the total loss of earning capacity at 21 percent, another at 10 percent. X’s pre-accident monthly earnings were HK$16,900. Based on X’s left hand injury resulting in left hand scar and left thumb interphalangeal joint and metacarpophalangeal joint stiffness, the Employees’ Compensation (Ordinary Assessment) Board (the “Board”), assessed a permanent loss of earning capacity (“PLEC”) of 12 percent, which was subsequently reassessed at 15percent. X appealed under s. 18 of the Employees’ Compensation Ordinance (Cap. 282) (the “ECO”), seeking an assessment under s. 9(1A) of the ECO of the percentage of compensation which would have been payable in case of permanent total incapacity as was proportionate to the loss of earning capacity permanently caused by the injury in any employment which, having regard to the special circumstances set out in s. 9(1A)(b), the employee was capable of undertaking at that time. P’s injury did not fall within the First Schedule to the ECO.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, finding that D was liable to pay compensation to P under the ECO, allowing the appeal and assessing compensation for permanent partial incapacity under s. 9(1A), that:</p>\n<ul><li>The nature of X’s injuries, his qualifications, previous training and experience constituted the “special circumstances” stipulated in s. 9(1A)(b) of the ECO.</li>\n<li>A post-accident monthly salary as a security guard of HK$9,117 involved a 46percent actual reduction in earnings [(HK$16,900 – HK$9,117) ÷ HK$16,900 x 100%], which was significantly more than the 15 percent loss of earning capacity assessed by the Board. In the circumstances, the <em>Paper Mills</em> formula would be applied and the appeal allowed by substituting 15 percent with 46percent pursuant to s. 18(3) of the ECO. Under s. 7(1)(c) of the ECO, the compensation for permanent total incapacity resulting from the injury, in the case of an employee aged 56 or over at the time of the accident, was a lump sum equal to 48 months’ earnings or 48 times the amount specified in the second column of Sch. 6 opposite s.7(1)(c) in the first column, whichever was less. Thus here, the award under s. 9 was HK$373,584 [(HK$16,900 – HK$9,117) ÷ HK$16,900 x HK$811,200].</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:224:\"<p>Employees’ compensation – permanent partial incapacity – special circumstances of employee stipulated in s. 9(1A)(b) applied – compensation for permanent partial incapacity assessed under s. 9(1A) – quantum</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:14:\"District Court\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:14:\"District Court\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:27:\"Li Kam Ling v Tse Wai Keung\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:27:\"Li Kam Ling v Tse Wai Keung\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"104\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744cc6400000151ebcd59ccd2054842&docguid=I329D44E1254047659D5213FDA394133F&hitguid=I329D44E1254047659D5213FDA394133F&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=16\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2060\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:14:\"5 October 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:14:\"5 October 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:10:\"Employment\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:10:\"Employment\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:27:\"Li Kam Ling v Tse Wai Keung\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458115031,1),('9330','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9334\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:27:\"Li Kam Ling v Tse Wai Keung\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9330\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9329\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3522:\"僱員補償 — 永久地部分喪失工作能力 — 第9(1A)(b)條指明的僱員特別情況適用 — 根據第9(1A)條評估永久地部分喪失工作能力的補償 — 所索金額<p>\n	Li Kam Ling v Tse Wai Keung</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6400000151ebcd59ccd2054842&amp;docguid=I329D44E1254047659D5213FDA394133F&amp;hitguid=I329D44E1254047659D5213FDA394133F&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=16\">[2015] HKEC 2060</a><br />\n	區域法院<br />\n	僱員補償案件2013年第394號<br />\n	區域法院暫委法官沈偉民<br />\n	2015年10月5日</p>\n<p>\n	X在D經營的車房做汽車技工；X在工作期間受傷。2012年7月14日，X用一枝連接着膠喉的高壓槍給一輛貨車噴注潤滑脂，期間喉管突然爆裂，X的左手被潤滑脂噴穿。意外發生時X年59歲。他只接受過小學教育，多年來做的就只是汽車技工。X的工作需要體力勞動。他用手動工具升起∕搬動逾100-200磅重的物件。聯合撰寫報告的骨科專家同意X左手受的是注射傷∕被潤滑脂槍所傷，後遺問題嚴重。他失去做細緻動作的能力，左手無力。X不再適合做他在意外發生前所做的工作，或任何需要強大的抓握力及靈巧度或需要中等至高體力勞動的工作。合適的工作選擇包括保安員在內。2012年9月的保安員平均月薪是9,117元。其中一名專家估計X 完全喪失賺取收入能力的百分率為21%，另一名則估計為10%。X在意外發生之前每月賺取16,900元。僱員補償(普通評估)委員會(「委員會」)基於X左手受傷導致左手留有疤痕，以及左姆指指關關節及掌指關節僵硬，評估X永久喪失賺取收入能力的百分率為12%，其後重新評估為15%。X根據《僱員補償條例》(第282章)(「《條例》」)第18條提出上訴，要求根據《條例》第9(1A)條評定補償的百分率，而該補償是在永久地完全喪失工作能力的情況下會是須付的補償，而該百分率為一個與在顧及第9(1A)(b)條列出的特別情況下，僱員在當時有能力受僱擔任的任何工作方面，因上述損傷而永久導致的喪失賺取收入能力情況相稱的百分率。X所受的傷不屬《條例》附表1所指明的損傷。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &mdash; D負有按照《條例》補償P的法律責任，申請人上訴得直，裁定根據第9(1A)條評估永久地部分喪失工作能力的補償：</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		X的損傷的性質，他的資歷，以往所受的訓練及所得的經驗構成《條例》第9(1A)(b)條指明的「特別情況」。</li>\n	<li>\n		在意外發生後做保安員的月薪為9,117元，收入實際減少46%[(16,900元&ndash;9,117元)&divide; 16,900元x100%]，委員會評估喪失的賺取收入能力為15%，兩者相距極遠。這情況會應用<em>Paper Mills</em>方程式，法院判X上訴得直，根據《條例》第18(3)條以46%取代15%。根據《條例》第7(1)(c)條，如意外發生時僱員年滿56歲，僱員因受傷導致永久地完全喪失工作能力而得到的補償，是一筆相等於48個月收入的款項或在附表6第2欄中相對於該附表第1欄指明的第7(1)(c)條之處指明的款額乘48所得的數目，兩者以較小的數額為準。因此，本案根據第9條計算判給的補償額為373,584元[(16,900元&ndash; 9,117元) &divide; 16,900元x 811,200元]。</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:189:\"僱員補償 — 永久地部分喪失工作能力 — 第9(1A)(b)條指明的僱員特別情況適用 — 根據第9(1A)條評估永久地部分喪失工作能力的補償 — 所索金額\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3502:\"<p>僱員補償 — 永久地部分喪失工作能力 — 第9(1A)(b)條指明的僱員特別情況適用 — 根據第9(1A)條評估永久地部分喪失工作能力的補償 — 所索金額\n</p><p>\n	Li Kam Ling v Tse Wai Keung</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6400000151ebcd59ccd2054842&amp;docguid=I329D44E1254047659D5213FDA394133F&amp;hitguid=I329D44E1254047659D5213FDA394133F&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=16\">[2015] HKEC 2060</a><br />\n	區域法院<br />\n	僱員補償案件2013年第394號<br />\n	區域法院暫委法官沈偉民<br />\n	2015年10月5日</p>\n<p>\n	X在D經營的車房做汽車技工；X在工作期間受傷。2012年7月14日，X用一枝連接着膠喉的高壓槍給一輛貨車噴注潤滑脂，期間喉管突然爆裂，X的左手被潤滑脂噴穿。意外發生時X年59歲。他只接受過小學教育，多年來做的就只是汽車技工。X的工作需要體力勞動。他用手動工具升起∕搬動逾100-200磅重的物件。聯合撰寫報告的骨科專家同意X左手受的是注射傷∕被潤滑脂槍所傷，後遺問題嚴重。他失去做細緻動作的能力，左手無力。X不再適合做他在意外發生前所做的工作，或任何需要強大的抓握力及靈巧度或需要中等至高體力勞動的工作。合適的工作選擇包括保安員在內。2012年9月的保安員平均月薪是9,117元。其中一名專家估計X 完全喪失賺取收入能力的百分率為21%，另一名則估計為10%。X在意外發生之前每月賺取16,900元。僱員補償(普通評估)委員會(「委員會」)基於X左手受傷導致左手留有疤痕，以及左姆指指關關節及掌指關節僵硬，評估X永久喪失賺取收入能力的百分率為12%，其後重新評估為15%。X根據《僱員補償條例》(第282章)(「《條例》」)第18條提出上訴，要求根據《條例》第9(1A)條評定補償的百分率，而該補償是在永久地完全喪失工作能力的情況下會是須付的補償，而該百分率為一個與在顧及第9(1A)(b)條列出的特別情況下，僱員在當時有能力受僱擔任的任何工作方面，因上述損傷而永久導致的喪失賺取收入能力情況相稱的百分率。X所受的傷不屬《條例》附表1所指明的損傷。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> — D負有按照《條例》補償P的法律責任，申請人上訴得直，裁定根據第9(1A)條評估永久地部分喪失工作能力的補償：</p>\n<ul><li>\n		X的損傷的性質，他的資歷，以往所受的訓練及所得的經驗構成《條例》第9(1A)(b)條指明的「特別情況」。</li>\n<li>\n		在意外發生後做保安員的月薪為9,117元，收入實際減少46%[(16,900元–9,117元)÷ 16,900元x100%]，委員會評估喪失的賺取收入能力為15%，兩者相距極遠。這情況會應用<em>Paper Mills</em>方程式，法院判X上訴得直，根據《條例》第18(3)條以46%取代15%。根據《條例》第7(1)(c)條，如意外發生時僱員年滿56歲，僱員因受傷導致永久地完全喪失工作能力而得到的補償，是一筆相等於48個月收入的款項或在附表6第2欄中相對於該附表第1欄指明的第7(1)(c)條之處指明的款額乘48所得的數目，兩者以較小的數額為準。因此，本案根據第9條計算判給的補償額為373,584元[(16,900元– 9,117元) ÷ 16,900元x 811,200元]。</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:197:\"<p>僱員補償 — 永久地部分喪失工作能力 — 第9(1A)(b)條指明的僱員特別情況適用 — 根據第9(1A)條評估永久地部分喪失工作能力的補償 — 所索金額</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"區域法院\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"區域法院\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:27:\"Li Kam Ling v Tse Wai Keung\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:27:\"Li Kam Ling v Tse Wai Keung\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"566\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"638\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744cc6400000151ebcd59ccd2054842&docguid=I329D44E1254047659D5213FDA394133F&hitguid=I329D44E1254047659D5213FDA394133F&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=16\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2060\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"2015年10月5日\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"2015年10月5日\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:9:\"僱傭法\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:9:\"僱傭法\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:27:\"Li Kam Ling v Tse Wai Keung\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183919,1),('9331','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9335\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:29:\"Hung Hing v Director of Lands\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9331\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9331\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2650:\"Small House Policy – amenability of decisions of Director of Land to judicial review<p>\n	Hung Hing v Director of Lands</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6300000151ebcde11f5a0bec0e&amp;docguid=IB02B96A27BA742268075001D945F9DDE&amp;hitguid=IB02B96A27BA742268075001D945F9DDE&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=19\">[2015] HKEC 1945</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Civil Appeal No. 118 of 2015<br />\n	Cheung CJHC, Cheung and Kwan JJA<br />\n	17 September 2015</p>\n<p>\n	Xs were registered owners of various plots of land in the New Territories, having applied to the District Lands Office (&ldquo;DLO&rdquo;) to erect small houses on such land under the Small House Policy (the &ldquo;Policy&rdquo;). There was no vehicular access to the land, as they were separated from nearby main roads by other lots which were resumed by the Government as part of a village expansion plan. Xs applied to purchase from the Government part of all the resumed lots to construct and maintain vehicular access. On DLO&rsquo;s refusal, Xs sought leave to apply for judicial review, which was refused at first instance. Xs appealed.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		As a general rule, Government decisions in relation to land leases and related matters where the Government wore the hat of a landowner or landlord were not amenable to judicial review. The Court was prepared to accept at the leave stage that some decisions made by the DLO in the implementation of the Policy might be amenable to judicial review. However, it did not follow that each and every matter associated with the Policy or its implementation was amenable to judicial review. Vehicular access was not a feature of the Policy. Under the Policy and its associated fire safety requirements, the provision of vehicular access or an emergency vehicular access was not a must; there could be fire safety alternatives. If there was no access then it was for the successful applicants, if they wanted this, to make their own arrangement. So there was no question of the DLO making any public law mistake in relation to implementing the Policy as regards its refusal to grant Government land to Xs for the construction of vehicular access.</li>\n	<li>\n		In any event, leave should be refused on the ground that Xs had not exhausted possible alternative remedies. The burden being squarely on Xs to show a reasonably arguable case, there was simply no or little available material to show that Xs could not acquire land for vehicular access by other means.</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:86:\"Small House Policy – amenability of decisions of Director of Land to judicial review\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2634:\"<p>Small House Policy – amenability of decisions of Director of Land to judicial review\n</p><p>\n	Hung Hing v Director of Lands</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6300000151ebcde11f5a0bec0e&amp;docguid=IB02B96A27BA742268075001D945F9DDE&amp;hitguid=IB02B96A27BA742268075001D945F9DDE&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=19\">[2015] HKEC 1945</a><br />\n	Court of Appeal<br />\n	Civil Appeal No. 118 of 2015<br />\n	Cheung CJHC, Cheung and Kwan JJA<br />\n	17 September 2015</p>\n<p>\n	Xs were registered owners of various plots of land in the New Territories, having applied to the District Lands Office (“DLO”) to erect small houses on such land under the Small House Policy (the “Policy”). There was no vehicular access to the land, as they were separated from nearby main roads by other lots which were resumed by the Government as part of a village expansion plan. Xs applied to purchase from the Government part of all the resumed lots to construct and maintain vehicular access. On DLO’s refusal, Xs sought leave to apply for judicial review, which was refused at first instance. Xs appealed.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the appeal, that:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		As a general rule, Government decisions in relation to land leases and related matters where the Government wore the hat of a landowner or landlord were not amenable to judicial review. The Court was prepared to accept at the leave stage that some decisions made by the DLO in the implementation of the Policy might be amenable to judicial review. However, it did not follow that each and every matter associated with the Policy or its implementation was amenable to judicial review. Vehicular access was not a feature of the Policy. Under the Policy and its associated fire safety requirements, the provision of vehicular access or an emergency vehicular access was not a must; there could be fire safety alternatives. If there was no access then it was for the successful applicants, if they wanted this, to make their own arrangement. So there was no question of the DLO making any public law mistake in relation to implementing the Policy as regards its refusal to grant Government land to Xs for the construction of vehicular access.</li>\n<li>\n		In any event, leave should be refused on the ground that Xs had not exhausted possible alternative remedies. The burden being squarely on Xs to show a reasonably arguable case, there was simply no or little available material to show that Xs could not acquire land for vehicular access by other means.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:94:\"<p>Small House Policy – amenability of decisions of Director of Land to judicial review</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:29:\"Hung Hing v Director of Lands\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:29:\"Hung Hing v Director of Lands\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"112\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744cc6300000151ebcde11f5a0bec0e&docguid=IB02B96A27BA742268075001D945F9DDE&hitguid=IB02B96A27BA742268075001D945F9DDE&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=19\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1945\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:17:\"17 September 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:17:\"17 September 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:8:\"Land Law\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:8:\"Land Law\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:29:\"Hung Hing v Director of Lands\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458112328,1),('9332','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9336\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:29:\"Hung Hing v Director of Lands\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9332\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9331\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2475:\"丁屋政策 — 地政總署署長的決定可會接受司法覆核<p>\n	Hung Hing v Director of Lands</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6300000151ebcde11f5a0bec0e&amp;docguid=IB02B96A27BA742268075001D945F9DDE&amp;hitguid=IB02B96A27BA742268075001D945F9DDE&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=19\">[2015] HKEC 1945</a><br />\n	上訴法庭<br />\n	民事上訴案件2015年第118號<br />\n	高等法院首席法官張舉能<br />\n	上訴法庭法官張澤祐<br />\n	上訴法庭法官關淑馨<br />\n	2015年9月17日</p>\n<p>\n	眾申請人是新界多塊土地(「該等土地」)的註冊擁有人，他們根據丁屋政策向分區地政處(「地政處」)申請在該等土地上興建丁屋。該等土地與附近主要街道由其他已被政府收回供鄉村擴展計劃之用的地段隔開，該等土地因而不連接任何行車通道。眾申請人申請從政府那裡購買全部已收回地段中的部分土地，以興建及設置行車通道。申請被地政處拒絕之後，眾申請人尋求申請司法覆核的許可，但該申請在初審時被拒。眾申請人提出上訴。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &mdash; 駁回上訴：</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		一般來說，如政府是相關土地的擁有人或業主，政府有關土地租賃及相關事宜的決定是不受司法覆核的。在申請許可的階段，法庭容易同意地政處在實施丁屋政策時所作的一些決定是可接受司法覆核的。但這不是說每一件與丁屋政策有關的事情或者丁屋政策的實施均可接受司法覆核。行車通道不是丁屋政策的重要部分。根據丁屋政策及與之相關的消防安全規定，行車通道或緊急車輛通道不是非提供不可；還有可能有其他符合消防安全規定的選擇。如果沒有通道，而成功的申請人又想有通道連接的話，他們可自行作出安排。地政處拒絕批出政府土地予眾申請人興建行車通道，就實施丁屋政策而言，當中不存在地政處在公法上犯錯的問題。</li>\n	<li>\n		不管怎樣，法庭應以眾申請人未有用盡其他可行的補救方法為由，拒絕給予許可。舉證責任全落在眾申請人身上，他們得證明案情可合理地辯證成立，但當時根本沒有或只有少量證據證明眾申請人不能透過其他途徑購入土地以興建及設置行車通道。</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:68:\"丁屋政策 — 地政總署署長的決定可會接受司法覆核\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2475:\"<p>丁屋政策 — 地政總署署長的決定可會接受司法覆核\n</p><p>\n	Hung Hing v Director of Lands</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&amp;src=rl&amp;srguid=ia744cc6300000151ebcde11f5a0bec0e&amp;docguid=IB02B96A27BA742268075001D945F9DDE&amp;hitguid=IB02B96A27BA742268075001D945F9DDE&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;td=1&amp;crumb-action=append&amp;context=19\">[2015] HKEC 1945</a><br />\n	上訴法庭<br />\n	民事上訴案件2015年第118號<br />\n	高等法院首席法官張舉能<br />\n	上訴法庭法官張澤祐<br />\n	上訴法庭法官關淑馨<br />\n	2015年9月17日</p>\n<p>\n	眾申請人是新界多塊土地(「該等土地」)的註冊擁有人，他們根據丁屋政策向分區地政處(「地政處」)申請在該等土地上興建丁屋。該等土地與附近主要街道由其他已被政府收回供鄉村擴展計劃之用的地段隔開，該等土地因而不連接任何行車通道。眾申請人申請從政府那裡購買全部已收回地段中的部分土地，以興建及設置行車通道。申請被地政處拒絕之後，眾申請人尋求申請司法覆核的許可，但該申請在初審時被拒。眾申請人提出上訴。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> — 駁回上訴：</p>\n<ul><li>\n		一般來說，如政府是相關土地的擁有人或業主，政府有關土地租賃及相關事宜的決定是不受司法覆核的。在申請許可的階段，法庭容易同意地政處在實施丁屋政策時所作的一些決定是可接受司法覆核的。但這不是說每一件與丁屋政策有關的事情或者丁屋政策的實施均可接受司法覆核。行車通道不是丁屋政策的重要部分。根據丁屋政策及與之相關的消防安全規定，行車通道或緊急車輛通道不是非提供不可；還有可能有其他符合消防安全規定的選擇。如果沒有通道，而成功的申請人又想有通道連接的話，他們可自行作出安排。地政處拒絕批出政府土地予眾申請人興建行車通道，就實施丁屋政策而言，當中不存在地政處在公法上犯錯的問題。</li>\n<li>\n		不管怎樣，法庭應以眾申請人未有用盡其他可行的補救方法為由，拒絕給予許可。舉證責任全落在眾申請人身上，他們得證明案情可合理地辯證成立，但當時根本沒有或只有少量證據證明眾申請人不能透過其他途徑購入土地以興建及設置行車通道。</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:76:\"<p>丁屋政策 — 地政總署署長的決定可會接受司法覆核</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"上訴法庭\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"上訴法庭\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:29:\"Hung Hing v Director of Lands\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:29:\"Hung Hing v Director of Lands\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"574\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"638\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-01-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:232:\"http://login.westlaw.com.hk/maf/wlhk/app/document?&src=rl&srguid=ia744cc6300000151ebcde11f5a0bec0e&docguid=IB02B96A27BA742268075001D945F9DDE&hitguid=IB02B96A27BA742268075001D945F9DDE&spos=1&epos=1&td=1&crumb-action=append&context=19\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 1945\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"2015年9月17日\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"2015年9月17日\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:9:\"土地法\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:9:\"土地法\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:29:\"Hung Hing v Director of Lands\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1451865600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183919,1),('9333','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9337\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:42:\"Wing Hong Investment Co Ltd v Fung Sok Han\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9333\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1454371200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456675137\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9333\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2362:\"<p><em>Building management – change of user – change of user materially different to user stated in occupation permit – change did not breach clause in deed of mutual covenant prohibiting illegal use of premises – Buildings Ordinance (Cap. 123) s. 25</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>P was the owner and developer of three sections of a land lot (the “Sections”). P developed a building on each of the three Sections which were linked together by common internal corridors on each floor and served by the same lifts, and which functioned as one building (the “Building”). P still owned seven of the eight ground floor units and four units on the floors above. D2–4 were the incorporated owners of the respective three buildings and D1 was the chairwoman of D2. Of the issues in dispute, one included a claim by Ds that the conversion by P of the carport into shops and godowns was contrary to the user as stated in the occupation permits and hence illegal and in breach of a clause of the deeds of mutual covenants (the “DMCs”) which prohibited illegal use of the premises.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, ruling in favour of P, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Although P’s change of user from carport to shops and godowns on the ground floor was not in line with the occupation permits, it was not illegal and did not contravene the DMC. Section 25 of the Buildings Ordinance (Cap. 123) was relevant. The provision in s. 25(1) required the person intending the material change of user to serve on the Building Authority (the “BA”) a notice of intended change. It was not a crime to adopt a material change in the user of the premises, but it was an offence under s. 40(2) of the Ordinance not to serve a notice to the BA under s. 25(1). If the changed or intended new user was not acceptable to the BA, it could always serve an order under s. 25(2) to prohibit the intended user or require the changed user to be discontinued. But there was no provision saying that it was an offence to adopt a user of the premises which was materially different from that stated in the occupation permit.</li>\r\n	<li>If the legislature had intended to make it an offence for a material change of user without approval from the BA, it would have legislated for it in s. 40 which contained dozens of offences for infringements of the provisions of the Ordinance.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:260:\"<p>Building management – change of user – change of user materially different to user stated in occupation permit – change did not breach clause in deed of mutual covenant prohibiting illegal use of premises – Buildings Ordinance (Cap. 123) s. 25</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2345:\"<p><em>Building management – change of user – change of user materially different to user stated in occupation permit – change did not breach clause in deed of mutual covenant prohibiting illegal use of premises – Buildings Ordinance (Cap. 123) s. 25</em></p>\n<p>P was the owner and developer of three sections of a land lot (the “Sections”). P developed a building on each of the three Sections which were linked together by common internal corridors on each floor and served by the same lifts, and which functioned as one building (the “Building”). P still owned seven of the eight ground floor units and four units on the floors above. D2–4 were the incorporated owners of the respective three buildings and D1 was the chairwoman of D2. Of the issues in dispute, one included a claim by Ds that the conversion by P of the carport into shops and godowns was contrary to the user as stated in the occupation permits and hence illegal and in breach of a clause of the deeds of mutual covenants (the “DMCs”) which prohibited illegal use of the premises.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, ruling in favour of P, that:</p>\n<ul><li>Although P’s change of user from carport to shops and godowns on the ground floor was not in line with the occupation permits, it was not illegal and did not contravene the DMC. Section 25 of the Buildings Ordinance (Cap. 123) was relevant. The provision in s. 25(1) required the person intending the material change of user to serve on the Building Authority (the “BA”) a notice of intended change. It was not a crime to adopt a material change in the user of the premises, but it was an offence under s. 40(2) of the Ordinance not to serve a notice to the BA under s. 25(1). If the changed or intended new user was not acceptable to the BA, it could always serve an order under s. 25(2) to prohibit the intended user or require the changed user to be discontinued. But there was no provision saying that it was an offence to adopt a user of the premises which was materially different from that stated in the occupation permit.</li>\n<li>If the legislature had intended to make it an offence for a material change of user without approval from the BA, it would have legislated for it in s. 40 which contained dozens of offences for infringements of the provisions of the Ordinance.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:259:\"<p>Building management – change of user – change of user materially different to user stated in occupation permit – change did not breach clause in deed of mutual covenant prohibiting illegal use of premises – Buildings Ordinance (Cap. 123) s. 25</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:42:\"Wing Hong Investment Co Ltd v Fung Sok Han\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:42:\"Wing Hong Investment Co Ltd v Fung Sok Han\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"112\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-02-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:270:\"http://login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&src=search&docguid=I9D614A2836AE44F2A2158703E6FF6FCF&hitguid=I9D614A2836AE44F2A2158703E6FF6FCF&rank=1&spos=1&epos=1&snippets=true&srguid=i0ad69f8e00000152a0b043e7cd94eb45&keep-search-state-crumb=true&maintain-toc-node=true\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2010\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:17:\"25 September 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:17:\"25 September 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:8:\"Land Law\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:8:\"Land Law\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:42:\"Wing Hong Investment Co Ltd v Fung Sok Han\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454371200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458112328,1),('9334','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9338\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:42:\"Wing Hong Investment Co Ltd v Fung Sok Han\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9334\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1454371200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9333\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2667:\"建築物管理 — 更改用途 — 把建築物的用途更改至大大有別於佔用許可證所指明的用途 — 該更改並無違反公契下關於禁止把處所作非法用途的條款 — 《建築物條例》(第123章)第25條<p>\n	Wing Hong Investment Co Ltd v Fung Sok Han</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&amp;src=search&amp;docguid=I9D614A2836AE44F2A2158703E6FF6FCF&amp;hitguid=I9D614A2836AE44F2A2158703E6FF6FCF&amp;rank=1&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;snippets=true&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e00000152a0b043e7cd94eb45&amp;keep-search-state-crumb=true&amp;maintain-toc-node=true\">[2015] HKEC 2010<br />\n	</a>原訟法庭<br />\n	高院民事訴訟2009年第2075號<br />\n	原訟法庭法官陳江耀<br />\n	2015年9月25日</p>\n<p>\n	原告人是某幅土地其中三段的擁有人兼發展商。原告人在該三個地段上各建一幢大廈，該三幢大廈每層以公用走廊相連、共用同一部升降機，實際上無異於單一幢大廈(下稱「該大廈」)。原告人仍然擁有該大廈地下八個單位其中七個以及樓上各層單位其中四個。第二至第四被告人是上述三幢大廈各自的業主立案法團，而第一被告人是第二被告人的主席。涉案爭議點之一是﹕各名被告人聲稱，原告人把汽車棚轉為店鋪和貨倉乃違背相關佔用許可證所指明的用途，因此既不合法，也違反公契下關於禁止把處所作非法用途的條款。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &mdash; 原告人勝訴﹕</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		原告人把地下汽車棚轉為店鋪和貨倉的做法雖與佔用許可證不符，但既無不合法，也沒有違反公契。《建築物條例》(第123章)第25條與本案有關。第25(1)條規定，有意對建築物的用途作出重大更改的人，須把擬更改用途通知書送達建築事務監督。對處所的用途進行重大更改，並非刑事罪行; 但根據《建築物條例》第40(2)條，不按照第25(1)條把上述通知書送達建築事務監督，乃屬刑事罪行。建築事務監督若然不接受已更改或擬更改的用途，定可按照第25(2)條送達命令，禁止將有關建築物用作該擬作的用途或要求中止將該建築物用作已更改的用途。然而，《建築物條例》並無條文規定把處所用作大大有別於佔用許可證所指明的用途屬於刑事罪行。</li>\n	<li>\n		立法機關若然有意把未經建築事務監督批准而對建築物的用途作出重大更改的行為定性為刑事罪行，便將在第40條下就之而立例，第40條訂立了多種涉及觸犯《建築物條例》規定的罪行。</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:240:\"建築物管理 — 更改用途 — 把建築物的用途更改至大大有別於佔用許可證所指明的用途 — 該更改並無違反公契下關於禁止把處所作非法用途的條款 — 《建築物條例》(第123章)第25條\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2665:\"<p>建築物管理 — 更改用途 — 把建築物的用途更改至大大有別於佔用許可證所指明的用途 — 該更改並無違反公契下關於禁止把處所作非法用途的條款 — 《建築物條例》(第123章)第25條\n</p><p>\n	Wing Hong Investment Co Ltd v Fung Sok Han</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&amp;src=search&amp;docguid=I9D614A2836AE44F2A2158703E6FF6FCF&amp;hitguid=I9D614A2836AE44F2A2158703E6FF6FCF&amp;rank=1&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;snippets=true&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e00000152a0b043e7cd94eb45&amp;keep-search-state-crumb=true&amp;maintain-toc-node=true\">[2015] HKEC 2010<br /></a>原訟法庭<br />\n	高院民事訴訟2009年第2075號<br />\n	原訟法庭法官陳江耀<br />\n	2015年9月25日</p>\n<p>\n	原告人是某幅土地其中三段的擁有人兼發展商。原告人在該三個地段上各建一幢大廈，該三幢大廈每層以公用走廊相連、共用同一部升降機，實際上無異於單一幢大廈(下稱「該大廈」)。原告人仍然擁有該大廈地下八個單位其中七個以及樓上各層單位其中四個。第二至第四被告人是上述三幢大廈各自的業主立案法團，而第一被告人是第二被告人的主席。涉案爭議點之一是﹕各名被告人聲稱，原告人把汽車棚轉為店鋪和貨倉乃違背相關佔用許可證所指明的用途，因此既不合法，也違反公契下關於禁止把處所作非法用途的條款。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> — 原告人勝訴﹕</p>\n<ul><li>\n		原告人把地下汽車棚轉為店鋪和貨倉的做法雖與佔用許可證不符，但既無不合法，也沒有違反公契。《建築物條例》(第123章)第25條與本案有關。第25(1)條規定，有意對建築物的用途作出重大更改的人，須把擬更改用途通知書送達建築事務監督。對處所的用途進行重大更改，並非刑事罪行; 但根據《建築物條例》第40(2)條，不按照第25(1)條把上述通知書送達建築事務監督，乃屬刑事罪行。建築事務監督若然不接受已更改或擬更改的用途，定可按照第25(2)條送達命令，禁止將有關建築物用作該擬作的用途或要求中止將該建築物用作已更改的用途。然而，《建築物條例》並無條文規定把處所用作大大有別於佔用許可證所指明的用途屬於刑事罪行。</li>\n<li>\n		立法機關若然有意把未經建築事務監督批准而對建築物的用途作出重大更改的行為定性為刑事罪行，便將在第40條下就之而立例，第40條訂立了多種涉及觸犯《建築物條例》規定的罪行。</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:248:\"<p>建築物管理 — 更改用途 — 把建築物的用途更改至大大有別於佔用許可證所指明的用途 — 該更改並無違反公契下關於禁止把處所作非法用途的條款 — 《建築物條例》(第123章)第25條</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"原訟法庭\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"原訟法庭\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:42:\"Wing Hong Investment Co Ltd v Fung Sok Han\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:42:\"Wing Hong Investment Co Ltd v Fung Sok Han\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"574\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"638\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-02-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:270:\"http://login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&src=search&docguid=I9D614A2836AE44F2A2158703E6FF6FCF&hitguid=I9D614A2836AE44F2A2158703E6FF6FCF&rank=1&spos=1&epos=1&snippets=true&srguid=i0ad69f8e00000152a0b043e7cd94eb45&keep-search-state-crumb=true&maintain-toc-node=true\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2010\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"2015年9月25日\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"2015年9月25日\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:9:\"土地法\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:9:\"土地法\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:42:\"Wing Hong Investment Co Ltd v Fung Sok Han\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454371200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458183919,1),('9335','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9339\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:48:\"Building Authority v Appeal Tribunal (Buildings)\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9335\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1454371200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456675169\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9335\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2525:\"<p><em>Government lease – construction of “appertain” – features outside of lots could “appertain” to lots if indispensable to construction of buildings of lots and/or essential to survival of buildings and structures on lots</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>X was the owner of two lots of land (“Lots”) which were subject to Government leases (the “Government Leases”). The Government Leases were subject to Condition 6 which required X to, <em>inter alia</em>, carry out repairs of “Walls, Banks, Cutting Hedges, Ditches, Rails, Lights, Pavements, Privies, Sinks, Drains, and Water-courses” which “belong or appertain” to the Lots. An L-shaped soil cut slope (the “Feature”) adjacent to a house, which was in turn adjacent to the Lots, was liable to become dangerous so as to cause a risk of injury to persons or damage to property. The Building Authority (the “BA”) issued a dangerous hillside order against X. X appealed to the Appeal Tribunal (Buildings) (the “BAT”), which found for X as a matter of construction of the word “appertain”, that X had no obligation to maintain and repair the Feature which lay outside the Lots. The BAT did not make any findings on the evidence adduced or determine the other arguments advanced. The BA applied for judicial review of the BAT’s decision.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, allowing the application, quashing the BAT’s decision and referring the case back to a differently constituted BAT for reconsideration, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The usual and ordinary legal meaning of the word “appertain” was “belonging” and this applied to Condition 6. Something would be regarded as belonging to a principal matter if it was part and parcel thereof by being substantially connected to or dependent on the principal matter. If it could be shown by evidence that a certain feature, even though lying outside the Lots, was indispensable to the construction of the buildings of the Lots and/or essential to the survival of the buildings and structures on the Lots, it was likely that such a feature could be regarded as “belonging” or “appertaining” unto the Lots.</li>\r\n	<li>The general rule of presumption against redundant words did not assist BA. It was regarded as “particularly weak” in construing conveyancing documents. The court could not insist on giving each word in a series a distinct meaning because draftsmen frequently used many words either because it was traditional to do so or out of a sense of caution.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:239:\"<p>Government lease – construction of “appertain” – features outside of lots could “appertain” to lots if indispensable to construction of buildings of lots and/or essential to survival of buildings and structures on lots</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2508:\"<p><em>Government lease – construction of “appertain” – features outside of lots could “appertain” to lots if indispensable to construction of buildings of lots and/or essential to survival of buildings and structures on lots</em></p>\n<p>X was the owner of two lots of land (“Lots”) which were subject to Government leases (the “Government Leases”). The Government Leases were subject to Condition 6 which required X to, <em>inter alia</em>, carry out repairs of “Walls, Banks, Cutting Hedges, Ditches, Rails, Lights, Pavements, Privies, Sinks, Drains, and Water-courses” which “belong or appertain” to the Lots. An L-shaped soil cut slope (the “Feature”) adjacent to a house, which was in turn adjacent to the Lots, was liable to become dangerous so as to cause a risk of injury to persons or damage to property. The Building Authority (the “BA”) issued a dangerous hillside order against X. X appealed to the Appeal Tribunal (Buildings) (the “BAT”), which found for X as a matter of construction of the word “appertain”, that X had no obligation to maintain and repair the Feature which lay outside the Lots. The BAT did not make any findings on the evidence adduced or determine the other arguments advanced. The BA applied for judicial review of the BAT’s decision.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, allowing the application, quashing the BAT’s decision and referring the case back to a differently constituted BAT for reconsideration, that:</p>\n<ul><li>The usual and ordinary legal meaning of the word “appertain” was “belonging” and this applied to Condition 6. Something would be regarded as belonging to a principal matter if it was part and parcel thereof by being substantially connected to or dependent on the principal matter. If it could be shown by evidence that a certain feature, even though lying outside the Lots, was indispensable to the construction of the buildings of the Lots and/or essential to the survival of the buildings and structures on the Lots, it was likely that such a feature could be regarded as “belonging” or “appertaining” unto the Lots.</li>\n<li>The general rule of presumption against redundant words did not assist BA. It was regarded as “particularly weak” in construing conveyancing documents. The court could not insist on giving each word in a series a distinct meaning because draftsmen frequently used many words either because it was traditional to do so or out of a sense of caution.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:238:\"<p>Government lease – construction of “appertain” – features outside of lots could “appertain” to lots if indispensable to construction of buildings of lots and/or essential to survival of buildings and structures on lots</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:48:\"Building Authority v Appeal Tribunal (Buildings)\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:48:\"Building Authority v Appeal Tribunal (Buildings)\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"112\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-02-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:0:{}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:48:\"Building Authority v Appeal Tribunal (Buildings)\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454371200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458112328,1),('9336','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9340\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:48:\"Building Authority v Appeal Tribunal (Buildings)\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9336\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1454371200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9335\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3175:\"政府租契 — 對“appertain”的詮釋 — 地段以外的斜坡如果對地段內建築物的結構是不可或缺的及∕或對地段上的樓宇及構築物的存留是必要的，便與地段有關，也就是“…appertain unto the same”<p>\n	Building Authority v Appeal Tribunal (Buildings)</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&amp;src=search&amp;docguid=IF59EF844E6E54529A7302AE718128472&amp;hitguid=IF59EF844E6E54529A7302AE718128472&amp;rank=1&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;snippets=true&amp;srguid=i0ad6290300000152a0ba15e11f579683&amp;keep-search-state-crumb=true&amp;maintain-toc-node=true#http://login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&amp;src=search&amp;docguid=IF59EF844E6E54529A7302AE718128472&amp;hitguid=IF59EF844E6E54529A7302AE718128472&amp;rank=1&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;snippets=true&amp;srguid=i0ad6290300000152a0ba15e11f579683&amp;keep-search-state-crumb=true&amp;maintain-toc-node=true\">[2015] HKEC 2201</a><br />\n	原訟法庭<br />\n	高院憲法及行政訴訟2014年第14號<br />\n	高等法院原訟法庭法官區慶祥<br />\n	2015年10月22日</p>\n<p>\n	X是兩地段土地(「該兩地段」)的擁有人，該兩地段受到政府租契規限。政府租契被當作已包含第6條條款，該條款規定X，除了別的以外，必須修理屬於(&ldquo;belong or appertain&rdquo;)該兩地段的「牆、斜坡、路塹、樹籬、溝渠、路軌、燈、行人路、旱厠、污水坑、排水渠及水道」。一幅L形削土坡(「該斜坡」)與一間屋相連，而那間屋又毗連該兩地段。該斜坡會坍塌或可能有坍塌危險，存在引致人身傷亡或財產損失的風險。建築事務監督向X發出危險斜坡修葺令。X認為自己沒有責任維修及修理該兩地段範圍之外的該斜坡，因而向上訴審裁小組(建築物)(「審裁小組」)上訴。審裁小組裁定X在對&ldquo;appertain&rdquo;一詞的詮釋上得直。審裁小組沒有對援引的證據作出裁斷或對其他提出的論點作出裁定。建築事務監督申請司法覆核審裁小組的決定。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &ndash; 批准申請，推翻審裁小組的決定，將案件發回由不同成員組成的審裁小組重新考慮：</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		&ldquo;appertain&rdquo;一詞慣常及通常的法律意思是&ldquo;belonging&rdquo;(屬於)，這意思適用於第6條條款。某物如果在很大程度上連接或依靠主物，因而是主物的一部分或分份，便會被視為屬於該主物。如果能有證據證明某幅斜坡對該兩地段內建築物的結構是不可或缺的及∕或對該兩地段上的樓宇及構築物的存留是必要的，那麽，雖然該幅斜坡位於該兩地段範圍之外，也相當可能被視為屬於(&ldquo;appertain&rdquo;或&ldquo;appertaining&rdquo;)該兩地段。</li>\n	<li>\n		不用贅詞的假定這一般性規則幫不了建築事務監督。這假定被認為在詮釋物業轉易文件時是「特別的弱」。起草人通常不是因為傳統關係，便是出於謹慎起見而使用多個詞，因此，法庭不能堅持在一連串的詞中逐個給予不同的意思。</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:252:\"政府租契 — 對“appertain”的詮釋 — 地段以外的斜坡如果對地段內建築物的結構是不可或缺的及∕或對地段上的樓宇及構築物的存留是必要的，便與地段有關，也就是“…appertain unto the same”\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3127:\"<p>政府租契 — 對“appertain”的詮釋 — 地段以外的斜坡如果對地段內建築物的結構是不可或缺的及∕或對地段上的樓宇及構築物的存留是必要的，便與地段有關，也就是“…appertain unto the same”\n</p><p>\n	Building Authority v Appeal Tribunal (Buildings)</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&amp;src=search&amp;docguid=IF59EF844E6E54529A7302AE718128472&amp;hitguid=IF59EF844E6E54529A7302AE718128472&amp;rank=1&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;snippets=true&amp;srguid=i0ad6290300000152a0ba15e11f579683&amp;keep-search-state-crumb=true&amp;maintain-toc-node=true#http://login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&amp;src=search&amp;docguid=IF59EF844E6E54529A7302AE718128472&amp;hitguid=IF59EF844E6E54529A7302AE718128472&amp;rank=1&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;snippets=true&amp;srguid=i0ad6290300000152a0ba15e11f579683&amp;keep-search-state-crumb=true&amp;maintain-toc-node=true\">[2015] HKEC 2201</a><br />\n	原訟法庭<br />\n	高院憲法及行政訴訟2014年第14號<br />\n	高等法院原訟法庭法官區慶祥<br />\n	2015年10月22日</p>\n<p>\n	X是兩地段土地(「該兩地段」)的擁有人，該兩地段受到政府租契規限。政府租契被當作已包含第6條條款，該條款規定X，除了別的以外，必須修理屬於(“belong or appertain”)該兩地段的「牆、斜坡、路塹、樹籬、溝渠、路軌、燈、行人路、旱厠、污水坑、排水渠及水道」。一幅L形削土坡(「該斜坡」)與一間屋相連，而那間屋又毗連該兩地段。該斜坡會坍塌或可能有坍塌危險，存在引致人身傷亡或財產損失的風險。建築事務監督向X發出危險斜坡修葺令。X認為自己沒有責任維修及修理該兩地段範圍之外的該斜坡，因而向上訴審裁小組(建築物)(「審裁小組」)上訴。審裁小組裁定X在對“appertain”一詞的詮釋上得直。審裁小組沒有對援引的證據作出裁斷或對其他提出的論點作出裁定。建築事務監督申請司法覆核審裁小組的決定。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> – 批准申請，推翻審裁小組的決定，將案件發回由不同成員組成的審裁小組重新考慮：</p>\n<ul><li>\n		“appertain”一詞慣常及通常的法律意思是“belonging”(屬於)，這意思適用於第6條條款。某物如果在很大程度上連接或依靠主物，因而是主物的一部分或分份，便會被視為屬於該主物。如果能有證據證明某幅斜坡對該兩地段內建築物的結構是不可或缺的及∕或對該兩地段上的樓宇及構築物的存留是必要的，那麽，雖然該幅斜坡位於該兩地段範圍之外，也相當可能被視為屬於(“appertain”或“appertaining”)該兩地段。</li>\n<li>\n		不用贅詞的假定這一般性規則幫不了建築事務監督。這假定被認為在詮釋物業轉易文件時是「特別的弱」。起草人通常不是因為傳統關係，便是出於謹慎起見而使用多個詞，因此，法庭不能堅持在一連串的詞中逐個給予不同的意思。</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:260:\"<p>政府租契 — 對“appertain”的詮釋 — 地段以外的斜坡如果對地段內建築物的結構是不可或缺的及∕或對地段上的樓宇及構築物的存留是必要的，便與地段有關，也就是“…appertain unto the same”</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:48:\"Building Authority v Appeal Tribunal (Buildings)\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:48:\"Building Authority v Appeal Tribunal (Buildings)\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"574\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"638\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-02-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:0:{}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:48:\"Building Authority v Appeal Tribunal (Buildings)\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454371200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458182662,1),('9337','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9341\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:42:\"Hingone Investment Co Ltd v Leung Tung Hoi\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9337\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1454457600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456675110\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9337\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1456394544\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:1485:\"<p><em>Court of Appeal – interlocutory appeal – application for leave should first be made to lower court, particularly in respect of case management decision – reasons for decision of lower court should be provided to Court of Appeal</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Judge refused Ds’ summons for leave to file supplemental witness statements and their application for leave to appeal against her dismissal of the summons. Ds now applied for leave to appeal to the Court of Appeal, but did not provide the Judge’s written judgment or the transcript or notes of her oral decision.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>An application for leave should be made to the judge below as the Court of Appeal should have the benefit of that judge’s view on leave to appeal. This was particularly so, when the appeal concerned a case management decision which, by its nature, was sensitive to the procedural history and circumstances leading to the decision.</li>\r\n	<li>The proposed appeal had no prospect of success and there was no other reason in the interests of justice to grant leave to file evidence at so late a stage. Inter alia, without including the Judge’s reasons (both in dismissing the summons and refusing leave) in the application bundle, Ds had failed to provide the necessary materials to substantiate their submission that the Judge had erred in principle or that the exercise of her discretion was plainly wrong.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:242:\"<p>Court of Appeal – interlocutory appeal – application for leave should first be made to lower court, particularly in respect of case management decision – reasons for decision of lower court should be provided to Court of Appeal</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:1468:\"<p><em>Court of Appeal – interlocutory appeal – application for leave should first be made to lower court, particularly in respect of case management decision – reasons for decision of lower court should be provided to Court of Appeal</em></p>\n<p>The Judge refused Ds’ summons for leave to file supplemental witness statements and their application for leave to appeal against her dismissal of the summons. Ds now applied for leave to appeal to the Court of Appeal, but did not provide the Judge’s written judgment or the transcript or notes of her oral decision.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\n<ul><li>An application for leave should be made to the judge below as the Court of Appeal should have the benefit of that judge’s view on leave to appeal. This was particularly so, when the appeal concerned a case management decision which, by its nature, was sensitive to the procedural history and circumstances leading to the decision.</li>\n<li>The proposed appeal had no prospect of success and there was no other reason in the interests of justice to grant leave to file evidence at so late a stage. Inter alia, without including the Judge’s reasons (both in dismissing the summons and refusing leave) in the application bundle, Ds had failed to provide the necessary materials to substantiate their submission that the Judge had erred in principle or that the exercise of her discretion was plainly wrong.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:241:\"<p>Court of Appeal – interlocutory appeal – application for leave should first be made to lower court, particularly in respect of case management decision – reasons for decision of lower court should be provided to Court of Appeal</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Court of Appeal\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:42:\"Hingone Investment Co Ltd v Leung Tung Hoi\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:42:\"Hingone Investment Co Ltd v Leung Tung Hoi\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-02-01 00:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:263:\"login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&src=search&docguid=I29C6DE84C7DC461CB6A3020E083F3F4E&hitguid=I29C6DE84C7DC461CB6A3020E083F3F4E&rank=1&spos=1&epos=1&snippets=true&srguid=i0ad69f8e00000152a4cbca80bc345060&keep-search-state-crumb=true&maintain-toc-node=true\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2426\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:16:\"17 November 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:16:\"17 November 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:42:\"Hingone Investment Co Ltd v Leung Tung Hoi\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";s:1:\"0\";s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";N;s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458115031,1),('9338','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9342\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:42:\"Hingone Investment Co Ltd v Leung Tung Hoi\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9338\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1454457600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9337\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:1838:\"上訴法庭 — 非正審上訴 — 特別就案件管理決定而言，應先向下級法庭申請許可 — 應向上訴法庭提供下級法庭的裁決理由<p>\n	Hingone Investment Co Ltd v Leung Tung Hoi</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&amp;src=search&amp;docguid=I29C6DE84C7DC461CB6A3020E083F3F4E&amp;hitguid=I29C6DE84C7DC461CB6A3020E083F3F4E&amp;rank=1&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;snippets=true&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e00000152a4cbca80bc345060&amp;keep-search-state-crumb=true&amp;maintain-toc-node=true\">[2015] HKEC 2426<br />\n	</a>上訴法庭<br />\n	高院雜項案件2015年第2604號<br />\n	上訴法庭副庭長林文瀚，上訴法庭法官朱芬齡<br />\n	2015年11月17日</p>\n<p>\n	本案被告人發出傳票，申請許可把補充證人陳述書送交法院存檔。原審法官駁回該申請。被告人不服，申請許可提出上訴，但亦遭原審法官駁回。被告人現向上訴法庭申請上訴許可，但未有提供原審法官的判案書或原審法官的口頭裁決謄本或摘記。<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &mdash; 駁回申請﹕</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		上訴許可申請應向下級法官提出，因為上訴法庭應能得到下級法官對上訴許可的看法協助。這特別適用於針對案件管理決定提出上訴的情況，因為該類決定的特性是相當取決於訴訟程序歷史和背景情況。</li>\n	<li>\n		本案被告人擬提出的上訴毫無勝訴機會，案中亦缺乏合乎公義的理由支持在如此晚段准許被告人提交證據。除其他情況外，被告人亦沒有在申請文件夾內提供原審法官裁定駁回傳票和駁回上訴許可申請的理由，從而未有提供所需資料，以支持他們指原審法官曾在原則上犯錯或曾顯然錯誤地行使其酌情權的說法。</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:162:\"上訴法庭 — 非正審上訴 — 特別就案件管理決定而言，應先向下級法庭申請許可 — 應向上訴法庭提供下級法庭的裁決理由\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:1829:\"<p>上訴法庭 — 非正審上訴 — 特別就案件管理決定而言，應先向下級法庭申請許可 — 應向上訴法庭提供下級法庭的裁決理由\n</p><p>\n	Hingone Investment Co Ltd v Leung Tung Hoi</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&amp;src=search&amp;docguid=I29C6DE84C7DC461CB6A3020E083F3F4E&amp;hitguid=I29C6DE84C7DC461CB6A3020E083F3F4E&amp;rank=1&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;snippets=true&amp;srguid=i0ad69f8e00000152a4cbca80bc345060&amp;keep-search-state-crumb=true&amp;maintain-toc-node=true\">[2015] HKEC 2426<br /></a>上訴法庭<br />\n	高院雜項案件2015年第2604號<br />\n	上訴法庭副庭長林文瀚，上訴法庭法官朱芬齡<br />\n	2015年11月17日</p>\n<p>\n	本案被告人發出傳票，申請許可把補充證人陳述書送交法院存檔。原審法官駁回該申請。被告人不服，申請許可提出上訴，但亦遭原審法官駁回。被告人現向上訴法庭申請上訴許可，但未有提供原審法官的判案書或原審法官的口頭裁決謄本或摘記。</p>\n<p>	<strong>裁決</strong> — 駁回申請﹕</p>\n<ul><li>\n		上訴許可申請應向下級法官提出，因為上訴法庭應能得到下級法官對上訴許可的看法協助。這特別適用於針對案件管理決定提出上訴的情況，因為該類決定的特性是相當取決於訴訟程序歷史和背景情況。</li>\n<li>\n		本案被告人擬提出的上訴毫無勝訴機會，案中亦缺乏合乎公義的理由支持在如此晚段准許被告人提交證據。除其他情況外，被告人亦沒有在申請文件夾內提供原審法官裁定駁回傳票和駁回上訴許可申請的理由，從而未有提供所需資料，以支持他們指原審法官曾在原則上犯錯或曾顯然錯誤地行使其酌情權的說法。</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:170:\"<p>上訴法庭 — 非正審上訴 — 特別就案件管理決定而言，應先向下級法庭申請許可 — 應向上訴法庭提供下級法庭的裁決理由</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"上訴法庭\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"上訴法庭\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:42:\"Hingone Investment Co Ltd v Leung Tung Hoi\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:42:\"Hingone Investment Co Ltd v Leung Tung Hoi\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"565\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"638\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-02-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:263:\"login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&src=search&docguid=I29C6DE84C7DC461CB6A3020E083F3F4E&hitguid=I29C6DE84C7DC461CB6A3020E083F3F4E&rank=1&spos=1&epos=1&snippets=true&srguid=i0ad69f8e00000152a4cbca80bc345060&keep-search-state-crumb=true&maintain-toc-node=true\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2426\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:17:\"2015年11月17日\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:17:\"2015年11月17日\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"民事訴訟程序\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"民事訴訟程序\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:42:\"Hingone Investment Co Ltd v Leung Tung Hoi\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454457600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458182662,1),('9339','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9343\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:47:\"Emperor International Holdings Ltd v Atnext Ltd\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9339\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1454457600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456674981\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9339\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2390:\"<p><em>Interlocutory injunctions – ex parte application for interim injunction restraining publication of allegedly defamatory articles – no compelling reasons for making application without notice – continuation of injunction refused</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>D, a BVI company, was the domain registrant of a website for the online version of a local Chinese newspaper (the “Website”). P, a Hong Kong listed company, brought proceedings in defamation against D and sought to continue an <em>ex parte </em>interlocutory injunction (the “Injunction”) to restrain the publication of two articles published on the Website, which allegedly suggested that P had bribed a senior mainland Chinese government official involved in a property development owned by X. D opposed the application.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>It was plainly wrong for P to have gone <em>ex parte</em> without any notice to D. P had sufficient time to give notice to D. Nor was this a case of a <em>quia timet </em>injunction. There was no evidence that D would take further action which would frustrate the application. The fundamental right to equality before the law and the right to free speech and freedom of the press were engaged. To restrain the media was a strong thing and there were no compelling reasons for making the application without notice. For this reason alone, the Injunction must be discharged. Further, as the application was made <em>ex parte</em>, none of the points eventually raised by D was put before the Duty Judge.</li>\r\n	<li>A plaintiff who applied for an interlocutory injunction in defamation cases must show the statement in question <em>prima facie </em>to be untrue. Here, the affirmation for P consisted of a bare and broad assertion that 12 statements quoted were false, without any evidence of particulars. Further, if it was based on information, the sources were not stated as required by O. 41 r.5(2) of the Rules of the High Court (Cap.4A, Sub. Leg.). The rule should be strictly complied with where, as here, objection was likely to be taken, especially an objection of substance and not a mere technical frivolous one. D was entitled therefore, as a point of principle, to object to the evidence adduced by P in the <em>ex parte </em>application and unsupplemented by any further evidence as defective.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:242:\"<p>Interlocutory injunctions – ex parte application for interim injunction restraining publication of allegedly defamatory articles – no compelling reasons for making application without notice – continuation of injunction refused</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2373:\"<p><em>Interlocutory injunctions – ex parte application for interim injunction restraining publication of allegedly defamatory articles – no compelling reasons for making application without notice – continuation of injunction refused</em></p>\n<p>D, a BVI company, was the domain registrant of a website for the online version of a local Chinese newspaper (the “Website”). P, a Hong Kong listed company, brought proceedings in defamation against D and sought to continue an <em>ex parte </em>interlocutory injunction (the “Injunction”) to restrain the publication of two articles published on the Website, which allegedly suggested that P had bribed a senior mainland Chinese government official involved in a property development owned by X. D opposed the application.</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the application, that:</p>\n<ul><li>It was plainly wrong for P to have gone <em>ex parte</em> without any notice to D. P had sufficient time to give notice to D. Nor was this a case of a <em>quia timet </em>injunction. There was no evidence that D would take further action which would frustrate the application. The fundamental right to equality before the law and the right to free speech and freedom of the press were engaged. To restrain the media was a strong thing and there were no compelling reasons for making the application without notice. For this reason alone, the Injunction must be discharged. Further, as the application was made <em>ex parte</em>, none of the points eventually raised by D was put before the Duty Judge.</li>\n<li>A plaintiff who applied for an interlocutory injunction in defamation cases must show the statement in question <em>prima facie </em>to be untrue. Here, the affirmation for P consisted of a bare and broad assertion that 12 statements quoted were false, without any evidence of particulars. Further, if it was based on information, the sources were not stated as required by O. 41 r.5(2) of the Rules of the High Court (Cap.4A, Sub. Leg.). The rule should be strictly complied with where, as here, objection was likely to be taken, especially an objection of substance and not a mere technical frivolous one. D was entitled therefore, as a point of principle, to object to the evidence adduced by P in the <em>ex parte </em>application and unsupplemented by any further evidence as defective.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:241:\"<p>Interlocutory injunctions – ex parte application for interim injunction restraining publication of allegedly defamatory articles – no compelling reasons for making application without notice – continuation of injunction refused</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:47:\"Emperor International Holdings Ltd v Atnext Ltd\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:47:\"Emperor International Holdings Ltd v Atnext Ltd\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-02-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:270:\"http://login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&src=search&docguid=I048D509FDC554F0789BDCE5CDBA8EC3A&hitguid=I048D509FDC554F0789BDCE5CDBA8EC3A&rank=1&spos=1&epos=1&snippets=true&srguid=ia744cc6300000152a4d5604bcbbbf38b&keep-search-state-crumb=true&maintain-toc-node=true\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2479\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"14 October 2015\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"14 October 2015\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:15:\"Civil Procedure\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:47:\"Emperor International Holdings Ltd v Atnext Ltd\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454457600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458112328,1),('9340','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9344\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:47:\"Emperor International Holdings Ltd v Atnext Ltd\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9340\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1454457600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9339\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2881:\"非正審強制令 — 單方面申請非正審強制令，以期阻止出版被指具誹謗性的文章 — 缺乏令人信服的理由以支持在不通知答辯人的情況下提出申請 —法庭拒絕下令強制令繼續生效<p>\n	Emperor International Holdings Ltd v Atnext Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&amp;src=search&amp;docguid=I048D509FDC554F0789BDCE5CDBA8EC3A&amp;hitguid=I048D509FDC554F0789BDCE5CDBA8EC3A&amp;rank=1&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;snippets=true&amp;srguid=ia744cc6300000152a4d5604bcbbbf38b&amp;keep-search-state-crumb=true&amp;maintain-toc-node=true\">[2015] HKEC 2479<br />\n	</a>原訟法庭<br />\n	高院民事訴訟2015年第2227號<br />\n	原訟法庭法官林雲浩內庭聆訊<br />\n	2015年10月14日</p>\n<p>\n	本案被告人是一家在英屬維爾京群島成立的公司，也是一份本地中文報章在線版網站(下稱「涉案網站」)的域名註冊人。原告人是一家本港上市公司。原告人提起法律程序，指控被告人誹謗，並提出申請，要求法庭下令一項針對被告人的單方面非正審強制令(下稱「涉案強制令」)繼續生效。涉案強制令阻止被告人在涉案網站出版兩篇文章，其內容被指意味著原告人曾經賄賂一名涉及由某人擁有的地產發展項目的內地政府高層官員。被告人反對上述申請。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> &mdash; 駁回申請﹕</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		原告人在不通知被告人的情況下提出申請，做法顯然錯誤。原告人有充分時間通知被告人。本案亦不涉及「預防對方犯錯」類別的強制令。案中沒有證據顯示被告人將採取進一步行動令原告人的申請徒然。本案牽涉「法律面前人人平等」的基本權利、言論自由及傳媒自由。阻止傳媒報道絕非小事，而案中缺乏令人信服的理由以支持原告人在不通知被告人的情況下提出申請。單憑此理由，涉案強制令已須予解除。此外，原告人所提出的屬單方面申請，因此當值法官並無機會聽取被告人最終提出的論點。</li>\n	<li>\n		在涉及誹謗的案件中，原告人如申請非正審強制令，必須證明涉案陳述表面上並非屬實。本案原告人一方所提交的誓章，純粹籠統地指稱被引述的12項陳述屬虛假，未有提供任何詳述作為證據。此外，假如該誓章的內容建基於資料，則原告人一方未有按照《高等法院規則》(第4章，附屬法例A)第41號命令第5(2)條規則述明資料來源。當答辯人相當可能反對上述申請、特別是反對理由實質而非純屬技術性或瑣屑無聊之時，申請人便應嚴格遵守上述規則。因此，原則上，被告人有權提出反對，指原告人在單方面申請中提交且未經進一步補充的證據有欠完善。</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:233:\"非正審強制令 — 單方面申請非正審強制令，以期阻止出版被指具誹謗性的文章 — 缺乏令人信服的理由以支持在不通知答辯人的情況下提出申請 —法庭拒絕下令強制令繼續生效\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2879:\"<p>非正審強制令 — 單方面申請非正審強制令，以期阻止出版被指具誹謗性的文章 — 缺乏令人信服的理由以支持在不通知答辯人的情況下提出申請 —法庭拒絕下令強制令繼續生效\n</p><p>\n	Emperor International Holdings Ltd v Atnext Ltd</p>\n<p>\n	<a href=\"http://login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&amp;src=search&amp;docguid=I048D509FDC554F0789BDCE5CDBA8EC3A&amp;hitguid=I048D509FDC554F0789BDCE5CDBA8EC3A&amp;rank=1&amp;spos=1&amp;epos=1&amp;snippets=true&amp;srguid=ia744cc6300000152a4d5604bcbbbf38b&amp;keep-search-state-crumb=true&amp;maintain-toc-node=true\">[2015] HKEC 2479<br /></a>原訟法庭<br />\n	高院民事訴訟2015年第2227號<br />\n	原訟法庭法官林雲浩內庭聆訊<br />\n	2015年10月14日</p>\n<p>\n	本案被告人是一家在英屬維爾京群島成立的公司，也是一份本地中文報章在線版網站(下稱「涉案網站」)的域名註冊人。原告人是一家本港上市公司。原告人提起法律程序，指控被告人誹謗，並提出申請，要求法庭下令一項針對被告人的單方面非正審強制令(下稱「涉案強制令」)繼續生效。涉案強制令阻止被告人在涉案網站出版兩篇文章，其內容被指意味著原告人曾經賄賂一名涉及由某人擁有的地產發展項目的內地政府高層官員。被告人反對上述申請。</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>裁決</strong> — 駁回申請﹕</p>\n<ul><li>\n		原告人在不通知被告人的情況下提出申請，做法顯然錯誤。原告人有充分時間通知被告人。本案亦不涉及「預防對方犯錯」類別的強制令。案中沒有證據顯示被告人將採取進一步行動令原告人的申請徒然。本案牽涉「法律面前人人平等」的基本權利、言論自由及傳媒自由。阻止傳媒報道絕非小事，而案中缺乏令人信服的理由以支持原告人在不通知被告人的情況下提出申請。單憑此理由，涉案強制令已須予解除。此外，原告人所提出的屬單方面申請，因此當值法官並無機會聽取被告人最終提出的論點。</li>\n<li>\n		在涉及誹謗的案件中，原告人如申請非正審強制令，必須證明涉案陳述表面上並非屬實。本案原告人一方所提交的誓章，純粹籠統地指稱被引述的12項陳述屬虛假，未有提供任何詳述作為證據。此外，假如該誓章的內容建基於資料，則原告人一方未有按照《高等法院規則》(第4章，附屬法例A)第41號命令第5(2)條規則述明資料來源。當答辯人相當可能反對上述申請、特別是反對理由實質而非純屬技術性或瑣屑無聊之時，申請人便應嚴格遵守上述規則。因此，原則上，被告人有權提出反對，指原告人在單方面申請中提交且未經進一步補充的證據有欠完善。</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:241:\"<p>非正審強制令 — 單方面申請非正審強制令，以期阻止出版被指具誹謗性的文章 — 缺乏令人信服的理由以支持在不通知答辯人的情況下提出申請 —法庭拒絕下令強制令繼續生效</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:12:\"原訟法庭\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:12:\"原訟法庭\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:47:\"Emperor International Holdings Ltd v Atnext Ltd\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:47:\"Emperor International Holdings Ltd v Atnext Ltd\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"511\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"565\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"638\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-02-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:270:\"http://login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&src=search&docguid=I048D509FDC554F0789BDCE5CDBA8EC3A&hitguid=I048D509FDC554F0789BDCE5CDBA8EC3A&rank=1&spos=1&epos=1&snippets=true&srguid=ia744cc6300000152a4d5604bcbbbf38b&keep-search-state-crumb=true&maintain-toc-node=true\";s:5:\"title\";s:16:\"[2015] HKEC 2479\";s:10:\"attributes\";a:0:{}}}}s:15:\"field_case_date\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:17:\"2015年10月14日\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:17:\"2015年10月14日\";}}}s:18:\"field_case_subject\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:18:\"民事訴訟程序\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:18:\"民事訴訟程序\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:0:{}s:18:\"field_court_number\";a:0:{}s:12:\"field_judges\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:47:\"Emperor International Holdings Ltd v Atnext Ltd\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:9:{s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454457600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458182662,1),('9341','O:8:\"stdClass\":41:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9345\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:8:\"Re G Ltd\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9341\";s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"case_updates\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1454457600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456675053\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9341\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1454992017\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2559:\"<p><em>Liquidation – foreign company – Hong Kong court empowered at common law to recognise and assist foreign liquidators</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>P sought to wind up C, a Cayman Islands company listed on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, on the grounds of insolvency. P also applied for an early hearing of its application to appoint provisional liquidators in Hong Kong (the “Application”). At the hearing on 2 October 2015, it emerged that C had sought its own winding-up in the Cayman Islands and an application to appoint provisional liquidators would be heard on 8 October 2015. The Judge held that P had not shown any reason to pre-empt the Cayman Court’s decision; and while P might have genuine concerns about the risk of documents being destroyed or removed, such fears did not necessitate the Application. The Judge therefore adjourned it pending the Cayman Court’s determination. On 8 October 2015, C’s application was unopposed and the Cayman Court appointed KPMG in both the Cayman Islands and Hong Kong as provisional liquidators (“Ls”).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the Application, that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>In respect of applications to wind up both solvent and insolvent foreign incorporated companies, there was a strong presumption that the appropriate jurisdiction to petition for a winding-up order was in the company’s place of incorporation. However, under s. 327 of the Companies (Winding Up and Miscellaneous Provisions) Ordinance (Cap. 32), the court had the discretion to wind up a foreign company in the circumstances specified in sub-s. 3.</li>\r\n	<li>At common law, a Hong Kong court had the power to recognise and assist foreign liquidators of insolvent companies wound up in their places of incorporation with similar insolvency regimes by giving them substantially similar powers to those which domestic liquidators would have, for example, to investigate the companies’ affairs by examination and production of documents.</li>\r\n	<li>If the foreign liquidators considered it necessary to seek recognition and assistance from the Hong Kong court, they could obtain a letter of request from the local court and then apply <em>ex parte </em>on paper for a recognition order. If the liquidators thought it desirable to wind up the foreign company in Hong Kong and that they could satisfy the criteria for assessing such petitions, they could apply for a winding-up order, and if required, apply to be appointed as provisional liquidators in Hong Kong pending the determination of the petition.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:128:\"<p>Liquidation – foreign company – Hong Kong court empowered at common law to recognise and assist foreign liquidators</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2540:\"<p><em>Liquidation – foreign company – Hong Kong court empowered at common law to recognise and assist foreign liquidators</em></p>\n<p>P sought to wind up C, a Cayman Islands company listed on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, on the grounds of insolvency. P also applied for an early hearing of its application to appoint provisional liquidators in Hong Kong (the “Application”). At the hearing on 2 October 2015, it emerged that C had sought its own winding-up in the Cayman Islands and an application to appoint provisional liquidators would be heard on 8 October 2015. The Judge held that P had not shown any reason to pre-empt the Cayman Court’s decision; and while P might have genuine concerns about the risk of documents being destroyed or removed, such fears did not necessitate the Application. The Judge therefore adjourned it pending the Cayman Court’s determination. On 8 October 2015, C’s application was unopposed and the Cayman Court appointed KPMG in both the Cayman Islands and Hong Kong as provisional liquidators (“Ls”).</p>\n<p><strong>Held</strong>, dismissing the Application, that:</p>\n<ul><li>In respect of applications to wind up both solvent and insolvent foreign incorporated companies, there was a strong presumption that the appropriate jurisdiction to petition for a winding-up order was in the company’s place of incorporation. However, under s. 327 of the Companies (Winding Up and Miscellaneous Provisions) Ordinance (Cap. 32), the court had the discretion to wind up a foreign company in the circumstances specified in sub-s. 3.</li>\n<li>At common law, a Hong Kong court had the power to recognise and assist foreign liquidators of insolvent companies wound up in their places of incorporation with similar insolvency regimes by giving them substantially similar powers to those which domestic liquidators would have, for example, to investigate the companies’ affairs by examination and production of documents.</li>\n<li>If the foreign liquidators considered it necessary to seek recognition and assistance from the Hong Kong court, they could obtain a letter of request from the local court and then apply <em>ex parte </em>on paper for a recognition order. If the liquidators thought it desirable to wind up the foreign company in Hong Kong and that they could satisfy the criteria for assessing such petitions, they could apply for a winding-up order, and if required, apply to be appointed as provisional liquidators in Hong Kong pending the determination of the petition.</li>\n</ul>\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:127:\"<p>Liquidation – foreign company – Hong Kong court empowered at common law to recognise and assist foreign liquidators</p>\n\";}}}s:11:\"field_court\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:23:\"Court of First Instance\";}}}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:8:\"Re G Ltd\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:8:\"Re G Ltd\";}}}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"474\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:2:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"100\";}i:1;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"103\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"612\";}}}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-02-01 08:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:18:\"field_citation_url\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"url\";s:270:\"http://login.westlawasia.com/maf//app/document?&src=search&docguid=I1173BFA4FC4D431A87D4336ABAE74