editor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458111751,1),('9433','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9437\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:61:\"China Anti-Monopoly Law Update: 2015 Review and 2016 Forecast\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9433\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1456099200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456310169\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9432\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1456310169\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:7828:\"Adrian Emch, Partner, and Jiaming Zhang, Hogan Lovells, Beijing<p>\n	To get an overview of the major anti-monopoly law developments in China in 2015 and a prediction of how the landscape might shift in 2016, Hong Kong Lawyer reached out to competition/antitrust law specialists, Adrian Emch, Partner, and Jiaming Zhang of Hogan Lovells&rsquo; Beijing office.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>2015 Review</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	In retrospect, 2015 will possibly be viewed as a year of transition for Chinese antitrust law. On the one hand, there appears to have been a change in pace in the enforcement of the Anti-Monopoly Law (&ldquo;AML&rdquo;). On the other hand, certain antitrust developments in 2015 reflect continuity with prior enforcement trends and policies. <br />\n	<br />\n	<em>Change in 2015</em><br />\n	<br />\n	In the Chinese antitrust field, 2015 started with the landmark Qualcomm decision. The decision is frequently viewed as one of the most, if not the most, controversial antitrust case in China in the past years. The National Development and Reform Commission (&ldquo;NDRC&rdquo;) imposed a record fine of around RMB 6 billion on Qualcomm for alleged abuse of dominance. To our knowledge, this fine is the second highest imposed on a single company in an individual case in the history of antitrust law &ndash; on a global basis.<br />\n	<br />\n	In the lead-up to the Qualcomm decision, there had been numerous complaints against a perceived bias in Chinese antitrust law enforcement, especially by foreign stakeholders (including the US government). Perhaps as a reaction to these complaints, the three Chinese antitrust authorities &ndash; NDRC, the State Administration for Industry and Commerce (&ldquo;SAIC&rdquo;) and the Ministry of Commerce (&ldquo;MOFCOM&rdquo;) &ndash; took somewhat of a &quot;lower profile&quot; in 2015 after Qualcomm. <br />\n	<br />\n	In parallel with the lower intensity in enforcement activity, the antitrust authorities undertook wide-ranging normative efforts in 2015. NDRC was busy drafting AML implementation guidelines on the abuse of intellectual property rights (&ldquo;IPRs&rdquo;); leniency; commitments; exemption procedure; calculation of fines and illegal gains; and rules for the automobile sector. SAIC was preparing its own proposal for guidelines on AML enforcement in the IPR field. MOFCOM was drafting guidance on IPR aspects in merger control, and worked on updating its merger filing guidance. <br />\n	<br />\n	Beyond this general shift towards a &quot;lower profile&quot; enforcement approach, to an extent, there were other notable changes in 2015. For example, as some sort of departure from prior practice, more enforcement cases in 2015 targeted state-owned enterprises (&ldquo;SOEs&rdquo;) or challenged government-mandated anti-competitive conduct. <br />\n	<br />\n	As to SOEs, for instance NDRC&#39;s Yunnan branch investigated and sanctioned four state-owned telecommunications operators for suspected cartel conduct. SAIC&#39;s local office in Liaoning sanctioned a tobacco company with a statutory monopoly for abuse of dominance. MOFCOM fined a series of SOEs for failure to file reportable mergers. The courts also examined cases involving allegations of anti-competitive conduct by SOEs &ndash; for example, Sinopec&#39;s refusal to deal case in Yunnan, though the appeal judgment in 2015 turned to be in the company&#39;s favor.<br />\n	<br />\n	As to government-orchestrated anti-competitive conduct, NDRC was particularly active in 2015. The authority significantly stepped up enforcement against &quot;administrative monopolies,&quot; challenging anti-competitive actions by a variety of government bodies throughout China, such as the Shandong Department of Transportation, the Yunnan Communications Bureau, and a local Health and Family Planning Commission in Bengbu, Anhui Province.<br />\n	<br />\n	In merger control, several developments indicated change in 2015. For instance, the so-called &quot;simple case&quot; procedure &ndash; though launched by MOFCOM in 2014 &ndash; really took off in 2015, as the number of filings under the new procedure surged to above 250 (compared to around 80 in 2014). Another important change to streamline the merger review process was the internal restructuring of MOFCOM&#39;s Anti-Monopoly Bureau. In September 2015, MOFCOM decided to convert the Consultation Division into an additional case team division, together with the Legal Division and Economics Division. Today, all cases are allocated to one of the three divisions, and a single case team from one of the divisions is responsible for reviewing a case from submission to clearance. <br />\n	<br />\n	<em>Continuity in 2015</em><br />\n	<br />\n	While 2015 brought many changes, there were also clear indications of continuity with past enforcement and policies. For example, a clear link with pre-2015 enforcement was that high technology and IPRs continued to be targets of AML enforcement, though perhaps in a more subdued way. For example, enforcement against abusive licensing of standard essential patents (&ldquo;SEPs&rdquo;) continued throughout 2015: NDRC adopted the Qualcomm decision; SAIC issued the regulation on AML enforcement in the IPR field, which includes a specific SEP provision; and MOFCOM imposed SEP remedies in the Nokia/Alcatel-Lucent case. <br />\n	<br />\n	For NDRC specifically, continuity with prior enforcement was visible in its actions in the automobile industry, and its handling of international cartel cases. In 2015, NDRC and its local offices continued antitrust campaigns against automobile manufacturers and dealers. For example, in April, NDRC&#39;s Jiangsu branch fined Mercedes-Benz and its dealers for engaging in anti-competitive agreements on resale prices (around RMB 350 and 7 million, respectively). <br />\n	<br />\n	Similarly, in December 2015, NDRC published a set of decisions sanctioning eight international shipping lines for alleged price fixing and market allocation, and imposed a fine of around RMB 407 million in total. These decisions reflect continuation of NDRC&#39;s enforcement against international cartels, starting with the LCD panels and Auto parts and bearings cases in 2013 and 2014.<br />\n	<br />\n	For its turn, SAIC&#39;s enforcement showed some continuity in 2015, for example in Liaoning Cigarettes, a tying case in the tobacco industry &ndash; in line with abuse of dominance cases against tobacco wholesalers brought by SAIC&#39;s provincial offices in Inner Mongolia and Jiangsu in 2014.<br />\n	<br />\n	<em>2015 Take Aways</em><br />\n	<br />\n	Overall, 2015 was a &quot;mixed bag&quot; of developments characterized by both change and continuity &ndash; with the authorities generally taking a &quot;lower profile&quot; in enforcement activities, but an increased focus on normative efforts.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>2016 Forecast</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	Going into 2016 and beyond, we would expect that &ndash; after finalising their normative projects &ndash; the officials at the Chinese antitrust authorities would go back full-steam to case handling. We would not be surprised if AML enforcement were to accelerate again soon.<br />\n	<br />\n	On the substantive front, some of the enforcement cases in 2015 &ndash; for example, the first refusal to deal decision by an administrative antitrust authority (in the Qingyang case, by SAIC&#39;s local branch in Chongqing) &ndash; and the guidelines on the IPR field and the automotive sectors may take Chinese antitrust law into new directions going forward. For instance, it may well be that the new guidelines for the automotive sector identify new types of illegal conduct (such as territorial restrictions imposed on distributors by non-dominant suppliers), and that such changes would expand to other sectors. <br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:63:\"Adrian Emch, Partner, and Jiaming Zhang, Hogan Lovells, Beijing\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:7484:\"<p>Adrian Emch, Partner, and Jiaming Zhang, Hogan Lovells, Beijing\n</p><p>\n	To get an overview of the major anti-monopoly law developments in China in 2015 and a prediction of how the landscape might shift in 2016, Hong Kong Lawyer reached out to competition/antitrust law specialists, Adrian Emch, Partner, and Jiaming Zhang of Hogan Lovells’ Beijing office.</p>\n<p>	<strong>2015 Review</strong></p>\n<p>	In retrospect, 2015 will possibly be viewed as a year of transition for Chinese antitrust law. On the one hand, there appears to have been a change in pace in the enforcement of the Anti-Monopoly Law (“AML”). On the other hand, certain antitrust developments in 2015 reflect continuity with prior enforcement trends and policies. </p>\n<p>	<em>Change in 2015</em></p>\n<p>	In the Chinese antitrust field, 2015 started with the landmark Qualcomm decision. The decision is frequently viewed as one of the most, if not the most, controversial antitrust case in China in the past years. The National Development and Reform Commission (“NDRC”) imposed a record fine of around RMB 6 billion on Qualcomm for alleged abuse of dominance. To our knowledge, this fine is the second highest imposed on a single company in an individual case in the history of antitrust law – on a global basis.</p>\n<p>	In the lead-up to the Qualcomm decision, there had been numerous complaints against a perceived bias in Chinese antitrust law enforcement, especially by foreign stakeholders (including the US government). Perhaps as a reaction to these complaints, the three Chinese antitrust authorities – NDRC, the State Administration for Industry and Commerce (“SAIC”) and the Ministry of Commerce (“MOFCOM”) – took somewhat of a \"lower profile\" in 2015 after Qualcomm. </p>\n<p>	In parallel with the lower intensity in enforcement activity, the antitrust authorities undertook wide-ranging normative efforts in 2015. NDRC was busy drafting AML implementation guidelines on the abuse of intellectual property rights (“IPRs”); leniency; commitments; exemption procedure; calculation of fines and illegal gains; and rules for the automobile sector. SAIC was preparing its own proposal for guidelines on AML enforcement in the IPR field. MOFCOM was drafting guidance on IPR aspects in merger control, and worked on updating its merger filing guidance. </p>\n<p>	Beyond this general shift towards a \"lower profile\" enforcement approach, to an extent, there were other notable changes in 2015. For example, as some sort of departure from prior practice, more enforcement cases in 2015 targeted state-owned enterprises (“SOEs”) or challenged government-mandated anti-competitive conduct. </p>\n<p>	As to SOEs, for instance NDRC\'s Yunnan branch investigated and sanctioned four state-owned telecommunications operators for suspected cartel conduct. SAIC\'s local office in Liaoning sanctioned a tobacco company with a statutory monopoly for abuse of dominance. MOFCOM fined a series of SOEs for failure to file reportable mergers. The courts also examined cases involving allegations of anti-competitive conduct by SOEs – for example, Sinopec\'s refusal to deal case in Yunnan, though the appeal judgment in 2015 turned to be in the company\'s favor.</p>\n<p>	As to government-orchestrated anti-competitive conduct, NDRC was particularly active in 2015. The authority significantly stepped up enforcement against \"administrative monopolies,\" challenging anti-competitive actions by a variety of government bodies throughout China, such as the Shandong Department of Transportation, the Yunnan Communications Bureau, and a local Health and Family Planning Commission in Bengbu, Anhui Province.</p>\n<p>	In merger control, several developments indicated change in 2015. For instance, the so-called \"simple case\" procedure – though launched by MOFCOM in 2014 – really took off in 2015, as the number of filings under the new procedure surged to above 250 (compared to around 80 in 2014). Another important change to streamline the merger review process was the internal restructuring of MOFCOM\'s Anti-Monopoly Bureau. In September 2015, MOFCOM decided to convert the Consultation Division into an additional case team division, together with the Legal Division and Economics Division. Today, all cases are allocated to one of the three divisions, and a single case team from one of the divisions is responsible for reviewing a case from submission to clearance. </p>\n<p>	<em>Continuity in 2015</em></p>\n<p>	While 2015 brought many changes, there were also clear indications of continuity with past enforcement and policies. For example, a clear link with pre-2015 enforcement was that high technology and IPRs continued to be targets of AML enforcement, though perhaps in a more subdued way. For example, enforcement against abusive licensing of standard essential patents (“SEPs”) continued throughout 2015: NDRC adopted the Qualcomm decision; SAIC issued the regulation on AML enforcement in the IPR field, which includes a specific SEP provision; and MOFCOM imposed SEP remedies in the Nokia/Alcatel-Lucent case. </p>\n<p>	For NDRC specifically, continuity with prior enforcement was visible in its actions in the automobile industry, and its handling of international cartel cases. In 2015, NDRC and its local offices continued antitrust campaigns against automobile manufacturers and dealers. For example, in April, NDRC\'s Jiangsu branch fined Mercedes-Benz and its dealers for engaging in anti-competitive agreements on resale prices (around RMB 350 and 7 million, respectively). </p>\n<p>	Similarly, in December 2015, NDRC published a set of decisions sanctioning eight international shipping lines for alleged price fixing and market allocation, and imposed a fine of around RMB 407 million in total. These decisions reflect continuation of NDRC\'s enforcement against international cartels, starting with the LCD panels and Auto parts and bearings cases in 2013 and 2014.</p>\n<p>	For its turn, SAIC\'s enforcement showed some continuity in 2015, for example in Liaoning Cigarettes, a tying case in the tobacco industry – in line with abuse of dominance cases against tobacco wholesalers brought by SAIC\'s provincial offices in Inner Mongolia and Jiangsu in 2014.</p>\n<p>	<em>2015 Take Aways</em></p>\n<p>	Overall, 2015 was a \"mixed bag\" of developments characterized by both change and continuity – with the authorities generally taking a \"lower profile\" in enforcement activities, but an increased focus on normative efforts.</p>\n<p>	<strong>2016 Forecast</strong></p>\n<p>	Going into 2016 and beyond, we would expect that – after finalising their normative projects – the officials at the Chinese antitrust authorities would go back full-steam to case handling. We would not be surprised if AML enforcement were to accelerate again soon.</p>\n<p>	On the substantive front, some of the enforcement cases in 2015 – for example, the first refusal to deal decision by an administrative antitrust authority (in the Qingyang case, by SAIC\'s local branch in Chongqing) – and the guidelines on the IPR field and the automotive sectors may take Chinese antitrust law into new directions going forward. For instance, it may well be that the new guidelines for the automotive sector identify new types of illegal conduct (such as territorial restrictions imposed on distributors by non-dominant suppliers), and that such changes would expand to other sectors. <br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:71:\"<p>Adrian Emch, Partner, and Jiaming Zhang, Hogan Lovells, Beijing</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"661\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"559\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:61:\"China Anti-Monopoly Law Update: 2015 Review and 2016 Forecast\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:61:\"China Anti-Monopoly Law Update: 2015 Review and 2016 Forecast\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-02-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"584\";}}}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:61:\"China Anti-Monopoly Law Update: 2015 Review and 2016 Forecast\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1456099200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458182662,1),('9434','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9438\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:104:\"Court of Appeal finds that Personal Impact of Defendant’s Conviction is No Basis for Stay of Execution\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9434\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1456099200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456888481\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9434\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1456888481\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3129:\"<p>Morley Chow Seto</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On 7 December 2015, the Court of Appeal (“CA”) ordered a District Court Judge to convict Stephen Chan, the General Manager of TBV and his assistant Tseng Pei-kun, following protracted proceedings (case citation). In 2011, Chan and Tseng had been acquitted in the District Court of charges brought under the Prevention of Bribery Ordinance (Cap. 201). The Department of Justice appealed the 2011 acquittal on the grounds that the District Court Judge had not fully set out the evidence which supported the defence of a “reasonable excuse”. That appeal was allowed and the case was remitted back to the District Court Judge to consider the evidence and to decide whether Chan and Tseng had a “reasonable excuse”. The District Court Judge then found the Defendants had a reasonable excuse and acquitted them. The Department of Justice then appealed the second acquittal. On 26 October 2015, the CA reversed the acquittal and found the pair guilty of one of the bribery charges. The Court remitted the case back to the District Court Judge, directing him to convict and sentence the Defendants on that charge. To this end, the Defendants appeared at the District Court on 13 November 2015, but made an application to stay execution of the CA’s order as the Defendants had applied for leave to appeal to the Court of Final Appeal (“CFA”) on a point of law of great and general importance. The District Court Judge adjourned the case to 18 December 2015. On 7 December 2015, Chan applied to the CA to stay its own order that he be convicted and sentenced until he had secured a final decision from the CFA.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The Decision</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn refusing a stay of execution, the CA said that the reason the case was remitted to the District Court was to prevent Chan from losing his right of appeal against conviction and sentence. Unless expressly stated by the CA, where a case is remitted to a lower Court with a direction to the trial judge to convict and sentence the defendant, it should be done immediately or as soon as possible. There was no basis for the submission that the CA had not indicated to the District Court Judge to execute the CA’s order within a set time. All convicted defendants will face a certain degree of difficulties. The difficulties faced by defendants will depend on their backgrounds and on occasion may affect the people related to defendants, but Chan’s background, social status, personal wealth and the impact of his conviction and sentence on other people would not affect how the CA deals with matters. Where a sentence may lead to an appeal or review, as something that only <em>may</em> happen, it did not serve as a basis for staying the CA’s order to convict and sentence Chan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Take Aways</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhen the CA remits a case back to a lower court with a direction, that direction should be complied with by the lower court as soon as possible. Personal circumstances, or the possibility of an appeal or review, do not affect how the lower court should treat that direction.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:25:\"<p>Morley Chow Seto</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3099:\"<p>Morley Chow Seto</p>\n<p>On 7 December 2015, the Court of Appeal (“CA”) ordered a District Court Judge to convict Stephen Chan, the General Manager of TBV and his assistant Tseng Pei-kun, following protracted proceedings (case citation). In 2011, Chan and Tseng had been acquitted in the District Court of charges brought under the Prevention of Bribery Ordinance (Cap. 201). The Department of Justice appealed the 2011 acquittal on the grounds that the District Court Judge had not fully set out the evidence which supported the defence of a “reasonable excuse”. That appeal was allowed and the case was remitted back to the District Court Judge to consider the evidence and to decide whether Chan and Tseng had a “reasonable excuse”. The District Court Judge then found the Defendants had a reasonable excuse and acquitted them. The Department of Justice then appealed the second acquittal. On 26 October 2015, the CA reversed the acquittal and found the pair guilty of one of the bribery charges. The Court remitted the case back to the District Court Judge, directing him to convict and sentence the Defendants on that charge. To this end, the Defendants appeared at the District Court on 13 November 2015, but made an application to stay execution of the CA’s order as the Defendants had applied for leave to appeal to the Court of Final Appeal (“CFA”) on a point of law of great and general importance. The District Court Judge adjourned the case to 18 December 2015. On 7 December 2015, Chan applied to the CA to stay its own order that he be convicted and sentenced until he had secured a final decision from the CFA.</p>\n<p><strong>The Decision</strong></p>\n<p>In refusing a stay of execution, the CA said that the reason the case was remitted to the District Court was to prevent Chan from losing his right of appeal against conviction and sentence. Unless expressly stated by the CA, where a case is remitted to a lower Court with a direction to the trial judge to convict and sentence the defendant, it should be done immediately or as soon as possible. There was no basis for the submission that the CA had not indicated to the District Court Judge to execute the CA’s order within a set time. All convicted defendants will face a certain degree of difficulties. The difficulties faced by defendants will depend on their backgrounds and on occasion may affect the people related to defendants, but Chan’s background, social status, personal wealth and the impact of his conviction and sentence on other people would not affect how the CA deals with matters. Where a sentence may lead to an appeal or review, as something that only <em>may</em> happen, it did not serve as a basis for staying the CA’s order to convict and sentence Chan.</p>\n<p><strong>Take Aways</strong></p>\n<p>When the CA remits a case back to a lower court with a direction, that direction should be complied with by the lower court as soon as possible. Personal circumstances, or the possibility of an appeal or review, do not affect how the lower court should treat that direction. </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:24:\"<p>Morley Chow Seto</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"662\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"101\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:104:\"Court of Appeal finds that Personal Impact of Defendant’s Conviction is No Basis for Stay of Execution\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:104:\"Court of Appeal finds that Personal Impact of Defendant’s Conviction is No Basis for Stay of Execution\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-02-01 00:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:2:\"87\";}}}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:104:\"Court of Appeal finds that Personal Impact of Defendant’s Conviction is No Basis for Stay of Execution\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";s:1:\"0\";s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1456310169\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";N;s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458112328,1),('9435','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9439\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:104:\"Court of Appeal finds that Personal Impact of Defendant’s Conviction is No Basis for Stay of Execution\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9435\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1456099200\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456310169\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9434\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1456310169\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:3159:\"Morley Chow Seto<p>\n	On 7 December 2015, the Court of Appeal (&ldquo;CA&rdquo;) ordered a District Court Judge to convict Stephen Chan, the General Manager of TBV and his assistant Tseng Pei-kun, following protracted proceedings (case citation). In 2011, Chan and Tseng had been acquitted in the District Court of charges brought under the Prevention of Bribery Ordinance (Cap. 201). The Department of Justice appealed the 2011 acquittal on the grounds that the District Court Judge had not fully set out the evidence which supported the defence of a &ldquo;reasonable excuse&rdquo;. That appeal was allowed and the case was remitted back to the District Court Judge to consider the evidence and to decide whether Chan and Tseng had a &ldquo;reasonable excuse&rdquo;. The District Court Judge then found the Defendants had a reasonable excuse and acquitted them. The Department of Justice then appealed the second acquittal. On 26 October 2015, the CA reversed the acquittal and found the pair guilty of one of the bribery charges. The Court remitted the case back to the District Court Judge, directing him to convict and sentence the Defendants on that charge. To this end, the Defendants appeared at the District Court on 13 November 2015, but made an application to stay execution of the CA&rsquo;s order as the Defendants had applied for leave to appeal to the Court of Final Appeal (&ldquo;CFA&rdquo;) on a point of law of great and general importance. The District Court Judge adjourned the case to 18 December 2015. On 7 December 2015, Chan applied to the CA to stay its own order that he be convicted and sentenced until he had secured a final decision from the CFA.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>The Decision</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	In refusing a stay of execution, the CA said that the reason the case was remitted to the District Court was to prevent Chan from losing his right of appeal against conviction and sentence. Unless expressly stated by the CA, where a case is remitted to a lower Court with a direction to the trial judge to convict and sentence the defendant, it should be done immediately or as soon as possible. There was no basis for the submission that the CA had not indicated to the District Court Judge to execute the CA&rsquo;s order within a set time. All convicted defendants will face a certain degree of difficulties. The difficulties faced by defendants will depend on their backgrounds and on occasion may affect the people related to defendants, but Chan&rsquo;s background, social status, personal wealth and the impact of his conviction and sentence on other people would not affect how the CA deals with matters. Where a sentence may lead to an appeal or review, as something that only <em>may</em> happen, it did not serve as a basis for staying the CA&rsquo;s order to convict and sentence Chan.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Take Aways</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	When the CA remits a case back to a lower court with a direction, that direction should be complied with by the lower court as soon as possible. Personal circumstances, or the possibility of an appeal or review, do not affect how the lower court should treat that direction.</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:16:\"Morley Chow Seto\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:3105:\"<p>Morley Chow Seto\n</p><p>\n	On 7 December 2015, the Court of Appeal (“CA”) ordered a District Court Judge to convict Stephen Chan, the General Manager of TBV and his assistant Tseng Pei-kun, following protracted proceedings (case citation). In 2011, Chan and Tseng had been acquitted in the District Court of charges brought under the Prevention of Bribery Ordinance (Cap. 201). The Department of Justice appealed the 2011 acquittal on the grounds that the District Court Judge had not fully set out the evidence which supported the defence of a “reasonable excuse”. That appeal was allowed and the case was remitted back to the District Court Judge to consider the evidence and to decide whether Chan and Tseng had a “reasonable excuse”. The District Court Judge then found the Defendants had a reasonable excuse and acquitted them. The Department of Justice then appealed the second acquittal. On 26 October 2015, the CA reversed the acquittal and found the pair guilty of one of the bribery charges. The Court remitted the case back to the District Court Judge, directing him to convict and sentence the Defendants on that charge. To this end, the Defendants appeared at the District Court on 13 November 2015, but made an application to stay execution of the CA’s order as the Defendants had applied for leave to appeal to the Court of Final Appeal (“CFA”) on a point of law of great and general importance. The District Court Judge adjourned the case to 18 December 2015. On 7 December 2015, Chan applied to the CA to stay its own order that he be convicted and sentenced until he had secured a final decision from the CFA.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>The Decision</strong></p>\n<p>	In refusing a stay of execution, the CA said that the reason the case was remitted to the District Court was to prevent Chan from losing his right of appeal against conviction and sentence. Unless expressly stated by the CA, where a case is remitted to a lower Court with a direction to the trial judge to convict and sentence the defendant, it should be done immediately or as soon as possible. There was no basis for the submission that the CA had not indicated to the District Court Judge to execute the CA’s order within a set time. All convicted defendants will face a certain degree of difficulties. The difficulties faced by defendants will depend on their backgrounds and on occasion may affect the people related to defendants, but Chan’s background, social status, personal wealth and the impact of his conviction and sentence on other people would not affect how the CA deals with matters. Where a sentence may lead to an appeal or review, as something that only <em>may</em> happen, it did not serve as a basis for staying the CA’s order to convict and sentence Chan.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Take Aways</strong></p>\n<p>	When the CA remits a case back to a lower court with a direction, that direction should be complied with by the lower court as soon as possible. Personal circumstances, or the possibility of an appeal or review, do not affect how the lower court should treat that direction.</p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:24:\"<p>Morley Chow Seto</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"661\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"563\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:104:\"Court of Appeal finds that Personal Impact of Defendant’s Conviction is No Basis for Stay of Execution\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:104:\"Court of Appeal finds that Personal Impact of Defendant’s Conviction is No Basis for Stay of Execution\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-02-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"585\";}}}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:104:\"Court of Appeal finds that Personal Impact of Defendant’s Conviction is No Basis for Stay of Execution\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1456099200\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458182662,1),('9436','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9440\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:69:\"SFC Bans another Fraudulent Trader for Life as Internal Controls Fail\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9436\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1456185600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456888424\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9436\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1456888424\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:6340:\"<p>Niall Coburn, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The lifetime ban imposed on a Hong Kong stockbroker has highlighted the need for firms to review their internal controls for the transfer of money from clients\' accounts without their written authority. The Securities and Futures Commission (“SFC”) recently banned Chow Chi Keung, a former licensed representative of Wocom Securities, for life for misappropriating HK$2.5 million from nine clients between 2010 and 2012.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nChow also concealed trading losses in clients\' accounts which mounted up over three years. After compliance changes in 2011, a number of client complaints emerged and Chow reported the fraud internally. Wocom referred the matter to the police and the SFC.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Summary</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe SFC, on 11 February 2016, permanently banned Chow from entering the industry. The investigation found that to conceal trading losses, which occurred between 2010 and 2012, Chow conducted unauthorised actions as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Forged clients\' signatures on 13 Wocom payment instruction forms to facilitate the withdrawal or transfer of HK$2.5 million of client monies from nine accounts to his wife\'s personal accounts or other client accounts maintained at Wocom; and</li>\r\n	<li>Sold securities in five client accounts without their authorisation and transferred the sale proceeds to other clients\' accounts.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Chow had been employed as an account executive of Wocom from 10 January 2000 to December 2012. His responsibilities included handling client accounts and completing payment instruction forms in accordance with client instructions.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOne of the basic rules, as set out in General Principle 1 of the Code of Conduct for persons licensed by and registered with the SFC, required individuals to act honestly, fairly and in the best interest of clients when conducting their business activities.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>New Controls Introduced</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn 2011, Wocom introduced new internal controls requiring account executives to state the relationship between the clients and the reason for the transfers between the client accounts and required further information to be set out on the payment instruction forms outlining the reason for the transfers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPrior to November 2012, Chow was able to bypass the internal controls and fabricated relationships between the clients. He also provided false reasons for the transfers on the payment instruction forms to facilitate transfers between different client accounts.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Pressure to Conceal Trading Losses</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt appears Chow was under significant pressure to hide the trading losses in clients\' accounts and was involved in conduct which ultimately, he would have been exposed simply because clients check their accounts in relation to trades undertaken. It was unsurprising that in November 2012, the SFC received two complaints alleging that Chow had misappropriated funds from their accounts.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis alert culminated in the appointment of a forensic investigator in January 2013 to conduct a review into the extent of the alleged misappropriation and other unauthorised acts in working client accounts. Chow admitted subsequently to Wocom he had forged clients\' signatures on 13 payment instruction forms to facilitate the transfers of money out of the clients\' accounts to his wife\'s account.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Analysis: Bypassing Internal Controls</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis case highlights the risk that employees may be able to bypass internal controls in the absence of spot checks or manager reviews of accounts. It raises the issue that firms have to review processes and exploit perceived weaknesses in procedures. Experience has shown that the major weaknesses in procedures and internal controls occur where there is no oversight over accounts for long periods of time.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe actions of Chow which had required account executives to state the relationship and reasons for client fund transfers on the payment instruction form show how easy it was for employees to manipulate the system under pressure of trading losses.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe cases raise another interesting point, in relation to firms not knowing when their traders have made significant trading losses. Trading losses are important to consider, know and monitor. These lessons should be well understood from the Barings Bank scandal when hidden trading losses brought the bank to the point of insolvency.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt is important for firms to understand that there have been numerous cases in Hong Kong and elsewhere where traders have acted fraudulently under pressure to conceal their clients\' losses. One of the lessons is that if firms are unaware of the trading losses it reflects on the failure of senior management oversight and that internal controls are failing.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nCodes of conduct, with clear ethical principles, rules and regulations, do not in themselves guard against fraud. Firms can only rely on proper internal controls and management oversight, including spot checks, and monitoring systems to ensure that traders, who are under pressure, cannot bypass the system.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe instances where internal controls and procedures within firms have failed because employees can bypass systems exposes weaknesses in the overall compliance structure and as in this case, many issues are only brought to attention because of clients complaints about Chow\'s handling of their accounts.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Final Word</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThese cases should make firms consider if there is a need to review their systems and controls and assess whether they can be bypassed in any way that would give rise to serious fraud. It also may be appropriate to conduct training sessions for employees and stressing if they make mistakes, or they are under pressure to conceal trading losses, emphasise the need for traders to \"put their hands up\" and encourage staff to report any problems and pressures they face.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn the long run this is a cheaper approach than having the SFC and police investigate traders and the firm, not to mention the time lost and the reputational damage involved.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:46:\"<p>Niall Coburn, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:6158:\"<p>Niall Coburn, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n<p>The lifetime ban imposed on a Hong Kong stockbroker has highlighted the need for firms to review their internal controls for the transfer of money from clients\' accounts without their written authority. The Securities and Futures Commission (“SFC”) recently banned Chow Chi Keung, a former licensed representative of Wocom Securities, for life for misappropriating HK$2.5 million from nine clients between 2010 and 2012.</p>\n<p>Chow also concealed trading losses in clients\' accounts which mounted up over three years. After compliance changes in 2011, a number of client complaints emerged and Chow reported the fraud internally. Wocom referred the matter to the police and the SFC.</p>\n<p><strong>Summary</strong></p>\n<p>The SFC, on 11 February 2016, permanently banned Chow from entering the industry. The investigation found that to conceal trading losses, which occurred between 2010 and 2012, Chow conducted unauthorised actions as follows:</p>\n<ul><li>Forged clients\' signatures on 13 Wocom payment instruction forms to facilitate the withdrawal or transfer of HK$2.5 million of client monies from nine accounts to his wife\'s personal accounts or other client accounts maintained at Wocom; and</li>\n<li>Sold securities in five client accounts without their authorisation and transferred the sale proceeds to other clients\' accounts.</li>\n</ul><p>Chow had been employed as an account executive of Wocom from 10 January 2000 to December 2012. His responsibilities included handling client accounts and completing payment instruction forms in accordance with client instructions.</p>\n<p>One of the basic rules, as set out in General Principle 1 of the Code of Conduct for persons licensed by and registered with the SFC, required individuals to act honestly, fairly and in the best interest of clients when conducting their business activities.</p>\n<p><strong>New Controls Introduced</strong></p>\n<p>In 2011, Wocom introduced new internal controls requiring account executives to state the relationship between the clients and the reason for the transfers between the client accounts and required further information to be set out on the payment instruction forms outlining the reason for the transfers.</p>\n<p>Prior to November 2012, Chow was able to bypass the internal controls and fabricated relationships between the clients. He also provided false reasons for the transfers on the payment instruction forms to facilitate transfers between different client accounts.</p>\n<p><strong>Pressure to Conceal Trading Losses</strong></p>\n<p>It appears Chow was under significant pressure to hide the trading losses in clients\' accounts and was involved in conduct which ultimately, he would have been exposed simply because clients check their accounts in relation to trades undertaken. It was unsurprising that in November 2012, the SFC received two complaints alleging that Chow had misappropriated funds from their accounts.</p>\n<p>This alert culminated in the appointment of a forensic investigator in January 2013 to conduct a review into the extent of the alleged misappropriation and other unauthorised acts in working client accounts. Chow admitted subsequently to Wocom he had forged clients\' signatures on 13 payment instruction forms to facilitate the transfers of money out of the clients\' accounts to his wife\'s account.</p>\n<p><strong>Analysis: Bypassing Internal Controls</strong></p>\n<p>This case highlights the risk that employees may be able to bypass internal controls in the absence of spot checks or manager reviews of accounts. It raises the issue that firms have to review processes and exploit perceived weaknesses in procedures. Experience has shown that the major weaknesses in procedures and internal controls occur where there is no oversight over accounts for long periods of time.</p>\n<p>The actions of Chow which had required account executives to state the relationship and reasons for client fund transfers on the payment instruction form show how easy it was for employees to manipulate the system under pressure of trading losses.</p>\n<p>The cases raise another interesting point, in relation to firms not knowing when their traders have made significant trading losses. Trading losses are important to consider, know and monitor. These lessons should be well understood from the Barings Bank scandal when hidden trading losses brought the bank to the point of insolvency.</p>\n<p>It is important for firms to understand that there have been numerous cases in Hong Kong and elsewhere where traders have acted fraudulently under pressure to conceal their clients\' losses. One of the lessons is that if firms are unaware of the trading losses it reflects on the failure of senior management oversight and that internal controls are failing.</p>\n<p>Codes of conduct, with clear ethical principles, rules and regulations, do not in themselves guard against fraud. Firms can only rely on proper internal controls and management oversight, including spot checks, and monitoring systems to ensure that traders, who are under pressure, cannot bypass the system.</p>\n<p>The instances where internal controls and procedures within firms have failed because employees can bypass systems exposes weaknesses in the overall compliance structure and as in this case, many issues are only brought to attention because of clients complaints about Chow\'s handling of their accounts.</p>\n<p><strong>Final Word</strong></p>\n<p>These cases should make firms consider if there is a need to review their systems and controls and assess whether they can be bypassed in any way that would give rise to serious fraud. It also may be appropriate to conduct training sessions for employees and stressing if they make mistakes, or they are under pressure to conceal trading losses, emphasise the need for traders to \"put their hands up\" and encourage staff to report any problems and pressures they face.</p>\n<p>In the long run this is a cheaper approach than having the SFC and police investigate traders and the firm, not to mention the time lost and the reputational damage involved.<br />\n </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:45:\"<p>Niall Coburn, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"662\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"114\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:69:\"SFC Bans another Fraudulent Trader for Life as Internal Controls Fail\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:69:\"SFC Bans another Fraudulent Trader for Life as Internal Controls Fail\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-02-01 00:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:2:\"87\";}}}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:69:\"SFC Bans another Fraudulent Trader for Life as Internal Controls Fail\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";s:1:\"0\";s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1456310169\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";N;s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458111751,1),('9437','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9441\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:69:\"SFC Bans another Fraudulent Trader for Life as Internal Controls Fail\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9437\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:7:\"zh-hant\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1456185600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456310169\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9436\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1456310169\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:6391:\"Niall Coburn, Regulatory Intelligence<p>\n	The lifetime ban imposed on a Hong Kong stockbroker has highlighted the need for firms to review their internal controls for the transfer of money from clients&#39; accounts without their written authority. The Securities and Futures Commission (&ldquo;SFC&rdquo;) recently banned Chow Chi Keung, a former licensed representative of Wocom Securities, for life for misappropriating HK$2.5 million from nine clients between 2010 and 2012.<br />\n	<br />\n	Chow also concealed trading losses in clients&#39; accounts which mounted up over three years. After compliance changes in 2011, a number of client complaints emerged and Chow reported the fraud internally. Wocom referred the matter to the police and the SFC.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Summary</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	The SFC, on 11 February 2016, permanently banned Chow from entering the industry. The investigation found that to conceal trading losses, which occurred between 2010 and 2012, Chow conducted unauthorised actions as follows:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Forged clients&#39; signatures on 13 Wocom payment instruction forms to facilitate the withdrawal or transfer of HK$2.5 million of client monies from nine accounts to his wife&#39;s personal accounts or other client accounts maintained at Wocom; and</li>\n	<li>\n		Sold securities in five client accounts without their authorisation and transferred the sale proceeds to other clients&#39; accounts.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Chow had been employed as an account executive of Wocom from 10 January 2000 to December 2012. His responsibilities included handling client accounts and completing payment instruction forms in accordance with client instructions.<br />\n	<br />\n	One of the basic rules, as set out in General Principle 1 of the Code of Conduct for persons licensed by and registered with the SFC, required individuals to act honestly, fairly and in the best interest of clients when conducting their business activities.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>New Controls Introduced</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	In 2011, Wocom introduced new internal controls requiring account executives to state the relationship between the clients and the reason for the transfers between the client accounts and required further information to be set out on the payment instruction forms outlining the reason for the transfers.<br />\n	<br />\n	Prior to November 2012, Chow was able to bypass the internal controls and fabricated relationships between the clients. He also provided false reasons for the transfers on the payment instruction forms to facilitate transfers between different client accounts.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Pressure to Conceal Trading Losses</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	It appears Chow was under significant pressure to hide the trading losses in clients&#39; accounts and was involved in conduct which ultimately, he would have been exposed simply because clients check their accounts in relation to trades undertaken. It was unsurprising that in November 2012, the SFC received two complaints alleging that Chow had misappropriated funds from their accounts.<br />\n	<br />\n	This alert culminated in the appointment of a forensic investigator in January 2013 to conduct a review into the extent of the alleged misappropriation and other unauthorised acts in working client accounts. Chow admitted subsequently to Wocom he had forged clients&#39; signatures on 13 payment instruction forms to facilitate the transfers of money out of the clients&#39; accounts to his wife&#39;s account.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Analysis: Bypassing Internal Controls</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	This case highlights the risk that employees may be able to bypass internal controls in the absence of spot checks or manager reviews of accounts. It raises the issue that firms have to review processes and exploit perceived weaknesses in procedures. Experience has shown that the major weaknesses in procedures and internal controls occur where there is no oversight over accounts for long periods of time.<br />\n	<br />\n	The actions of Chow which had required account executives to state the relationship and reasons for client fund transfers on the payment instruction form show how easy it was for employees to manipulate the system under pressure of trading losses.<br />\n	<br />\n	The cases raise another interesting point, in relation to firms not knowing when their traders have made significant trading losses. Trading losses are important to consider, know and monitor. These lessons should be well understood from the Barings Bank scandal when hidden trading losses brought the bank to the point of insolvency.<br />\n	<br />\n	It is important for firms to understand that there have been numerous cases in Hong Kong and elsewhere where traders have acted fraudulently under pressure to conceal their clients&#39; losses. One of the lessons is that if firms are unaware of the trading losses it reflects on the failure of senior management oversight and that internal controls are failing.<br />\n	<br />\n	Codes of conduct, with clear ethical principles, rules and regulations, do not in themselves guard against fraud. Firms can only rely on proper internal controls and management oversight, including spot checks, and monitoring systems to ensure that traders, who are under pressure, cannot bypass the system.<br />\n	<br />\n	The instances where internal controls and procedures within firms have failed because employees can bypass systems exposes weaknesses in the overall compliance structure and as in this case, many issues are only brought to attention because of clients complaints about Chow&#39;s handling of their accounts.<br />\n	<br />\n	<strong>Final Word</strong><br />\n	<br />\n	These cases should make firms consider if there is a need to review their systems and controls and assess whether they can be bypassed in any way that would give rise to serious fraud. It also may be appropriate to conduct training sessions for employees and stressing if they make mistakes, or they are under pressure to conceal trading losses, emphasise the need for traders to &quot;put their hands up&quot; and encourage staff to report any problems and pressures they face.<br />\n	<br />\n	In the long run this is a cheaper approach than having the SFC and police investigate traders and the firm, not to mention the time lost and the reputational damage involved.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:37:\"Niall Coburn, Regulatory Intelligence\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:6189:\"<p>Niall Coburn, Regulatory Intelligence\n</p><p>\n	The lifetime ban imposed on a Hong Kong stockbroker has highlighted the need for firms to review their internal controls for the transfer of money from clients\' accounts without their written authority. The Securities and Futures Commission (“SFC”) recently banned Chow Chi Keung, a former licensed representative of Wocom Securities, for life for misappropriating HK$2.5 million from nine clients between 2010 and 2012.</p>\n<p>	Chow also concealed trading losses in clients\' accounts which mounted up over three years. After compliance changes in 2011, a number of client complaints emerged and Chow reported the fraud internally. Wocom referred the matter to the police and the SFC.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Summary</strong></p>\n<p>	The SFC, on 11 February 2016, permanently banned Chow from entering the industry. The investigation found that to conceal trading losses, which occurred between 2010 and 2012, Chow conducted unauthorised actions as follows:</p>\n<ul><li>\n		Forged clients\' signatures on 13 Wocom payment instruction forms to facilitate the withdrawal or transfer of HK$2.5 million of client monies from nine accounts to his wife\'s personal accounts or other client accounts maintained at Wocom; and</li>\n<li>\n		Sold securities in five client accounts without their authorisation and transferred the sale proceeds to other clients\' accounts.</li>\n</ul><p>\n	Chow had been employed as an account executive of Wocom from 10 January 2000 to December 2012. His responsibilities included handling client accounts and completing payment instruction forms in accordance with client instructions.</p>\n<p>	One of the basic rules, as set out in General Principle 1 of the Code of Conduct for persons licensed by and registered with the SFC, required individuals to act honestly, fairly and in the best interest of clients when conducting their business activities.</p>\n<p>	<strong>New Controls Introduced</strong></p>\n<p>	In 2011, Wocom introduced new internal controls requiring account executives to state the relationship between the clients and the reason for the transfers between the client accounts and required further information to be set out on the payment instruction forms outlining the reason for the transfers.</p>\n<p>	Prior to November 2012, Chow was able to bypass the internal controls and fabricated relationships between the clients. He also provided false reasons for the transfers on the payment instruction forms to facilitate transfers between different client accounts.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Pressure to Conceal Trading Losses</strong></p>\n<p>	It appears Chow was under significant pressure to hide the trading losses in clients\' accounts and was involved in conduct which ultimately, he would have been exposed simply because clients check their accounts in relation to trades undertaken. It was unsurprising that in November 2012, the SFC received two complaints alleging that Chow had misappropriated funds from their accounts.</p>\n<p>	This alert culminated in the appointment of a forensic investigator in January 2013 to conduct a review into the extent of the alleged misappropriation and other unauthorised acts in working client accounts. Chow admitted subsequently to Wocom he had forged clients\' signatures on 13 payment instruction forms to facilitate the transfers of money out of the clients\' accounts to his wife\'s account.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Analysis: Bypassing Internal Controls</strong></p>\n<p>	This case highlights the risk that employees may be able to bypass internal controls in the absence of spot checks or manager reviews of accounts. It raises the issue that firms have to review processes and exploit perceived weaknesses in procedures. Experience has shown that the major weaknesses in procedures and internal controls occur where there is no oversight over accounts for long periods of time.</p>\n<p>	The actions of Chow which had required account executives to state the relationship and reasons for client fund transfers on the payment instruction form show how easy it was for employees to manipulate the system under pressure of trading losses.</p>\n<p>	The cases raise another interesting point, in relation to firms not knowing when their traders have made significant trading losses. Trading losses are important to consider, know and monitor. These lessons should be well understood from the Barings Bank scandal when hidden trading losses brought the bank to the point of insolvency.</p>\n<p>	It is important for firms to understand that there have been numerous cases in Hong Kong and elsewhere where traders have acted fraudulently under pressure to conceal their clients\' losses. One of the lessons is that if firms are unaware of the trading losses it reflects on the failure of senior management oversight and that internal controls are failing.</p>\n<p>	Codes of conduct, with clear ethical principles, rules and regulations, do not in themselves guard against fraud. Firms can only rely on proper internal controls and management oversight, including spot checks, and monitoring systems to ensure that traders, who are under pressure, cannot bypass the system.</p>\n<p>	The instances where internal controls and procedures within firms have failed because employees can bypass systems exposes weaknesses in the overall compliance structure and as in this case, many issues are only brought to attention because of clients complaints about Chow\'s handling of their accounts.</p>\n<p>	<strong>Final Word</strong></p>\n<p>	These cases should make firms consider if there is a need to review their systems and controls and assess whether they can be bypassed in any way that would give rise to serious fraud. It also may be appropriate to conduct training sessions for employees and stressing if they make mistakes, or they are under pressure to conceal trading losses, emphasise the need for traders to \"put their hands up\" and encourage staff to report any problems and pressures they face.</p>\n<p>	In the long run this is a cheaper approach than having the SFC and police investigate traders and the firm, not to mention the time lost and the reputational damage involved.<br />\n	 </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:45:\"<p>Niall Coburn, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"661\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"576\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:7:\"zh-hant\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:69:\"SFC Bans another Fraudulent Trader for Life as Internal Controls Fail\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:69:\"SFC Bans another Fraudulent Trader for Life as Internal Controls Fail\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-02-01 07:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"585\";}}}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:69:\"SFC Bans another Fraudulent Trader for Life as Internal Controls Fail\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:8:\"dc:title\";}}s:7:\"created\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:7:\"dc:date\";i:1;s:10:\"dc:created\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:7:\"changed\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:11:\"dc:modified\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:15:\"content:encoded\";}}s:3:\"uid\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:has_creator\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:4:\"name\";a:1:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:9:\"foaf:name\";}}s:13:\"comment_count\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:16:\"sioc:num_replies\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:11:\"xsd:integer\";}s:13:\"last_activity\";a:3:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:23:\"sioc:last_activity_date\";}s:8:\"datatype\";s:12:\"xsd:dateTime\";s:8:\"callback\";s:12:\"date_iso8601\";}}s:3:\"cid\";i:0;s:22:\"last_comment_timestamp\";s:10:\"1456185600\";s:17:\"last_comment_name\";s:0:\"\";s:16:\"last_comment_uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:13:\"comment_count\";i:0;s:4:\"name\";s:5:\"admin\";s:7:\"picture\";s:1:\"0\";s:4:\"data\";s:241:\"a:7:{s:5:\"block\";a:1:{s:6:\"system\";a:1:{s:4:\"main\";i:0;}}s:16:\"ckeditor_default\";s:1:\"t\";s:20:\"ckeditor_show_toggle\";s:1:\"t\";s:14:\"ckeditor_width\";s:4:\"100%\";s:13:\"ckeditor_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:18:\"ckeditor_auto_lang\";s:1:\"t\";s:7:\"overlay\";i:1;}\";}',0,1458182662,1),('9438','O:8:\"stdClass\":39:{s:3:\"vid\";s:4:\"9442\";s:3:\"uid\";s:1:\"1\";s:5:\"title\";s:92:\"UN Plays Key Role in Combating Islamic State Finances, \"Meaningful\" Progress Made, says FATF\";s:3:\"log\";s:29:\"Created by FeedsNodeProcessor\";s:6:\"status\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"comment\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"promote\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"sticky\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"nid\";s:4:\"9438\";s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"article\";s:8:\"language\";s:2:\"en\";s:7:\"created\";s:10:\"1456185600\";s:7:\"changed\";s:10:\"1456888444\";s:4:\"tnid\";s:4:\"9438\";s:9:\"translate\";s:1:\"0\";s:18:\"revision_timestamp\";s:10:\"1456888444\";s:12:\"revision_uid\";s:3:\"217\";s:4:\"body\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:\"value\";s:2846:\"<p>Brett Wolf, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\r\n\r\n<p>United Nations Security Council resolutions and related sanctions are a key tool in cutting off money for the Islamic State, but member states must work to ensure that blacklisted parties are cut off from the global financial system, an international anti-terrorist financing body determined during a special meeting on Sunday, 14 February.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\"Participants considered steps that should be taken to enhance implementation of key provisions in those resolutions, as well as additional steps to protect the international financial system from abuse by ISIL (Islamic State),\" the global anti-money laundering standard-setting Financial Action Task Force (“FATF”) said in a press statement released Wednesday, 17 February.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSecurity Council Resolutions 2199 and 2253 said that trade in oil and other resources with ISIL is prohibited and authorized new efforts by the ISIL and Al-Qaida Sanctions Committee to address the threat.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nParticipants agreed \"meaningful progress\" had been made in degrading ISIL\'s financial strength. They discussed the group\'s financial links to foreign branches and a need to better engage countries where those affiliates operate, FATF said. They also addressed the need for more coordination to combat foreign terrorist fighter financing, including better information sharing.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSunday\'s meeting took place in Paris and included delegates from FATF and the so-called Coalition Counter ISIL Finance Group (“CIFG”), a coalition of dozens of countries and organizations led by Italy, Saudi Arabia, and the United States. The goal of the meeting was to impose \"the full weight of the international community’s anti-money laundering and counter terrorist financing expertise against ISIL,\" FATF said.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThose present concluded that ISIL\'s primary revenue sources have not changed since FATF issued a report examining the terrorists\' money flows in February of last year, a statement issued by US Treasury Department Assistant Secretary for Terrorist Financing Daniel Glaser, stated. Bank looting, extortion, and control of oil fields and refineries remain the group\'s primary money making activities, he said.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nProgress against ISIL\'s pocketbook can be seen in \"signs\" the group is struggling to pay its fighters in some regions and to provide basic services to local populations, Glaser said.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHe added that the global bodies plan to continue coordinating efforts to interrupt ISIL\'s finances and combat terror finance more broadly.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA spokeswoman for FATF did not respond to an inquiry regarding any discussions of the role of the private sector in efforts to combat ISIL\'s finances. Nor did a spokeswoman for the US Treasury Department.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\";s:7:\"summary\";s:44:\"<p>Brett Wolf, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\r\n\";s:6:\"format\";s:9:\"full_html\";s:10:\"safe_value\";s:2773:\"<p>Brett Wolf, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n<p>United Nations Security Council resolutions and related sanctions are a key tool in cutting off money for the Islamic State, but member states must work to ensure that blacklisted parties are cut off from the global financial system, an international anti-terrorist financing body determined during a special meeting on Sunday, 14 February.</p>\n<p>\"Participants considered steps that should be taken to enhance implementation of key provisions in those resolutions, as well as additional steps to protect the international financial system from abuse by ISIL (Islamic State),\" the global anti-money laundering standard-setting Financial Action Task Force (“FATF”) said in a press statement released Wednesday, 17 February.</p>\n<p>Security Council Resolutions 2199 and 2253 said that trade in oil and other resources with ISIL is prohibited and authorized new efforts by the ISIL and Al-Qaida Sanctions Committee to address the threat.</p>\n<p>Participants agreed \"meaningful progress\" had been made in degrading ISIL\'s financial strength. They discussed the group\'s financial links to foreign branches and a need to better engage countries where those affiliates operate, FATF said. They also addressed the need for more coordination to combat foreign terrorist fighter financing, including better information sharing.</p>\n<p>Sunday\'s meeting took place in Paris and included delegates from FATF and the so-called Coalition Counter ISIL Finance Group (“CIFG”), a coalition of dozens of countries and organizations led by Italy, Saudi Arabia, and the United States. The goal of the meeting was to impose \"the full weight of the international community’s anti-money laundering and counter terrorist financing expertise against ISIL,\" FATF said.</p>\n<p>Those present concluded that ISIL\'s primary revenue sources have not changed since FATF issued a report examining the terrorists\' money flows in February of last year, a statement issued by US Treasury Department Assistant Secretary for Terrorist Financing Daniel Glaser, stated. Bank looting, extortion, and control of oil fields and refineries remain the group\'s primary money making activities, he said.</p>\n<p>Progress against ISIL\'s pocketbook can be seen in \"signs\" the group is struggling to pay its fighters in some regions and to provide basic services to local populations, Glaser said.</p>\n<p>He added that the global bodies plan to continue coordinating efforts to interrupt ISIL\'s finances and combat terror finance more broadly.</p>\n<p>A spokeswoman for FATF did not respond to an inquiry regarding any discussions of the role of the private sector in efforts to combat ISIL\'s finances. Nor did a spokeswoman for the US Treasury Department.<br />\n </p>\n\";s:12:\"safe_summary\";s:43:\"<p>Brett Wolf, Regulatory Intelligence</p>\n\";}}}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:0:{}s:11:\"field_image\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_contents\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"662\";}}}s:20:\"field_practice_areas\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:3:\"114\";}}}s:12:\"field_images\";a:0:{}s:14:\"field_featured\";a:0:{}s:11:\"title_field\";a:1:{s:2:\"en\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"value\";s:92:\"UN Plays Key Role in Combating Islamic State Finances, \"Meaningful\" Progress Made, says FATF\";s:6:\"format\";N;s:10:\"safe_value\";s:102:\"UN Plays Key Role in Combating Islamic State Finances, &quot;Meaningful&quot; Progress Made, says FATF\";}}}s:13:\"field_authors\";a:0:{}s:19:\"field_journal_issue\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:\"value\";s:19:\"2016-02-01 00:00:00\";s:8:\"timezone\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:11:\"timezone_db\";s:14:\"Asia/Hong_Kong\";s:9:\"date_type\";s:8:\"datetime\";}}}s:19:\"field_jurisdictions\";a:1:{s:3:\"und\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:\"tid\";s:2:\"91\";}}}s:11:\"field_video\";a:0:{}s:14:\"title_original\";s:92:\"UN Plays Key Role in Combating Islamic State Finances, \"Meaningful\" Progress Made, says FATF\";s:11:\"rdf_mapping\";a:11:{s:11:\"field_image\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:2:{i:0;s:8:\"og:image\";i:1;s:12:\"rdfs:seeAlso\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:10:\"field_tags\";a:2:{s:10:\"predicates\";a:1:{i:0;s:10:\"dc:subject\";}s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"rel\";}s:7:\"rdftype\";a:2:{i:0;s:9:\"sioc:Item\";i:1;s:13:\"foaf:Document\";}s:5:\"title\";a:1: